text: a very sexy orange hazy pour with a tiptop offwhite head and sexy lacing .  mouthfeel : i only had a couple mouthfuls ( did n't even make it through one bottle ) , but it felt more substantial and less watery than o'douls or warsteiner .
appearence : pours a heavy , dark almost-black brown with a giant , frothy beige head .  m : was ok , but nothing to write home about .
the smell was delicious . so many different scents to pick out . this beer smells like christmas .  it had a light feel on the palate with very high carbonation .

it poured a light orange with lots of cloudiness and sediment . there was a thick and frothy 1 finger head which lingered and finally dissolved leaving a fine lacing .  mouthfeel - kind of effervescent .

eye : black in color with ruby highlights , this brew is everything that a doppelbock should look like . the head has good retention , is tan in color and appears to be creamy .  perfect creaminess with a decent bite . mouthfeel - the only thing left is a slight bitterness on the sides of your tongue , average here . drinkability - above average , creamy and satisfying , could have a few of these without an issue .

5.0 s : the nose on this is incredibly powerful , but also incredibly pleasant . a blind man with a cold would be able to figure out there was a beer in the room based on the force that this puts out . there is a bit of sugary sweetness in the taste as well , but nowhere near as strong as the nose ( which is a good thing ) .  the mouthfeel is a bit overcarbonated and burns the tongue a bit .
smell- glorious cherry cordial nose , slight hint of chocolate chips .  light mouth feel . hops win out . ; )

the atwater vanilla java porter is big on aroma , but short on body . this porter is very light . the aroma is filled with vanilla and coffee . still worth a try however .  a big surprise with this one smells great a west coast from the east coast t more big hop flavors but not quite as strong in the mouth but still quite good m a little flat and not as thick as i would like but it leaves some grit on your gums and the flavors hang out for a while d i really liked this beer i nearly took down the jug on my own in no time very unexpected winner with this one , after seeing it 's 7.1 % alc i give it even more props because the whole time i thought i was drinking a low booze ipa .

poured a clear amber , really a reddish gold . was well carbonated , giving a dense one finger head with plenty of bubbling well into the beer .  mouthfeel : a little on the thin side with high carbonation and a slightly dry finish .
s : stunning . hops .  mouthfeel : it seems like a light body beer but the dry pokes and hop prods keep it active until the nearly numbing dry of the aftertaste begs for more .
s : soft fruit , earthy hops , and a bready malty backbone make this one of the most balanced noses i 've come across . pretty good . its like a subtle version of sweetwater ipa .  a little thin .

a - pours a pale , clear yellow , with a huge , billowing three fingers of rocky head . plenty of lacing and excellent retention .  tastes smooth and creamy sweet malt with light fruit flavor hints of spice and light alcohol finish good easy drinking beer little on light side but it does enhance drinkability .

pretty shitty pour on my behalf , with nearly two fingers of off-white , light tan head . slightly hazy burnt orange in color , very pretty to look at . head retention is stellar .  feels quite frothy and wild , perhaps a little over done . the carbonation also seems to mess with the flavor in a distracting sort of way . i get the impression that i 'm missing some of the flavor due to the wild carbonation . the big downfall for me was the carbonation .

as soon i popped open the cap on the bomber , i could smell the aroma , and this came right out of the fridge . some sweet caramel malt shows up as the beer warms up further , but the hop aroma also improves nicely . taking a sip , some tropical fruit and citrus bitterness upfront , then a wash of caramel and bread malt finishes off the tongue . after such a nice aroma , i was slightly disappointed the flavor of the hops did n't play a bigger part in the taste , but still a good dipa . light to medium body with some nice gently prickly carbonation and lightly slick on the tongue .  m : light to moderate body with very little carbonation ( like a cask ) .
frothy head ! that 's pretty much the highlight of this one .  m : light body .

pours a crystal clear deep caramel color with red highlights and has a two finger head that lasts forever .  mouthfeel is a dissapopintment . with this much head , had little carbonation to feel and was also a bit watered down for my taste .

a - black with an enormous head that takes an eternity t fade and leaves thick webs of lacing everywhere on the glass . a mountain of head rests in the middle over still half an inch of head . very pretty .  mouthfeel is a little more thin than i would prefer .

the aroma is excellent , it smells like brown sugar , raisins , figs , cherries , belgian yeast , rum , ginger and some pepper . there 's also a bit of a bitter finish , which i did n't expect since the aroma was so sweet and malty .  medium carbonation and body . nose is the normal malty/hoppy-ness of a porter , starts malty and hoppy and finishes with a nice mostly malty bite . very fresh - brewed 12/13/03 . the abv is 4.5 % .

from notes 9/8/08 : einhorn beer company hefe vigorous pour into my hefe glass yields 2 fingers worth bananas , bananas , bananas good carbonation great nose mouth feel is a little thin , finish is thin left minimal lacing and zero head retention overall i would say , well balanced and a good example of the style . i still think it 's a good example of the style and a refreshing hefe .  holy crap , i think this is the first `` 1 '' i have ever given on taste for a brew . the only thing i can taste is friggin licorice and i hate licorice . this is a bad , bad brew , enough said .

s - grape and cherry permeate the aroma , possibly including some blueberry or tart apple . t - being a lover of wine , too , i immediately taste the tannic presence of the zinfandel . the cherry and tobacco notes from the zinfandel are appealing , however , and keep this from being a horrible score .  if you like pecan you will like this . s- a little too light weight for me .
this beer poured a beautiful , crystal clear cherry brown with little clumps of off white head the left behind a few spots of lace .  mouthfeel - average .
very minty aroma , with really nice accompanyments of herbs , earth , yeast , lemon , and hay - wow , what an unexpected combo ... .  mouthfeel was rather thin for a porter .

appearance : pours a clear amber body with a dense , lush off-white head .  however , you have few choices , this is most likely your cheapest option and most widely drank option . it wasnt terrible , but it just had no real good flavor . if i had a choice between coors light and this , i would have to choose the cheaper of the two , as they are about the same .
whoa ! crazy huge impossible head . looks good once you get it into the glass .  m : light to medium body with fairly high , rough carbonation . lively enough , but a bit unrefined .
amazing aroma ! like nothing i 've ever smelled in a beer .  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and an extremely dry finish .

pours a dark as night black from my `` bomber '' bottle . looks great .  smell the smoke , not overpowering and nice . this is a mild tasting smoke beer . recommended for those who find other overwhelming . this is something i could drink alot without geting tired of the smoky taste . seems like the lager styles are milder .

this beer pours a deep , deep amber color that glistens a rich and gorgeous mahogany when held to light . not as dark as i expected , i was pleasantly surprised with the look of this beer and spent nearly a minute admiring it before having a smell .  the mouthfeel is somewhat lacking , however . the lighter mouthfeel only makes this brew easier to drink .
nitro tap into pint glass a : tar black . the softest , tightest head i 've ever seen . beautiful .  it was listed as an imperial stout , but had a relatively light body for such a labeling .

750ml bottle opens with a pop , the deep black liquid pours into a chalice and generates a big amount of cascading foam . it 's surface is actually convex at first , and transitions in color as the liquid trickles through it . the cappucino tan head fades into a charred mahoghany tone closer to the liquid line . fantastic .  mouthfeel was a little lacking considering the initial sweetness .

a- this beer is a yeast hazed golden color with a moderate amount of carbonation rising to the top . the head is nice and white , and has a cloud like texture that is dense . the lacing is also excellent , with dense bubbly goodness clinging to the glass like nothing .  i found it very highly carbonatedalmost too carbonated ( prickly , carbonic qualities are a bit distracting ) .

appearance : pours a hazy orange caramel color with a huge 4 finger thick and creamy off-white head . a touch of sediment pools right on top of the billowy head . the head was so big it rose a full 2 fingers above the rim of the goblet . perfect head retention .  m : just a tiny bit heavier than what i would consider light bodied . wish it had a bit more carbonation , it just feels watery .

very dark appearance with a beautiful tan head . smelled like hazelnut , vanilla , and butterscotch candy . it was very tasty and could see this beer paired well with a desert like tiramisu or cheesecake .  first sip , light bodied brew with almost no carbonation , little watery texture but very crisp , and refreshing on this humid summer eve .

appearance & gt ; black like coffee . great lacing . the ipa is so dark , you 'd never recognize it ... in fact , deschutes calls it a new style `` cda '' -- - cascadian dark ale .  mouthfeel is highly carbonated , i feel a little less carbonation may showcase this beer a little better but overall this beer rocks , i 'm glad i got to try it !

nitro widget results in an absurdly creamy white head that looks and tastes like whipped cream . phenomenal lacing .  m- fairly light and refeshing feel . pretty smooth , but a little over carbonated for the style though .
smells like a beer should in a real classic beer smell that makes beer heritage proud .  feel is a little thin , flat and viscous .

definitively one of the better smelling ipas i 've had in awhile . overall : 4 great smelling beer , but the taste profile is more average to me .  m : a bit thin and watery ; smooth , but i prefer my hefes with a little more body .

s : pure cherry aroma , sweet , pie crust like malt ; this smells like a fresh baked cherry pie ! m : light-bodied , lightly carbonated , watery/lightly silky up front with a crisp , tart finish , wait for it ... like a cherry .  this beer is just flat out terrible . it smells like a loaf of bread soaking in a very bad pitcher of beer . flavor is sour with a hint of bitterness but just plain bad..the only thing i can say for davidson brothers at this point was this beer was not bottled by you it was bottled by shipyard brewing and hopefully they trashed it not you . i do not reccomend this beer to anyone , besides people who like budweiser because it might be slightly better than that .

the aroma is nothing short of phenomenal . the aroma is citrusy and spicey with a lot of fruits and a touch of barnyard funk that i have come to love in good saisons .  mouthfeel is a tad disappointing , not quite as slick , oily , or full as i would have preferred .

color is a rick dark red-brown with no cloudiness .  let me start this by saying that i love all of gl 's beers and appreciatte their quality and price . taste was more of the same with a surprising cooked spinach taste also . aftertaste was also quite disturbingleaving a lingering vegetable taste . i bought a sixer of this beer but could only stomach four of them . i do n't know if the beer intended to taste like this , but even gl makes a mistake every once in a while .
a : looks pretty impressive .  the same followed through to the taste , some malt , but again ruined by the corn . it is smooth , and with the light body it probably would n't be bad in the summer .
unbelievable retention , and perfect lacing .  m : light body , slight effervescence ... not much here .

the beer as it sets in my chalice a pitch-black with the head modest in size and the texture semi-creamy and the color a nice light chocolate color as it ever so slowly dissipates , the lace forms a concealing veil to hide the glass from view .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin , but the flavor makes up for it .

great lakes blackout stout ( 2006 release ) poured deep black topped by a thick mocha head and outstanding lacing .  claims to be be a no carb beer , better described as a no taste beer . almost clear in appearence . it was refreshing i give it that , and if it was really , really hot , it would be a plesant drinking experience , but if you actually want your beer to taste like beer , i 'd give it a miss . it seemed to have gone after the gimmick ( nop carbs ) rather than trying to produce a flavoursome beer . it 's a shame as i hear the rest of the burleigh range is okay .

s : surprised with the nose on this one . plenty of flaral hops . sweet malts in the foundation and a nice citrus zest to freshen it up . t : biscuity malts that were n't very sweet up front left it a little flat ( maybe just a let-down from the smell ) .  mouthfeel - medium body mouthfeel . a tad bit watery .

this one pours a clear copper with a huge nitro head that slowly settles into a finger 's of dense , creamy head .  this beer was an amber color with a thick white head that dissipated quickly . a nice fruity/spicy taste , with some warmth in the aftertaste . it was a little too fizzy for me , but still a very smooth and drinkable beer

a : pours a most pale straw hue , just slightly hazy ; fast growing , huge and tightly silky white froth ( exactly like a perfectly aerated capuccino head ) sustains brilliantly , supported by a lively carbonated body underneath .  m : medium bodied .
absolutely gorgeous .  mouthfeel : medium body , light carbonation .

2011 vintage a- pours a bright orange with a massive fluffy head , very tight bubbles , thick and sticky lacing all over the glass .  m : oily texture with average carbonation and a bitter finish . the mouthfeel is the weakest aspect of the beer .
a- pours a sunset orangey red hue with a nice , 2 finger frothy head which leaves a ton of lacing on the way down .  mouthfeel is okay , but not great .

s- instantly my nose is greeted with the odor of resiny pine and strong grapefruit . very hoppy to say the least . some bread in here too .  a : clean , dark brown/amber , no sediment s : malty , dark fruit , and caramel , t : well balanced bitterness , malty , thick syrupy , dark fruit and caramel , m : thick , smooth , lack of carbonation is the big detracting factor , d : as noted , we had two to make sure - the alcohol is subdued and we quickly finished both bottles ; it 's really that good .

a ) looks great ... deep dark black with a thick cocoa head .  quite honest and good mnchner beer . better than most of the german lagers , like warsteiner , lwenbru and bitburger . excellent taste , nice smell , very good appearance and drinkability . good balance among malt , yeast and hops . it worth a try , for sure .

poured a deep cloudy yellow , with a tall creamy head that dropped down to 1/8 ' lasting head with some lacing . man that 's a good looking beer .  lots of bitter orange , banana , even cinnamon in the taste , with smooth but underwhelming mouthfeel .

pours slightly cloudy golden orange color with 2 fingers of a dense off white head with incredible retention that reduces to a thick cap that lasts forever .  body is medium full , but the carbonation is quite low .
s : funky barnyard aromas up front , but it is not overwhelming . lots of subtle complexities in the nose . i love the nose , but the flavor is really bland .  mouthfeel is average .

amazing fruit nose . taste : surprisingly simple after such a complex nose . initially , some ever-so-slightly bready malts and some black pepper and pine resin . eminently quaffable .  m- medium body , goes down smooth . i was n't too impressed with the mouthfeel .

a- pours a hazy straw yellow with the whitest head of foam out there . literally , one of the most impressive looks for a dipa that is around s- lots going on here .  mouthfeel lacked continuity . good weight for a bpa though and a nice interpretation of the style .

deep-ass black , the darkest head ive seen yet , this just after drinking black tuesday and the abyss . pillowy too .  mouthfeel was a bit of a letdown . it seems the cask had been open for a little while , as the natural carbonation was quite weaker than other cask beers i 've had .

s - intriguing smell , quite unusual . honey , bread , licorice , bubblegum ( heaps ) , sweet liqueur , strawberry and various flower aromas . crazy ! o - just a wacky beer all over . aroma is simply amazing . overall though probably a little bit hardcore given the exceptionally high levels of carbonation and peculiar combination of tastes .  it 's light on the palate and slightly dry . i 'm not a huge fan of wheat beers but this one is really not to my liking .

bottle provided by chris , poured into a perfect pint glass ... a huge whoosh upon popping the cap . a light black with a huge dark tan head , great retention and lacing ... the aroma is sweet chocolate , oak , lactic acid , not a good balance , seems infected to me .  begins sweet , the top is skimpy in its mouth feel , with the finish delightful in its hop spicy bite and the carbonation perfectly matched , also the somewhat bitter and dry aftertaste makes it quite refreshing , quite the quaffable brew , and a new favorite .

s : intense aroma of freshly mowed grass with summer flowers and dandelions . t : over the top hops .  the only real knock on this beer is that the mouthfeel was a bit thin for an imperial stout , if it was more viscous it would be an a+ beer to me .

'' a - 3 finger merengue head sits on top a cloudy golden body and has excellent retention and beautiful belgian lace .  the mouthfeel , however , was watery for a porter , the body medium and the carbonation light . highly quaffable .

it had a very nice hoppy aroma that i could n't wait to try .  smelled of floral hops with a heavy alcohol presence . yeast and hops i guess ? hugely intense ( like a kick in the teeth ) flavor of hops and alcohol . sometimes the hop flavor won out , but mostly just alcohol . bummer . overall i was super dissapointed by the floaties and the overpowering alcohol presence .

this is one of the prettier light beers i have seen . mostly due to the huge thickness and creaminess of the head . the beer itself is crystal clear straw yellow with lots of carbonation bubbles .  but i do n't like ipa . there is flavor , but those damn hops just interfere too much . average feel , but i could n't even finish the sample .

a- poured with a 2 1/2 finger white cloud of foam into a tulip glass . beautiful orange blossom honey hue . minimal lacing , but head sticks around for a while .  m - pretty straightforward . average .

looked fantastic after the pour : a golden yellow-orange color with a big , white , fluffy head that bubbled down very slowly to a lace across the whole top of the beer .  on tap at the brewpub . creamy rich aroma of sweet sugary hops , full of lime juice , fresh grated ruby red grapefruit and a waft of fresh mountain pine . fantastic aroma . flavor is a pandoras box of fresh oranges , mandarins and tangerines , reduced and drizzled over a grainy bite of malt . a bit of that hop buttery note on the finish , with a long creamy smack of grass and cilantro . a touch of chewiness . long aftertaste of apples and bitter resin . a top ipa !

this beer looks great poured out of the bottle with a big billowy head and cloudy golden color .  herbal aromas with toasted grains , similar to a barleywine 's fermented sweetness . the taste is very sour , which builds in layers with each sip . outside of the sour , there is not much flavor except for a slight hint of malt . it is presented as a spring seasonal and it just does n't work , no matter what time of year .

an unusually nice looking beer .  m : very light and delicate mouthfeel . lighter body than i prefer , but it does not bother me whatsoever , all things considered . very slick , almost oily mouthfeel .

am going to sparks tomorrow , looking forward to another pint or two . it looks dark but has a light almost watery mouth feel .  loaded with fresh hops flavor , spicey , that good bitter smack finish . i used to prefer darker beers to american pale ales , but this beer is the one that changed my mind . this beer goes great with crawfish and pizza .
this smells amazing . vinegar coupled with cherries and other ripe to over-ripe fruits . d : this is a great flanders red .  mouthfeel is a little thin and watery .

bbd of oct 06 pours deep honey to amber color with pretty good clarity & a fluffy white head . great lacing & head retention smell : slight leather and fruit notes taste : citric & apricot notes , slight tea-like bitterness with dryness .  light carbonation , exactly what i expected from the appearance , not bad .

the 09 was awesome , the 10 was just good , the 11 was not seen painted ladies pumpkin 09 a 5 deep hazy amber with a beauty of a light beige head .  somewhat dry in the mouth , kind of the weak point of the beer .

a - clear amber , and with a hard pour i got an easy 4 fingers of off white head . retention is decent and a thick cap remains . very nice looking .  s-moderate , almost medium-light body , with a carbonation that at times seemed just a bit too much .

smells good , my kind of ipa .  fruits and booze , non-sweet tastes very sweet at first , but it dies down considerably , which is good . it has a syrupy feel at first , but that fades away too ... more carbonation would have been better .
this beer is absolutely beautiful .  mouthfeel is pretty average i guess , a bit on the thicker side , creamy carbonation .

appearance - the beer pours a dark brown/black colour with a very large frothy and rocky light brown coloured head . i ca n't see much carbonation due the darkness of the beer and there is very nice lacing running down the sides of the glass .  m- this beer felt sightly heavier than it was .

smell wonderful aroma of deep , rich malts . can they be both roasty and toasty ? this dark ale was an awesome nose . taste the taste didnt quite keep pace with the nose . the flavors are nice , but they didnt deliver on the aromatic promise . drinkability a nice attempt at an extremely difficult style .  the body is nothing special however . feels overcarbonated and lacks a nice texture .

s. pungent and tart as heckfire ! funky funk funk , leather , only the finest sweaty gym socks , vinegar , simply out of control ! this is possibly the most pungent , abrasively acidic beer i 've smelled . almost too intense . t. tart .  mouthfeel strikes as kinda light bodied .

the aroma was simply outstanding . it had a sweet hop presence which was citrus in nature ; however , i found it to be sweetly unique in that it resembled a pineapple moreso than orange or grapefruit .  the only fault here is that the mouthfeel is a bit too full for a pilsner . it is thick to the point it seems a bit flat even though there are abundant bubbles . only fault is the weird thickness to this .
the initial aroma of pumpkin and spices is pleasent , but not powerful .  mouthfeel : medium body with hardly any carbonation and a slightly slick finish .

a : pours a hazy golden-straw color with a couple fingers of incredibly dense bright white head that took forever to fade into a dense , thick film that left thick stripes of lacing down the glass .  light , sweet malt aroma ... very little hops . mouthfeel is to style but with an explosion of tiny bubbles .

a-dark orange color ... little head ( which normally i would be against but for ipa 's i actually enjoy ... yes i know the head releases boatloads of fun for most people but for me i do n't like it excessive so this is fine with me ) - s-big huge tropical fruits intermingled with some caramel notes ... .the tropical fruits are fantastic to smell ... i just sat and smelled this beer for about three minutes it was so enjoyable ... mangos , papaya , pineapple , oranges , sweet grapefruit , tangerines and then some peaches and apricots as well ... smells sweet rather than bitter ... .not terribly complex as the pine , tobacco and earthy notes are not evident but no complaints here ... i love a juicy tropical fruit laden dipa and that is what this is.- t-similar to the aroma ... same fruits just not as sweet on the taste ... hops begin to lend a blast of bitterness ... a splash of alcohol evident as well but it mixes nicely and adds some spiciness ... more bitter tasting than the nose led me to believe it would be ... . with 15 hop additions every 15 minutes i expected this to be bold , bitter , and flavorful ... .check ... .check ... check ... .  mouthfeel is thin , but not watery . nice carbonation .

a : pours a perfectly cloudy lemony-yellow with a full , two-finger off-white head .  pleasnt middle ale taste . smooth flavor and easy to drink.no unpleasant aftertaste which i dislike in an ale . generally speaking i prefer fairly strong ales and beers , but this one seems to be of decent quality without excessive hoppiness . recently discovered at a local beer discounter so further review may continue..

first time trying this beer ... i 'm always excited to try american makes of belgian ales , to see who has the real deal skills , but i 'm always leery too , because so few get it anywhere close to right . great funk in the nose . they nailed the nose , that 's the best part of this beer by far . yup , it 's unbalanced . it 's off by a good margin , the malt does n't come through that well and the hops kind of leave you feeling flat and sad .  feels light bodied with tons of carbonation .
poured from the bottle to a golden copper color , with thick off-white head that lingered through whole glass and then reduced to excellent lacing .  carbonated swallow is a tad sharp .
it has a perfect pilsner color .  this really could have been something with a little less carbonation .

rivals the clarity i 've seen from some very highly rated micro 's ! s - wow , dry hopped but very mild aroma - floral and citricy hops , bready malts .  the mouthfeel doesnt impress me . seems a bit thin and maybe chalky from time to time ... maybe from the hoppyness .

a huge blast of sweet citrus assaults the nose , orange rind and lemon . obviously hoppy , and the abv is given away by a trace of alcohol . that gives way on the swallow to a flavor reminding me of cheap gin , and then a half-gin/half-hop aftertaste lingers .  seemed thin in the mouthfeel with almost too much carbonation .

the smell is 90 % hop and 10 % malt . the hop smell is flower and one can almost distinguish the different kinds of hops , but my nose is n't experienced to tell you what they are .  m : light to moderate body and carbonation .
great retention and several sticky lace rings .  feel : the fizz i feel could be less . sips feel light , masked by carbonation .
i think this smells quite good . t - this tastes like a bad cola .  mouthfeel was a bit thin for my liking .

source , serving : draft , 33cl @ trappist smell : lively citrus , honey , yeast and cider , apple soda notes . all blend together with nothing dominating . oddly reminiscent of a zesty italian spritzer . taste : much deeper , darker fruit than you get in the nose . citrus oil and prominent caramel/honey malts come through at first and have an unusual depth which my guess is due to some barely perceptible citrusy hop oilyness and bitterness . definitely different than the refreshing , lively nature of the nose . in the middle its quite hoppy ( mostly grassy ) but has enough cariander/nutmeg and belgian yeastyness to keep it interesting .  and now i know why people say it tastes like chocolate syrup , because it kinda does . but this is really good if you like chocolate . probably 1200 calories in this bottle . but who 's drinking beer and watching calories ?

pours a hazed-copper with an inch of lingering creamy off-white head . lots of carbonation and thick concentric bands of lace .  m - this part is a bit underperforming , but only relative to the rest of its strengths ; it just does n't have the substantive feel that i want , but it has proper carbonation and relative weight .
courtesy of jrancan via gif 2.0 poured an orange-cooper color with a thick tannish head .  m : average carbonation and the hop bitterness sticks around .

appearance : a yellow / amber colored body topped off with a fluffy white head . the retenion was pretty good and the lacing was abundant .  founds this a bit too fizzy for the style , possibly overcarbonated , possibly i do n't know wtf i 'm talking about .

nice very uniformly hazy straw yellow body that is served with a 1/2 finger foamy white head . head has really good retention and lacing is left most of the way down the glass .  m : it feels light to medium bodied with high carbonation . rather smooth though .

pours about half a finger length of head atop a dark brown body with a red tinge when held up to the light . when the head is high , the legs are nice and thick as i tilt . my initial impression was this tastes awfully similar to a turbodog brown ( not sure if it 's the malts they are using ) .  mouthfeel/drinkability : mouthfeel is pretty medium bodied , a bit thin and not overly impressive for an ris .
pours a deep amber color with a really cool creamy head .  m - i would 've preferred a slightly more viscous feel .

from start ( awesome appearance due to the creamy head and lacing ) to finish ( great nutty aftertaste ) this was quite an enjoyable christmas evening treat !  i noticed to yeast in the bottom of the bottle after i read that it was bottle conditioned on the label . the malt comes through as i drink . there is the malt backbone with some hops . i guess i 'm just so used to ipa 's and dipa 's . this is a really drinkable beer .
when we finally opened it , it wafted aromas : stouty roasted malt , bourbon .  mouthfeel is a but flat .
smell is extremely nice with strong notes of ripe fruit , caramel , toffee , and toasted malt . very pleasant mixture .  mouthfeel- a little thin and soapy feeling .

this oktoberfest pours a very deep copper-red into my mug with a moderate white head that quickly diminished to thin skim but with a patchy lasting lace . i must say the color of this brew is truly something to marvel at , incredible dark copper-red with extreme brilliance .  mouthfeel is decent but a little slick .

s - chocolate milkshake , smoked meats , light roastiness .  poured from bottle to sniffer , looks like weak drip brewed coffee , ok head that diminished to a lace that stayed till the beer was gone . smelled of chocolate malts and coffee . the taste was that of black coffee with chocolate syrup added . i like this beer alot this is number five of six so drinkability is up there .

pours a deep dark brown with lighter hues on the edges . a creamy off white head from a hard pour goes from about an inch to a couple centimeter cap after a few minutes . retention is superb and lacing is superb as well .  peach / apricot on the nose with a bit of yeast , very interesting bouquet . a little taste of toffee/candy , again apricots , but not overwhelming . mild bitterness . very drinkable , very refreshing , i could see myself drinking this on a hot summer day ( unlike today ) , but nothing complex about it .
a : i love the look of this beer . nice head and great lacing .  m : i wish this beer had a bigger presence on the palate as the feel is too light and overcarbonated for the style .
lacing was excellent ; the glass was a history of every sip taken .  it was medium in body with moderate carbonation .

the nose is great . it 's been a while since i had a unibroue , but i never tire of their awesome yeast . clean , phenolic , very spicy , a little musty , a little wild , maybe souring milk , very rich with tropical fruit like mango and pineapple .  light mouthfeel , good session brew for this time of year .
12 oz bottle poured into a tulip tumbler . a cloudy dark brownish orange with a massive head .  one of the best winter warmers i 've had .

smells great . yeasty , malty , fruity - especially mango and citrus .  pours a thin , tan head , light brown/red coloring . aroma is a little hoppy but has a nice malt background . big hop flavor , small hints of toffee , but overall a nice maltiness . bitterness is on spot for an esb , as well as the floral marks . i 'd very much buy this again if i can find it .
this filtered masterpiece pours from the growler a golden hue with crazy lace and a beautiful head .  m : nothing to extremely special . a nice round fullness .

poured a dark dark brown with a super creamy light mocha head .  i found this beer to be a touch watery compared to other oatmeal stouts ( specifically b.o.r.i.s . ) , but overall a nice stout that convinced me to try other beers from anderson valley brewery .
smell of dry pine wood and chocolate and a lot of vanilla . the aromatic smell was enticing ! t : i would have expected this to taste a bit smoother than it did .  a medium body and a little thin .

rocky , tawny brown head atop dark body . color is a dark brown with red hints when held to the light . i wish most browns were this dark and i understand that my color bias is 100 % personal opinion .  by far my favorite pumpkin beer . actually taste like pumpkin pie and not beer with a hint of pumpkin like some other pumpkin beer . o'fallon 's is a distant second . have tried southern tier pumking , shipyard 's , lakefront pumpkin lager , post road , blue moon , jack 's pumpkin spice and imo it 's the best !
a jet black beer with lovely head that resembled the crema from espresso and a nose of a rich dark chocolate .  light bodied , this one is extremely drinkable .

fills an american pint glass perfectly with an full 2 inch head . a beauty to behold , a visually striking beer .  the mouthfeel is a bit on the light side , but maybe that contributes to its overwhelming drinkability .

the appearance of this beer is pretty cool , the nice cascading pour and the crisp golden color with a creamy white head .  at first the taste is disappointing , high carbonation seems to block out the taste of the beer , combined with a thin mouthfeel .
pours a gorgeous dark fire-ish glow . absolutly beautiful , with a nice head .  mouthfeel : not a lot of body , a little thin .
complex , hoppy nose : oily , piney , resiny .  m : full-bodied , slick , oily , and a bit resinous . there is no carbonation , so this ale remains still in the mouth .

great aromatic hops batman ! lord , that was weak but it just came out and now i 'm ashamed . one of the best smelling apas i can think of . well balanced , sizeable , and satisfying . my only neg would be that the nose promised more hops than the taste delivered . an excellent warm weather beer that remains satisfying . nicely done and very well balanced .  ha ha , funny guy ! for a macro that smells terrible , the taste is almost palatable . it still is n't good , but it 's not the road-kill skunk i recall . maybe it was the locales . or the company . not a good beer . at the risk of sounding snobbish , if my choice is old latrobe or apple juice , i 'll be happy to grab a cardboard container of juicy juice .
a- pours an amber tinted orange , kind of a stereotypical 'beer ' color .  medium mouthfeel and light diacetyl .

great smelling beer , really complicated , very impressive . taste is a sweet caramel but very light bodied , and much huge brown sugar on the palate .  mouthfeel : becomes somewhat flat and watery as it moves across the palate .

a : nice burnt hue to it ... dark amber with a touch of cloud nice fluffy white head that retreats unevenly and fast . tons of lacing and sticky sticky look to it .  the middle is a little thin , a little plain , with pepper and a little butter at temperature . sweet apples abound in an otherwise dry finish . apples and grains in the aftertaste . good .

the aroma is amazing and slightly unexpected . the flavor is just as exciting as the aroma . rich smooth roasted grains hit you up front , and soon you are enjoying the sweet caramel malt . tobacco and musty wood create a fantastic finish . the mouthfeel is creamy and smooth with subtle carbonation .  mouthfeel is a tad thin for my liking , but not so much as it is a problem .

the color saves the appearance which would otherwise be lacking because of the zero head factor s_beautifully sweet cherry aroma , marachino syrup t_strongly resembles a diet cherry soda . pure cherry , one dimensional m_mouth washing , extremely high carbonation -- too high d_hard to drink too many of because of the intense flavor and high carbonation  mouthfeel : a little thin on the palate , but otherwise felt good .

wow , this looks good ! thick , heavy poor , black like coffee . huge , robust head that takes ages to dissapate . dark caramel in color .  i wish this would be a bit softer in the mouth , a bit less sharp .
two fingered fluffy white head gathered at the top after an aggressive pour , almost like whip cream . left beautiful lacework on the glass as the beer was consumed .  mouthfeel is slightly thin .
served room temperature , this beer had a dense , whipped-cream head that took a half an hour to melt .  for the style it seemed light bodied and almost over-carbonated .
ok , maybe went to far there , bu tthe nose is really really good on this .  m : very light with little to no viscosity . tap was much better , but most likely force carbonated .

the nose hints at light sweetness , with big white pepper and spicy hops on a bed of hay . great , appetizing , enticing nose . on the palate , this beer is quite sweet , due to both malts and , it would seem to me , present alcohol .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh and overcarbonated .
pours a hazy murky yellow with a large rocky white head that retains well and laces the glass .  m : thinner than i was expecting ... .

pours a bright , pale amber with pilsner like highlights at the bottom of the glass . great two finger head that slow recedes to a vey thick foam with strong lacing , not too mention the bubbling .  m - a little like bodied for a stout , but still light and creamy .

once settled , the hat is a solid inch thick , and amazingly tightly packed . it 's like a solid mass of bisque white shaving cream .  lighter than expected on the palate . crisp . the low hop content ( 33 ibu ) is lost in the malt and alcohol . in fact its all malt and alcohol and a bit too cloying at that . i often wonder if some brewers actually taste their beers before they release them , because not only does this taste like one of my first homebrew bombs , but i agree holy jesus , what are these goddamn beers ?

this poured a hazy copper , big frothy head , that left puffs of lacing all the way down , smell was of raisins and fruit , taste was light fruity and tangy , mouthfeel is light and slightly tart , and highly carbonated , drinkability is fantastic , just another fine product from ommegang .  i felt that it was easy to drink and lives up the the quality of beer that sn makes mouthfeel : thin but not too think .

the is a aroma of is sweet and rich , a mix of almond , maple syrup , raisins , nutmeg and alcohol . the taste was mainly malty and less complex then the aroma , with more emphisis on the alcohol , and the finish somewhat balanced by the bittering hops , but not enough for you to forget the +8 % abv .  delicious and refreshing , a bit too thick for my tastes .

pours almost jet black , with crystal clear dark brown at the edges , forms a nice meringue like 1/8 '' head of very fine dark tan bubbles .  it was watery with some carbonation and a slightly bitter aftertaste .
i loved the smell , the bouquet .  mouthfeel is ok. a bit too lean on the finish , but still decent .

good complex aroma , very pleasing . a bit abrasive , nothing like the nice pleasing aroma would indicate .  nice clear beer . they filter well at this brewery . the taste is caramel notes finishing with hops on the tongue . is this a winter warmer asks the alstrom brothers ? i think not . a drinkable red ale that delivers the goods .

nice 1 inch foam has great retention and leaves lots of lacing smell - floral and citrus hop smell .  m : a little too thin , but passable for a nut brown ale d : good , complex flavor , nothing overwhelming , but it feels like something 's missing .

the pour was pitch black with a good two finger head that dissapated to a light ring on top of the beer .  there is n't much to the feel of this beer , it 's light bodied , but smooth and pleasant so i have trouble scoring this higher than average .

frickin ' a beautiful . i shit you not . dark and rich and black and medium dark head of tiny bubbles that lasts forever . not ridiculously thick and certainly not thin and they really must have worked at this . beautiful .  m - just a touch thin but the carbonation is fine .
s -- loads of chocolate , roast nuts t -- sweet roasted malt , chocolate finish .  average mouthful , good taste , maybe some caramel flavor to it , easy to drink several as a session beer .

a - gorgeous burnt orange colors , creamy white head s - i have a cold , hard to tell , but not too powerful aroma .  smell : coffee , roasted barley taste : coffee , roasted barley again , maybe some chocolate too mouthfeel : weird carbonation ; real small bubbles throughout drinkability : light bodied , you can have many in one night

smell : hops , hops , and more hops . extremely citrusy , grapefruity , and spicy alcohol notes . it had that green intense hop aroma . taste : extremely malty , very thick and sweet .  the mouthfeel is maybe a tad thin for my liking , but drinkability is good .

it has a very complex rich smell . there are notes of dark fruit mixed in with some sugary smells . the aroma makes me very intrigued about what is next .  i find this to be a very clean tasting beer with good thin mouthfeel .

the head is a fluffy inch thick and seems to have flowing currents through it from the carbonation jets that stream all along the edges of the tulip glass , creating a brilliant trail in the beer .  feels very light in the mouth , not creamy enough .

pours a rich black color with a gorgeous white and creamy , foamy head that just sits on top and waits , and waits and remains clinging to the bottom of the pint glass even when it is gone . plenty of lacing sticks around as well , and the foamy head is present at every sip .  mouth feel is exceptionally carbonated almost to the point of obstructing the flavor .
pours a near black with two fingers of head and some webby lacing .  taste was good , mouthfeel a little thin , drinkability fine .
the head is a huge 4 '' + , off-white , great retention and plenty of lace .  mouthfeel is light and carbonated .

a= pours a nice dark brown with some extremely dark red highlights and a beautiful two finger beige head that 's thick and creamy with great retention and lacing .  taste/mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is oddly thin and the carbonation , while crisp up front , is weak at best -- that 's not good .

nice strong scents , banana and cloves , wonderfully spicey ! sasafrass , fresh ginger even maybe ? nice and malty , just slightly dark . there is a hit of sasafrass and a lot of nice clove in the finish , even a bit of a clove tingle on the tongue -i like that and have always loved the taste of clove .  been wanting to try this for quite a while ... went to boondoggles and they knew nothing ... lacing is extraordinary , low head but very stable and crazy good foam .. smug ? ... is a rich golden colour ... nice bitters ... a good beer , did n't quite meshing with the others.. another great brew from real ale..

s : amazing sweet caramel malt , floral hops , whiskey and an earthy , woody quality . t : a hoppy , caramel body is surrounded by less than subtle hints of bourbon whiskey and oak .  mouthfeel medium , if a bit light and strongly carbonated .

presented with an incredibly luscious foamy mocha-colored head and generous belgian lacing ( unfortunately , this was the best part ) throughout the tasting .  very little lacing , needs more carbonation and a bit too thin on mouthfeel , but very drinkable , and an excellent value as well .

bottle into a tulip glass . a : opaque black color with over two fingers of beige foam head . heavy lacing remains on the glass .  mouthfeel - medium and refreshing drinkability - i could definitely drink two or three , but that 's would probably be eenough
exquisite . the taste follows and reminded me of the first great cup of flavored coffee i 've ever had in my life .  mouthfeel - very carbonated , light .

a - this beer stands out in how it looks . very tall fluffy head with good atop a cloudy dark golden body , with great sticky lacing . looked great in the schneider weizen glass as well .  mouthfeel is good but not good .

smell - hello bourbon , i was told this spent 2 years in the barrel , and it certainly smells that way . wonderful notes of bourbon , vanilla , and dark ripe fruits . taste - fantastic brew , the bourbon is very present upfront along with dark sweet rasins , dates and figs and great caramely malts . very sweet . mouthfeel - smooth and velvety with little or almost no carbonation .  this brew is a bit thin otherwise .
absolutely huge head , beautiful ruby color glowing with orange and scarlet highlights .  body is medium and carbonation is very active..a bit too active for me .
beer pours a dark golden color with lots of bubbles . head is very sticky with a good lace .  the mouthfeel is thus fairly thin , but finishes with a nice clean dryness .

smells quite nice t : the front is sweet with cherries and grapes , this gives way to a bitterness in the middle which seems out of balance with the delicate sweet flavors on the front .  on the palate the beer feels light and thing , and a subtle malt flavor yields to a building , albeit , not overpowering bitterness that is highly drinkable but nothing special .

i 'm impressed . taste = good malt flavor , a little bland in other departments .  the flavor is malty and fruity with an emphasis on bananas and citrus . the palate is typical of the style . the aftertaste is bread like and a little sweet but fairly dry for a hefe .
beautiful looking beer .  very light mouthfeel , but spritzy .
appearance is used motor oil black , with a frothy long lasting head that looks like chocolate milk with a touch of coffee color .  mouthfeel was just ok though .

s - a great smelling brew . huge sweet malt aroma with spicy hops .  aroma of chocolate malts , coffee , mild hops . starts with a creamy chocolate and coffee taste . finishing light to medium body with hop bitterness .
moderate carbonation . a- deep , dark orangeish brown with tan head .  m : do n't exactly know how to judge mouthfeel yet either but i promise to work on it .

poured from a bomber into a perfect pint a- pours a really nice shade of amber with a real puffy three finger offwhite head . lacing is stellar as you 'd expect from rogue s- nothing .  m - high carbonation and medium to full body .

appearance - pours a pleasant red amber into a pils glass . 2 fingers of thick , rocky , beige head . taste - a good tasting roasted malt flavor , more than you would think considering the color has an amber shade , it does n't really appear capable of delivering such a warm roasty flavor .  mouthfeel is tingly , aftertaste is of chocolate and hops .

the colour is deep red-orange-amber ; the liquid is a little hazy . the two finger head is warm white and compact with a fine uneven surface . it sinks slowly leaving massive amounts of lacing .  mouthfeel : too smooth drinkability : great .

a : pours a three finger tan colour head . excellent thickness . the head is perfect , delicate , and soft . the retention is incredible for the high abv ; i 'd estimate about ten minutes . colour is a solid nontransparent black .  ) different malts , so that explains that ) mouthfeel - this beer is a bit on the watery side .

smell is really strong and nice . very close to mountain dew . tastes rather light for a belgian tripel but very complex . after reading the bottle i can detect the presence of oats and wheat .  but i ca n't ... the carbonation is out of control and really thins out the body . the mouthfeel is crisp and dry .

s - heavenly . i smell the sweet malts , and fruit flavors such as apricot and raisons . t - good , but not as good as the smell . but nothing that blows you away . d - it 's good , but not good enough to drop another 10 spot on a bomber . but i do n't mind contributing $ towards rebuilding the theatre where i have had so many tasty terrapins .  it had a medium mouthfeel , which was nice , but the taste was a combination of perfume , bubble gum and cereal . the finish was dry , but it left a lingering taste of cereal in my mouth .

clear , sparkling yellow with a bright , white head that slumps around the perimeter , sheeting the glass with lace and leaving a mesa of foam standing tall in the middle . streaming carbonation props up the persistant head .  m - mouthfeel is where this beer is lacking for me .
the aroma is wonderful . yeast and malts with the characteristic belgian spiciness .  m : light-medium with avg carbonation .

pours a beautiful bronze colour , with a firm foamy head ... smell is very fresh and soury ... taste goes into caramelized apples , a bit of wild cherries , very sweet and very sour ... .  this beer was extremely disappointing . neither toasty , nor full bodied . i expected the sense of fall in germany , but instead ... it tastes more like a pilsner . there is little depth and complexity to the beer , although it is very drinkable as it has a nice , crisp aftertaste . ... especially from a beer brewed in munich [ home of oktoberfest itself ] .

unfortunately , the beautiful aroma is the best thing about this beer .  mouthfeel is spritzy in its carbonation and aggressive across the top of the palate , which seems to collide with the inherently thick body and expected smoothness of a big stout .
it 's opaque as can be ; the head is large , chunky , and tan colored .  this beer is pretty complex but overall the feel is a bit thin and the flavor a bit too roasty for my preference .
the cascading effect was amazing ... but that 's where the amazement ends .  the mouthfeel is weak similar to others in class .

very malty aroma hit me as soon as i popped the top on this bad boy . the wonderful malty smell hits you fallowed by a light hops .  poured from a 12 oz bottle into a imperial pint glass . has notes of citrus and pine hops plus some apricot hints in there too . first taste it has upfront hop taste like a 90 minute ipa with a smooth fruity taste on the finish . this beer is a very refreshing ipa with a not to much fruit back but just enough to make it refreshing .

dynamite hoppy aroma . grassy , floral notes at first , but sweeter elements of grapefruit , peach , and pineapple come out more as the beer warms . finishes very hoppy with an oily bitterness and the barest hints of sweet fruits . medium carbonation and a decent drinkability , though the palate 's ruined for anything else .  m- carbonation is on the low side for an ipa , thin body .

a : pours a beautiful head that lasts forever - 3 fingers and leaves a great skim across the top during the entire session . cloudy orange in appearance s : nose is a bit weaker than i hoped - citrus , hops , malt t : taste is quite bitter - makes you pucker up and has a lot of citrus rind flavor .  mouthfeel : very carbonated , the amount of sugar can be felt on the tounge .

hazy golden with a hotd type of generous white head . lacing is top notch , rocky , it 's a battlefield to admire as it diminishes a bit .  the mouthfeel is nice , it 's well-carbonated and prickly on the mouthfeel .

s- this aroma is really nice . it hits you right off the bat with a wall of tropical fruits .  the carbonation was much too high for the style ( seems to be a trend with australian versions of british beers ) but the remainder of the mouthfeel was okay . would make a great session beer at 3.8 % abv and packed with plenty of flavour .

1 inch head , great lace and retention s-big malty aroma , there all here and then some . carmel , simple syrup , biscuit , bready , brown sugar , dried fruit , tropical dried fruit . quite a complex malt profile . hops are not as big in the nose .  thin mouthfeel , just washes around in your mouth - i was hoping for big and beefy , but at least it makes for good drinkablity , this could be a session beer .

there 's a sharp blast of booze in the nostrils comprised of bourbon , vanilla extract , banana and some raisin , though not as much as the quad , it 's close cousin .  m : thinner side of medium in body , carbonation is medium as well but falls off fast .

s - as hoped , the pumpkin smell is very prominent , with some clove or allspice in the back . it pretty much smells like a pumpkin pie ... with malts . you have to let it sit a bit before the other flavors that you 're getting with the smells really open up . pumpkin is certainly present , although not as much as i 'd hoped , but the clove and ginger kind of make up for it .  m-a bit more carbonated than i expected . body is medium , nothing special here . the carbonation makes it a bit filling . very good beer overall .

s : strong , roasted barley predominant , toasted nuts as well t : syrupy , quite a bit of alcohol in the flavour as well -- a bit too much for my liking m : thick and rich d : while enjoyable , this was slightly less appealing .  the mouthfeel is medium with sharp bubbly champagne-like carbonation .
sweet & malty chocolate smell . very inviting . the taste is very satisfying .  mouthfeel is a tad thin , and contributions in body and mouthfeel from the oats are n't noticeable .
this one poured pitch black with a 2 '' creamy , off-white head and some of the best lacy sheeting i 've seen in awhile .  carbonation was appropriate , maybe just a tad too sticky in the feel .
s : a pleasant though not strong toasted malt aroma predominates . this is a really nice aroma . t : toasted malt flavor .  light carbonation .

aroma was a very strong mix of sweet malty toffee and raisins . the only drawback to this beer was the watery and almost metallic finish , whicnh led to a poor finish of an otherwise very enjoyable beer .  great complexity of flavors m : average medium to light body . its a good feel .

a- deep rusty dirty copper color with a gorgeous wrinkly sticky cap of beige foam . lace is freakin everywhere , coating the glass like like a thin covering of new fallen snow .  a - light and cloudy like a thick fruit juice , small head with little to no lacing s - sweet and pleasant t - refreshingly sour , a little thin at the end but a pleasant bitter flavor helps to hide it m - slightly over-carbonated and thin d - very refreshing , easy to drink , would be a great session beer on a hot day or while tailgating .

s : very sweet chocolate , brownie mix mostly , some espresso , smells exactly like espresso brownies . l : very dark brown , ruby highlights , light tan head that dissipates , light dusting on top .  creamy on the palate , perhaps a bit too heated for mass consumption , but overall quite well done .

beautifully clear light golden hue , perhaps from fining and / or filtration . sticky , thin , tight head leaves intricate lace . beautiful in appearance , but lackluster otherwise .  m : mouthfeel is really where this beer takes a hit .

a - totally black in appearance with no light showing through . fantastic retention and thick , foamy lacing is left . perfect appearance .  imitation maple . : ( there are good qualities in the taste and smell ; this would be a pretty good brown ale if it were not for the flavoring . the same goes for the overall feeling for this beer it would be an ok beer with some good qualities if it were not for the awful fake flavor .
a : very beautiful . i love the nitro head on a non stout .  `` you will get some hop burps from this one '' mouthfeel a bit on the light side , with a tangy carbonation spike .

huge fruity hops scent hits you in the face . lots of grapefruit and other citrus scents . taste- ummm , mind ale this is not . mouthfeel- damn this one had the great flavor , but it was really watery . not to the point of being bad , but it would have been so much better , maybe even a `` 5 '' taste better if it had just a bit more backbone . drinkability- even with the watery aspect , it 's still a very good beer that i would definitely buy again in the future .  had 2 drafts of this beautious brew at `` point brugge cafe '' in the point breeze section of pittsburgh yesterday for brunch ... a surprisingly light yellow/straw color for what is usually an amber beer ... ( mind you , i 've just been to the penn brewery o-fest where their o-fest is a definite amber hue ... ) really impressive fine foam head ( a la nitrogen charged beers ... ) i love that .. really love it ... lends to better taste ... a quintessential marzen i feel ... malty germanic goodness with slight citrusy essence in the mid-palate and a nice clean finish ... the 6 % abv is apparent as i felt nice after 2 drafts ! @ girlfriend and i are going to get a case of this in the bottles for this weekend , we 're that impressed ... although i know i 'm in for a big disappointment with the bottled version ... bottled beer never as good as kegged versions ... . : ( session beer to the extreme ... . !

appearance : jet black and opaque ; nice brown head with tight bubbles smell : a little too non-descript for a stout taste : a little bitter and chemical tasting ... no coffee , chocolate , etc .  m : a bit light - almost watery .

s - very strong aroma ... can smell it when the glass is sitting on the table . also a pretty good alcohol aroma in the background .  mouthfeel is nice . carbonation is just a bit above medium level and a bit too high . nice above average body .

it is golden and pale , and rich in color , the head meets the top of the pint , and does not rush away the smell is perhaps the best smell on a beer i have ever had ! the hops meet the smell of freshness and make your lips stretch into a smile before you have even tasted the beer !  i love kolsch , but this one does n't quite add up . clean on the palate with a pleasant herbal dryness . finish is rather short but crisp . still very refreshing and thirst quenching , but that is to be expected from probably any example of the style . good to see another addition to the domestic kolsch list but this one is miles behind pyramid curve ball and others .

pours out to a hazy caramel-amber , forming a tall light beige head with excellent retention and nice sheets of lacing . the carbonation is moderate .  m : a little watery , but i do prefer thicker drinks .

beautiful blackish brown with ruby highlights and a thick , creamy tan head with some nice lacing .  ponderosa ipa . let me start this review with a nod to the brewewrs for keeping an ipa on tap at all times . average is the best blanket statement . but an average ipa is better than most mass-marketed beers . and by average i do n't want you to think it is n't good . i have seen many people try it and realize that an ipa ( and hops in general ) do n't have to be intimidating . but hopheads looking for the holy grail of ipa 's will have to keep searching ... consistant brewing is what pbc has always offered .

s : the best smelling dipa out there . just fantastic . the taste is a bit of a letdown after the smell , but still a fantastic beer . this is a wonderful dipa when fresh . fantastic aroma and taste , very drinkable and amazing for the price as compared to the other top in the style .  very light mouthfeel .

matilda pours a lovely orange amber color that glows nicely when held up to a light source . it is just slightly cloudy with an amazing frothy white head that leaves killer lace .  the mouthfeel is ok does n't really stick to your mouth , but the taste lastes awhile .

actually a really nice looking beer . thick , creamy 2 finger head forms in my tulip glass . lots of clinging lacing here . beautiful looking beer , but looses a bit in the flavor department .  adequate carbonation ... decent drinkability , more a sipper than something you 'd want a few of , but a beer i 'll definitely seek out again ( especially considering its very reasonable price ) .
really a great smelling beer that jumps out from feet away .  lighter in body .
this lager poured a deep , clear red with a decent head that left a nice amount of lacing clinging to the glass .  a little lighter in the mouth than i would like .

pours extremely cloudy . a beautiful lemon juice color that looks almost white at the edges .  the mouthfeel was extremely creamy since it was a nitro tap but i think it could have used a little bit more carbonation .

the beer poured a crystal clear deep amber with an off-white to tan head that rose tall and fell slowly to lace the glass .  i like a good lambic and a good sour , but this was way beyond anything i 've ever tried before . worst beer i 've ever tried .

appearance : one finger head that dimishes quickly with a nice deep dark reddish brown body smell : loads of sour cherries and funky oak taste : very tart/sour cherries which makes your mouth pucker . also you get a nice malty and funky backbone on this brew which compeletly hides the alcohol .  taste , the same except with raspberry syrup added . has an unpleasant twang . i dont believe i would even take one for free . well not if there was any other option available that is .

a- cloudy orange hue with an absolutely massive whipped cream head that goes on for miles . breathtaking to look at in a duvel glass ( imagine that ! ) s- smells of belgian yeast , sweet grains and some slight indistinct fruits .  mouthfeel suffers as a result .

s : citrus , specifically lemon are noticeable at first , and this beer brings the funk smell . the nose is seriously the best part about this beer . smells like it 's going to be great . t : starts off with sourness and tartness , feels like this is going to be a great beer , and then a second later the let down happens quick .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with sharp carbonation .
this smells incredible . smells just like thier red barn but with more sweet belgum yiests .  the mouthfeel was light but with heavy heavy carbonation .
bottle poured into a tulip glass . very dark but seems moderately clear . fairly large light tannish head with some nice lacing .  it may be a bit too carbonated , though .
amazing retention and lacing .  the body is surprisingly and disappointingly thin for such an otherwise huge beer .

appearance is crystal clear and orangeish with a thick , bright white head .  the mouthfeel came off a little light and felt a bit watered down . the initial aroma was very pleasing and my only real complaint about this one was the mouthfeel being a little too light .
s-really aromatic citrus hops ( orange , and tangerine ) with the slightest hint of caramel malt .  mouthfeel could be better , severely low carbonation .
aroma : a rum soaked raisin/plum nose . strong bouquet . some oak and alcohol smells too .  the texture was thick , and left a thin film in my mouth almost like when you eat too much syrup .

the beer pours out a beautiful slightly cloudy golden yellow tinged with apricot . the monstrous , rocky , snow white head seems to challenge the effects of time and easily lasts until the very last sip , leaving hefty clumps of foam sticking to the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel light body with a bit of carbonation .

a - a clear , amber body , topped with a finger and a half of off white head . if nothing else , it its an unusually good looking beer .  mouthfeel was somewhat effervescent but that was the only thing average about the beer .

12oz bottle dark brown with autumnal plum highlights . leaves a pillowy cap of dreamy , cloud-like head on top . thick as balls and no joke .  the mouthfeel was lacking , i was hoping for a heavier beer , but this medium light feel was ok .

it pours a nice dark chesnut brown with a finger plus of eggshell colored head consisting of large bubbles below a tight , creamy topping . plenty of carbonation and a medium plus body .  m. disappointing that there was n't much head and carbonation . tastes almost flat .

smells wonderful . t - tastes like it smells , but not quite as sweet .  poured from a 750 to a sierra nevada hop etched glass . good to see that haze in a commercial beer , makes me feel better about my homebrew not being super clear . big citrus in the nose , grapefruit and orange predominant among those smells . the malt is more hidden in the background than in the regular 90min , and the is a bit of booze smell in there as well . despite the hop aroma , it is not at all overly bitter tasting . curacao in the citrus flavor , with a bit of almost orange rind bitter at the end .

nose is a heavenly mix of bourbon like oak , vanilla , tannins , and the hops that make the regular ab what it is . unfortunately , the oak really does not come out in the taste . all i really get is your typical arrogant bastard taste , the harsh bitterness from their hops , and some malt . i am a bit disappointed in the taste .  the palate is thin but acceptable .

fantastic , my favorite part of this beer .  nice clean alcohol as it warms or as i feel it ... not sure which is having that effect on the taste : -/ dry , mildly carbonated and very much the viscosity of water .

color was a very beautiful amber with mahogany highlights .  nose is malt and honey , some gentle spiciness , licorice . quite nice . taste is malty and pleasantly sweet . finishes up with a subtle , dty licorice flavour . good as a one off . too sweet to drink a ton of , but interesting enough to be worth a try .
s : i have to say , the smell is divine . but still , so wonderful ... vanilla , toffee , a hint of bourbon .  m : the body is quite light for the strength . less carbonation would help .

from a 750ml crown top bottle . very dark ale with a beige head , with a good head retention .  it is very carbonated with lots of bubbles coming up throughout . my other major complaint is that the beer itself is a light in feel , i want it a little more robust . overall , this is very good and reminds me a lot of insanely bad elf . a highly drinkable winter ale that packs a great alcohol punch . needs a little tweaking on the feel and to give the aroma some oompf but so close .

initially very sweet , sugary , and syrupy smell . however , after a moment a robust and roasty smell dominates . the taste of this beer is superbly solid .  mouthfeel- a little syrupy , with some sand.. drinkability- not coors light . gulp gulp , ph

tan head over an encouragingly dark beer . it has one of the finest smells from a porter : dark fruits , a hint of chocolate , smokiness , and dark malts . licking some of the head , it actually tastes like smoke .  medium bodied very average to little carbonation .

pours an exceptional dark brown/ruby color with a huge tan head that last all the way down and a great cligning lace as well .  deep dark brown color with sweet chocolate aroma , the prominent caramel sweet roast flavors make up for a lighter body than most stouts .

from memory ... a : muddy black , supple tan head that left some great lacing and a moderate cap throughout the tasting .  lots of different flavors coming through beer is way over carbonated which messes up the smoothness . flavors were great , smelled good , looked nice , but the carbonation was my only problem .
the aromas from this beer are very nice . it has subtle scents that are fruity while the hops are very present .  mouthfeel is mild with little carbonation .

very fresh , great smelling beer ( i suppose it helps that the brewery is less than an hour away ! ) t - the sweetness of hops and malt greet the palate .  smooth feel but i thought the body was a little too light .

this one is n't for anyone but the biggest hop fans . the ending was a little bit too bitter for my tastes , but it was definitely a fine brew . i drank it standalone , big mistake . when i open the last bottle today , it will be with food ; i imagine something complimentary will make this out of this world !  it truly does hold that `` summer-time '' feel . the pour produced a nice rich white head which lasted for quite sometime . as it drank down , the lacing left just a soft amount on the glass , but it 's to be expected from this wheat beer . i would recommend this to anyone looking for a nice , clean , and refreshing evening beer to accompany good `` porch-sitting weather '' of the summer months .

it smells very nice with honey and pear taking the lead .  loads of caramel and toffee with some bready malt detectable . there is also a slight alcohol note . overall this beer was decent but not one of my favorites . just a bit too sweet .
great look overall .  thin malt backbone . carbonation is relatively high .

s-complex multi-layered aromas : fruit notes including raspberry , fig , date ; chocolate ; roasty/burnt malty backbone w/hint of sourness that complements the blend of dark fruit and sweet malt . could smell this all day . t & m-light sourness and fruitiness upfront that opens up to a malty backbone midway that is balanced by a sweet/sour/burnt sensation . d-shocked me initially since i was n't expecting the style on the first sip , but it is quite good , refreshing , and even sessionable .  m - medium bodied with a medium carbonation level . lighter on the tongue than i expected .

central waters bourbon barrel barleywine pours a completely opaque mahogany , with a towering pile of light tan foam sitting atop the beer . it legitimately took five mininutes for the foam to recede , and leaves gobs and gobs of lacing down the side of the glass .  malty , slightly bitter ... a good sort of bitter mouth feel.. medium carbonation . thin to medium body .
perfect appearence , evidence of the natural nature . glorious head and dark brown color .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery for a brown ale .

love the color ... , nice dark cherry red color with a thin tan head , little carbonation . the only negative ( and this is coming from my wife , who usually does not sample beer ) pertained to the orgy art work on the beer case .  served from a 2 liter flip top bottle bought at the brewery , poured into a pint glass bought from the brewery . light amber color in glass , hazy finish . big head that dissipated quickly , little lacing on glass . light aroma of citrus on pour . went down quickly , i was surprised how fast i finished the first pint . a typical wheat , but a good pint none the less .

smells like a bag of freshly opened tropical skittles . probably the most citric smelling beer ive ever had . good beer , not great . becomes a bit cloying and tough to finish near the end .  the mouth-feel was not great as the beer seemed a little thin .

lacing is excellent and head retention is very good . looks great .  awesome job with this one , not quite as risky as i would have liked , but very unique flavors m - very light , extremely easy to go down . could be improved , very carbonated and bubbly d - outstanding , once you get over it being over carbonated the true flavor comes bounding out of all corners leaving no rock unturned .

having said that , this is a very attractive looking beer . as good for appearance as an am .  surprisingly light body , dry but a bit fizzy mouthfeel - this makes the beer seem lighter than it really is ...

still an outstanding looking beer , almost like some food stylists created it in a lab .  the hop aroma lays , subtly there in the background t : cocoa , toasted nuts hints of earthy bitterness that make this a very well balanced brew m : medium bodied beer with average carbonation overall , this is a good sessionable beer , i think ill get this again

smells absolutely divine : complex sweet and tropical fruitiness , with a nice spiciness and gentle yeastiness . exceptionally refreshing .  the flavor is nicely malty in addition to the rest , but the body is significantly thinner than that of its bigger brother , the 10 .
nice dark pour . sticky carbonation that peppered the glass from top to bottom . very dark mahogany brown in color .  sufficient carbonation , low effervesence , medium-bodied , but a bit oily .

thick head lasts very nicely , with tons of sticky lacing .  probably the only product bells makes that i dislike . it smelled like chocolate covered cherries , very delicious . but the taste , whoa step back . bitter and thick as hell with an overwhelming cherry taste ( and aftertaste ) . good lord this crap is bad .

overall i thought this was a very good beer with a nose that is simply phenomenal - an almost perfect balance between smokiness , roasted malts , and unsweetened chocolate .  mouthfeel was unexceptional .

the grapefruit and honey melange in the notice is exquisite , and unique enough , particularly for the style . wow , the honey is real powerful here , almost masking the hops and alcohol both , which would otherwise seem difficult to do . the booze is understated but does still take a toll if you do n't sip .  more sweet than sour ; it has a predominant taste of cherry m - does n't linger as much as other , imo , more complex sours/lambics .

had on tap at cock and bull served in a franziskaner pilsner style glass . a- light golden body with a solid bright white head that settles to a thick film on top of the beer . soapy lacing covers the glass . hazy and bright , great hefe .  mouthfeel ... keeping in mind it was brief was ok but drinkability was awful , i could not finish the bottle and poured the rest down the drain , i think my taste buds are ruined for the day .

poured from a bomber bottle app- bright , bright red with a lacy white head sm- tart cherries and that 's about it .  mf : light body , medium carbonation o : tasty , well balanced and easy drinking .

there is the ever present hop haze from the all the hops in this beer . s - amazing hop aroma as soon as the bottle is opened ! just amazing aroma on this one ! t - very similar to the aroma . very bitter at the front of the mouth with a mixture of peach and grapefruit notes . a very well balanced beer ! m - great malt backbone makes this one have the perfect mouthfeel mixed with the cleansing ability of the hops . this beer is 8 % and that can really sneak up on you !  unfortunately the mouth was just a bit too thin and too carbonated for my liking .

the beer smelled great , very spicy very fallish .  the aroma is very sweet from the malts and the hops is sweet as well . for flavor the malt is sweet just like you would think from the aroma . the hops is a solid bitternes as if you were drinking an esb . over all this beer is very tasty .

a : the head on this thing is crazy huge . it 's tan and creamy like the head of a rootbeer float poured directly over ice cream . the beer itself is black and very dark brown at the bottom of the glass . lacing is immense , and does not back down while drinking .  m : crisp and light , on the watery side of things . smooth and refereshing .

the beer itself is an amber-golden color ... lots of bubbles from the pour and some nice cloudiness . rich creamy white head ... looks like a fantastic beer ! this one has a maltier smell than the real ale pale ale ... maybe even a little towards the malt side of the malt/hops balance for this one .  m- the mouth is light to medium bodied , which is a sin in my book for a stout . lively carbonation .

a- an inch thick bubbley tan head on a pretty clear dark ruby body . there are a ton of dubbels out there that blow this one out of the water .  the mouthfeel for me is the only downside for this beer .
the deep amber color is impressive . it carried the fluffy , bubbly small head of a beer from a cask .  m - feels medium-light , crisp , but just way over carbonated .

what a beautiful looking beer !  lightly bodied and over attenuated , with a lanky mouthfeel that could use additional girth . a tasty doppel , although it falls a bit short on complexity and body . drier than most , for sure .
poured a beautiful dark color with a creamy head that lasted the entire time .  mouthfeel was a bit of a letdown- on the thin side and made the beer seem less substantial .

s - green apples , raisons , anise , good amount of hops , booze , faint chocolate , butterscotch , toffee . t - grapes , juicy hops , prunes , licorice , light brown sugar , toffee , raisons , chocolate malt .  rich aqueous body with virtually no carbonation ( i wonder if that 's intentional ? ) , but this beer pulls it off like few could . as drinkable as such a rich beer could be , though arguably a carbonation presence would improve things .
aroma is very inviting . taste : smooth and wheatish .  seems a bit thin , shame , because i really like this brew . the carbonation is good just seems that it is watery .
heavily carbonated , and pours a creamy two-finger head that is persistent . leaves excellent lacing .  m : medium body , lots of prickly carbonation . a little too prickly .

clear reddish-amber in color with a creamy off-white head that leaves some foam sitting on top of the beer and awesome lacing . lucky for this beer , appearance is 20 % on this site for some incomprehensible reason .  the mouthfeel is on the thin side , very drinkable , & coats the mouth & throat . funny that the irish dry stout is distinct from milk stouts , because i feel the style is very lactic feeling .

this beer has a beautiful color , almost like cola with some extra glow , which is one of my favorite things about it .  a slightly sweet taste and smell , and a toasty aftertaste which i had completely forgotten about over the years . not a lot of carbonation after the pour . goes good with food , especially with a local delicacy - a zweigle 's white hot .

winey , sour nose , complex , very intriguing . almost smells like a good balsamic vinegar . huge nose . district wood up front , a bit harsh , with a fruity middle of grapes , stone fruits , and a slightly tart finish .  m - carbonation is lacking and the mouthfeel is a bit thin compared to porters , stouts , etc .

vanilla and molasses richness . slight whiff of cinnamon and roastedness . kinda reminds me of xmas fruitcake .  quite a smooth feel , but i just felt it was too thin . if this had a little more viscosity it would be a real winner for me .

a : really a lovely pint : crystal-clear complexion , few sleepy bubbles wriggling upward . plentiful head , a shade under a finger 's worth of ivory cream . beautiful lace in wide stripes , as if daubed on with a sponge .  mouthfeel : lively carbonation is on the edge of fizzy , body is a bit light , and the finish is oily .
