solid malt nose too . great balance in the aroma . t - does n't totally match the aroma but still damn good . bitter , piney , dry , citrus , pine .  m : smooth , not as robust as i would like in a ris , a little thin , pretty average . d : the lessened mouthfeel adds to the drinkability , making this probably the most drinkable ris that i 've ever had .

smell is musky and fruity like peaches on the verge of being over ripe . aromas of peach , plum , fig , raisin and grapes . strong oak wood aroma here . i am sure that there are those who do n't like the smell of maturing wine in barrels but i sure do and that gives this beer a bit of a plus in the aroma category .  the taste comes on mildly hoppy at first , but sweetens in the middle , possessing an almost carmel-like overtone . the finish is clean and refreshing . i would consider this a fine session beer for a hot , sunny day .

s : dark chocolate , bitter , with just a little bite from the alcohol . still good , and i bet it could make some killer half and halfs .  as others have said , this is very reminiscent of an ipa , the aroma of fresh hops and pine are similar to that style . this brew has an amber color and when poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glass creates a nice white head . the taste is very refreshing and seems like a fabulous brew to have on a hot summer day . i could , and would like to , drink this again . too bad i can never find it .

's appearance : deep and dark with glints of toffee around the edge . two fingers of off white head slip down to a touch of sticky lacing .  the body is medium-light with medium carbonation , and could benefit from being a touch heavier so that it boosts the flavour even more , but its okay as it is .

the aroma is the highlight of this beer , being nice and hoppy . very clean and citrusy , with a definite vegetal character , you can tell this thing was just loaded with dry-hops . the combination is really quite balanced , although ending on an uncomfortably bitter note with just a ton of booze . the boozy finish is unsettling and i maybe would prefer it to be a little dryer and a little less sweet and the bitterness is a little harsh and lingering .  mouthfeel seems dominated but a fast carbonation , over a thin to medium liquid .

aroma of rich earthy chocolate cake , vanilla , dark malt and a hint of hops . smells rich . taste is surprisingly balanced .  the body was cloudy and a deep yellow color . the off white head and lace was very creamy . this might have been the sweetest flavored weizen i had ever tasted . it was very banana like and a bit of bubble gum to it . as with all of their beer though i did find it to be thin .

s : wow . hops ! very bold smells . d : i think this thing was too hoppy without enough malt to balance it nicely .  this is well-done and a clear american classic , but the mouthfeel seemed a little thin and i think the beer could have been a tad more aggressive wrt maltiness and/or malt complexity without hurting the smoke profile at all .

poured out of a 500ml bottle into a wheat glass . pours out golden yellow with a thick creamy head that is fluffy like soap suds . carbonation is lively as it should be in a wheat beer . head laces the glass very well .  a : golden straw/amber hue , passes lots of light , nice white head , mild lacing s : strong bourbon , vanilla , malty t : vanilla , bourbon , mild caramel m : decent carbonation , light to medium bodied , watery overall , this beer has a great nose and taste .

pours a deep brown with an exceptional head .  the body is moderately light and mouthfeel is clean . the beer is not brewed with corn and it 's good for another 10 months so i do n't know what the problem is . i expected a helles with less body and malt flavor , but what i got was a corny mess . i ca n't imagine why they would even sell this beer .
a : liquid black gold , great head , with good retention , amazing after all it was a cask , it looked soild black , and i barely let the light pass through the glass ! !  mouthfeel : medium-bodied .

poured like heavily used motor oil with large , lasting two finger tan head .  hints of raisins & toast with a dry , fruitty ( dates ) finish mf : a bit sharp with a little too much carbonation drinks fine , just a little too young ( i think )

pours a deep copper breadcrust mixed nicely with volcanic bubbles ascending to the surface . about one and a half finger head with a thick foam .  m : light to medium body . medium level of carbonation .

it has a dark brown , near black , with a hint of red . the head is thick and lasts long , plenty of lace also . the looks sets your brain for something better , thus the whole experience is dissapointing , however it works as a `` light '' beer , if i may say .  mouthfeel is average , medium body and on the crisper side with the finish .

a-pristine amber beer , showing high carbonation . slightly off-white head retains well while being constantly replenished by the streams of carbonation bubbles ; remains as a thick layer through the whole drink .  a bit thin , imo .
absolutely lovely pour .  the mouthfeel was a bit weak for the style .

a - opaque brown black with a small coffee head and good lacing s - tiny bit of a coffee scent but not much t - malt with a little coffee .  the mouthfeel is smooth , but a bit lacking in the carbonation .

poured into a tulip glass . amazing lacing along sides of glass : sheets , lines , and clumps abound .  mouthfeel : nice mouth-coating , but a much weaker carbonation than i was expecting ( the tap ? ) .

outstanding aromas ! it smells like christmas , they totally nailed it !  extremely mild , even for an english style , however it had an interesting coffee finish , which i do n't think i 've ever found in a nut brown before . particularly curious , since the malts were not all that roasted . hmm .

pours a hazy golden orange amber with a huge creamy off white head that retains well and laces the glass .  taste : a true witch 's brew of vegetables , raspberry punch , and a thin maltiness . finishes tart and watery . mild carbonation .
a very comlex aroma of sweet malt , coffee , brandy , sasparilla , and a distinct woodiness . wow . i am not getting any pumpkin or yam .  medium bodied with an oily texture .

reviewed 1/1/2009 ( bottle ) : pours a hazy yellow color body with a humongous craggy white head , very lasting .  my main complaint is the mouthfeel , which is a little lacking given the style . a porter should be a little bit thicker , with more substantial body .

12oz bottle to tulip . wow , this is one awesome looking beer . a beautifully dense head capping a brew that is the deepest of amber , with a shine that would make any ruby gemstone jealous . stunning .  pours really great , decent aroma for a porter , nice head and lacing , but the taste seems to be a little off ... but in retrospect the flavor is ok. enigma ... what the hell . seems like i got kicked in the head by a pack of wild hyenas , and then my throat got ripped out by a flock of roaming vampires and then my essence was drained by a murder of migrant tigers . weird stuff .

poured from the 750ml brown bottle into a wine glass the poured yielded a beautiful 2 finger , fluffy , white head atop a light brown colored beer . streams of carbonation bubbles ran up the glass and generous spots of lace stuck to the glass throughout the sample .  nice ... mouthfeel : somewhat dry and crisp , but the body is 'way ' too thin for an oatmeal stout . they should thicken it up for a more chewy mouthfeel .
thick , healthy crop of rocky light beige head is erected on top . the retention and lace abilities are very good .  mouthfeel : this beer kind of dries out my mouth .

admittedly i 'm a sucker for raspberries , so for me this aroma is to die for . the nose is predominantly raspberries , soft and creamy in texture , no real tartness . as much as i adore raspberries , the flavour tends to not live up to what it advertises with the above two categories . definitely not up to par with what unibroue has capably proven to us in the past of what they can accomplish .  mouthfeel is decent , but the carbonation is way too pronounced , very fizzy and bubbly .

this beer was brilliantly clear golden honey with tiny , active carbonation . the head was creamy and dense and left clingy foam in the glass .  medium dark lager yellow color with a smallish head that disappears rather quickly . aroma is a little soapy with pumpkin pie spices ... like from a can . flavor is pure pumpkin pie spice powder without the pumpkin meat . just spice sprinkled over a malt beverage . there are much more complex and genuine tasting pumpkin beers out there .
it looked and smelled so good , but it ended up in the drain .  medium to full bodied with carbonation on the high side .

smell - gorgeous grassy and floral aroma . corn-grainy vanilla , just luscious . taste - i notice the hop bitterness over all and the flavour seems a bit thin .  complex hops all the way and some fruity esters but not too strong just the way i like it mouthfeel is ok for the tyle but not as refreshing as i like i will probably revisit this next summer
this beer pours a huge head with amazing retention and a nice golden color .  medium body , light effervescence .

| 8.0 % abv | 2010 brewer : unibroue style : belgian strong dark ale glass : duvel tulip appearance : it pours a fiery dark amber with a bountiful cumulus of foam .  the mouthfeel was light with a decent aftertaste of malted wheat .

the aroma is very nice . it promises a beer that is a balance of sweetness and roast and floral notes , the beer however does not quite deliver like i had hoped .  i had this at the kickbacks cigar city/st somewhere dinner . i 'm reviewing this by memory on this i had this at the kickbacks cigar city/st somewhere dinner . i have had most of cc 's regular beers but i have not tried this yet . it 's not a sour saison , pretty malty and more bosy than usual style and the hops were more nocticble as well , a little citrus on nose and taste .

looks great . hazy , sunny orange , bright white pillowy head of a few fingers , lace is great , retention is good . looks great , but it 's a bland , uninteresting offering .  mouthfeel : light-bodied . medium carbonation .

i think this beer is absolutely beautiful . its a dark purple haze with a soft head that stays wrapped around the inside of the glass like a silky spiderweb . since , the look was so exquisite i expected fruity goodness , but to be honest it made me want to puke .  carbonation was a bit heavy but no head developed as i poured . plenty of mouthfeel for the style .

hops are balanced in with the malts good . malts are chewy and hops are very interesting . sweetness of brew is strong .  m : fairly light body with matching carbonation . a little less substantial than would be ideal .

for smell , this was great . ca n't pinpoint the smell , but maybe fruit and pine . i was pleasantly surprised . drinkability ... you could drink these all night .  mouthfeel : far more carbonated than most stouts and my only fault with this beer .
this beer poured a deep rich brown color .  m -- perhaps a little too thin , but the carbonation is about right d -- nice sessionable porter here .

malts are n't quite enough to balance an otherwise fantastic bouquet , though . with balance , this aroma is exceptional . the flavor in this hop monster is pinw qith a big resinous aspect though it goes a tad `` rindy , '' the rind flavor adding a hint of saltiness before an astingently bitter floral finish .  m : combination , lime tang drinkability : yes yes yes ... football beer

i just loved the appearance of this brew , on arrival it had better than a two fingered head of tan bubbles , as it slowly disapated , it gave a moon crater like affect .  the only redeeming fact was the mouthfeel was decent ; aside from that , it 's pretty bad all round .

pours a thick , rich black , as the head begins to foam to the top .  fresh hops and grapefruit wedges sprinkled with sugar all wrapped up in a big big big aroma . bitterness is overwhelming on the tongue . very welcome for a local beer . has balls . tastes great and ct needs more intensity . here it is . a+

it pours up a egg shell colored head that is fine bubbled and creamy . this tops a deep brown elixir that features hints of deep mahogany against a backlight . it is brilliantly clear leaves a lot of lace behind .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with some prickly carbonation .

pours clear , copper/orange in color with abundant big bubbled head which sticks around nicely , eventually subsiding to leave behind a sticky , webby lacing .  mouth feel was a little thin , but there was little , if any , astringency .

by the appearance though , this produces a good amount of sticky white head , that leaves other , i suppose lagers , out to dry .  the mouthfeel is kinda sticky and medium bodied , but once you drink about half of one , you feel very refereshed , even for the relative bitterness .
jet black in appearance .  m/d : very drinkable since it is light in the mouth because of smell and after flavor i would buy again .

750 ml bottle with a bbd of march 07 pours straw colored with a slight chill haze & super fluffy 2 fingers+ white head .  feel : prickly at the begninning but eventually going down smoother . by far one of the best bulgarian beers .

notes from 5/3/10 the pour is pitch black with a long lasting 1 finter head . a stir of the glass presents good lacing .  appearance was only the can , which looked simple - nothing really wrong with it very little smell like bud light initially tasteless , except for the aftertaste bitter in a natural light kind of way mouth feel was alright - one of the better aspects the taste has made me hope to never be so desperate for a beer that i drink this again .
it looks great ! ! !  m & d : light to medium body , but overly carbonated imo . the carbonation makes for a brew that stings a bit on the way down .

this beer pours a jet black with a decent 2-inch tan head on top . great retention and perfect sticky webbing all over the glass . this is a beautiful beer .  the mouthfeel is okay , but not the highlight of this beer .

s : amazing scent of dark fruits and molasses , with a chocolate and bourbon finish that smacks of a fine dessert . t : rich chocolate cake and bourbon filled dark chocolate .  m - a little bit over-carbonated .

the bottle poured an attractive , amber-orange body with a tall , fluffy tan head . fantastic rings of lacing were etched into the sides of the glass at the top , and since the head was so well retained , great , sticky patches of lacing ensued down the sides .  this beer 's body was a little light for style . the hops and sweetness do play on the roof of my mouth and the carbonation tingles my tongue .

the smell is that of a delicious smelling baked bread and malts ... very nice !  bland and offensive . m- creamy with a boozy burn . if you have the patience to wait for the foam to die down to a point you can actually drink it you wo n't be rewarded .
served on tap at westwood tennis club in richmond va a : deep copper with a one finger creamy head . leaves some solid lacing behind .  m - a bit thin , in my opinion , for a complex beer like this .

pours perfectly for a tight forming off white head , with great retention . the body of the brew is cleanly filtered with no chill haze , and is copper in color .  mouthfeel : oddly thin but with a smooth silky texture . the carbonation is really low which is n't too far off but still could be higher .
appearance : beautiful . dark brown , practically black , with an incredible cascading effect from the nitro-tap . tons of lacing , too .  a very carbonated mouthfeel , lots of fizz .

poured a giant 4 inch foamy white head that took forever to fade.a clear golden amber color with a orange hue.a very light tasting ale with a splash of citrus and hops.a little watery on the finish.very average , nothing really stands out except for the appearence .  mouthfeel is a bit watery , not nearly as thick as a stout ( but as-expected for a porter ) .

s-pumpkin and spice , in short-pumpkin pie ( and quite pleasantly so ) . t-unsurprisingly , pumpkin is the primary flavour , although i found that the spice does not quite live up to the complex blend of tastes its smell promised ( it tastes more like alcohol with a few spices mixed in than a proper pumpkin pie spice blend ) .  i think i stand by my previous opinion of mouthfeel and drinkability .

a : this is possibly the most gorgeous beer i have ever seen . poured into a water goblet and held up into the light of the early morning sun , this maredsous 10 is a radiant orange . the soft , cloud like white head is supported by a lively stream of carbonation .  it takes away from every aspect of the beer . the taste was week in the malt department and nonexistant in the hop department . rice was detected . a-b should be ashamed .

the beer pours a beautiful golden color with a nice white head that does n't persist for long , but leaves behind beautiful lacing .  very dry pils . and by the way , pils taste completely different in bottles than they do on tap . looks absolutely stunning in a bischoff glass . fish especially .

it was gorgeous in the glass , pitch black against a pure white head . the head really deserves mention . frothy bubbles , gives it a real draught personality . very elegant .  thick mouthfeel but not as dense as some in its class , which i suppose makes it more drinkable than most in its class .

appearance- deeper golden colored pour with a two fingered and creamy head . leaves behind some large sticky patches of lacing .  taste : : malts , roasted malts , bitter cocoa meets with a mildly bitter hops mf : i think that this pour was pretty thin .

poured into a goblet from 12 oz brown bottle , slightly cloudy deep amber color , looks wonderful held up to the light , with a moderately dense tan head leaving a nice lacing on the glass .  m : this beer feels a touch too thin .

smell is wonderfully hoppy and citrusy ( if that 's a word ) . perhaps my favorite smelling beer . taste is powerful for an ipa . goes down easy . this beer is one of my favorites .  with the amount of carbonation this has , i have a really hard time picking out anything other than the wheat and banana . it also leaves a pretty dry aftertaste .

'' askew pours a darkened gold color that turns orange-ish later on when i get to the bottom of the bottle . until that last pour it was crystal clear and full of tiny bubbles , then it went opaque . a white head between one and two fingers thick quickly forms and stays for nearly twenty minutes , and leaves quite a bit of lacing .  m - very low carbonation , a little creamy but a little thin for an oatmeal stout .

very unique combination ! super complex and interesting .  out of bottle . not my type of beer at all . did not match the typical belgian flavor beer of which i am not a big fan of anyway . for me this had a charcoal , ashtray type taste that is just not a match for my palatte . seems some folks enjoy this , so give it a try if you 'd like . i have turned the page on this one .

appearance : normal pour resulted in huge white , rocky head . great retention and lacing . gorgeous !  mouthfeel : good medium body but just a tad under carbed overall impression : its surprisingly good for a gimmicky beer ; very nice taste and very drinkable .
hazy golden orange with a big head that settled to a heavy film . gives up decent lace throughout .  m - i wish actually for more bite and nip to clean up the palate a bit better .

nose is a delight with candied fruits and a clean biscuity/bready component . nose is my favorite aspect of this ale .  m : light to medium-light body with mild carbonation that coats the mouth and leaves a tingling sensation on the finish .
smell is a mixture of orange and pineapple juice . also reminds me of fruit coctail .  mouthfeel was a bit on the thin side , in my opinion .
the smell is freakin ' wonderful , though . i 'm just underwhelmed .  highly carbonated with a long lasting white head . a bit thin , but well balanced .

s - big cherry and chocolate nose . very nice t - the cherries are tart but not overwhelming . not wverly sweet or dry , nice finish d - if you like cherries and stouts this is a very good beer .  winter warmers are one of my favorite types of beer . however , i 'm a rheinheitsgebot type of guy . i taste nutmeg and maybe ginger in this beer . that 's outside the boundaries for me , even if the flavors were managed through some odd hop/malt/yeast combination . i had to dump it down the drain after a couple of tastes .

nice looking , light on the fizz with a creamy , foamy head .  a - murky red with orange yellow depending on the light with a nice head when poured vigorously enough , but it dissipates quickly s - sweet caramel and bubble gum t - sweet , floral , light at first and yet heavy with a regular beer aftertaste m - only slightly better than bud light ( my fav mass beer ) d - all the time brew .

a : in a snifter , this has impenetrable blackness . it looks like a candle in the glass , with a gelatinous chocolate mousse head .  some harsh roast flavours show up in the finish and it is also sorta sorta chalky . mouthfeel is ok i guess , but who cares when it tastes this bad ? i 'm guessing this flavour comes from some sort of cheap grain/adjunct .

s- this one smells great . very refreshing rasberries that do not dominate the nose but yield to other scents of wheat and alcohol .  this beer poured a pale yellow colour , simmilar to a pint of stella . it had a thin yet bubbly and large head , which dissipated quickly . it had a very delicious taste , with a metallic note and a slight taste of honey . it smelled sweet , also with that metallic note . this was my first bosnian beer , and it will not be my last .
this beer poured a huge fluffy white head that lasted till the last pull . the color was a light cloudy gold .  mouthfeel is a little thin but carbonation levels are average and work well .

s- wow . vinegar . sour and stinky ( in a good way ) . t- very pleasant and tasty . green apple , ripe limes and lemons , funky spice and herbs , earthy flavors , straw , flowers . d- so flavorful and enjoyable . the sour notes are no cloying .  mouthfeel : well carbonated , strangely thin but not in a bad way .

great smell . t - tastes of faded fruity hops , and a little bit bitter . some people at the tasting thought it had faded a lot , and i personally do n't see if getting better with age , but i thought it was very enjoyable and smelled amazing . if i was sitting on some bottles of this i would drink them now , and would love to try it again .  m- thin to medium body with a little unattenuated sugar . there 's a little bit of soft carbonation here as well ... but for such a sweet and malty brew , i would have liked to have more unattenuated sugar ... a chewier and more textured mouthfeel ... d- very very drinkable ... a perfect fall or winter nightcap ... and the alcohol is very well hidden !

poured a gorgeous hue of cocoa brown with a soft head carpeting the surface . very nice to look at and pretty close to what i want the style to look like .  m : good amount of carbonation , could be cut back a little bit .

this beer starts out as classic sam adams , the perfect head with lacing and retention , perfect clarity , lovely color ... .only this time it does n't seem forced to generic .  smell : roasty wood smell , with some chocolate and coconut , and something resembling coffee ... taste : strong coconut flavor , sweet malty chocolate , some brown sugar almost maple flaovrs then ends with a roasted coconut flavor mouthfeel : medium body , sweet feel , medium carbonation , nothing special drinkability : really sweety , pretty drinkable though , good flavors .
pours a nice one inch white head that is creamy with some bubbles . good retention and huge lacing .  if not for the thin mouthfeel this would be one for the ages .
this brew pours a brassy tea color with a one inch creamy tan head that dissipates down to a respectable skim .  ) mouthfeel - not bad , perhaps a trifle thin .
crisp golden malt aroma with a generous dash of floral hop at the end . very appealing . the flavor is extremely hoppy .  just hoping future versions can improve that mouthfeel .

clean , amber , orange , fluffy white head smell is great . one of the better smelling beers that have ever reached my nose .  first sip reveals a very fine carbonation that gently tingles my palate . the body is fairly thin , but not watery .

pretty pour color . a huge brown head that retains fairly well , leaves some nice lacing , and makes some overall neat patterns in the foam as it recedes . very pretty .  m : the mouthfeel is slightly slick .

poured with a huge , dense , tan head over a burnt orange body , with plenty of carbonation floating up .  taste & mouth feel : decent crispness over a light body that holds some unnatural dextrin in the mouth feel . vague beer flavor , nasty herbal flavors flail around chaotically .

dark brown/black in color with ruby highlights .  mouthfeel leaves a little to be desired in my opinion , comes across a tad bit too syrupy , but at the same time a proper amount of bubbles for the mouthfeel .
smells quite potent . like cidery , tangerine .  mouth : slightly tingly , a sweet bitter hop presence stays around , fairly thick bodied .

appearance : poured for the 22 oz bomber black into a pint glass ( two pours ) . brown head about 1/4 inch sits on the black viscous liquid that light does not penetrate .  m - too light for my liking , and sometimes even border-line watery . at least there 's a strong carbonation , and it 's nice to kind of toss around on the tongue to search for the other flavors . still , fairly average .

ah the beauty of a stout in your glass , all atramentous in color with the crown all frothy and light chocolate in color and after its decomposition , the velum like curtain of lace that clings so lovingly to the glass .  in th mouth , though , it 's a little too watery for a weizen .

great red ! being a local portlander ... i was waiting a long time to see a great red . always drinking weinhards red when i was in a weinhards kind of mood ... this one stands out . the color is rich and bold.. makes a statement . makes you say `` oh boy , here it goes , a real red '' .  watery rather than full bodied for a stout . fantastic . ' i just wish it was a bit thicker in terms of oral sensations .

appearance : clear golden blonde , but with tiny little freckles that danced in suspended animation , crowned with very nice head that seemed to have two layers of head ; large , soapy bubbles were trapped underneath a thick dense foam on top .  some nice foam when poured . dark brown/copper appearance not too much in the nose , but smells vaguely of belgian yeast spice up front , sweeter flavor and then ending with a cinnamon and alcohol taste . notes of vanilla and banana . overall a good beer but could use some subtlety .

a : pours an attractive bloody amber . two solid fingers of stiff tight head forms and holds like a champ .  it leaves a pleasant fruity citrus taste in the back of your mouth . the carbonation is moderate . worth trying if you feel like something light .

that 's not too much of a detriment , as the nose is just outstanding . perfection for an irs imo , this is a great blend with an exceptional balance between chocolate , fruity oxidation and a rich fudge like character , more so than the 12th anniversary and the bb irs .  medium body , lingering flavors .

pours crystal clear light orange amber color with a dense 2 finger off white head with great retention that reduces to a thick lacing cap that lasts .  a bit chalky . hints of grapefruit and bold coffee flavor .
poured beautifully , perfectly presented in its correct chalice . lovely head over amber to red-brown body .  the mouthfeel is a little uneventful .

pours a spectacular , clear , brassy-hued honey . thick , creamy , off-white head sports great retention -- pockmarks appear as it slowly fades , leaving thick , nealry opaque curtains of lace .  i have been known to sit and smell the beer for five minutes before i drink it . the taste is carmel with a almost pine after taste . after four beers the tart pine after taste is really noticable . i really like this beer . though sometimes they do n't taste right . i do n't know if i just have an old one or maybe it is too new and needs time to mellow .

the pour was a stunning crimson color . the deepest hue of any oude kriek i have ever seen .  oy gevalt ! pours an interesting reddish brown slightly hazy body with a finger of beige-white head . head lingers and it laces the glass well . aroma is nice and sweet . tastes very hoppy with dates dark fruit notes . a bit of a bite in the aftertaste , that is not pleasant !
super dark body with a tan foaming head and impeccable never ending retention and webbing .  body is light to medium , carbonation is perhaps a bit high for my tastes .
very clear amber colored brew that poured with a tall head that retreated to about a 1/4 inch foam layer that lingered , and left lace .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel is okay .

misty burnt sienna with eddies of bubbles feeding the monumental cream-colored stack of foam . it erodes into large pocked craters leaving a interestingly formed mesa on top of the liquid . then it goes totally vacant .  the mouthfeel is a bit thinner than i expected , with medium carbonation .

it pours a lovely opaque black , once in the glass there is a finger or so of rich mocha brown head .  mouthfeel was a tad thin , surprisingly , but did n't affect my overall impression of the beer much .
berry aroma . where the other chimay beers are shooting for finess over intensity , i believe this one achieves it .  the feels is about average for a lager with moderate carbonation .

the smell is so wonderfully hopped , i think i could get as much enjoyment out of just smelling this one as drinking it .  tropical hops , brown sugar , molasses , earth , sweet yeast and a bit of oak m - light , a bit of carbonation , light to medium acidity and short finish and some what balanced d - nice for an ipa , easy to drink .
appearance was fantastic . it poured as a clear light straw color ( much lighter than a budweiser would look ) .  mouthfeel slacks off a little .

appearance : pours a gorgeous hazy red with an off white head .  however , it almost lacks a bit in body and gets watery towards the end instead of carrying the expected viscosity of an oyster stout .
pours a huge tan head and you can not see through the glass as it laces .  m : hefty , frothy , and over-carbonated . it 's quite a mouthful , but not always in the most pleasant way .

brown bottle with a great looking label on the front , three flyods style all the way . pours a crystal clear ruby color with no cloudiness what so ever . head formed with only the slightest help , with a off white hue .  the head is only a half inch and it does back fast , leaving a thin foam coat and the carbonation seems to keep it replenished . the taste is rich and fizzy : like the carbon dioxide gets release when it hits my tongue . this is good stuff , although i agree it is darker than most saison .

just a barrage of hop scents from across the spectrum . wonderful . certainly not a hop overdose , the malt backbone is so evenly balanced that it serves to accentuate the hop taste ( somewhere between grapefruit and pine resin ) .  carbonation is very low , could be higher really . very unorthodox but amazing anyway .
the appearance of this brew is top notch with it 's deep dark ruby body and milk chocolaty head that lasts minutes after the initial pour .  light body , sandy mouth feel , faint malt spine .

pours out of a nitro can pretty black with a perfect two finger light tan head with excellent retention . say what you will about what the nitro does to a beer , to me it makes for an exceptional appearance , and i love to watch nitro stouts settle .  m- the body is a little on the light side .

it smelled phenomenal , like a bar a hershey 's finest -- again , not really like beer , but i guess i was in a desserty kind of mood . it feels really silky on the tongue , almost like chocolate milk , but the taste was surprisingly bitter .  moderate to thinner in the mouth with mild carbonation .

it smells pretty good like berries , booze , and brown sugar . awesome smell . taste is overwhelmingly like nail polish remover , artificial strawberry , and fire .  m : a little on the light side of medium bodied , and i 'm afraid my somewhat rough pour put almost all of the carbonation into the fantastic head - it feels a bit flat .

bud american ale has a beautiful red/amber color and a smooth crisp finish . some may think im crazy for saying this , but i found it to have the same taste as a very very weak ipa .  m : a little carbonated , slightly burns .

aroma is a malt lovers wet dream . just the sweet smell of malt here , almost to the point of being meaty . caramel & alcohol linger in the nose .  definite hints of caramel and roasted malts in the flavor and the hint of roasted malt lingers a bit on the palate along with a candied sugar taste . goes down ok , a good session beer .
pours with an orange amber body topped by a thick white head with lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but not exceedingly so .

2007 bomber courtesy of clockworkorange poured into a tulip . pours dark , dark brown out of the bottle and settles in close to black with a fluffy tan head that recedes to a cap and leaves tons of lacing .  can really feel the carbonation , it almost foams up a bit in your mouth .

a - hazy , cloudy rust colored body with creamy white head and nice lacing .  just beer . this beer is good , let me say that first . that said , there is absolutely nothing salient about the brew . taste is almost like a brown ale , but without the caramel flavor or biscuit-y quality . tastes like beer , drinks like beer , great for packing 'em in .

s - incredibly sweet smelling , hints of anice , black current , cherries , cranberry , coffee and chocolate .  meekly carbonated finish , bitter , hops understated , alum dry aftertaste , different from what i would normally drink , so it takes a lot of contemplation to be accurate in my judgment , drinkable , but something i 'd not want to sample on a regular basis , but after some serious decanting i found it to be a bit more pleasing to my palate , so if your not into the sediment at the bottom of the bottle , even if it means pouring a bit of the beer back into the bottle you may make a serious misjudgment of taste .

golden in color and a bit cloudy . the head is enormous , frothy and white , which laces wonderfully .  m-medium bodied , though lacking a bit of the rich mouthfeel i like to see in an oatmeal stout .
this is a deep jet black pour with a chocolate color head.. is there a krakken living somewhere in there .  it was a little fizzy , but that was a minor problem .

a - absolutely gorgeous brew , dark amber coloration , nice thick head of froth , excellent retention , sedimentary lacing . overall presentation - perfect .  the only thing i mark this beer down for was it mouthfeel . i tought it had a very light mouthfeel and certainly no creaminess .

appearance- pours a clear rusty burnt orange that breaks to a very metallic looking orange at the bottom of the glass . nice thick , creamy head that holds very well . sticky , creamy head laces nicely down the side of the glass . very attractive .  had on tap at the brewery in moab , ut . i believe this is just the cream ale served with jalapeno peppers served in it . this also tastes like a wet cat in a pool of vomit ... absolutely disgusting , with a `` beer-like '' flavor trying to emerge ... pale malts , and butterscotch combine gloriously with the jalapeno . no heat is evident , either . this is a horrible mistake .

poured into a samuel smiths pint glass at a perfect cellar temp of 55 degrees . a : enormous head from a fairly gentle pour . head fills the glass to the top , sticks around forever and leaves tons of lace . wow ! beer is black and stout like .  this is a great porter . i have been a fan of anchor brewing and this porter is tops . beautiful black color when poured into glass . and the aroma is very mild . enjoyed this on a really cold night and i could n't have picked a better porter . i could be wrong , but this porter was almost sweet . good meal in a glass .

almost pitch-black , impenetrable colour - big brown head with generous lacing . very low carbonation , thick and oily mouth feel , medium body .  poured into s snifter , with a very nice quick vanish head and a even nicer lacing around the walls smells quite boozy almost brandy like with a faint fruity winey aroma taste oaky with obvious caramel and molasses characters . finishes with a biscuit like citrisy aftertase very complimenting this is a decent old ale and being this years ( 2011 ) batch my guess is it will get a little better with age . 9.8 50 ibus
i love the appearance of golden body in contrast to the white , gold , and red of the label .  i liked this beer , but the mouthfeel had a little high carbonation for a new belgium beer .
a_pours a rich copper red with a fluffy , fluffy three finger head . plenty of lacing .  mouthfeel : highly carbonated as youd expect , but dare i say a little watery ?
a : pours a very deep near opaque brown , with a thick creamy dark tan head . excellent retention and lacing .  feel is a little on the weak and thin side despite a decent amount of carbonation .
glad to find this one at the local beer store ... a : perfect ! pitch black with no light shining through .  mouthfeel : a bit watery .
pours a murky dark brown . very good lacing . amazing to look at .  medium bodied with a slightly watery , though smooth , finish .

looks a beautiful dark amber tone that has a light lace .  its now called winter warmer , not strong ale , but i figure they 're the same thing . mouthfeel is just a touch on the light side , but the flavor of this beer makes up for it !
hazy golden body highlighted by shooting strands of bubbles rising to the outstandingly sturdy head .  m - medium to full mouthfeel . tongue feels chalky .
moderate lacing on the glass with a very mild head retention and is crystal clear . the bright reddish hue of the beer is really rather stunning .  is a bit watery , though .

pours a dark mahogany color that takes on a look of hazy ruby when held up to the light . big , creamy-looking light tan head that hung around for a while and left a sticky webbing on the sides of the glass .  i actually like a few of the canadian brands better ( as some have the actual raisins and what not in the bottle still , and better carbonation levels and lower abv ) . taste is great malty , sweet , and very filling ( it 's nutritous to boot ) . i only generally drink water , tea , coffee , beer , wine , spirits , juice , and dairy ( kefir , etc ) . this is the noly soda type beverage i drink and it is absolutely stellar hangover relief ...

it looks like a black cow ( vanilla ice-cream and coca-cola ) , a jet black body with a huge billowy coffee-and-cream head that lasts and lasts . the head is really incredibly bubbly , with super-sized bubbles normally only found in soda . it looks wonderful .  light bodied , heavily carbonated , became foamy in the mouth at times .

appearance : fine-looking murky copper body with a creamy , off-white head . plenty of lacing throughout .  light in body though it does n't live up to the initial crispness of the nose . carbonation seems appropriate .
a : clear golden with a large white head that has great retention and lacing .  m - light body . slightly watery finish .

nice and clear s : lots of wood and cherry sour . that 's an awesome smell by the way . a little bit of darker fruit showing up in the background t : huge amounts of flavor .  the first and dominating aroma was apples , and then other fruits . flavor was that of apples , bananas , malts , and carmel . the finish was a bit sharp .

poured at room temp into a pint glass , the eber is a pitch black color with creamy tan head of 1 cm . fades gradually but leaves tight and windowpane lattice as it recedes . first sip reveals smooth spacious carbonation with average body and silky texture .  m : hardly carbonated , but the subtleties between the aforementioned sweetness and hoppiness make for an interesting drink .

this seems to be my last oktoberfest purchase for the year since the seasonal batches look to be drying up . dark copper liquid filled my glass with a small amount of head that could not hide the malty goodness that filled my nose .  mouthfeel is rather thin , as expected .

poured exceptionally well , perfect head and great lacing .  s - overwhelming peach . that is all this beer has , and i found it to be utterly unbalanced . d - my partner and i drank many different beers over two weeks in belgium . also , i do n't think this has any lambic as in it , as that it not claimed by dubuisson on their website .
large white head with sticky lace and great retention .  as noted , the mouthfeel is both on the thin and flat side .
bomber , a : pours a clear yellow with a full , lasting white head , excellent lacing .  not a run-of-the-mill pale ale by any means but i 'm finding it a little thin .
this one was a winner opaque brown/black with a semi-foamy guinness type head of tan . very nice sheet lacing .  the body is pretty thin but the feel still comes across as creamy to some extent .

beer poured to an abundant head with exceptional retention . color was dark brown with just a touch of amber . i believe the label said , `` exceptionally smooth , and ruby red brown '' .  t : wheat flavor , lemon , and slight banana/clove taste m : a tad on the overcarbonated side but not too bad d : good easy drinking hefe , would like to try again sometime .
the appearance of this brew when poured it gives off two fingers of off white head , and laces quite well .  lack of head on the initial pour but this beer is definitely carbonated .

lots of aroma similar to a quality hefe , some clove , very light note of bubble gum ... even some dry fruit scent in there .  a very unique apperance . the taste is very hoppy and refreshing . has a bit of a bite to it . i am not a big fan of ipa 's but i would drink this again .

s- cherry , roasted malts , vanilla , chocolate , and a touch of anise . the more this warms i get coffee and oak scents .  mouthfeel is crisp and very highly carbonated ( only complaint and wish it was toned down a bit ) .
the beer arrived at the table a translucent black . the head was tan and long lasting .  m- light bodied , maybe a little on the watery side . the carbonation is a bit too high .

smells of burnt cinnamon and sugar , as well as dates , plums , and ... ( at this point my notes on the aroma teetered off for some reason ) . i do remember the bouquet opens up quite well , and it 's quite complex . flavors of spices , mild chocolate , and farmhouse funk near and at the finish .  mouthfeel is light , not much carbonation or bite on the finish .
the color is jet black with a creamy tan head .  body is a bit flat and thin .

from the brewer : what makes this copper coloered beauty so wildly popular ? ( ibu 's : 60 ) my review : nothing looks better than a nitro-tapped beer . thick foamy head that lasts forever leaving a solid blanket of lace throughout the tasting .  body is about average and carbonation is quite lively .

poured into tulips . ar : mmm , tart , cherries , green apple , light acidity/sour , light apple cider vinegar , nutty malt , earthy with brett , fruit down in intensity with time , light floral , *delicate , *caramel ap : light tan very large coarse chunky head , lace , clear light amber , rocky head , best head retention i 've seen t : brett earthiness , light vegetative , brett bitterness , tart hints , herbal spicy hop , nutty/crackery malt , fruity hints ( peach , light tropical fruit , cherry ) , long dry complex brett and hop bitter end , green apples ( light ) assertive but not aggressive , clean ( crisp ) medium caramel , woody spices m : dry lasting brett bitterness , lightly astringent , medium/high fine carbonation , *resin o : good , brett rather bitter , complex and clean , would like more sour in taste , would like it less vegetative , *darker than expected , *a strange beer , not really a full brett character , not sour , aroma and appearence are the best parts , *appearance is flawless *= ideas of fellow taster  very lightly carbonated .
a very nice looking pilsner .  found the texture to be overly thick and needing more carbonation to compliment the sharp flavors .

blossoming cream colored head that stays at 1 1/2 '' scents are chocolate covered lemon cookies with hints of vanilla , banana & clove . heavy on the chocolate component - nice . the deep roasted flavors follow from the scent . no spiciness detected which was apparent in the nose . overall a great beer that i 'm very delighted i found at the cloverleaf in metro detroit .  m : this beer is thiner then i was hoping for , but still good d : great beer nice flavor
a - very attractive , ruby brown with a long lasting head and lacing .  mouthfeel is carbonated , which kind of deadens everything .

a. impressive , light tan creamy head extended nearly to the bottom of the glass !  mouthfull is medium , not as thick as you 'd expect from such a good russian stout , but you get past that very quickly .

though the smell does n't set my nostrils raging , the color is very inviting . this is a beer i always go back for when there is n't a micro that is catching my eye .  mouthfeel was average ; nothing great , or bad .

sweet , ripe fruit esters hit the nose at first , and caramel & toasty munich malt quickly follow -- a trace of herbal hersbrucker hop nose rounds out the aroma .  unfortunately thinnish in overall body , with an overly lean , passably viscous mouthfeel .

i was rewarded with a lovely looking , clear , old gold coloured beer with a large , snow white head . plenty of bubbles rising upwards to the head indicated a lot of carbonisation .  mouthfeel is off due to the alcohol burn feel to it .

s - a fairly nice aroma of roasted coffee beans and malt . nice . t - not to complex .  taste first of sweet pine , then fading into a rich , malty , yeasty sweet oblivion . this beer tastes surprisingly belgian to me . aftertaste is thick , sweet , yeasty , mildly floral with a bit of bitter hops in the back of the mouth . i actually really liked this beer for the price ( i believe it was around $ 3.50 for a 22 oz ) , surprisingly flavored for a northwest brew .
duvel poured a brilliant straw yellow . a thick , long lasting white head built within seconds .  mouthfeel is slightly thin , but not watery .
appearance : pours a deep burgandy / brown color with a thick three finger tan head . nice lacing develops during the session .  the liquid is smooth and a little sticky .

smell sweet and hoppy , it lets you know its and ipa .  about 15 minutes or so later , the aroma became or of a solvent one ( like expo markers ) and tropical fruit . t- soy sauce , alcohol , belgian yeast , and a touch of hops . m- high to medium . o- very complex .

not only was the glass itself decorated with a colorful , festive motif , the contents were equally gorgeous . it had a creamy , light tan head which lasted well through the night , leaving a solid layer of froth and excellent lacework .  it was smooth , but a bit too thin ( ie . watery ) .
nice light amber color with a big pillowy white head ; great retention and lacing .  pretty average mouthfeel .

good aromas ... can notice this across the room . it 's good , but nothing overly adventurous , a safe beer even . probably not deserving of the critics # 1 aussie beer , but its still very nice .  the body feels a bit thin and flat .

interesting . t : dry white wine is an odd touch to an otherwise marmalade/jelly-esque hops presence .  from 12 ounce bottle . i will not finish a brew that i do not like , so this was tossed after 2 mouthfuls ! it tasted to me of rancid coffee and it left a nasty aftertaste that unfortunately lingered quite a while !

i have not been a fan of most pumpkin beers i 've tried , but this one was a very pleasant suprise . lots of spice in the nose , and it reminded me of pumpkin pie baking in the oven .  only fault is perhaps excessive carbonation , but i 'm getting more sensitive to that so maybe it 's my problem .

head stayed and left nice thick lacing down the nonic . clear of sediment . a very nice dark amber/red color .  flavors are again hopcentric , with a fresh-hopped feel to it . the beer is mid-bodied , yet cloying and slightly sticky in mouth , with a bitter and spiced hops aftertaste . very green , with an overall fresh-hopped feel .

aroma is heavenly , notes of dark chocolate and toasted marshmallow ( mmm ... s'mores anyone ? flavor is somewhat disappointing . the first few sips there was a slight stale cardboardiness . slightly nutty , hints of almond .  mouthfeel was slightly slick and long after the finish this brew becomes dry and oaky - grainy wood seems to slide across the tongue .

just an absolutely beautiful beer . deep golden and somewhat cloudy . a tremendous head that takes awhile to dissapate and as it does it leaves beautiful chunky lacing all over the inside of my glass .  mouthfeel is medium/thin but with a bit of a creamy mouthfilling quality . light balance and a bit watery with little character . flavors are just simple and watery . flavors taste like a decent lager to which one has added about 50 % water .
this brew pours with massive amounts of head with a sligthly vigorous pour .  mouthfeel is slightly diluted and flat but the overall feel and enjoyable nature leads to a quite drinkable brew .

poured into a tulip glass . a - 1 finger head with no lacing . great copper color .  medium carbonation , very light and crisp with a slight malt taste mixed with a nice strawberry flavor . it 's sweet , but not a bad overpowering sweetness and i think the brew is just the right mix of fruit to give it flavor and still be a good beer . this was very tasty and refreshing , went down easy ( almost too easy as i drank 2 in 15 minutes ) , and is the type of beer i could drink all night when it 's hot outside . overall a good summer beer !
appearance - pours a clear , pale straw with a rocky , 2 finger white head .  medium bodied and tingly from the carbonation .
overall nice , attractive smell .  m - very light and smooth . grain water .
super hoppy smell , citrus , fruit , alcohol . quite nice . pretty strong taste upfront .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel of ruby is nothing out of the ordinary . mild carbonation and a lighter body .
pours into a chalice with very dark brown color with creamy dark head .  mouthfeel is rather thin , the only real drawback to this beer .

this beer is nearly completely black with a head that retains well .  overall a very good beer for the warmer weather around the bar-b-que . if you are looking for a complex brew that you can stare at in amazement , this is not it . this is the type of beer that you grab when you are thirsty , standing around a garage looking a car , or just something to drink while you are doing something active , like softball or ping pong . this is a perfect beer for those who want a macrobrew but have a couple extra bucks or a `` macro '' chip on thier shoulder .
translucent light burnt orange color , wisping head of fairly large bubble size .  m : it has an average mouthfeel .

a-pours foamy and it chocolate dark in color s-nothing to special t-very thick and heavy and has a malty bittersweet aftertaste .  sweet and sour start , the top middling in feel and the finish mildly acidic , hops are forceful in their bite , quite dry aftertaste .
pours out a beautiful hazy and rich gold at the bottom of my hefe glass and a rich orange tint . incredibly enticing .  very bland and acidic . can taste the 9 % all the way through .
pours black with 2 finger chocolate head .  m : prickly carbonation with a relatively full mouthfeel . to be honest , i would n't mind the carbonation being dialed down a touch .
pillowy big bubble head . nice eye candy .  mouthfeel is ok. on the heavier side of medium bodied . it starts smooth and ends sharp .

this beer is cheap . appearance - light straw color . presentation - awesome tall green grenade .  light body- almost too light bordering on watery with only moderate carbonation . overall i liked this and it 's drinkable , but i wish it had a little more body and i 'm not crazy about the bitter alcoholic aftertaste .

a massive 3 '' head nearly overflowed my tulip , even after a slow steady pour . the head hangs around for a little while , and eventually fades to a big fat blob in the center of the glass .  a : cloudy urine yellow s : acidic and unpleasant ; not like lemon ; more like lemon rind t : like a cheap mass-produced lager , yuengling for example , with an unwelcome metallic finish m : somewhat velvety , then dry and acerbic . watered down ?

weihenstephaner korbinian is a solid , crystal clear , brown-red beer with an oily , bubbly , beige head .  medium bodied , highly carbonated and prickly from the hops . i 'm a little put off by the amount of carbonation and i prefer the sweeter stouts .

it is popping with a fresh and spicy roasted pecan aroma . the nose is beautiful and i know plenty of people who would love this beer .  palate is slight corn and slight malt with a slight bitter hops and the carbonation . odouls is a slight of everything brew , no yummy malt , no well bittered hops bite , just a lot of gas ( carbonation ) and if you ask me , its a slightly boring brew .
very nutty aroma . t : nutty .  mouth -the beer leaves quickly and body does n't add much to overall characteristics , but nice tingling on front and clean but not dry finish .

a - a perfect reddish brown complexion allowing traces of light to pass . it 's color is medium tan , almost caramel colored .  the carbonation here really attacks my mouth in a way that makes it a bit unpleasant .
big spice aroma .  m : somewhat thin for the style .

extremely pleasant . taste : sweet pumpkin flavors mixed with some maltiness , it 's tough to tell where one ends and the other begins .  mouthfeel is where this beer falls a bit for me . very carbonated , too much so for me .

the nitrogen helps it to produce an awesome brew to look perfect . i loved it to pour and to watch its great neck .  m : medium in body , the carbonation is a touch high for me , paired with a fairly dry finish , the mouthfeel seems a little too active for the style .
nice looking beer , pours a bright red / amber color with a nice big off white head .  the mouthfeel was a bit sharp at first .
most amazing looking beer in a plastic cup .  m : the beer was almost still . just the slightest hints of carbonation after an extremely aggressive pour .

nice looking bottle that stood out on the shelf . you know with a wax dipped cap and neck , this has to be something special . nice 1 1/2 '' tan head that quickly evaporated into a thin lace .  m : needs more body i thought , but after i ate i noticed it had more body ?

aside from the finger 's worth of foam atop this beer , it looks like a glass full of unfiltered clover honey . great head retention , and lots of lace leaving rings down the glass .  the mouthfeel is very spritzy ... too much so .

smells exactly like champagne , very aromatic . taste is spicy yeast up front , with a tart sour apple middle , and a surprising amount of bitterness in the finish .  mouthfeel/drinkability- lightly carbonated going in , it never gets interesting enough to best highlight the hop and malt features to its potential .
so complex . beautiful . i want a flower power ipa air freshener .  mouthfeel : this is a little thin somehow .
the smell was sweet apples , very rich if not a little deceiving .  this is a medium bodied brew that is excessively carbonated . it is quite bubbly and fizzy on the tongue .

m : the alcohol is strong but the spices and perfume aroma are very pleasant . d : the drinkability is limited by the strength , but this certainly can suffice as a night cap .  this is a full-bodied beer , but mouthfeel is a bit weak compared to the rest of this beer 's qualities .

bright , clean fruity esters : lime , pear , green apple , apricot , and honeydew . bright citrus and tropical fruit : melon , apricot , lime ; swarmed by a slick and oily hop character . the hop profile is best described as juicy , with no astringency or mustiness . slick , warming alcohol is certainly evident , but not as overpowering as expected .  carbonation is very high on this one leading to a prickly mouthfeel that is just a little bit too much .
the soapy head on top is billowy with low density , the body being brilliant and gold in color . beautiful !  m : medium carbonation , very light body , definitely too watery for my taste .

s : wow hops ... . very floral with a hint of spiciness , just a little malt here ... there is also some citrus note here . d : very hoppy yet crisp ... not a session beer for me , but it goes down pretty easy .  m : a bit to much carbonation initially , but it gets calmer after a while and all in all the beer is very smooth and creamy .

14.9oz nitro can guinness draught was almost black , but was actually a dark crimson red color when held to a light . the head was fantastic , thick and creamy with great retention and plenty of lacing left behind .  mouthfeel leaves something to be desired in that it 's a bit too light , but this still a nice wit overall .

750ml bottle , thanks brad ! pours a very slightly hazy honey orange with a fine soapy head . awesome lacing .  alot of the reviews i read said this was michelob 's best offering in their craft beer line . not even gon na try and be a beer geek here and sound intelligent . i just do not think this my type of beer . tasted like rotten bananas mixed with bad oatmeal . i wish i could say something nice but i can not think of a thing .
smell - rich , complex smells . leather , smoke , chocolate and figs .  m - nothing typically outstanding in the mouthfeel , but it is more than made up for in taste .
translucent amber color with a big creamy light-tan head . tons of sticky lacing and great retention .  medium-light bodied , a bit thin , with gentle carbonation and a light hop bite .

wonderfull complex smell , which keep me sniffing for 10 minutes .  personaly , i 'd like the mouthfeel a bit fuller , but perhaps i 'm spoiled by the big pilsner which initiated the hoffmann series .

very grassy and floral to the nose like running through a field of wild flowers with freshly mown grass . the scent is definitely inviting . now the first sip , lightly toasted malts in a sea of grain and grass , kicked back by a sharp floral hop adding spice and dryness . mouthfeel is like a champagne , very bubbly and dry but light in body as a pilsner should be .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , which seems a bit on the lighter side for a barleywine .
pours a very nice wit beer color with a nice frothy head that lasts the duration of the beers life . nice lacing .  too carbonated .

poured a hazy , honey-golden amber into a snifter with a huge , billowing , frothy cream-colored head that slowly dissipated leaving moderate amounts of lacing on the glass .  flatness of mouthfeel is a negative factor but i still thought it was a tight attempt at the style for a relative newcomer to the trade .
poured mahogany with a light tan head that left some lacing .  good balance m- light and watery . lots of hops that stick to the tongue .

this is one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced with a porter . less intense qualities of the aroma . this feels thin for some reason . outstanding aroma , good taste , too thin .  the feel was light bodied with light carbonation .
another beer from this brewery that is a beauty to behold in the glass , crystaline bronze and glowing .  slighty carbonated , with a nice albeit thin mouthfeel .
s- bananas ! it is amazing how much this beer smells like bananas . m- very light and wheaty .  exceptionally smooth mouthfeel , a buttery diacetyl eases it along .
lightly roasted malts and a beautiful smoke contribution . t : hearty bread .  the feel is amazing here , silky creamy smooth with just the right body on it .

the smell is its best feature with grassy and bitter hops and sweet honey notes the flavour does not live up to it however and just shows a strong hop presence but no complexity the mouthfeel is full bodied but leaves a slight coating which deducts from the drinkability  m = medium heavy body , great carbonation level , great mouthcoating , almost no real burn from the high abv and what there is goes so well with the flavors and warming winter mood that it fits perfectly .

there 's certainly caramel in the air with this beer . big coffee smell as well . this is only going to get better as it warms up . i 'd like to be wrapped up in this beer as if it were a warm blanket . all is very good , but difficult to identify . d - i 'm happy i have more in the fridge , but i think i 'll have to savor them for a later date .  big and chewy with a very smooth , creamy finish .

aromatics are pungent and complex , and seem predominately derived from the yeast . comice pears , clove , fresh milk , wildflowers , banana and almonds all come to mind . the flavor closely follows the aromas , adding a solid foundation of ( melanoidin ? creamy mouthfeel , with a pleasant warmth from the alcohol .  with the ginormous head , i expected the carbonation to be knocked out of this brew somewhat , and it has been . no complaints here : the medium body has a gloriously soft , silky feel as a result .
s - this smells like pure vanilla , with some butterscotch aroma in there as well .  great dry mouthfeel , perfect on style points .

interlude by allagash is a wild ale aged in french merlot and sirah oak barrels . it smelled of cherry , dark fruits , malt , toffee and some red wine . it is very wine like but it seems a bit off .  perfect balance in this mouthfeel , perhaps the best quality of this beer .

a : poured from can an amber color , good sized white head , good lacing down the glass s : smell is very nice . sweet , caramel , toffee scents t : sweet taste at first , slight bitter hoppy bite at the end .  feels wonderfully silky and smooth on the palate .
an aroma of spices , flowers , and citrus .  m-very smooth and creamy , full bodied , good carbonation and a crisp grainy finish .
appearance : deep amber . tons of white frothy head .  the mouthfeel is very thick and pleasant , almost creamy .

the smell is even better - sweet and fruity . a very good combination of the two - the tart hits you immediately , then the aftertaste mellows into a fruity sweetness , followed finally by the sour . this is a highly-carbonated beer , which fits the taste and smell perfectly ... it really plays on the tongue nicely .  the mouthfeel has an almost perfect extra virgin olive oil and buttery finish to it .
the only thing it is good for is to sit it on a shelf , let it age , and admire the pretty bottle !  m : full body , not the least bit cloying . awesome . d : great for it 's weight .

bottle : poured a hazy dark yellow beer with a huge head with incredible retention ( i never though id mentioned that in a review , but the head was so persistent that it was still there 30 minutes after the beer was poured .  mouthfeel is very full and creamy , easily the strongest point of this beer . strong hoppy ale with a great mouthfeel .
this beer smells absolutely incredible , with an aroma of vanilla and caramelized sugar that is as close to actual creme brulee as i can imagine .  mouthfeel : pure silk from beginning to end .

a : pours black body with a two finger off white head on top . has good retention and lacing .  the taste is mellow chocolate on the front as it glides down with its thick silky mouth feel . almost a fudge aftertaste .

a hint of lactic acid and pale malts in the background make for a solid , enticing nose . admittedly , i 'm not the hugest sour ale fan . but this beer is good ... really good . overall , another insanely impressive sour from new belgium .  viscous , creamy and full . medium low carbonation .

the aroma of hops overwhelms in a good way -- floral , piney and fresh -- this scent should be captured and used as air freshners ( first 5 i 've given ) . this was very nice -- lots of fruitiness but not overly bitter , and i 'd put down 3 pints before i knew it .  sooo nice .

s - friggin wow . deep meaty dark fruits , sweet and thick , booze evident . happy to say .  with arthur , shaun consistently demonstrates his mastery as a brewer - and the mouthfeel department might be his greatest strength . this is exactly what i want my saison to feel like .
the smell is of orange creamsicle .  its alcohol is hidden well underneath my favorite part of the ride , the thick , creamy mouthfeel bcs provided .

still quite good . the beer has good thickness and breadiness .  medium-thick with a nice velvety feel in the mouth . high carbonation ; letting it sit in the mouth , one feels light bubbles on the tongue . pretty exceptional . yes .

smell is amazing with the usual toasted malts followed by a deep vanilla and cocoa nib aroma . it was subtle yet dominating .  would be better if it were more balanced with the malt . really velvety . nice appearence , really dark , good tan head tops it off .
pours a clear lemon yellow . a superb , thick frothy head leaves sticky lace .  has a perfect 10 body with an exhilarating highly carbonated mouthfeel .

nose was roasty and chocolatey , but more in the roasty department . i enjoyed it . taste was not as good as the nose .  juicy taste.. great medium thickness and silky texture . abv is most noticeable as a warming sensation in the stomach , and the fire definitely builds up down there . i can put away hercules like nobody 's business , this thing is a digestif at best .

s- has a very pleasant citrus/orange smell with a hint of malts .  a feel : i actually loved the medium-bodied mouthfeel as it just seemed to have a perfect flow across the palate with the hops and malts doing wonderful things to tickle me.. this is what a doppelbock should feel like.. drinkability : is ok - its a very strong beer and sierra nevada certainly did not try to mask the alcohol too well , nor the hops nor.. well , anything .

smell : it smells so good . extremely sweet and fruity smelling , bananas , apricots , peaches , flowers . it sounds unpleasant , and may be to some , but i like it . overall : lives up to its reputation , a great ale with an amazing smell and good taste , highly recommended .  extremely smooth with very fine bubbles of co2 , medium bodied , superb texture .

room temperature or heated , the smell is just amazing . it begs one to take a taste , and flows right through the flavor reassuring one of the contents with a nearly overwhelming amount of cherries .  wonderfully dry mouthfeel .
smell is pretty citrusy with no hint of alcohol .  m : extremely full-bodied , thick and viscous . a big stout , but the alcohol is well hidden , a very smooth drinker .

good looking beer and even better smelling . this beer has been in my fridge for at least a half a year by now and it smells incredibly fresh right out of the bottle . floral hops jump out at you over a lightly present sweet malt . great ipa , once again i 'm jealous i do n't have access to this one more .  feel : low carbonation , rich full body , ridiculously smooth and creamy , somewhat dry finish . drinkability : fantastic english-style stout .

appearance : dark brown-black body with lighter brown around the edges . creamy khaki head sits on top and retains pretty well . great lacing for a barrel-aged beer !  matching taste and awesome creamy mouthfeel .

heavenly strawberry aroma with the delectable notes of lacto sourness . absolutely amazing , perfect blend of the fruit and lactic acid . lack of carbonation is a bit of a downer , but i am surprisingly still loving this beer , a delightful sensory experience . damn i love lambics ! i wish i had 20 more of these around , awesome beer .  extremely smooth and creamy mouthfeel .

creamy pleasures await the salivating husband springtime chills will come this beer started off promising but left a weird taste in my mouth . it is thick , creamy with a solid head but has a pretty unnecessary aftertaste . overall , it still is n't that bad of a beer in small quantities but the aftertaste becomes more noticeable the more you get through your bottle .  mouthfeel is medium to full bodied . incredibly creamy with extra smooth carbonation .

very nice aroma on this one . the bourbon and oak come through nicely . there 's also a slight fruity quality ... maybe raisins or dates ?  taste : excellent body , the cherries and acidity make a wonderful balancing act , the murky , yeasty funk is there and the alcohol is solid and warming at the end .

really super pretty pour for a scotch ale . nearly opaque deep dark red with a giant and wonderful head that 's stick and leaves great lacing . really it 's hard to come across a more appetizing looking beer .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is amazing . just about medium bodied with quite a bit of fine carbonation .

aroma shows wonderful complexity . deep rich fruity quality that surrounds roast , coffee , dark malt . this aroma is outstanding . black with 1/4 to 1/2 inch head that 's dark and steady . very attractive . flavor matches aroma , but carries with it more of the roast . might not have as intense character as others in this style , but overall an extremely pleasurable beer .  could be because of the spices , but it tastes more like a full bodied saison , with less yeast , and a well done version at that . it has a great texture to it , and the taste is amazing .

a 4.5 cloudy honey in color , big frothy head , excellent retention and lacing s 5.0 incredibly hoppy , as it should be - wow it sure really gets some points for the aroma ! !  `` imperial '' means alot here . good light malty base to keep this full & thick . very welcome bitter finish after the malt & citrous front end , nice & dry . like most rogue products , quite drinkable , but the taste of alcohol tends to put one off a bit .

the enormous and profoundly malty aroma delivered by phoenix red is exceptional . few beers can boast a fragrance this distinguished and robust . the smell is positively symphonic in its complexity and grace a standout feature to be certain . the taste doesnt fully carry the aroma as emphatically as one might hope . however , the malt profile is succulent and profound with the raw sweetness of unfermented wort . scale the bitterness downwards a notch or two and tilt this beer unabashedly towards the malt and i think phoenix red would give its arrogant southern cousin a good run for the money .  incredibly thick and creamy , and perfectly carbonated .

s - lots of pine and other woody aromas . t - piney hops dominate , with the oak adding a good deal of spiciness to the brew . malts are well-hidden , but just assertive enough to balance this enormous beer . d - to be honest , i ca n't see myself drinking more than one of these in a single sitting . it 's a damn good beer , but the spiciness of it is a bit much for me .  mouthfeel is oily , heavy and smooth with a low amount of carbonation , magnificent .
quite good aroma with nice complexity . the flavour is a bit weird when served cool but the aroma is great .  the mouthfeel is really nice .

oh , this smells nice . prickly grapefruit and sweet floral hops and caramel , smells like a juicy sweet citrusy west coast pale ale for sure . it 's a good beer , if one dimensional .  the lack of carbonation and warm temperature really allow these flavors to develop , creating a wonderfully complex palate . mouthfeel is full , rich , thick , and the finish is creamy . delightful . overall this is the best blue point has to offer , and on cask it 's even better .

musty and dry . as the beer warmed , the mustiness really intensified . extremely acidic . earthy , musty , funky and barnyard-y.the dry , semi-tannic finish was oaky , funky and musty with an intense lemony tartness .  the mouthfeel is what really stands out about this beer , it is very coating and penetrating , a very different sensation from most other beers .
the smell is a rich milk chocolate and molasses malt with some hints of a citrus hop aroma .  perfect mouthfeel .

quite a big scent , quite complex , and excellent . t : a great tartness blend of cherry and green apple . a beautiful wood subtleness in there - not quite as complex as the scent suggests , but nice nonetheless .  mouthfeel - perfect . so smooth .

i can smell strong boozy notes up front and immediately upon putting my nose to the glass . very enjoyable nose . the alcohol is very strong in the taste as well .  mouthwatering feel that 's very creamy and silky smooth with a grainyness that 's pleasing .

5.0 s : an exceptional smelling saison for sure . hay-like funkiness with subdued peach and apricot notes 3.0 t : compared to how good the nose is , the taste is rather flat though still pretty good .  in the middle there is a dry briney sort of flavor with just the slightest hint of salt , which just tingles on the tongue because of the delightful carbonation . this beer is delitefully light bodied with a zesty sort of carbonation that just feels great on the pallate .

the smell is extraordinarily fresh and shows a great bouquet of red fruits with a very enjoyable sweetness . the very dry hoppiness invades and conquers the mouth with together with some oily notes .  the mouth feel is big and round with almost a sticky lip smacking finish that is pleasant and has you eager for the next sip .
s : bitter chocolate with alcohol smell in the back and a smokey smell as well .  highly interesting mouthfeel does the trick .

the smell is quite nice and different . i 'm sure that this beer is past it 's freshness date and has had some exciting adventures between armenia and my computer desk here in boston .  high carbonation and a light body leave a mildy dry finish and a marvelous mouthfeel .
huge tan head .  delicious m - this is probably one of the smoothest beers i have ever had .

ahh ... if it smells like pumpkin pie , and tastes like pumpkin pie , is it brewed with pumpkin pie ? ) by the time it got to my table it has a flat head , but a nice orange-amber color in the bar lighting .  perfection . o= one tasty treat .

coffee , chocolate , brown sugar , prunes , and roasted malts come together to make this very delightful nose . smells are very sweet . bitter chocolate was the first taste .  m- creamy and oily at the same time . smooth with a lasting syrupy finish . d- absolutely delicious . unique with well-hidden alcohol .

the aroma was magnificent ! i would eat/drink this because of the scent ; be it beer , bread or blonde . i may not be able to describe great aroma , but i know it when i smell it . the taste was a let down after that wonderful aroma ( sniff ) . while i raved about yulesmith holiday winter ale , summer left me cold , just sweet and bitter mixed with no real purpose in mind .  very smooth body and almost creamy carbonation .
i love the color of this beer . medium to dark bourbon amber with good clarity .  mouthfeel/drinkability : mouthfeel is full , thick and creamy . totally awesome in my opinion .

a-nice cloudy gold with a thick cream colored head s-this smells great . it smells of banana and some funk . good strength t-comes in with a malty and faint taste of banana and some funk . m-light creamy carbonation with a watery finish o-the appearance and smell got me so excited but i was let down by the taste .  mouthfeel is great , super thick and creamy .

s : sweet , warming alcohol reveals a surprising and delightful layered floral fragrance . notes of violets , lily , and lilac . lush and romantic . i could n't stop sniffing this one . t : sweet and heady , corresponds to smell- fresh flowers , sherry with faint nuttiness , sweet warm alcohol . d : lush , heady , and strong , this is not a beer for pounding . a little bit goes a long way , plus you 'll want to savor it . best in easy doses .  m - so beautifully thick and creamy on top and then thinner once you penetrate through the top layer . a softly sweet mouthful . perfection .
ginger obvious on the nose as well as other exotic spices that gives a real pleasure to feel the drink .  mf- the feel is the best part for me .
whoa , very atypical aroma , with raspberry and strawberry scents as well as coriander and licorice .  a very drinkable dubbel with a smoothness that gives a fantastic mouthfeel .
aroma is a huge assault of leafy , citrusy hops in the nose and alcohol .  unbelievably smooth and creamy mouthfeel .

smell is awesome . molasses , musky spiced rum , raisins and figs and lots and lots of roast malt .  this brew shines in the taste and mouthfeel department ! extreme bitter hops up front and an alcoholic bite lingers .

very interesting smell - quite vinous with a good amount of red wine / vinegar in the nose . there 's a bitter aftertaste and unfortunately it smells much better than the overall taste .  the feel is outstanding . full bodied and creamy .

reviewed from notes : appearance : golden yellow orange with a 1 finger head smell : citrus fruits , caramel , malts , has a great nose taste : citrus , hops , bready , malts , mouthfeel : mild carbonation , medium body , overall : this is a very nice pale ale . i will have to agree with some other people that the nose on this beer was outstanding and since it 's the first reaction . the second is the taste and it could n't live up to the smell . but overall nice beer and glad i finally got to try it .  4/5 m : velvet in the mouth here with a medium fuller body and small carbonation . beautiful . 5/5 d : very easy going down and plenty of balance .

s : quite nice with a buttery apple sweetness with hints of orange peel floral hop character and a great malt backbone , very inviting i think my mouth is watering .  mouthfeel is full bodied , creamy , and quite smooth on the palate .
but the smell was awesome . very nutty and roasty with some barley noted .  mouthfeel is perfect , bright , but still substantial enough to stand up to the chicken .

the aroma is amazing- a wonderfully fresh coriander and thyme smell with underlying lemon . unusual and very interesting .  soft , so soft . like drinking velvet . it felt amazing and looked and smelled good . well worth trying for the texture alone .
aroma is pungent and excellent . loads of dank noble hops with notes of earth , minerals and lemon . much less bitter than expected , but still pretty good .  beautifully carbonated and smooth .

wonderful and rich aromas that are multi-layered and carry great depth and complexity . t- again , the maltiness comes out strong with a bug rush of oakiness .  f - the ultra-sticky , resiny feel we know and love . this is basically unchanged from the bottle .
