aroma is wonderful and distinctly of raspberry without being sweet or overpowering ( and to me , it smells natural , not of candy or raspberry flavored cough syrup ) .  the lactose makes it presence known as well adding the smooth and velvety creamy texture which is spectacular . overall this is one of the top 3 milk stouts i have ever had ; perfect example of the style .

the aromas are divine . vinous and chocolate malt mix a with notes of floral hops . the flavors are similar to the aromas , although there are some pleasant blackberry notes here too . a nice hop bitterness and flavor , but not so much that it is dramatically out of style .  mouthfeel smooth and creamy , with a full body and low carbonation .

aroma is massively malty , filled with notes of caramel , molasses , buttery toffee , toasted bread , honey , ripe fruit , and a whisky-like burn of alcohol . to bad the mouthfeel is so weak because the flavor and nose are both great .  m : full bodied and velvety smooth . there is enough carb there to liven this thick brew up a bit .

smell : the aroma is fantastic . this smells like peach yogurt , smooth and slightly sour , with a little funk lurking in the background . overall : drinking this was enjoyable , and the aroma in particular was fantastic . having only one flavor and not much depth takes away from any desire to revisit this beer though .  nice warming sensation from the alcohol . rich , velvety and creamy .

the complex aroma involves big dark fruits , sweet malts , grain , spice and bubblegum . goes slightly rough with a ubiquitous alcohol heat , which never bothers me .  the nose was somewhat sweet and the mouthfeel was really full , almost creamy , nearly belying the idea that it was cask-conditioned .

thin wispy tan head with quick dissipation but leaving of some nice soapy and sudsy lacing . smell is the amazing feat of the beer : a sugary caramel-like coating of the toasted hazelnuts with a hint of chocolate sweetness .  this was a surprise , very drinkable and excellent mouthfeel .
straight up clean alcohol with a huge ripe fruit aroma , rum raisin comes to mind as well as over ripe apples . hops are there but very faint .  mouthfeel is silky , creamy , like a milkshake .

the smell was very interesting . the first smell to hit me was viognier grapes . also some tart apple notes , as well as tropical fruits . it had a very complex yet pleasant taste .  this is a big beer , with a full body and a thick , syrupy mouthfeel . chewy .

extremely complex and intriguing . i am seriously digging this . awesome . d- for the abv and strong flavors , i notice my glass emptying faster than expected .  the thick mouthfeel is a st trademark style and it really works for this beer .
the aroma is alluring , rather heavy on hops would be my guess .  m- thick full body with some carbonation .
pretty full aroma . taste is very sweet .  probably the best balance of chocolate and stout roastiness i know of , with a smooth , somewhat creamy mouthfeel .

wow , what an amazing smell . t - slightly spicy at first , then comes the banana/yeast body , fluffy , and then it ends with the spices returning , plus a pleasant wash of clove . d - outstanding , could do this one anytime .  m- perfect for this style . the natural carbonation from the cask worked wonders and made the body feel extremely smooth .

s- the smell is the best aspect of the beer . coffee and dark fruits . smells of the best cherries i can think of . t- dry , malty coffee with a hint of dark fruits . really nothing special , but definitely better than `` average . '' m- in my estimation , this beer is medium bodied . d- 1. it is a stout .  mouthfeel was beyond exceptional with this beer .
s : definite raspberry , honey , and fruity alcohol in the nose .  very , very nice .

aroma is robust , bombastic , and delicious ! intense milky vanilla and toffee notes sweep the show , some light coffee tones , and it is a gorgeous phenomena . the flavour is equally intense , yet not as cohesive as the aroma . starts with both sweet toffee and dry roasted malts , continues with a dry coffee middle , although with an underlying milky and caramel sweetness . mouthfeel is medium-bodied , not as thick as i had expected , but this is a good thing as the flavour is intense enough on its own . wow , that was quite the trip .  perfect feel .

aroma is full of rich , complex malt . very complex and just big ! good toasty malt flavor with high alcohol providing most of the balance . a wonderfull beer , with excellent malt character .  m : extremely creamy and oily as it goes down . this is probably the smoothest beer i 've ever had . d : goes down so damn smooth . i found myself wanting to drink more just so that i could maintain the slick feel in my mouth .

smells great . big hoppy citrus nose . still , pretty tasty . good level of bitterness .  goes down smooth with no bite at all and finishes crisp with just the right amount of dryness on the palate . just as good as their vollbier . great stuff .

s - strawberry and figs no fusil despite the 13 % . very pleasant . makes me remember happy christmas things , snow and fireplaces and cinnimon buns cooking in the oven . m - aside from the scalding burn it 's nice .  mouthfeel is smooth and creamy ... excellent ... one of the best .

overall the really nice smelling hops come through .  like velvet as it goes down , with a nice bit of prickly carbonation . very nice body for a regular ipa . not watery or lacking at all in this department .

smells of fresh grinded pale malts and caramel apples . very fresh and lush , almost syrupy . smells spot on to any decent german bock i tried . the scent of this beer was the highlight for me .  big abv but not hot , well carbonated , the amazing mouthfeel , fantastic complexity and drinkability .
the aroma when first poured reminds one of a freshly baked pumpkin pie .  mouthfeel is perfect : medium carbonation and medium body .

on the nose with cherries , literally . fragrant cherry aroma hit me immediately . looks great in my duvel glass , perfect lacing and nice head . as it warms , noticeable oak , well balanced . drinkable ?  m : medium body , just about perfect carbonation .

i thought it would be overly sweet , but it was very tastefully done . very tasteful . i loved the smell and the taste . big fan .  t- super balanced across the board . m- very balanced . d- delicious .
this is really complex and amazing . t : sweet sugary malt . caramel and toffee .  m - the feel is amazing . it begs to be savored over and over again .
great nose that did n't come through in the beer at all .  carbonation is spot on . very gentle carbonation , just how i like it .

smell : there are lots of sweet fruity/estery note coming from this beer . i get notes of banana , papaya and passion fruit . taste/palate : its firm medium body has an overly sweet character which becomes cloying after about half the pint . as the aroma suggested there are loads of tropical fruit flavor notes with sugary and bready/malty sweetness . no trace of hops or hop bitterness can be found to give any balance and there is just a very slight hint of booziness .  '' i in truth have never experienced a mouth feel that was so smooth that packed that amount of flavor , but the downfall with most dark beers is while they taste great , and may have a great mouth feel , you never really want to just drink them non stop .

the spices are a little out of balance , mostly because the cinnamon seems to dominate , but it still has a nice pumpkin pie flavor and aroma . the hops are subtle , which seems appropriate . it 's somewhat cloudy , but i 'm not sure if that 's what we should expect in a pumpkin beer . overall the beer is quite drinkable if you like the style .  mouthfeel= nice creamy mouthfeel .

quite delicious . t : not as hoppy as the nose suggests with a lot of rum-like sweetness coming through on the palate .  nice full mouthfeel that 's not sickening like some can be . carbonation is perfect .
very nice nose on this . 4.0 t : the taste is good , but it 's missing the thick , aggressive sweetness that defines the style .  felt outstanding in the mouth .

t : this is only my second roggenbier and i really like it , although i remember liking troegs ' a little bit more . everything from the aroma was here , making for a deliciously refreshing beer . it tasted and smelled great regardless .  mouthfeel : this is one of the best feels i have gotten from an ipa . unbelievably creamy , with a light level of carbonation .

poured into my st. bernardus watou glass a very nice black color , very high carbonation , very nice huge three finger creamy tan head , which just leaves some small islands in my glass .  more malty sweetness under it all ( caramel and toffee ) m- full-bodied , creamy , smooth , ca n't really imagine it any better d- very solid beer , easy to drink and very happy to receive this gift
smells fantastic , aged pungent .  medium-bodied and silky smooth cask mouthfeel . long finish .

very complex nose of the classic belgian kind . doughy white bread yeast surrounded by light skin fruits and minor citrus . sweet but not as much as the scent led me to believe .  mouthfeel is superb , full bodied and zesty .
smell- very lovely aromas from this light brew .  m - incredibly creamy mouthfeel .

scored this little treasure from scoobydank a- a light yellow beer with a decent head s- hoppy citus with a grassy smell . you can smell the freshness in this one . this beer just pops at you has a malty character in the nose as well . one of my faves . t- a great juicy citrus beer that hangs around for a short time and fades quickly . i think this beer is amazing right when canned , but losses its flavor drastically fast . m- very light on the carbonation .  mouthfeel is thick and lush . wonderful overall , a great scotch ale .

take a big huff and the smell is wonderful . sticky piney hope . orange , grapefruit , clemintines , and floral soap . the bartender said there were four different hops one of which was centenial causing me to hesitate as i try and avoid peppery , centenial based ipas .  pours a murky gold with an insane pillowy head that i had to eat with a spoon before i could finish my pour smell - all i pick up is apples taste is sweet spiced apples and light grain this beer has perfect mouthfeel - light crisp and creamy with very active carbonation drinkability is almost perfect - had to take off .5 because all the carbonation made me burb too much overall this is a great summer/fall brew .

a : crystal clear medium amber body beneath a very nice three-finger head of soft , frothy white foam . great rocky retention , and plenty of lace . gorgeous beer .  mouthfeel is excellent the lacing is about medium . had it in a six pack from local store .

poured into an impy pint glass a darker shade of brown with some dark orange tint a craterouslight brown one finger head atop that settles quickly into a creamy-like mass.big caramel notes when the bottle was first popped open fruity esters began to settle in after a bit as well as some engraned brown sugar hops peak thru with a hint of herbalness.a somewhat sharp mouthfeel stings a little at first seems a bit fizzy , the mouthfeel takes away from the flavor a bit in my book its malt tilted no doubt caramel and borwn sugar sweetness dominate the alcohol shows itslf no doubt with a finishing burn honestly i dont pick up alot of hop presence other than a hint of herb in the finish.it started out promising but seed to fizzle out a bit no pun intended still not all bad .  mouthfeel is very viscous and rich , probably my favorite part of the beer .

s : great smell , on first opening the bottle you get a burst of pine hops , very pungent . t : at first i thought i was going to try and compare this to pliny the younger , but that is a fallacy , they are completely different beers .  digging the mouthfeel on this one . it 's damn near perfect for the style .

the smell is very fruity , bready , and light scent ; almost smells like a white zinfandel , and very little like beer . it smells almost exactly like fruitcake ! great to look at and smell but not much to eat ( or drink in this case ) ...  mouthfeel is full and round .

smell : ok , i think i 've nailed it : fresh cut lumber . yes , this beer smells like sawdust , home depot , and all the good memories you have from your days with a circular saw .  m : exceptionally not that big while being silky smooth . too sweet imo , but still the individual flavors of the beer were pretty good and the mouthfeel were simply phenomenal .

s : raspberries , sour funk , straw or hay . here 's hoping ... t : extremely acidic , tannins , abv well evident . there is a certain amount of challenge i do n't mind , especially in a wild ale or gueuze , but this tastes more like a less refined attempt .  the mouthfeel are carbonation is excellent so this makes the drinkability high .

massive floral hop aroma with citric and sweet malty undertones ... smells like a freshly-mowed field of hops , if there was such a thing .  i really enjoyed the balance of flavors and the wonderful mouthfeel .

we shared this in pint glasses so did n't get the full effect , but it 's quite nice looking . aroma is very pleasant with hints of both dark , black coffee and espresso , as well as some bitter chocolate . flavour is a bit disappointing after the aroma -- not bad , but very one dimensional black coffee . honestly , not something i 'd purchase again -- i love coffee , but there are a lot better coffee beers out there , and i do n't think a doppelbock is the best style for it .  mouthfeel and drinkability are both top-notch . smooth , silken texture that sticks around just long enough to show off a pleasantly sweet aftertaste .
*i did not mind it and would not buy again* app : looks great big and sexy .  the feel in the mouth was outstanding and was that of milk or cream .
the aroma was pure raspberry and lots of it .  very slight carbonation .

smell : strong . chocolate , apricot , raisins , yeast , alcohol , nice dryness hidden among the sweet overtones . good and calling this an `` extreme beer '' is a good thing .  first sip smooth silky texture and average body with fine fizzy carbonation . easy drinker that has a very nice feel to it .
smell was fantastic . fruity raspberry sweetness .  huge thick luscious body .

the pour yielded a very lovely light maple hue with a nicely formed white head . bands of white lace and well retained . wonderfully clear .  the body is just right , medium and silky , silky smooth .

s- some hops , and some nice sweet notes , like a raspberry with a little tart . t- woah .  the mouth-feel was great , champagne liveliness that excited my tongue . i wont have this too often unless i am teaching a friend about trappist beer or have a specific craving upon seeing the bottle .
the smell hit me the second i opened the bottle , strong floral hops , something sweet in there as well .  big powerful mouthfeel with a puckering of the tongue due to the hops .

aroma is amazing spicy and malty and perfumey . malty and slightly sweet . carmel and toffee . very drinkable but it does not live up to its wonderful nose . mouthfeel is full .  o : very good eye appeal and remarkable mouthfeel .

excellent smell on this one , dank and juicy ! flavor is slightly less then potent , especially after such a strong nose .  mouthfeel is , on the contrary , excellent . extremely creamy and smooth , with good carbonation .
a : massive 4-finger rocky white head takes forever to settle . like meringue on a pie . huge icebergs of foam cling to the glass .  ultra creamy mouth feel , smooth .
no hops to speak of , very nice . full points for aroma .  m : fantastic amount of carbonation .

blonde hop monster was served from a 12 oz . bottle , with a rather home-made looking label promising of hoppy goodness . the nose was awesome , beeming with a mouthwatering hop bouquet of fresh acidic orange citric , floral peach , perfumey ripe fruit , and subtle resiny notes to die for . a good matching bitterness was present throughout , and the finish left orange-nectarine essence .  m : incredibly smooth .

a large inch and a half fairly frothy white head . excellent head retention .  huge full body with medium carbonation ; very creamy and slick mouthfeel that goes down fairly smooth . a bit of alcohol noticed in the back of the tongue , with a decent sized warming on the finish .
t - caught me off guard a little bit , was expecting some nice complexity from the nose ... but not so much .  m-medium carbonation , nice creamy finish , just perfect !

the aroma is excellent , very german-hoppy and dank at first , though this develops into a fresher herbal character . the flavor is a bit thin for a pils , and i was expecting a lot more based on the aroma .  ( m ) - smooth as silk . spot on carbonation level .

a- pours black with a thin white head s- cold cold coffee or cafe mocha t- dark chocolate , coffee , and roasted malts m- satin with vanilla bean finish d- not for the faint of hearts , excellent example of a porter .  it is thick with a slight creamy feel to it . interestingly , the 7.2 % abv is hardly noticeable alongside the bold flavors this beer embodies .
rich , golden amber in appearance , this american classic poured into my dogfish head ale glass with a massive head and seriously huge lace .  it has a fabulous creamy mouthfeel .
smell : nice , nutty caramel sweet goodness ! good buttery carmel nutty finish though .  mouthfeel is just about perfect for an ipa .
the smell is malty ith a berry scent .  it has a really creamy mouthfeel as well .

s- big peaty malts , as expected . t- follows the smell with peaty malts , and a good dose of caramel .  m = heavy body , exceptionally good mouthcoating , luxurious creamy feel , slight heat from the alcohol , but no medicinal alcohol tastes .

4.5 s : lots of barnyard funkiness with a good deal of brett . very nice . 3.5 t : surprisingly sweet .  it feels really silky on the tongue , almost like chocolate milk , but the taste was surprisingly bitter .

smells like fresh peaches with hints of bubblegum and vanilla . i ca n't really decide if the flavor is to style or not , but it is pleasing .  the mouthfeel , i am guessing due to the aging , is nearly perfect . just a hint of spiciness on the palate leaves this fairly dry and wonderfully smooth .
aroma : sweet , malty with aroma of caramel , honey , raisins and spices .  the fruity flavors go nicely with the crisp mouthfeel , perfect for the style .

incredible vanilla nose impresses as soon as the cap comes off . sweet vanilla kicks things off . roast coffee perking underneath . sweet but not over powering .  this brew is full bodied and creamy smooth .

these aromas are all over the place and quite exceptional with figs , molasses , licorice , dark fruits , and toffee .  mouthfeel is thick and rich with a low/moderate carbonation that allows everything here to sit , settle , and linger .

body is a pale yellow straw . s - earthy . carnations , rose stems , hay , yeast .  creamy and thick , one could even say there 's a slight syrupy quality to it , but that is to be expected to an extent from this style . still , an outstanding beer and a great intro to duck rabbit for me .

poured into a samuel adams new glass appearance - 5 pours a nice one inch head . i 'm getting thirsty .  m - this one feels zingy and electric on the tongue , and the hoppy aftertaste is really nice . wow ! d - this could become a summer staple in my beer fridge .
aroma is sweet fruit with white grape and melon dominating .  mouthfeel : terrific . full bodied , smooth , and creamy .
it has a pleasant sour/spicy aroma at the end coming from the blend of spices and/or yeast strain used in the brew .  perfect as far as i 'm concerned for an imperial stout .
i love that smell . taste is like smoke sausage .  thick mouthfeel ... which i really like in a stout .
awesome aroma though , full of chocolate , raisins and all manner of malty goodness .  m - full bodied and well balanced . just wow .

it smells delightful , to be sure , but taste is simply roasty .  mouthfeel this one is a hair above medium-bodied , its actually on the lighter side for the style , with fluffy cheek-puffing carbonation and a light alcohol warming . but man oh man this beer defines a velvety mouthfeel .

nose that is a big and pure and assertive gewertzraminer wine grape with that sweet apple and spicy character . the nose is the real winner and strength of this brew . nice acid in the sour character that makes this a nice food beer . love the nose ; flavors are wanting .  m : one of the more viscous porters , has a feel more in line with a stout . extremely smooth and creamy , finish is perfect bitter sweet ( and the hop presence does n't wear out it 's welcome ) .

the smell is pure , unrefined malt syrup , and it is wonderful . i could smell this all day .  very smooth mouthfeel , almost perfect . went down smooth , but not really a sessionable beer , can drink more though .

very mysterious combination but intriguing combination . hopefully this improves in taste with time , as deschutes recommends .  the mouthfeel here is awesome . medium-full body , very chewy , even tannic almost .

nose is full of those oily west coast hops . citrusy and flowery , hints of grapefruit , sweet pine needles . breathtaking . light bready malt prevents a classic overhop . just an amazing aroma . major bitter woody hops , leaving a stinging aftertaste at the swallow . but a top shelf imperial ( ish ) ipa .  a silky smoothness and a sugary thickness finished up a fantastic drinking experience .
the nose is excellent , i sensed aromas of candied prunes , cranberries , and malt .  this is among the thickest , chewiest , densest body i have experienced .
a- this beer looks perfect for the style .  coated everywhere , and felt so smooth .

the aroma is medium in strength , pretty nice and complex . bourbon , oak and vanilla present a lot , a pretty nice mixture of the three . overall , another fw disappointment to me .  m : huge body for the abv with very light and fine carbonation giving it a very soft , silky texture . quite dry with a lingering bitterness .

s : wonderful brett aromas . awesome . t : funky barnyard , hay , grass brett flavors that follow the nose . again , very complex and awesome . m/d : a light to medium body that is crisp dry and very refreshing .  the mouthfeel is fantastic , a smooth , airy , coating ; just perfect .

huge coffee aroma immediately upon pouring , along with a little roasted malt . this was a decent beer , but was somewhat of a disappointment in the taste , after such an amazing smell . in the end the beer was good but i wish the flavor had more of a coffee punch .  m : very creamy and smooth . fairly thick in the mouth . quite strong .

the nose is beautiful ; smells exactly like hops added very late to the boil . wonderful ! some maltiness too .  mouthfeel is right where a saison of high quality should be . high carbonation , incredible dryness , and a nice drinkable viscosity .

( t ) - much more pine presence than what the smell foretold , however the fruits are there too ; just more subtle . a good malt backbone with bits of caramel sweetness . a decent balance with a hop forward piney bitterness . good malt backbone . does tend to get rather bitter the more into it i get . ( d ) - a solid dipa with a serious hop profile .  mouthfeel : full creamy body .

s - hops . possibly cascade and summit , maybe a dash of simcoe . smelled of citrus and floral , mixed with some slight pine and earth . d - i liked this beer , thanks to a trade with ba ricksawyer i was able to get two bottles of this lovely beer .  m-just perfect carbonation .
delicious smell ! i could sit and sniff at this all day .  m : the flavor is great but the mouthfeel is the best aspect .

d - the most outstanding element of this beer is the spectacular aroma . the clove notes are more distinct and clear than those of any beer i have ever had ; like a handful of fresh cloves .  amazingly chewy .
the aroma is really amazing : spices are very predominant ( not sure if added , or ferm .  the carbonation is perfect ... d : a really good beer .
the aromas are brilliant : vanilla grape jam coffee cream and cigarrettes . back off on the ibus and this might be a perfect porter .  m- thick , chewy , syrupy , pillowy , warming .

s : amazing unique nose on this beer . the vanilla and cream come through in amazing amounts . quite good .  the mouthfeel is marvelous , again especially for a bottle . full body , silky texture , very low carbonation .

s- the smell is quite complex . very rich aromas of cocoa , vanilla , and toffee with hints of rich , dark malt , malted milk balls , caramel , oak , and a touch of delicious bourbon-y goodness . t- the taste is n't quite as pronounced as the smell .  f - beautifully silky-smooth . perfect carbonation level .

seriously complex stone fruit and heavy malt aroma . the type of beer you could easily sit back and sniff for a good while before drinking .  mouthfeel : light-bodied but excellently carbonated ; frothy and velvety smooth . drinkability : flavorful and robust but still extremely refreshing .

the aroma is super strong and complex . it starts off with tons of cocoa and is very strong throughout . there are some good things going on here and if they tweak this it might be a good one .  thick , chewy and velvety smooth .

there is a big citrus hop aroma , more noticable than the malt or grains .  malty , hoppy , sweet are all combined in the taste . immense taste and great balance . i keep commenting on the balance but that 's the most remarkable characteristic of this beer . it 's not at all well mannered like a pliny the elder but it succeeds as a full on palate assault .
i kid you not . good finish . m - good carbonation and coating .  the mouthfeel is a little shy of medium-bodied , and has the perfect amount of carbonation and feels just right .

s- sour , grapefruit/lemon , sour green grapes and some red sweet grapes , some funky barnyard underlying .  feels great . milky , sweet , toffee malt , light coffee , light chocolate milk . carried very nicely by the density . its all there . a meal and dessert at the same time . fantastic .
the aroma of coffee , cream , chocolate and soft and roasted malt .  awesome texture , just a very slight tingle from carbonation , great body , great feel .

s - strong bouquet of citrus hops jump off right out and intoxicate the aroma . very inviting . t - mostly dominated by grapefruit hops , but somewhat muted compared to what the strong aroma suggested .  as expected for a cream ale the mouthfeel is like silk . packs a punch but not at all rough on the edges , smooth as silk .
nice spicey hops aroma . the malts and hops combine to almost give a light cinnamon and pumkin sweet aroma , before tha hop citrus smashes that to bits .  excellent for the style .

no head retention , some lacing ( beer engine would n't have hurt ) smell ; riot of frutiness , raisins , dates , honey & alcohol taste : alcohol , frutiness & intense dryness . tart , tart finish with wheat malt hints mf : syruppy but way under carbonated alcohol taste intensity makes this 2 beer max for me .  mouthfeel was thick and creamy like it should be .
aroma is sweet and malty . a touch of hops ... very tiny grapefruit afternote .  mouthfeel- super velvety smooth ! drinkability- the mouthfeel alone make this brew worth trying .

sublime . the taste is a bit too sweet and lacks a deep rich maltiness i have come to expect in the style .  mouthfeel is wonderful ... velvety smooth , perfectly rounded , syrup-like without overbearing stickiness or thickness ... just perfect .

smells nice as soon as i pour . coffee notes and some sweetness . even some floral notes .  founders black biscuit does n't have the intense flavors to blow you away but it 's incredible balance and perfect mouthfeel make it an extremely impressive offering .
salami and smoked ribs come to mind . worth a try but nothing real special going on here , imho  m : fantastic blend of carbonation , sweet malt , and bitterness . goes down very easy .
this beer looks great . it 's extremely carbonated and pours with a huge head , at least 8 fingers worth .  mouthfeel is perfect for a dipa -- not too syrupy/thick , not too thin .

pours a hazy dark golden orange with a huge rocky creamy off white head that retains well and laces the glass .  mouthfeel : well carbonated , creamy and very , very smooth . this brew is extremely smooth and drinkable .

not my favorite of the varietal series . a nice pine cone and deep woody nose tops a smallish head on top of a light/medium copper body .  incredible balance , not quite the devil its name makes it out to be . light to medium in body with lots of carbonation and incredible drinkability .

this is from a 6 pk picked up at the local grocery this has to be the freshest batch of goose isl ipa i think ive ever had , first it didnt look amazing out of the glass which isnt anything new but boy when you get to the nose on this one its all citrus and floral and a light malt backbone , the taste is right on par with the nose and has a wonderful fresh hop taste with a good solid bitter , this is a stunning beer which hasnt happened ever before when ive drank one of these .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy . the aftertaste is extremely clean ; not sticky , dry or anything bad .

s. the hops are over powering . i knew it was an `` indian '' brown ale but that was a surprise . caramel and maybe some coffee in the smell . t. this is a good brown ale that just is over whelmed by hops . this is a very enjoyable beer , but perhaps it 's just not for me . i enjoy the flavor but it 's too much of a mix between a great dark beer and a refreshing ipa and it leaves my mouth confused .  wonderful smooth texture .
despite the wonderful smell and nice color i was not impressed with the mingling of cherries and nutmeg .  top-notch mouthfeel , creamy frothy and just a hint of rawness .
s- chocolate , hints of coffee and licorice . toffee undernotes .  m- the mouthfeel on this beer is exceptional . it is smooth and heavy and clean from beginning to end .
beautiful reddish-brown with a thin but rich and persistent head .  m- full , smooth , creamy , oily , thick ... .pretty much exactly what i want in a stout .
s : like smelling a melted hershey bar . t : a blast of chocolate that slowly fades to hints of oatmeal/coffee/caramel ... reminds me of chocolate chip pancakes !  the mouthfeel is very thick .

very hoppy aroma , lots of citrus and dryness . grapefruit , some pine but more sweet grapefruit than dry pine . very balanced , very tasty .  quite a full and velvety body . it had excellent body too , and the alcohol was fairly well hidden .
s - sweet bread , buttery toffee malt . very inviting aroma . notes of pine and citrus .  mouthfeel is spot on : wonderful carbonation combined with a luscious consistency .

i smells like a malt bomb went off . surely to style and all , but the aroma promised a heavy beer , darn it ! good taste - very malty . no hops detected and , heck , you would n't want 'em anyway !  m - outstanding , big chewy dipa .

complex ! t/m : smooth body with date , toffee , caramel , and chocolate flavors . d : another excellent offering from clipper city . this one was great to sip .  the mouthfeel is particularly noteworthy , and every swig leaves a viscous coating of robust barley goodness on the tongue .

smell is a lot of chocolate , roasted nuts , beautifully rounded with an espresso aroma . complex . taste is similar , but more faint than indicated by the aroma .  average belgian pa that is saved by the incredible body that seems to be characteristic of italian craft beer .
smell : whoh nelly , fantastic funk going down on this one !  a solid milk stout , with good aroma and flavor , and impeccable mouthfeel .

one of the first fruit flavored beers i 've had that i could drink multiple of . a perfect blend of blackberry and wheat . the beer itself is a nice orangey , copper color and is somewhat hazy .  m - the best part about this beer is the mouth feel . it 's got the perfect mouth feel with a nice look and delicious taste to back it up .

this is the first chocolate beer i 've tried , and i expected it to be very dark and bitter . i thought it smelled great , it smelled like chocolate - as it should .  into the mouth it goes , the smoothness and creaminess of the beer is heavenly and excites me for the whatever flavor could be coming my way . pine , sticky sap , and caramel are among the flavors that rule it all .

aroma was excellent ; a great array of floral and citrus hops , a slight sweetness , and an earthy grass smell . very nice . unfortunately the smell does n't translate quite as well to taste .  very creamy and smooth . the carbonation is quite low which gives this even more appeal . perfect . d- not the most complex beer , but still something i look forward to drinking ( and collecting ) each year .

very , very well blended smelling . hints of lemon and mild cherry on the back . very good . t : wow , this is a bit of a disappointment at first .  mouthfeel - quite thick and chewy , you will know that much from the pour . perfectly smooth on the palate . slightly below average carbonation .
a very nice scent , with spices and sugar prominent , particularly cinammon .  the flawless velvety , silky medium body melts the flavours together perfectly .

appearance - dark brown color with a definite pronounced head with larger bubbles , very appetizing . smell - i love the way this beer smells . definite hints of coffee and other roasted goodies .  the mouthfeel is indeed creamy and the beer is quite drinkable . edit , re-review : had a bottle at the milwaukee airport 10/09 , and i was struck by just how creamy and perfect the mouthfeel on this brew is .

aroma is abundant with caramel malt sweetness , some green apple and a bit of melon .  the mouthfeel , however , is fantastic . this is an exceptionally smooth and creamy feeling beer , and it really improves the drinkability considerably .
s- great smell . citrus mostly with some really nice sweet tropical fruit notes .  rich , thick and full bodied , with flavors of brown sugar , belgian yeast , chocolate , booze and raisins .

deep ruby/amber pour with a large billowing and frothy off white cap . lots of nice lace is left on the glass , and the head retention is great .  taste & mouthfeel : insane smoothness rolls of the tongue like a million dollar beer if i ever saw one .
aroma is of pungent onion , leafy tobacco ... .interesting multi-faceted green noble hop smell .  mouthfeel is fantastic , thick and smooth , soooo smooth .

on the nose , this is where this beer really shines , and i have to give rogue credit for what they 've accomplished with this beer . there is a huge , smokey aroma , but there 's also considerable maple and bacon as well . there 's even a hint of salt on the nose as well , and i loved the combination of sweet maple , bacon and smoke in this beer . unfortunately ( i guess ) , very little of this comes through on the palate ... there 's a hint of smoke and maple , but otherwise this is a fairly bland , nothing special ale . there are no off flavors , and the beer certainly is n't repulsive ... it 's just kind of boring .  mouthfeel is amazing , thick , viscous , almost like a milkshake . best mouthfeel i have had in a beer .

phenomenal smell . bitter chocolate with espresso . but right off the first taste there 's something funny . then it 's really nice through the middle .  t/f : feel was wonderfully rich and creamy smooth , without being heavy , thick , or filling .

the foam reminded me a duvel s : smell is just perfect . a bomb of honey , pepper , clove , vanilla , fruits ( apple and pear ) and a bit of citric zest . malts , the traditional belgium yeasts and flowery hops are also very noticed t : follows the nose , however much less sweet than expected which is a very positive point here .  excellent body ; truly perfect for the style .

) poured into my large gulden draak tulip , john by is is a blackish brown with a ridiculously large dark tan head that has tediously long last leaves heavy lace .  the body to this brew is full and creamy which really gives it a nice mouthfeel for a barleywine .

it smells honkytonkin fresh , and i 've never had a bock this fresh so it is an experience . it has a nice subtle but noticeable hop character along with some fruitiness and nuttiness .  between medium and full bodied , the elements are peppery and memorable , and an underlying creaminess impresses like satin on the tongue .

s- raspberries covered in warm dark belgian chocolate with a hint of phenols in the background . d- decent to pretty good stout overall , it just needs some time to let the alcohol settle . the smell is immaculate and i wish it tasted more like it smelled .  a - a wonderful pale apricot topped with a pure white lace that fades quickly into the glass s - light and grassy , with a hint of the alcohol to come t - potent bitterness at the front mellows to sweet dried fruit flavors , with a spicy bitterness at the finish m - perfect ? in mouth feel is exactly balanced against the bitterness , and then coats the mouth to balance the lingering bitter bite d - dangerously so .

smell : outstanding . freshly squeezed orange juice and hop notes are present as well as a hint of grapefruit . i find it bland and boring . the smell promises great things but when you actually get around to tasting the beer you are sorely disappointed .  m - perfect . absolutely spot on with both body and carbonation .
either way , great stuff t/m : sweet sugary oaky fruit . overall , amazing stuff . d : pretty intense . god , i love toronado  dangerously tasty with an amazing mouthfeel .

s= huge huge floral boquet of hops , massive overdose of sniffing ; some hints of malts . great air-freshener or for someone with a sniffing obsession . great deodorant or cologne .  m-on the low side of medium carb the beer is very full and creamy with no detectable oiliness . the texture is possibly the best i have had in an ipa , and although not bitter enough to satisfy true hop heads , the flavor is very interesting and pleasant , and the aroma complex .
this is an extremely hoppy ipa , one of the hoppiest ever i think .  very easy to drink with a soft silken mouthfeel .

smell : a strong scent right off the bat . a good dose of belgian yeast rounds the nose out nicely . taste : like the nose , but unfortunately much weaker and less impressive , though still pleasant . sweet malt initially with some dark and red fruit , mostly berries and raisins .  absolutely perfect . d : thanks to jdv for this one .

poured from cask at the blind tiger ale house in nyc - got the last glass before they changed cask to brooklyn blast ( awesome beer btw ) for a brewery event first thing i noticed was the strong bourbon aroma - to be expected i suppose . not much head to be found in this glass . very smooth , tastes like bourbon as well - without the harshness though .  the texture rocks - silky and almost chewy .

aroma is incredibly rich , with fresh ground coffee , cocoa nibs , vanilla , roasted coffee beans , caramel , and a touch of oak . taste is not quite as explosive as the aroma , but still good . lots of coffee , roasted malt , caramel/vanilla sweetness , some toffee , and it finishes with some light astringency and whiff of alcohol .  i truly enjoyed every sip and the palate cleansing carbonation made every bite like the first . the carbonation and strong complex flavors force you to slow down a little to appreciate this truly unique concoction .

s : a wonderful blend of dark malty aromas and strong , lightly acidic , medium roasted coffee . the coffee smell is soft but dominates the aroma . if you are a coffee beer lover , this is where it 's at for coffee beer aroma .  soft and creamy texture , medium body and almost no carbonation . really nailed this .
the smell was absolutely wonderful , and was probably the best aspect of this sample .  - feels bloody velvet sick lovely .

it is juicy and resiny in the aroma . just wonderful . the flavor is juicy , and a bit resiny , with the grapefruit flavors coming through .  mouthfeel is smooth creamy heavy on the tongue a bit chewy nice , overall this is wonderful and ill never turn this down .
s : one of the best smelling pumpkin ales i 've tried . strong aroma of pumpkin pie spices , plenty of notes in it .  mouthfeel is very pleasing , smooth and medium bodied .

s- wow , some really dank hops ! ! ! i 'm hit with exceptional floral hops , lavender and jasmine , followed by citrusy hops and mangoes , you can get a very light sweet yeast smell in the backround but almost unnoticed . t- taste is nothing as promising as the smell , definate floral hop , lavender and jasmine , citurs and mango flavors are somewhat lacking almost a little watered down on the taste , of course it follows with a nice light belgian yeast to subdue the hops . nice light/medium body , would have liked more body , seemed watery .  m - full , rich , viscous , light carbonation , chocolate creamy finish .
pours an almost-perfect looking irish red . a great , bright red color with a thick white head that retains throughout the entire drink .  full , super creamy body .
smells wonderful ! big citrus notes with some grapefruit and a great citrus peel . bursting with aroma . taste follows the nose , but is a bit more subdued .  velvety smooth mouthfeel , actually .

hints of port on the backend . smells perfect ! t : a nice nice blend for a strong ale . some grape juice in the middle with some port on the backend . a nice clean finish . the nose was a bit deceiving because the booze bite smelled a lot stronger than in tasted . it is a very solid brew , and i would definitely like to grab a few more bottles .  silky in the mouth .
smells excellent . sweet , spicy graham cracker , hints of nutmeg , cocoa powder , vanilla , tootsie rolls and malt .  mouthfeel was smooth and silky . very nice ale .

this beer looked great , right from the start . nice nitro cascade as it was poured , resulting in a 2 finger thick creamy head that left a heavy lace from start to finish . color was an inviting gold/amber .  mouthfeel - very nice feel , smooth and creamy with the perfect amount of carbonation . the bottle conditioning really left a nice feel .

smell-wise it 's exactly what i 'm looking for - tons of subtly sweet floral hops . though this beer is complex and intriguing , it does n't leave me in the mood to have another . so this is n't an everday drinking beer , more a quality novelty .  fantastic mouthfeel helping to make this a truly drinkable brew .

served in a tulip glass , came to me as a beautifully perfect pour , a creamy full inch of head and a hazy golden amber .  m : creamy with a very smooth carbonation , tiny bubbles . and what a beautiful body .
appearance : the beer pours a dead black .  palate : perfect , really .
pours a crystal clear copper with a full off-white head that has stellar retention . torpedo is a very beautiful beer .  really good mouthfeel .

carmel sweetness on the nose . robust malts . surprising yeasty profile . musty . very complex and shifting nose . where does this beer start ?  mouthfeel is very smooth , with low to medium carbonation , and a full body .

s : a refreshing , sweet pine scent hits the nose with some lemon and spice behind it .  for all the previously mentioned bitter qualities , the mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth . perfectly carbonated .

s-heavy diacetyl aroma , malty backbone , with a slight citrus hop note . t- delivers what the nose promises , tastes buttery with a nice sweet malt backbone and finishes nicely with some bittering hops .  definitely a sipper d/t high abv , bourbon taste and thickness . one of the best imperial stouts ever .

tastes good too , a little bit less hoppy than it smells , but still good . tends to leave me with a slightly bitter mouth , but very drinkable otherwise .  t & m- big lush mouth feel with a long drawn-out smoothness .

s : you can easily smell the spicy notes , coriander , and lemon - a reviving scent . t : lemon and spicy/peppery at the start , but the lemon dominates the aftertaste .  a thick , chewy body rounds out the mouthfeel , and the full malt profile hides the alcohol while accentuating the flavors making this beer strong , but very drinkable .

the nose on this beer is great . rich chocolate malts , roasted malt , sweet milk chocolate , there is a hint of tootsie roll and powdered cocoa . very nice chocolate taste , but i dont think you would think this was beer in a blind taste test .  a fantastically smooth and creamy mouthfeel that leaves you begging for another pint .
had a very good aroma , fresh raspberries and a gingerbread malty .  mouthfeel is heavy as hell and thick , very chewy with minimal amount of carbonation , heavenly .
really , the coffee notes in the nose are fantastic . t : taste is really hitting the spot !  m : superb in my opinion .

aroma is of a simcoe forward dipa .  floral taste flows into a yeast-centric raisin and fig body with a clove punch and an incredibly round , estery mouthfeel that warms in the mouth as the malt matures . fruity , but in a fig sort of fruity way , with a round , peppery , malty , incredibly complex and balanced body that also possesses a certain nuttiness to it . very smooth .
i love the cascade effect from the nitro and the head that it leaves .  feels nice and chewy in the mouth and is quite drinkable despite the ever present tinge of alcohol .
really great looking beer .  awesome mouthfeel !

the perfect aroma is sweet candi sugar with just a touch of funk !  mf- is creamy and lush , big and forward . very inviting dr- needs time to age , a year or 2 will open this big bold beer imensely.lots of potential .

pours a cloudy golden with a huge frothy off white head .  m - super creamy and full bodied almost like pudding , this is the highlight of this for me , one of the best mouthfeels of any beer i have had .

smell : cereal grains , sweet brown sugar , nougat and toffee are all heavy aromas . creme brulee would be the best way to describe the aroma , to a `` t '' .  it has a very nice creamy mouthfeel to it that i really like in my stouts .

tart pineapple mysteriously emanates from this spiciness adding a wonderful dimension to this smell . the flavor stats with a pleasant strawberry and under ripe melon that is bombarded by carbonation , releasing a grapefruit rind and peppery yeast dryness that picks up hints of cardboard and copper in the finish . the smell is really the highlight , and it went down hill from there .  this beer has a very thick mouthfeel , with a creamy sweet taste to it . very nice thick and full mouthfeel . top notch balance between an easy initial crisp feeling , and then a thick and full finish .
the smell is wonderful , a clean citrus/grapefruite scent .  mouthfeel was superb . thick bodied , smooth and creamy .

s - big roasted grain character , earthy notes , smoke , chocolate , molasses , some alcohol . somehow distinctly european - fruity yeast character i think . t - taste is more in line with what i expect from mikkeller - roasted grains , smoke , char , slightly astringency , and not as much of the promised belgian chocolate .  texture is smooth , creamy , very thick .
not expected , but very nice . this light bodies brew first throws some bubbly on your tongue .  very nice full bodied mouthfeel .
the color is really nice ( caramel/orange color ) .  the mouthfeel is exceptional i believe .
s : big burnt malt character with lots of spicy hops .  m : like the taste , excellent creaminess to this one . utterly brilliant .

) s : very inviting ; white chocolate , melon , honeydew t : very good belgian-style ale ; pear ; not sweet ; not bitter ; rather boozy , so a good ride ; but it lacks the refinement of a classic belgian tripel m : viscuous ; needs better clarity overall , a decent solid beer ; not the finest example of its style , but a fine beer nonetheless  m - exceptionally smooth , a sight tingle of carbonation . a beer with a great body .

the aroma is very inticing - an inviting mixture of almonds , butter , coffee , burnt currant , toffee , plum , cherry , and the list goes on and on . after the swallow , a roasty coffee flavor combines with the almond and lingers pleasantly . the mouthfeel is luscious and creamy . overall , i came to this expecting to be underwhelmed or at best , mildly impressed .  great feel in the mouth , absolutely . fluffy and great body .

s : hot bourbon upfront with tons of maple and brown sugar . the spices that were easily noticeable in the other versions seem to be masked by the bourbon , but the oak backbone really kept my nose inside my glass for quite a while . t : the first thing i noticed was the thin and alcohol-like bourbon flavor up front , followed by strong maple and brown sugar . but overall , a near perfect flavor profile .  the mouthfeel is extremely thick and really coats the entire mouth .

it smells like fresh fruit and is simply amazing . from the smell i would n't call this one a wheat ale as it smells quite hoppy , but this is still one of the best smelling pale ales i have ever encountered . the taste does n't quite live up to the nose but it is still incredibly enjoyable . this one is super smooth and extremely easy to drink ... dangerously easy to put down at 7 % . drinkability would be higher if the flavor could match the incredible nose on this thing . mouthfeel is on the lighter side and the alcohol is not really detectable .  the mouthfeel is a strong point for this beer . nice a full mouthfeel with lots of fine carbonation and a dry finish .

samuel adams white ale boston beer company ( samuel adams ) style : witbier abv : 5.20 % bottle & gt ; imperial pint glass , reviewed 3/1/09 a 4.5 - amber/cloudy honey on color , noticeable suspended sediment in acton , excellent head , retention and lacing , tight collar and big foamy surafce bubbles s 5.0 - mild but complex spiced witbier aromas dance , exactly as i would expect t 3.5 - semi sweet on palate , mild tart on finish , complex spicy backbone mf - 3.5 - creamy and smooth on palate , low-med carbo , smooth mouthfeel , interesting d 4.0 - better witbier than most macro examples , excellent appearance and aroma , a nice surprise from the sa/boston team !  m : extremely smooth and creamy . great carbonation carries this beer . surprisingly my favorite part .

aromas are very pleasant - smoke ( burnt wood/campfire - maybe hints of some smoked meats ) , some roasted malt , and some sweetness with hints of licorice and molasses .  richly smooth and medium-full body .
super lacing & very good head retention s : plums , pears & apples t : plums , apricots & leafy hops up front .  mouthfeel is velvety smooth , thick & creamy .

i was very impressed with the nose on this beer . the aroma is fantastic and smells like a great belgian . so excited i was by the smell i was already thinking this could be a beer i would buy multiple sixers of . all ingredients thrown together with a yeasty malty finish .  flavors are big , and the mouthfeel is incredibly full and well rounded .

hard to explain this hefeweizen . i recommend it . has a huge head , great mouthfeel , and an excellent summer session brew !  body is thick , smooth , rich , creamy , and as close to perfect as you can get . an enjoyable , if strange , experience .

brandon : candied citrus , very good smell , the best aroma hop in this series of 10. very earthy flava flav .  for the style , this beer has incredible feel and almost unreal sensation of bitterness .
pours a brilliant orange with a frothy egg-white head . smell is strong of grapefruit and pine .  m - really shines here , with a nice , round mouthfeel . very nice .

beautiful s : tart cherry , bright citrus hop . layer of sweet caramel underneath . really interesting and inviting . dusty aspirin , a little cat pee ? overwhelming wildness . very funky . too dry and chalky and mediciney d : poor .  mouthfeel is appropriately thick and chewy .

for us people on the east coast it reminds me alot of dogfishhead 90 minute ipa , very hoppy . i am just not a big hop fan . i have tried russian river temptation and found it a very good beer and would still like to try pliny the younger if i ever get the chance .  mouthfeel is amazingly thick and rich .
really strong smell .  again the hop flavors are earthy and grassy m : good amount of carbonation and a good medium mouthfeel perfect for the style .
nose is absolutely awesoe . loads of freshly cut pumpkins and buckets of cinnamon and nutmeg .  m - big , full , and smooth , with just a prickle of heat .

gorgeous . taste - grapefruit ; a very astringent , bitter , piney hop flavor ; some faint , lingering malt , ultimately overpowered by the hops .  the carbonation is near perfect for me , not overwhelming like most pale ales .
smelled fantastic , takes citrusy to a new level .  m : perfection . my words simply ca n't do justice to the body of this beer .

aroma is complex and highly charged , resembling barleywine in ways . sweet , fruity , dark rum , mollasses , brandy , raisins , figs , cherries , and a huge whiff of alcohol . thick , warming mouthfeel , large malt presence , and a strong hop profile . great balance , in a big beer . uniquely tasty ! a flood of flavor takes charge on the palate , with strong , sizzling hops doing a wardance on the tongue . a remarkable beer ! i once taste-tested this against a regional version , leinie 's big butt doppelbock .  mouthfeel from the cask conditioning is amazing . smooth and almost creamy , very light on the tongue .

wo n't wear my sunday suit to walk that street that would feel byzantine 12 oz bottle ... ultra dark inky pour into my snifter with a nice thin mocha head that swells and then heads rapidly to lurk around the edges like some two-bit hoodlum .  excellent mouthfeel ... nice and viscose with just the right amount of carbonation and foam .

its very impressive how aromatic st got the chocolate character to be .  tastes strongly of the caramel and finishes with the hops and alcohol.. the full-bodied creamy mouthfeel and warming alcohol make this sipper a solid holiday barleywine .
appearance : pours a clear , copper body with a large , frothy , white head . gobs of sticky lace on the way down .  mouthfeel is extraordinary . everything about it is just perfect .
very exciting aroma . a very distinct and mellow chocolate nose .  really tart-fruity and tasty with an amazing feel to it .

smell : it has that signature west coast ipa aroma.. hoppy , citric , and piney . not to be forgotten , there 's a sweeping big malt backbone that adds a nice dimension to the beer while balancing out the hoppier character .  mouthfeel - very silky . just the right amount of carbonation drinkability - goes down really easily , but the sour might wear on me after a while .
aromas are oak like , of stewed fruit , cereal grains , and booze . finish has an alcohol kick and warmth to it .  excellent , ok heck , perfect mouthfeel for this beer .

it smells like roasted malt , oats and some chocolate . overall it 's a very sweet smelling beer .  mouthfeel is sublime . creamy , oily and full - this really just makes the difference between a good and great ipa for me .
nice head ( but disappeared quickley ) and fantastic aroma , maybe a little citrus here .  m : the mouthfeel is really excellent on this beer .

the aromas are very nice , the flavors are there but it 's just thin .  burnt brown head poured incredibly thick and foamy with very small bubbles and a meringue like topping ... a good one finger of foam remained throughout.. some thick lacing lines ... aroma - lots of roasted sweet chocolate malts backed with caramel and strong coffee , toasted nuts - hazlenuts mainly , quite earthy , some faint citrus notes , liquorice , brown sugar , honey notes , some light smokiness ... taste - tons of dark chocolate up front followed by strong black coffee notes , roasted malts , cocoa powder , some light smoke just coming through , dark fruits ( black cherries and currents ) , nut brittle , treacle / molasses , warming alcohol is just noticeable.. feel - smooth and velvety with just a little sharpness underneath ... full bodied ... pretty drinkable for an 11 % brew although becomes quite sweet towards the end ... overall - another superb example of an imperial stout from southern tier although again a 650ml bottle is way too much ... definitely recommended though ...

a= looks like yellow snow from someone who needs to drink more water . s= hops jump out and sting my nose . piney and grassy hops . so dissapointed . all i got was water to match the intense smell that burned my nose . dissapointed .  m- this is my 51st ba review and i have to say that of all the beers i have reviewed i think the sa octoberfest has the best mouthfeel .

aroma- has a huge pumpkin aroma from the beginning and light spices in the background . what i like most about the aroma of this one is that the pumpkin was so huge ! flavor- has nice spice and then finally pumpkin but very light with both of them . very sweet also and malty . not sure its in my top 5 of pumpkin brews ( except for the aroma ) . its still very good for the style !  mouthfeel is perfect , thick to go with the maltiness , and great carbonation to help the sourness .
delicious smell ! t - rather weak . huge disappointment after the smell .  velvety , smooth mouthfeel , goes down like a thai ladyboy hooker . it 's a wonderful texture , impeccable even .

smell is almost sour , some big yeasty notes , some lemon zest , a hint of darker fruit , some clove and some booze .  mouthfeel is exceptional , as a cream stout needs to be , and this brew from st. peter 's goes above and beyond .

as with the stone , beautiful sage notes , forest , meadow , glorious . almost seems to be a hint of heather in there , intoxicating . t : sage is immediate and full .  mouthfeel is perfection . silky , perfect body , great carbonation .
smell is great . fruity apples raisins and some malt .  mouthfeel is fantastic . carbonation is spot on .
very strong but pleasant smell . taste features plenty of sweet malt to balance out a lot of spicy , citrus hops .  m - thick and creamy without becoming chalky or cloying .

s : the aroma makes this beer into something truly special . a bit of fruitiness from the belgian yeasts play with the fruit bouquet coming from the berries . i love this . t : initially i was absolutely whalloped by the oak .  mouthfeel is very creamy and dessert-like . this one is truly a treat .

the smell is the most interesting part of the experience . citrus and pine aromas from the hops come through and blend well with a maple sweetness .  as smooth as they come , with a thick , luscious mouthfeel that does n't dissappoint .
smell is very good . smells of roasted nuts , caramel and coffee .  mouthfeel is great , thick and syrupy .

this is easily one of the best smelling brews i 've encountered in this genere . i love it . again , the combination of sweetness and bitter and tart hops creates an unusual , lasting aftertaste . the beautiful hops would be compramised -- and the food itself would be rendered bland .  m - fucking awesome . i ca n't describe it better .
( a ) - pours a clear yellow color that produced a good white frothy head with great retention behind it . plenty of lacing left behind as it slowly dissipated .  m - it was very soft and velvety .

s : citrus piney hop aromas up front with no malt presence and orange juice like notes popping in the nose as well . t : grapefruit hop bitternees with not much malt balance hints of celery , booze , and orange zest .  the texture is excellent for the style : creamy but not too heavy .
the nose on this ale is absolutely gorgeous however !  medium to full bodied and extremely smooth and creamy , definitely a sipper but it sure is a delightful one !
a - jet black color with a brown colored head .  the taste of faint coffee , caramel and roasted malt slid on my tongue like silk , not too cold and felt just right . nicely balanced .

nose on this one is very aromatic . lots of sweet ripe fruity esters . great sticky caramel malt body , works in perfect sync with other notes . aroma overall , is just perfect - lovely zesty fresh intoxicating fruity madness . very effervescent . by this , i mean huge . it 's zesty , highly sugary , and very assertive .  mouthfeel - wonderfully smooth , medium-bodied with a memorable resilience post-swallow .

smell : a very pleasant hoppy and fruity aroma on the nose .  m - great . it had an almost creamy mouthfeel that it reminiscent of a stout on tap ( not quite to the level of nitro-tap , but it 's close . ) d - the alcohol really puts a damper on drinking this beer , it 's overall lack of flavor strength does as well .

big and powerful passionfruit and fruit salad hop aroma , galaxy are used but i smell nelson sauvin too . the stone and wood boys have proved its possible . t- while crisp , tasty and unoffensive the flavour is a slight let down after the dizzying highs of the aroma . hops are fresh as you can expect and the malt is clean with hints of banana and other wheat like notes . nice thinking . d- top marks .  it has a perfect amount of carbonation and crispness .

the aroma is intensely hoppy with floral , piney , and citrus notes . still a very drinkable beer with great hop aroma .  however , the richness of those hops combined with the oppulent mouthfeel still make his a truly great ipa .

smell : this one is pretty complex . yeast is dominant , but also has hints of everything that makes a good doppelbock : caramel , molasses , cloves ( and other spices ) , citrus fruits .  nice carbonation o - it looks great and has fantastic mouthfeel , i just wish more of the barrel character came out or even more of the citrus ... just a bit one sided .
s wonderful , truly wonderful . all hops with just a hint of malt and cinnamon .  m - creamy and luxurious . the bite is done through alcohol rather than carbonation .

as soon as i popped the top of the bottle i was met with the amazing sweet , sour yeasty aroma with lots of esters , one of the most appetizing smelling beers i 've tried .  m - nice thick mouthfeel with minimal carbonation . very oily and damn smooth .

a gentle pour produces a thick , custard colored head , the consistency of the foam is creamy and milky . lacing is gorgeous , very delicate bubbles slide across the glass . the body color is the same as the brown bottle glass .  mouthfeel is amazing , an incredible smoothness and creaminess . very full and round in the mouth .

'' review from a rare growler.. very nice doppelbock ... .cola colored ... minimal head ... great nose of sweet malts ... black cherries ... .raisens ... .dates ... .molasses is very evident ... and brown sugar ... brown sugar ... lower carbonation but full bodied ... rich and smooth ... .good dose of alcohol spiciness on the finish ... very sweet flavor ... .nice clean sweetness though ... tight..flavors mimic the nose but do n't quite match in strength.. this is a high abv brew and you can taste it ... nice example of the doppelbock style ... .i wish this could sit for about 6-12 months as i feel the `` heat '' would tone down a bit and the malt flavors would blend even more nicely ... but out of a growler it is not possible ... great winter warmer ... as i type this it is -15 outside and i am warming up immediately ...  it is milkshake creamy and is truly amazing . i have not read catherine the greats review but i hope she appreciated it in 1795 as much as i did in 2011 .

aroma was fantastic - tons of warm winter-feeling spices , like opening a spice cabinet or entering a spice shop .  feel : low carbonation , smooth body , exceedingly thick and creamy ( almost as much as the egg nog i had earlier ) , dry finish .

aroma makes up for what this brew lacks in looks ; wonderful , wonderful aroma of dark cherries , some cinnamon and apple . i considered this a good thing , but if you 're turned off by cherries this will decidedly not be your deal for the taste carries over the cherry aroma . really pretty great stuff , but not your typical drinking experience by any means , and definitely for special occasions .  m : this is where this beer really shined for me .

smell is really good on this beer , unfortunately it is far and away the best part about it . light caramel maltiness with a healthy dose of alcohol . bready yeast aroma as well . i enjoyed this beer , especially the aroma . a whole bomber to myself might be a but much , but i think it is a decent american tripel .  m : very full bodied and it is like i am eating a fresh piece of grapefruit when i take a sip .

the aroma is a true gift . many good smells involved ; clove/orange/spice/even cotton candy . another truly wonderful belgian offering .  mouthfeel was superb . very smooth and thick , and with just enough carbonation .

the pour dropped a nice 2 finger cream head that receeded and left great lace . this is one seriouly good looking beer .  this has a nice , smooth mouthfeel , and the foam leaves a good lacing around the glass .

i like the bell 's two hearted ale and when i spotted a single case of bell 's hopslam in my neighborhood beer distributor , i had to purchase the case served into a shaker pint glass . s : the most amazing aspect of this beer is the smell . i detect a mix of grapefruit , orange and pineapple aromas . t : for a beer whose label declares it to be a `` biting , bitter , tongue bruiser '' , it has a nice sweet malt backbone . notes : this is a pricy beer , but a must try for any hop head .  mouthfeel is full , rich and lush . i almost wonder if they added some maltodextrine to beef up the mouthfeel .

s : outstanding aroma , and not what i expected from a saison . a light yeast funkiness comes through shortly after that , adding balance and complexity . outstanding .  there feel is pure perfection . it coats the mouth and leaves a satin residue in the finish .

aromas of smoked meats , chocolate , peat , and woody . tastes of smoked meats , woodiness , a pile of raked autumn leaves , vanilla , and very light whisky .  wonderfully thick and viscous in mouthfeel , slick with a subtly prickly carbonation teasing the tongue .
startling aromas of grow-room just before harvest seem appropriate to the style . very assertive .  the feel is full , velvety , and soothing .

purchased through west lakeview liquors , chicago price - $ 10.99/6-pack appearance : wow , this beer looks awesome in a glass .  m : the mouthfeel is exceptional . a very nice silky smooth body with light fluffy carbonation .

this has an intriguing , absolutely wonderful aroma to it .  m : fantasticaly smooth - medium bodied , fine bubbles . velvety ! d : gettin ' up there in abv % , but this one 's just really well crafted - better so than the unearthly , in my opinion - and is one of the better dipas i 've had the pleasure of trying .

s : hoppy pine aroma with a fruity afterthought t : very strong initial hops taste that leads into a fruity citrusy feel that overwhelms your palate . hops tastes like christmas barf/potpourri but it smells a lot better than it tastes  this is a little heftier than the supposed style stalwart , hoegaarden , but the soft , almost creamy mouthfeel makes this a surprisingly satisfying beer without being heavy .

wow . otherwise , this beer is incredibly complex , with aromas of chocolate and vanilla , coupled with the cognac brandy smell . the flavors on the palate generally replicate the nose , except the brandy flavor is a bit more subdued .  full bodied , silky smooth and creamy .
the aroma on this is crazy good . malts , coffee and an irish cream aroma , smells even better than it tastes . very good but not great .  m - super creamy , coating the whole mouth . very nice .

i 'm really impressed . the flavor is definitely like a hefeweizen . the flavor is n't quite as strong as the smell , but it 's still really good . it 's cloudy and thick , but it goes down very easily and paired well with some pasta .  m : super smooth with a thick body .
hot damn that smells like pumpkin pie .  m : low carbonation yields a smooth and silk laden mouthfeel .
smell : sweet fruity esters come out with brown sugar and one of the greates smells of all time ... vanilla cake !  very impressed d- good imperial stout , great mouthfeel !

aroma is excellent . behind some lemon and sourness i almost get a west-coast ipa - apricot , grapefruit , orange , tangerine , maybe a bit of pine .  m - full bodied , sticky sweet but not cloying . coats the mouth perfectly , with a touch of dryness in the back end . good carbonation , too .

aroma - definitely it 's best quality - sweet pumpkin pie - sugar - cinnamon - nutmeg - malty taste - sweet and pumpkiny up front - hoppy and dry finish - not a bad combination - very suprising and unique mouthfeel - smooth - carbonation not overbearing drinkability - great pumpkin , but i like this style a tad bit more smooth and sweet at the finish .  the mouthfeel is right on the money !
monk madness smells of fresh doughy bread , also kind of piney and sweet malt aromas .  feels like liquid velvet , as all of the best tripels should , imo .
the aromas were permeating- harsh cirtusy hops , leafy rawness ; great for a refreshing aroma , though the maltiness is lost almost immediately .  the mouthfeel is a pleasurable experience .

aroma - overpowering smoke and meat aroma which is indistinguishable from cooking sausage . awesome i ca n't imagine a better smoked aroma .  flavor is exceptional , very subtle and complex on the palate full body excellent complement to the flavor .

on tap at churchill 's pub & grille in san marcos , ca a- crimson copper with bright garnet hues , two finger off white head , good retent , leaves thin lacing s- sweet , malty , caramel , toffee , pine , citrus , cherry t- sweet toffee up front that yields to some pine hop flavors that produce some bitterness but do n't overcome the malts . m- medium body , carbonation tickles , smooth d- amazing complex flavor and jaw dropping beautiful color .  mouthfeel is full and round .

nice aroma on this ! deep dark chocolate with cocoa , lots of cocoa . smells wonderful ! chocolate , cocoa , coffee , walnuts with a hint of vanilla and a nice hop bite . this tastes great !  m - huge milkshake like feel on this brew makes it feel great in the mouth . this is an excellent full body for a porter with this much chocolatey flavor .

smell : for a pale ale it packs a punch . definately a west coast pale ale as there is a huge citrusy hop aroma . the centennial and cascade hops used are very noticeable . huge grapefruit rind and hop resin in the nose . from the smell alone i would call this an ipa . taste : the flavor does n't quite live up to the aroma . this is a very good american pale ale , but again , the aroma promised more .  m : nice full body with a creamy mouthfeel .

6 oz bottle purchased at monument wine and liquor in concord , ca appearance was a dark brown with lighter highlites toward the bottom smelled great . one of the better smelling beers ever . very cider-y with what smells like a very strong brett nose . tasted good .  m - creamy , velvety , perfect .

s- strong smell of booze but with a sweet note that makes it quite nice . t- nice flavor that 's almost surprisingly sweet but boy does it burn .  m : thick but clean in the mouth , almost oily , with a warming alcohol effect down the throat . light carbonation balances the thickness of this brew quite perfectly . d : hmm , i do n't think this beer gets all the credit it deserves .

a : pours a black opaque with rich reddish brown fizzy head b : smells of licorice and blueberry as soon as i opened the bottle t : lightly bitter , blueberry comes in the aftertaste , definitely not a `` fruity '' beer . m : rich and smooth over the tongue d : good stout  t/m-extremely full bodied and quite syrupy . very smooth on the palate and a low level of carbonation that i actually very much enjoy .

s : abundant volatile citrus peel and tropical fruit fills the room to announce this beer 's hop presence . pale toast and fusile alcohols strain to be detected upon closer examination . t : begins dry with floral , pine , and grapefruit citrus hop flavors .  m : perfect body and balance !

the aroma is easily the highlight of this beer for me and is among the best of any barrel aged stout i 've tried . rich balanced blend of flavors , focusing on the coffee and sweet bourbon/vanilla from the barrel aging . unfortunately i enjoy the aroma much more than the rest of the experience as the flavor is more similar to the cw bourbon barrel stout , as well as the too thin , undercarbonated body . the finish is also particularly short and dry resulting in disappointment . the flavor is much more bourbon and vanilla forward than the aroma and is lacking the richness and balance of the aroma . i 'm enjoying the central waters beers i 've tried so far , but maybe my expectations are too high as i keep waiting for one to `` wow '' me and that has n't happened yet .  mf= medium body with a slightly crisp to crisp mouthfeel . carbonation was near perfect for the style in my opinion .

the aroma is stunning and sublime , conjuring images of freshly baked pumpkin pie , with a huge serving of cream . the crust is warm , sweet and nutty , and the pumpkin is perfectly spiced . if only the real deal smelled this good all the time ! its replaced by a moderately bittersweet spiciness in alcohol kick , which serves as a precursor to the pumpkin filling itself . the aroma is a revelation to me , and it seems to have a lot in common with rogue 's hazelnut nectar .  mouthfeel is very full and chewy .

the first thing you notice about this beer is the smell . it is like sticking your nose in a grapefruit is is so citrusy and tart . what you smell is what you taste , but it gets bolder on your tongue . the hops really let you know they are there by the time this stuff hits you throat . a overall very nice , flavorful ipa .  mouthfeel is amazingly soft over the tongue , and drinkability is superb as well .
the smell is delightful . this is sweet biscuity malts , chocolate , molasses , and caramel .  perfect . 5 an easy drinker .
complex aromas , with tartness full-on and up-front . robust enough to feel like an ale , but only just . undeniably delicious .  mouthfeel is silky smooth .
you can smell the hops from across the room . i think that 's the one thing that sticks out the most is the hop smell of this beer .  the mouthfeel is very full , rich , bold , and creamy .

if you love the smell of hops , this is great stuff . brewdog again did it for me . smell is fantastically green herbs hops and grass , also the apricot ( ?  sits in the mouth well extremely creamy porter that was very enjoyable .
insane lacing & very good head retention s : sweet caramel notes & fruittyness t : caramel sweetness up front , then dryness .  m - creamy and velvety , not syrupy by any means . low carbonation .

as soon as i opened it , i was immediately reminded of my grandmother 's famous and extremely delicious strawberry pie ! the taste is no different than what one would expect from a beverage that smells like a strawberry pie . the natural tart of strawberries popped out with one swig .  the mouthfeel was super bubbly , light and creamy on the palate .

s : this beer is awesome here . smoked bacon . it sounds bad until you try this one .  m : a silky smooth mouthfeel that was also very crisp . an awesome feeling beer that was very easy to drink and very , very smooth . d : excellent mouthfeel and taste combination .
) great aroma upon agitating the beer . nice crisp hoppy smell .  m : medium bodied , slightly carbonated , and incredibly smooth .

this is one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen .  this feels more like a stout to me ... the mouthfeel is amazing . it 's almost like licking a wet board , freshly hewn from the live tree . there 's a graininess reminiscent of chewing on raw sugar cane , and i can feel all of the wonderful fibrous matter in the mouthfeel of this beer .

great aroma and flavour backed with enough malt sweetness to make it palletable . i could n't drink too much of it but hop heads will love it . a slight green tinge in colour from the hops is visible .  i would say that mouthfeel is perfect for the style , chewy and full , and the carbonation is there but very light with a natural feel .
excellent smell , very subtle all around .  m : smooth , medium to light body ; small particles of yeast give an interesting texture d : extremely drinkable , smoothest hefeweizen i 've had .

has a strong bubblegum/clove yeast aroma . sweet malts underneath with a little sugar and something citric even further in the background . the nose really reminds me of aventinus weizenbock , and to me that 's a good thing .  the mouthfeel is the best part of this beer .

seriously smells like a fresh bag . unbelievable . sweet almost port flavor with sweet cherries , raisins and then that beautiful twizler flavor . phenomenal . has some syrup feel to it , but complements flavor appropriately . very impressed with this .  m : nitro + stout = perfection . huge , silky body with a 100 % chance of creaminess .

really nice . t & m : big , aggressive first sip -- carbonation and alcohol-heavy coffee taste .  this mix is just exceptional ! mouth feel is creamy , thick , carbonated , and just wonderful . you can sip on this for hours .

great aroma and really inviting .  m- thick , chewy , sticky . great adjectives for a strong beer . a nice mellow carbonation is present enough to give an even fuller feel . d- very good , if pours of this were n't $ 7 a pop i would have drank this all night .

s : lots and lots of hops ! wonderful smell as well . t : just as i thought , lots of hops and citrus . i loved almost everything about this beer except the tast .  luscious , velvety and silky smooth ... what any exceptional dipa should feel like . all in all , i prefer `` plain '' un-earthly .
smell - there is good amount of malty goodness right away .  mouthfeel is very full and round .
appearance : giant fluffy white head on a clear pale yellow body showing strong carbonation .  exquisite mouthfeel front , middle , and finish .

i had this beer poured from a can into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a light amber color , with some golden highlights and a small white head with minimal lacing ... s : the smell the best part , nice and hoppy ... t : after the hoppy aroma , i was very unhoppy ( pun intended ) to find a dearth of hoppiness . more sweet and malt than hoppy , and this is a fresh can ( from june 25th ) ... m : a little too chewy for an apa , at least , imo ... d : eh , its not bad , but i prefer snpa over this one .  amazing . this is just the second beer i 've had from alesmith and they both lived up to their reputation .

the beer gave off aromas of different spices like cinnamon , dried basil , and paprika along with the aroma of alcohol and fruits .  mouthfeel is light/medium bodied with the perfect amount of carbonation , love how this one feels .
s- smell is pleasantly hoppy .  it has a richness to it that is accentuated by the velvety mouthfeel .
