berry and malt aroma with strong spicy hops . tastes significantly less exciting than the intense and wonderful aroma . low hops upfront that continue into an excellent bitter finish .  the high carbonation makes for a wonderfull mouthfeel for a hefe-weisse .
beautiful mocha or capuccino color head . head has lots of protein chunks , dissipates very slow , and leaves beautiful lacing .  mouthfeel - perfect about of carbonation and body .
s : fantastic aroma . loads of citrus up from with a very clear grapefruit juiciness .  silky creamy as it gives a nice full mouthfeel . i prefer this to the regular .
very nice hop aroma , but the taste was lacking .  perfect balance on the hop weight throughout the beer .
smells very good ! little to no hop presence . this beer has super flavor , again , very sweet . mini alcohol burn .  nice weight , carbonation , and roundness in the mouth .

hazy yellow body with a musty , funky , grassy , barnyardy aroma . taste starts flat with an salty , effervescent selztery quality , moves into a tart mid-palate followed by a sharp , hop bitterness in the finish . the aroma is this beer 's high point , but i would recommend this beer to a saison drinker on the strength of the aroma alone .  very full bodied , bordering on syrup but with a silky smooth finish .
the hop aroma is amazing to me . i get grapefuit and citrus in the nose .  i have no idea how this absolutely stunning mouthfeel got attached to a mediocre beer like this .

enjoyed at the papago bar . an unusual one.great pear aroma , also sweet honey .  t-alot going on here starts out with the sweetness that the nose hints and finishes with a wonderful bitterness on the back of your tongue that lingers so you know you just drank an ipa , but it is incredibly smooth almost silky good medium to light body with an incredible carbonation level makes it a nice ipa even for someone not used to the style .

smell : complex and delightful ! cloves and apple cider are prominent . just a beautiful boquet ! carbonation is quite mild which works well though the mouthfeel is a little thin.. notes : altogether a delightfully balanced and enjoyable brew , but just not at the top of the heap in terms of complex flavors .  beautiful pour and very thick on the tongue ; its a pretty heavy brew , but still quite drinkable .
it actually has a pretty decent ipa aroma with a nice amount of pine and citrus hops .  mouthfeel is absolutely perfect .

nice nose . all around beautiful and promising . very short finish .  m-this beer has a medium-full mouthfeel with a very creamy texture with a soft faint alcohol warmth in the finish . d- this beer has a smooth flavor that has a very subtle complexity and a nice flavor but the creamy texture and head is just amazing .

decent strength here as well . quite nice . taste : toasted and wheat malt again with nots of caramel and sweet candy sugar as well .  m- big heavy resiny sticky mouthfeel . nice minimal carbonation with a nice creamy mouthfeel .

sadly retention and lacing are pretty poor , even for a gueuze . smell : man , i love gueuze ! stunning nose - lots of tart fruit ( lemon , green apple , sour grapes and apricot ) , apple cider vinegar , wet wood , damp hay , musty basement , black mushrooms and an odd herbal note . as the beer warmed the earthy character grew to almost dominate . at one point i thought i picked up a hint of smoke ( i could be crazy though ) . a second sip confirms it - the flavour is a bit of a letdown in terms of both sourness and complexity . tart fruit dominate with musty basement , vinegar , hay and a touch of urine all noted .  m : notable because of how damn smooth it is .
outstanding retention .  entry is silky smooth with just a touch of carbonation showing on the back of the tongue .

the exotic aromas are powerfully fruity with some alcoholic depth . hints of freshly ground black pepper & crushed cloves add to the overall complexity . the flavor starts off with just a touch of honey sweetness , but evolves into a very hoppy , dry , slightly ( yeasty ) & peppery finish .  mouthfeel was full and creamy with a lot of vanilla up front , followed by a mounds-like coconut/dark chocolate taste on the finish .

smell is absolutely delightful . notes of citrus , spices and yeast are all present in the nose .  m- smooth as a baby 's ass . d- something this smooth goes down real easy . truly fantastic , be sure to try this if you have n't already .

aroma of creme brulee , vanilla , cream , coffee with cream , caramel . not as pleasant as i envisioned on the palate : cola with pours of vanilla , light coffee , caramel , syrup .  it is very creamy , great mouthfeel .
brown with light brown highlights , there 's an off-white head with excellent retention and lacing . truly gorgeous .  for the style and flavor of this beer it has a perfect mouthfeel .

smells amazing when you first pour it . smells like chocolate and coffee , as it warms that smell changes to mainly hops . very hoppy flavor , but not too much .  mouthfeel - very smooth , agreeable carbonation level , slightly heavy , right on for the style .

anyhoo , the brew had a wonderful nose : crisp hops and fruity malt . the fruitiness was very clean , not all messed up with yeast and funky phenols . very inviting . kinda reminded me of white chocolate or vanilla . after that though was a brief dose of grain alcohol ( think cheap vodka ) .  a little light for a german style but still tastes distinctly german . creamy mouthfeel and very , very smooth . medium bodied well carbonated making it quite drinkable .

great aromas of cocoa dominate the nose . i feel like i 'm smelling a hot chocolate or the inside of a powdered packet of hot chocolate mix . great aroma and taste and easy to drink on top of that .  mouthfeel is great . crisp , clean , and dry finish .

smell : oh , sweet mother of god -- this is what the panties of angels must smell like . damn . taste/mouthfeel : strong hop presence right off the bat . the taste is very bold , but oddly , no particular flavor really stands out . it 's not novel or extreme , but it 's really , really good . drinkability : well , i mean , come on , it 's almost 10 % and so thick it gets into your pores ; you can only drink so much of this stuff .  m- perfect . d- nice to hang out and have a couple .

smells inticingly fruity , filled with citrus and light fuity aromas . hopping is definately a big player , adding a nice light piney aroma . malts lie beneath , providing a smooth balance filled with caramel and whipped topping and a nice toasty core . an absolutely , hands down , mouth-watering aroma . tastes mildly sweet and oddly blank . i enjoyed the full hop bitterness and fruity nose , but ca n't help but think that the flavor could have been better .  m - mouthfeel is perfect . silky smooth bubbles and full bodied texture .
the smell is all hazelnuts : sweet and earthy .  the mouthfeel is what surprised me as it felt very rich and smooth .

very nice and complex aroma . with a swirl of my sniffer , there is a blast of toffee aroma ! very nice . the aroma had me expecting a lot more than what i got . m-full thick syrupy almost feel .  smooth body with a near perfect richness and carbonation .
aroma is very nice full of pine and citrus .  mouthfeel is full and round .
d : nice . very beautiful nose . otherwise a bit plain .  excellent carbonation neither overwhelms nor underimpresses .
excelent ! its a beautiful thing . overall , one good ipa - though the boquet easily outshines all other characteristics .  great mouthfeel . very drinkable .

i get tons of clove and tons of cinnamon and it just smells absolutely fantastically fresh and bold and full of wheaty goodness .  m - full body and medium-light carbonation makes for a smooth texture that fizzes slightly on your tounge . it warms the mouth and feels creamy . very unique feel and one of my favorite things so far .

opaque black/brown with a brown sugar colored head .  very full bodied , viscous , almost chewy and smooth on the palate , with soft carbonation - one of the best mouthfeels i 've ever came across in imperial stout .

poured from the hippie designed bottle w/ 3 pumpkin men appearing to be brewing their `` autumn ale '' into a 16oz jack 's pumpkin spice ale weizen glass . aroma- has the closest aroma you can possibly get to having pure cinnamon and red apples while being in a beer ! unbelievable ! no hops to be found but may be very sweet with malt . sweet and then a bit watered down . overall impression- while jimmy john 's shops across the nation promote `` free smells '' with a neon light outside each one , this brew had an aroma i gladly paid for ! awesome amount of cinnamon and apple in the nose but then the taste hit and it was a tad watered down ... would have liked much more body in this one and it might have been in my top 10 brews of all time !  the body is nice , not thin and not slick , wonderfully smooth and crisp .
while i did think the smell was wonderful i was left wanting in taste .  mouthfeel- thick and rich like a good imperial stout should be . great carbonation and texture .
caramel/smokey fragrance soon after opening . pure stout with a creamy mouth-feel and smooth swallow .  silky smooth in the feel care of the nitro delivery .

the nose on the beer was delectable . a light maltiness sat underneath prevalent esters of banana and spicy cloves .  low carbonation , and an astringent finish , with a hint of warming alcohol . perfect . d- excellent .
aroma is fantastic ! ... sweet , malty , almost rumlike .  mouthfeel- the texture is creamy and sublime , absolutely perfect in every way .

the hop aroma is amazingly resiny . overall , an incredibly good wet hop ipa .  one of the thickest beer i have ever tasted , equal to the thickest , this is milkshake thick . quite an interesting beer but way to thick to drink in quantity .
overall , this is a tasty , aromatic , and very smooth-drinking dubbel . another amazing offer from the rarely-disappointing north cost .  the mouthfeel on this beer is really what sets it apart .

very pleasant aroma makes me anxious for that first sip . d - the dryness in the mouthfeel definitely leaves me wanting more , and the great aroma makes me happy to keep bringing it back .  mouthfeel is perfect . a rich , creamy treat .

even before the glass met my nose i could pick up the smoky aroma . that aroma was strong yet oddly made my mouth anticipate what was to come . one would expect such an assertive taste as smoke to dominate or destroy the other flavors that are present in this beer , but that was not the case at all . the smokiness is most definitely there and in force , but somehow the darker malt flavors still manage to poke their heads above the smoky storm and make their presence known .  m/d : perfectly carbonated , smooth , and incredibly easy to drink . champagne-esque mouthfeel and drinkability .

poured into a plastic water glass as i had nothing else ... the beer pours a ridiculous white head that is tall , thick and beautfiul atop a clean pale gold beer .  feel ( 5/5 ) very effervescent on the tip of the tongue in the initial taste ( almost reminiscent of the more carbonated belgian ales , like duvel in this respect ) . this transitions to a wonderful fullness as it washes to the back of the mouth .

the aroma came off very sweet but did not mask the large alcohol smell . think of sherry , or cognac .  first , the appearance and mouthfeel are perfect by my standards for the style . mouthfeel is perfect ; thick , smooth , creamy and a long lasting citrus rind and biting hop finish .

big roasted coffee and dark chocolate presence in the nose ; very pleasant to the point where i 'd buy it as an air freshener for my car . however the flavor , while not bad by any means , did n't seem as robust as the nose .  mouthfeel : incredibly smooth and crisp . definitely the best part of this beer . drinkability : the clean flavors and really smooth mouthfeel make this incredibly easy to drink .
soapy noble hops . what can i say i love the aroma but i am not too fond of the finish .  mouthfeel is super thick and coating .

sweet chocolate malty aroma with a very nice roasty character and subtle vanilla . very complex aroma , hopefully the flavor lives up to it . hints of oatmeal , toffee , very burnt toast and licorice with a nice dry bitter hop character in the finish . it 's a bit too harsh for me and extremely bitter , taking away from the silky chocolate and vanilla notes that i liked so much . pretty complex but a bit one dimensional for me .  great , great mouthfeel .
the pour is very duvel-like with a large frothy head and lively carbonation rising to the top .  great mouthfeel , nice and crispy , but not before you get to taste the beer .
smells wonderful ! this brew has a caramel and grapefruit nose that is deep and fulfilling .  wonderfully smooth body .

absolutely fantastic . t : exactly as above with some freshly shaved lemon/orange zest .  finishes crisp with slight honeysuckle sweetness & a slight peppery edge mf : light bodied & crisp , perfect balance super drinkability , a near perfect kolsch .
s : fresh brewed coffee , maybe a hint of chocolate , maybe some orange juice notes ? very tasty smelling , almost `` natural flavor '' coffee smell though .  extremely creamy mouthfeel !

extreme bourbon in the nose along with cherry and vanilla . fantastically balanced so that every nuance can be appreciated . quite good , but neither worth the price ( $ 30/750ml ) nor hype .  and this was a grave mistake , as this beer is truly excellent . i noticed the mouthfeel before the flavor : the bottle conditioning mj pointed out on the label made this beer velvety smooth .
a - huge pillowy head . great lacing . orange hint of color .  very viscous .

the aroma is super sweet and matly . vanilla dominates this then you get some nice notes of brandy , and wood . the feel is really weak here . overall , this is ok , nothing special , the grand cru crushes this .  fantastic palate , great mouthfeel , smooth silky yet carbonated very well .

a great beer to smell . not an amazing beer to drink .  black cherries take on a sweet and sour lemon , with balsamic edge , which is both mouth-puckering and refreshing . carbonation comes out as creamy in the forefront , with a medium blast in the throat , all at the same moment . then returns to being creamy and rolls down the throat . pleasing .

complex aromas sets this beer apart from others of its style . every time i took a whiff , i could pick up different aromas like oatmeal , raisins , brown sugar , and flowery / earthy hops ( no doubt a result of dryhopping ) . easily drinkable and pairs well with a nutty cigar . the best damn us maibock i 've had yet . this brewery is growing on me .  m : perfection here , this is a great beer for chewing .
pretty nice looking , fits the bottle color scheme and the devil motif pretty well .  the carbonation , while lacking in the glass , is perfect on the palate . the mouthful is fantastic .

one thing about hop bombs , for all their flaws , is they smell amazing . this does n't disappoint . nice .  slightly dry taste toward the end m : perfect mouthfeel as far as i 'm concerned , very smooth and creamy goes down very well .

very fragrant , very complex smell t : caramel , molasses , dark fruit ( fig/raisins ) , m : heavy bodied beer , drinks pretty smooth . d : nice cold weather sipping beer , very tasty .  mouthfeel - 5.0 loved the mouthfeel .

big beer , big aroma . reallly big aroma . gobs and gobs of sweetness here . it 's interesting . not so sweet as to overpower though , as in their doppelbock .  it 's extremely mouth filling and hefty , yet luxuriously smooth , like a silk-covered sandbag . the feel of it alone will keep me coming back . finish is long and roasty .
the smells are great , but the taste i find to be a little normal .  this is an extremely active beer with an incredible mouthfeel .
strong citrus hop aroma , hints of orange that fades .  perfect texture .

t- sweet , caramel , maple syrup , vanilla , and bourbon ! i 've had many bourbon aged beers , but this is over the top but tastes like dirty bastard with a few shots of bourbon . crisps , dry , and sweet ! d- not my style , but could drink one or two on a cold winter night .  mouthfeel is excellent , smooth as butter .

smell was rich and aromatic . initially when poured from the bottle , it was sweet and candy-like with noticeable milk chocolate and fragrant caramel malt aromas .  m : perfect . big bodied , oily , and effervescent .

we shall see ... nose ... sometimes beers just `` smell '' like california ... i 'm not sure if it my early experiences with sierra nevada ( or boontville esb ) that has made such impression on my mental remembrance of the olfactory experience that is west coast goodness ... fresh , deep hops buttressed by caramel/sweet malt , the complete package , this smells spot on , it has that `` red '' sharpness to it was well , sort of giving it a dry-ish feel , the hops can be teased out and pronounce themselves sharply when sought after ... great . taste etc ... medium bodied , the carbonation does n't really sparkle here like i feel it should to give this a better ride , the aftertaste is exactly like the smell , and i am digging that but the initial sips seem to be lacking a bit , this tastes more like an apa or a weak ipa.. not that styles are n't meant for interpretation ... i am just not mclovin ' it .  thick and chewy with minimal carbonation ... exactly as this beer should be .

pours a dark orange color that turns black in the glass , very light for an imperial stout . smells of spiced milk chocolate with coffee notes and american hops to finish things off . absolutely intoxicating aroma . spiced chocolate and coffee blend flawlessly into a single unified flavor that ive had before , but cant place . great flavor , but the lack of body here just is leaving me amazingly under whelmed .  this is a medium bodied brew with an exceptionally smooth feel .

smell was actually really good . malt , caramel , and roasted aromas .  m : smooth , rich , creamy , this is how an ris should feel . not overbearing , but the perfect balance of robustness and smooth dessert like feel .
though it smells absolutely fantastic , the taste is not all that great .  mouthfeel on this beer is damn near perfection in glass .

the smell is extraordinary - something like pecan pie . compared to the superb nose , the taste is a bit of a downer - flat and a bit thin ( i have never used such words to describe a rogue beer before ) . there is a nice malty finish , but it just falls short of the best examples of this style .  just has a silky smoothness that feels great going down .

after a long pour from the tap the head finishes with two and a half fingers with this fantasic crown on top . i would love this beer to have a little more i.b.us to give it a little more bite .  the mouth feel was perfect and represented an oatmeal stout very well .

looks fantastic though and smells like heaven . strangely , i was getting faint vinegar notes in the times i have tasted this beer .  the mouthfeel on this beer is practically perfect , slightly sticky with a slight creamy texture added by the everlasting head .

quite the interesting ipa , and not what i expected . it 's light orange in color , with a perfectly even balance between hops and a very sweet citrus aroma . the most notable comparison of another ipa i can draw to this is samuel smith 's , due to its toned-down character , lack of a biting hoppy finish , and the sweetness .  mouthfeel : thick , rich , and velvety . harmony : i am very impressed by how balanced this is . : yes .

normally i would not describe saisons or brettanomyces as smelling amazing , but saison-brett 's nose is absolutely off the charts . this beer looks , smells , and feels amazing , just too bad the taste may be the weakest link here ( though it is still good ) .  the mouthfeel is phenomenal , with high carbonation and light to medium body relative to its strength .
s - it smells just like banana bread : heavy on the banana , light on the spices .  great creamy carbonation .

hardly pale at all . molasses . cherry wood . freshly baked whole wheat and lots of it . surprisingly it smelled of sour milk and mint .  a creamy , medium body . perfect . in general , i love the look , aroma , and taste of this beer ... but it sits rather heavy , and the bittering is particularly forward .
exceptional nose . bubble gum esters mixed with vanilla and banana topped off with a little pepper . solid effort on this hefe-weizen .  m - medium bodied , creamy goodness . highly satisfying .

slighty cloudy . s- i could smell the hops the second i popped the cap . once it was pouredthe nose was very hoppy and citrusey with a sweet malt backing . very citrusey and piney .  m = luscious , thick , excellent mouthcoat .

this beer has an amazing aroma - possibly one of the nicest smelling beers ( certianly that i have experienced ) . light carbonation ... overall - a exceptional beer - one of my favourites ... highly recommended ...  m - incredibly creamy and smooth , with good carbonation . terrific mouthfeel and very well balanced .

a great aroma ! the taste however is pretty weak .  this is a meaty brew ; full bodied and luscious , one of the best in my opinion . carbonation that was not very visible reveal themselves while sipping ; nice .

the lace sticks pretty well w/ rocky cap that is like a mound of cream s - a smell that is akin to dessert -imagine a cinnnamon and apple scent like the filling of a dunkin donut apple cinnamon donut . the sweetness is apparent w/ dark stone fruit quality and red pear elements w/ mild juiciness in the nose w/ subtle nutmeg and cinnamon stick notes w/ a gentle arom of raisin m - the feel is spicy and light tartness w/ mild sour fruit and mild bitterness w/ high carbonation level and bitter spicy finish w/ a dry slightly astringent quality t - a taste that is both fruity and surprisingly bitter compared to the nose and for the style w/ piney and bitter grassy notes w/ subtle honey and apple flavor w/ slight alcohol influence on the palate . the beer has mild tart apple skin taste that continues into the drying finish d - a pretty tasty biere de garde , but it seems like an americanized take on the style with generous hops and inensity of alcohol , it is n't as true to style as it could be but was certainly interesting enough to hold my interest - thanks tb69 for sharing !  mouthfeel is quite nice .

another whiff of the ale rendered even more hoppy aroma with a deep dark almost smoky note from the malt . the hop aroma was complex but pleasant and the strong alcoholic content is revealed in the nose of this formidable heavy hitter .  imho : a good representation of the style ; good balance , very sweet with a great mouthfeel .
aroma of tart apricots is obviosuly present but a simple ipa jumps out with some herbal hop notes and sweet malt .  the mouthfeel is heaven ! round and full , yet thin enough to be easily drinkable .

just a stunning beer to look at . deep , dark black , with a huge brown head .  m : smooth carbonation , almost velvety mouthfeel and nice dry finish that keeps this from being an overly sweet cloying beer .

a : a huge , tight head impressively crests the beer , gently churning , but never quite collapsing . a dark tan , it tops a much darker brown beer , completely opaque . good lacing .  mouthfeel is great , it 's moderaletly carbonated is surprisingly very dry and you get a blast of flavor before you even swallow .

big citrusy hops notes are very prominent . lots of grapefruit and orange and a nice touch of lemon . wonderful presence of rich , caramel malts balance it out . smells like a beautiful dipa/iipa . the hops hit the palate first . the caramel malt backbone tries its best to bring balance , but it just is n't quite strong enough to pull it off . it 's no secret that there has been a lot of talk about this one being a pliny clone . nicely full-bodied . thick , smooth and creamy .  smooth creamy flavor compliments light acidity which ends in an exceptionally clean finish .

a-pours medium brown with a thick beautiful head .  m- about as thick of a beer as i have had and it is great . the smoothness of it is wonderful . you barely pick up any carbonation and that is fine by me .

boy not sure what exactly this is but i like it.. love the aroma ... one of the best smelling sweeter beers i have experienced..a lot of the doughy yeastiness , and also some white pepper ... tasty ... .i get a lot of yeasty , doughy , breadyness right off the bat ... then strong notes of corriander and banana 's ... let 's call it a belgian golden ale/whit/hefe/ hybrid ... .taste is n't quite as good as the aroma but it is still very enjoyable ... body is medium ... there is a spicy , peppery note on the finish.. very enjoyable beer ... .widmer is kicking ass with their seasonals ... brr was an awesome amber ale ... .this is a great stab at a belgian golden ale ... i was never a big fan of this brewery ( did n't dislike them but nothing seemed real impressive ) but they are changing my thoughts with beers like this .  4.5/5 mouthfeel - smooth almost has a chewiness . exceptional .
the body is a smidge to thin given a stout , but still good . d- nice coffee stout , especially @ $ 7.49/6pk .  solid , smooth and somewhat silky mouthfeel ; full and great drinkability .

aroma of very spicy hops , some meaty malts ... an all around exciting aroma . unfortunately the taste does n't back it up .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . the carbonation seems a bit higher than other imp stouts , but it goes well with the very thick , almost syrupy texture of the beer .

smell is big , bold , and mouth-watering ... have to fight an initial impulse and not layer whipped cream on top of this . really delicious . 9 % abv , could of fooled me .  m : great mouthfeel , perfectly carbonated and medium bodied .

ultra dry , petroly tasting geuze sampled at the delerium caf on 8-18-08 . plenty of funky horse hair aromas , gasoline , grapefruit , dust , etc ... flatish body is forgiven as the wildness of it all more than makes up for it .  so complex , loving it ... a wonderfully viscous lip smacker .

pours a slightly hazed golden orange color , with a tremendous , bright white head that stays put , huge clumps of sticky lacing ... just phenomenal looking in the glass .  lower carbonation levels and rich body lend to the extra smooth feel .

nice nose , bright and fresh hops , hard candies , orange , and lots of other sweet citrus notes . hoppy beer with less malts than i expected .  the palate is silky smooth and warm with just great balance and character .

smell is fresh hops , very floral and citrusy and even fills in with some piney notes for good measure . taste is a little bit of a let down after the strong smell . mouthfeel is a little oily .  mouthfeel is perfect for this style .

s : phenomenal aroma . there is an incredible wild yeast sourness in the nose . every time i smell the beer , searching for additional scents , i become completely distracted by the incredible sour aroma . t : unique for sure . the beer lacks the complexity i expected from the intriguing scents .  m : full bodied with a great carbonation feel . awesome here !

picked up a bottle of this when on the east coast recently ... the aroma was a noseful of hops . i enjoyed it , and am glad i tried it , but would not go out of my way to buy it again .  very smooth and creamy mouthfeel to this one . moderate carbonation , extremely refreshing .

the beers pours a jet black color with a think , persistent , creamy head .  the taste and feel to me are perfect . not super thick , but still able to coat and linger . a well balanced flavor not too sweet or bitter , and carbonation that lasts to the bottom .

great nose ... sugar sweet citrus fruit ... grapefruit coated with sugar ... oranges ... outstanding ... .pours a light brown color ... the head is weak and the mouthfeel is a little light in the shorts too ... great taste though ... .great balance between the hops and the sugary sweet maltiness ... very low carbonation ... .nice tight bitterness on the long finish ... i guess i 'd compare this in some regards to old ho but not quite as good ... different hops too i 'm pretty sure ... i like the hop flavor of this one better but the malt load is not comparable to old ho ... this is more sugary sweet than caramely sweet ... great hop burps ... .  real big , nice an simple mf/o : super viscous , super smooth , creamy , and velvety . the best feel to a beer that i 've ever experienced .
nice , oily floral hop aroma with a mild sweetness of pine sap and alcohol . very nice .  coats the mouth - very clingy .

the aroma is dominated by banana-smelling byproducts produced by the yeast , very inviting . it has a light banana fruity flavor with a hint of malt and almost imperceptible hop aftertaste . it has a light , refreshing flavor and wonderful aroma .  the mouthfeel is right where it should be .

smell- one of the best scents from a stout i have set my nose upon . huge hit of burnt coffee grounds , plus some dark chocolate and cigarette smoke smell .  smooth and full bodied , creamy as anything i 've ever had .

12oz single , i think from barriques on pd ( a true gem of a beer store / general establishment ) appearance : pours into an imperial pint glass - big bold mahogany body with a huge ( but well maintained ) head and terrific retention ... extremely nice looking beer to say the least smell : sharp blueberry aroma , creamy , lightly roasted malts and oats ... not much more to say about the aroma - about what you would expect from the title taste : this is a good beer !  m : well , due to nitro , it 's incredibly smooth , especially considering the style of beer .
hops are faint and yeast is nigh undetectable .  mouthfeel is perfect for the style .

lots of spicy hopy with a huge caramel sweetness overtone . some grains in the background that help this brew maintain a very bold nose . some burnt grains and a hint of citrus , with a burnt bitter finish .  very very thick and chewy . almost a meal by itself .

serving type and glassware : 1.9 pint bottle poured into 16 oz tumbler a - off-white head , not lingering , low apparent carbonation with a transparent copper color s - sweet candy-like smell , cherry lolipop comes to mind ( corny i know but oh well thats what i thought ) , really the smell is one of the highlights of this beer t - equally as sweet , some toastiness pulling through with a slight bitterness in the finish , a mildly present alcohol taste throughout m - stickiness of the malt is the feature to note here , with a medium-light body all around i bought this beer on a whim and was n't disappointed .  mouthfeel was velvety , body was about the same as chocolate milk . it was n't overly thick , giving it a clean smoothness perfect for sessioning .

aroma : absolutely invigorating grapefruit aroma rolled in oily lemon hops . the finish is acrid , though not intense .  its all creamy peanut butter with chocolate , actually its really awesome , but has me perplexed as on tap it was tons of vanilla and bourbon . a tad too rich for me , but its good ... the taste gets us back on track , more oak , chocolate and bourbon come through , still missing the vanilla though . finish is bitter , adds to keep the experience interesting . the alcohol is hidden well , creamy from start to finish . this was good , but not as good as tap where i was blown away .

as for the nose - mangoes , you say ? plenty of that , with very ripe mango character present , along with a little citrus and grapefruit zest .  it 's strong point was the mouthfeel . it was amazingly very smooth , probably the smoothest beer i 've had to date .
aroma is sweet and spicy with quiet funk underneath . curacao and ginger , clean dirt .  m/d - mouthfeel was rich and creamy and coats the mouth .
an aroma of malt , dark fruit and spices .  mouthfeel is pure silk . very creamy .

s- a very beatiful hop aroma it has a good mix of a citrus hop smell and a piney hop smell t- the smell does n't reach the bar that the smell set .  really big , rich mouthfeel . thick and chewy with a smooth carbonation , which suits the decadence of the flavour well . in fact , this is one of the most perfectly matched mouthfeels i 've come across , so top marks for goose island !

s - nice hop aroma , quite citrusy .  the mouthfeel is full , lucious , slick and creamy , which makes for a most addictive imbibing experience . overall , a fantastic brew , i will certainly seek out other vintage offerings from this brewery .

s - strong aroma of dark fruit , black cherries and plums . the dark fruit in the nose is unusually nice , and the smooth dark flavors coat the mouth nicely without ever overwhelming the palate .  it tastes very nicely and ballanced of amber malts , hops , smoke and juniper , and it just feels great , full and creamy body with moderately low carbonation , just the way i like it .

smells very delicious . loads of roasty coffee bitterness on the palate . amazing smell and great appearance save this beer from a pretty average score .  extremely smooth from start to finish , one of the most pleasant beers in mouth and after .
a pleasant bready aroma with some dark fruits . a soft and enjoyable nose . t : follows the nose .  m - heavy . think store-bought chocolate milk made with whole milk .
i love the vanilla aspect and it smells sublime , but there are just a few minor things preventing this from being what it could .  incredible carbonation for such a headsy brew .

the rich caramel smells wafted around with a hint of vanilla and cedar . the taste was fantastic , full in the mouth with a faint trace of whiskey , all caramel and wood .  a great mouthfeel that is easily recognizable .

appearance drags down an otherwise fantastic beer s : rich pumpkin pie spice , cinnamon , mace , nutmeg & some pumpkin flesh as well , superb nose t : follows the nose ; nutmeg , all spice & general pumpkin flavor up front , along with some herbal hop bitterness . one of the better pumpkin beers out there imo  mouthfeel is like the appearance , a wondrous experience . it sets the standard for mouthfeel on a stout .
a : crystal clear amber orange color with a thick almond colored bubbly head and some really nice lacing .  mouthfeel is just about perfect .

the aroma is exceptional in both its power and its depth . present are citrus , grapefruit , belgian yeast esters like pepper and clove . overall this is an exceptional beer . it is a little odd at first and maybe even eccentric , but that being said , i like it .  f : body has medium viscosity . full and creamy , goes smooth over my tongue .
high hop aroma , citric mainly .  love the mouthfeel on this , creamy , and a quick swish turns this into a frothy coffee milkshake .

s : amazing florals immediately eminate when uncapped . d : an excellent assertive beer . very drinkable with a food pairing due to the alcohol content . chicago style pizza and most mexican food comes to mind .  the body is fantastic . it is -- just as the name says -- like cream : slick , glassy and wonderful .
smells wonderful . lots of really green hops - vegetal and super piney . this one is very drinkable in my book .  medium-light and very creamy in the mouth ; lots of bubbles .
it pours a very deep brownish-black color with a nice sized tan head . leaves nice lacings .  smooth , creamy mouthfeel with light carbonation .

i really like this nose it is a bit off the style but i 'm ok with it . also this rather strong smelling which is nice for a lot of reasons .  truly exceptional creaminess . overall this was a refreshing take on the style with exceptional mouthfeel .

awesome nose , ca n't wait to try it ! t - whoa , a lot different than i had anticipated from the nose . d - i really do n't know how i feel about this beer . i feel like it had nice complexity , but the flavors did n't seem to mesh well for me .  wonderfully thick and coating .
lovely aroma with intense fruity and vinous notes , spices are very much present too .  the body is delightful , silky smooth , a little warmth is all the warning you get from this strong brew .

full of citrus fruits , yeast , spices and some good malt character . t : following the nose , there is a great mix of citrus fruits and malts . o : very pleasing brew , the flavours are great as is the aroma . the alcohol shines through a tad to much and it could lessen the bitterness .  smooth and creamy mouthfeel with a hop free finish .

the smell is dry , more woody than piny , very pleasing to the olfactory senses . it 's very phenolic , plenty of cherry cough syrup and dirty band-aid but not as much of the pine and citrus notes i enjoy so much in other hop bombs .  m - thought this beer was very smooth and carbonated to perfection , definetely got the mouthfeel down pat .
the nose is outstanding - fruity , tangy , wheaty . some much for the nice things i have to say .  m : extremely creamy and smooth , this goes down better than most any beer i 've tried .

s - good lord this smells delicious . milk chocolate , mocha , caramel , toffee , molasses , cocoa , nuts , light roast , oatmeal . strangely , i 'm not getting any coconut ... t - the taste is remarkably different from the ultra sweet candied sugar , chocolate , etc picked up in the aroma ... coffee and dark chocolate dominate with plenty of roastiness and a hint of brown sugar . i wish it was more pronounced , but this is still very tasty . m - low to medium body , prickly carbonation .  mf : this beer excels compared to other dipas with a velvety mouthfeel and the perfect amount of carbonation .

aroma was great . smelled of slightly tart granny smith apples , a little spice . the smell was strong and i could n't wait to down this brew . how it smells so good but tastes so bland .  mouthfeel/drinkability- one of the finest textures of any belgian beers i 've sampled , the mouthfeel is stunning ... smooth and rolling foam that only gets better the longer it 's there .

aroma : very yeasty . fruity , banana . banana bread . taste : brown sugar , cloves & spicy , yeasty flavours . it reminds me of guava ( a tropical fruit ) juice .  the mouthfeel is ultra smooth and creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .

i 'd never had a blueberry beer before so i did n't have anything to compare it to , but hoped it had some reminiscent qualities that would make me think of blueberries . it strongly smelled of blueberries , which i was very pleased to discover . after smelling the beer i was hoping the blueberry taste would be as strong .  mouthfeel : stupendous . initially evervescent so as to allow a cascade of flavors and finally dry and comforting .
really nice aroma on this . really crisp , clean finish .  crisp , well carbonated , has that indescribable quality that makes you want to drink more , and yet more .

pours into a tulip glass a beautiful deep orange/garnet color . it 's very clear , though so dark that it 's hard to tell . the head was a quickly dissipating off-white .  light spice gorgeous balance . flawless . the carbonation make this beer in my opinion .
the aroma is malty , chocolatey , slightly roasty with oak and bourbon .  m : excellent : rich , tongue-coating medium body , supported throughout by abundant , smooth , rolling carbonation .
this is one nice ipa . hops make their presence known , but not overwhelmingly .  m : thick , viscous and chewy ; one of the creamiest mouthfeels i 've ever encountered . yes .

amber orange color , hints of gold highlights . white head jumps up about two fingers full , and sticks like there 's no tomorrow .  m : this is what makes this beer one of the smoothest i have ever experienced . almost like silk .

a beautiful aroma beckons , with rich chocolate and rum-soaked dark fruits combining with a faint nose of clove and some undetermined spice .  though the bittering is brazen , the plush mouthfeel makes for a high quaff quotient .

perhaps the best smelling beer ever . t - toasted grain , grapefruit , then sweet orange and plenty of bitterness . fantastic . d - yes , yes , yes .  m & d -- mouthfeel 's the strongest of the beers i sampled from sly fox -- super creamy and mellow .
strong sweet malty aroma , some earthiness .  m : medium-full bodied and silky smooth . this is one of the creamiest , smoothest beers i 've ever had and is an absolute joy .

the aroma is honey and orange with alcohol and prunes/raisin smells . there are also some floral notes like those from a belgian triple yeast . overall a very nice and complex winter sippen ' ale .  mouthfeel - more carbonation that what is visible . the mouth and tongue become numb after a while between the hops and the carbonation . quite memorable .

the nose on this thing is somewhere between hershey 's syrup and fresh brownies . tons of chocolate , but that 's what it 's about so kudos . really cool beer and one of the best in the series so worth trying out .  mouthfeel is stellar with this beer . full and creamy with a touch more carbonation than the average stout .

smell : the smell is incredibly complex , with huge grain and oat notes . taste and mouthfeel : the taste is not as incredibly complex as the smell . it 's a rather straight forward creamy yeasty taste . drinkability and overall : it 's not the best tasting , but it looks wonderful , smells delicious and feels oh so good in the mouth .  perfect for the style .
smell is excellent . dark fruit , berries , and sweet nutty aromas .  great carbonation .
love the nose on this one . toasted nuts , chocolate , roasted malts , a little smoke and char ... oh yeah ! nice nuttiness . nice taste .  really smoothe and thick on the mouth .

it was a nice amber color , and had a great hop aroma . beyond the bitterness , it finished smooth , a nice aftertaste .  t/m : the taste is a citrus , grapefruit hop dominance , but the mouthfeel is as creamy as a glass of milk . a very interesting brew that works out very well .

decent enough ipa ... very nice pungent hop aroma ... .bong resin , tobacco , pine , and some earthy notes ... taste is pretty bitter at first and this seems a little one sided ... then some caramel/toffee notes emerge and blend in ... body is light side of medium..carbonation is a little too low ... .finishes pretty dry and bitter .  but what it lacks in scent , it makes up for in mouth-feel and taste : a moderate hoppy bite in the mouth with a superbly mellow honey-like finish and a nice residual alcohol taste . the mouth feel is as thick as melted ice cream .
the aroma is quite extraordinary and captivating , but sadly the taste does not quite match .  silk smooth mouth .

nice and solid stout appearance . i noticed the head gradually sunk in the center , which left the foam raised on the sides of my glass . interesting appearance .  carbonation is perfect . kudos on great mouthfeel .

this smells absolutely amazing . t : pine resin and bready malts hit first .  the alcohol just lingers in the mouth a while , hence the 5 for mouthfeel . full bodied and thick in the mouth with a nice warming feeling .
very nice hoppy/grainy scent erupted as the bottle cap cracked .  thick and constantly evolving . they have fresh and full body . very dry .

pours a very beautiful gold , perfectly clear , carbonation even and all-around beautiful . i would n't mind to put something that looks like this up as a display in my kitchen .  crisp and smooth in mouth , despite being served at sub-zero temperatures .
smells delicious . t : brown sugar , apples , metallic taste , alcohol .  m - light to medium body and moderate carbonation .

poured a hazy brown color with a huge frothy light brown head that was fully lasting and produced excellent lacing .  i 've had triples with higher content and less alcohol taste -nice feel in the mouth . smooth , malty and sweet . -not a bad beer by any means , just not what i was expecting . this beer did n't have that nice belgian greeting you get with the first mouthful .
the nose is very good . the taste is a real let down and it is from the rye .  mouthfeel is quite lively , but does not make up for the almost empty taste .

luscious wafts of chocolate dipped raspberry and buttery fudge . softer milk chocolate notes and lightly burnt cookie notes surface as the beer warms . very appetizing aromawise . if it only tasted as good as it smells ...  m - good . nice and thick , which is what you would expect for a decent imperial stout .
appearance - hazy , golden yellow body with a beautiful white pillowy head . other beers wish they could look this good .  m : good , full body , adds quite a bit to the beer .

pours a perfectly clear reddish amber color with a very nice two plus fingers of light beige head . retention and stick are both quite good .  m - this stuff is very thick , definitely full bodied , chewy , and a decent amount of carbonation .

i popped the top and took a long inhale noting the nutty scent . my nose isnt fully developed just yet so if i can pick something up then you know it is in there .  this beer is full of funk and bubble gum , yeasty , doughy , a little too sour for a saison . but it may be better with food not an easy brew to drink alone unless you want half 3 philosophers and half duvel in the same glass : ( sorry hut dissapointed . tastes better with food
smells of typical pumpkin spice with a good dose of yeast in the nose .  good mouthfeel ; medium body ok , but not somethin i will go out and purchase
s - bitter roasted malt aroma with hints of charcoal and chocolate .  nice body .

i was intrigued by the complex smell of the grapes mixed with the spices and the faint belgian yeast aroma .  smooth and syrupy feel , but this is way too sweet to enjoy a full bomber . making this beer bigger in the wrong way ... more hops please .

smells really good , like what you want to wake up to every day . i loved the idea of this beer , and upon smelling it , i was really excited . upon drinking it , i was really dissapointed .  the softness of the honey comes through in the middle . th creamy textue is captured in theabout thirty seconds after the sip . it slowly shows that faint dollop of cream .

750ml bottled poured into my la fin du monde tulip ... pours a hazy pale orange with a nice three finger soft/off-white head ... very nice floral `` wet '' hoppy scent up front , reminded me of founders harvest ... was a little let down by the taste after the very nice aroma ... decent amount of hops , but not much bite at all , was expecting a stronger upfront hop bitterness . sweetness tries to come through a bit as it warms but overall there is just dry/grassy mild hop bitterness with not much balance ... mouthfeel is decent at best , thin , but nice tingle from the somewhat high abv ... drinkability is average , tastes and feels light which makes it easy to drink but eventually you realize the 8.5 % ... overall , a little let down by this beer , started off so nice with that great fresh hop aroma but the taste and feel just could n't match ...  the nose is great and it has a good creamy mouth feel , but its just somewhat a little ashy in my opinion .

very nice . unsurprisingly , coffee is the big flavor here , also , but there is a sweetness that i did n't pick up in the nose .  33cl bottle a : nice head light golden , pale straw colour , nice carbonation , overall looks like it shoulkd look s : hops , malts , sweet bread t : basically the same thing as the smell only with a slight metallic taste m/d : good mouthfeel , very drinkable .
a- this is dark , really dark . nice looking head leaves great lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with a nice carbonation tingle .

ommegang abbey a : pours a very dark amber with a lively & enormous brown-orange head that displays magnificent retention . looks as if someone dropped a mini throw-pillow on top of it . gorgeous .  body is smooth and slightly creamy , which is pleasant and very much in character for the style . still , while refreshing , this is n't a particularly tasty beer .
a : hazy blonde , thick foamy head s : malts , grains , with a bit of sourness too .  smooth and crisp mouth feel with a high carbonation level .

poured with about 2 '' of tan head that receeded slowly in a lumpy mass and stuck all over the glass . seriously impressive for a brown ale , the best looking brown i 've seen to date . it really brings out the mouthfeel and head retention and works well with the typical brown ale flavor profiles .  nice light body and sparkly carbonation .

hales aftermath begins with an inspired hop aroma thats very floral , very fresh . but soon after the hop aroma is released , a malty pungence pokes through and carries the aroma in a malty direction .  moderate carbontation , full bodied .

super cascading effect is better out of hte can than on tap . deep yellow color adorned by a giant off-white head that laces the entice length of the glass .  i bought this one at new beer distributors in nyc , a non-conditioned warehouse with a great a great selection ... im worried that its gone bad : a. pours a cloudy dark amber , with almost no head s. smells like sweet and sour yeast , malts , and a hint of bitter fruit t. sweet up front with some light malts , hints of sour , and finishes with a slight oakey , bourbony alcohol warmth m. medium and chewy d. not very , too sweet , this one is a sipper this beer does not taste very fresh -- it was aging in hot warehouse , probably for over a year , reminds me of a sweet bruin aged in oak barrels .

lots of citrusy hops , and the rye shows up well , smell is remeniscent of a fresh baked loaf of dark rye . the rye shows up very nicely . and a bit of citrusy hop flavor comes thru shortly thereafter . drinkability is quite good .  somewhat creamy mouthfeel , finishes bitter .

s- alot of pumpkin spice and a ton of nutmeg . smells like a sweet pumpkin spice candle from yankee candle . t- as soon as you put this in your mouth it 's sweet but then the pumpkin spice takes over and your tastebuds just scream out as if to say `` what the hell is that ? a bit overpowering . feels good .  mouthfeel : goes down oily , yet finishes crisp and leaves no residue . very pleasing .
honey-like sweetness on the nose , clove , pepper , yeasty .  good doseage of carbonation in there feeding a mildly creamy mouthfeel .
i love the smell of an islay whiskey so this smell was up there for me , peaty smoke , a hint of biscuit malt , and some orange peel .  light bodied and very smooth going down .
awesome nose to this beer , notes of quality wheat , toasty grain and some definite detection of bright citrus-like hops .  good .
appearance : black as night with a creamy brown head that lingered , good lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

there is a wonderfully elixer-like nature to this great aroma . i asked others to smell it and they were universally impressed . the flavor is great but a bit over the top on richness and fullness . but this is a very rich beer , rather like the too-rich nature of a great piece of pecan pie .  good carbonation .

on to the beer : this one forms a very thick head on top on the pour . the color is hazy autumn brown , with hues of orange and yellow . outstanding head retention .  yet the body is fairly rich in texture .

dark roasted malts , chocolate and hints of vanilla are in the background as well . fantastic aroma ! t- the taste like the aroma is dominated heavily by the bourbon barrel aging flavors along with the delicious roasted malt and chocolate flavors with a lot of warmth in the finish from the alcohol . d- overall , regular old rasputin is awesome but these barrel aged anniversary editions really are special . these are tasting great fresh but i can only imagine how magical this beer would be with some aging .  the mouthfeel is good , thicker and only slightly carbonated .
smell is very nice . t - at 9 % the alcohol flavor comes through .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is on the low , smooth side of the medium range . the body is full , and somewhat slick .

s : hot spirituous bourbon prevails here , showing many interesting facets and remarkable depth that speak to the more subtle contributions of other spirit barrels involved . t : begins extremely sweet , with potent fruit qualities , carnivorous savoriness , and strong ethyl alcohol . its early flavors overwhelm the senses while remaining true to the smell . it is able to lift the bourbon and other spirits from the wood successfully , yet their presence is short-lived .  light to medium bodied , relatively smooth and a touch dry .
the aroma was unbelievable in this one ! after that , very light pumpkin but still very enjoyable . an easy drinking pumpkin i would definitely come back to !  m - it has a full mouthfeel .
a medium thick to thick tan head sits atop a burgundy body with a good amount of lacing left behind .  m - medium bodied with a good carbonation level .

a : clear light amber with two-finger , white , foamy head that lasted more than a few minutes . phenomenal lacing .  she 'll drink lindemans , but complains it 's too sweet . this is definitely less sweet and more funky . flavor is of tart raspberry juice with a funky edge , perhaps the oak . i 'm pretty sure this lambic is hopped , because there 's a really interesting play between the sour flavors of the lambic and bitter undertones in the beer .

smell : rich , decadent aroma dominated by berries . incredibly strong black cherry smell with a sugary kick . there 's a fresh , damp wood / forest component that ties into the buttery hops .  its probably the mouthfeel and the smooth sweet after taste that has changed my mind about this one .
smells of nice piney citrus , sweet malt in the background . very inviting and delicious to the nose . the smell leads into a disappointed taste .  m : good for a good english ale .
a- a very deep leathery brown liquid with a thick and creamy mocha head that has excellent retention and leaves lacing as it works down the glass .  mouthfeel is about medium good carbonation .
the aroma is wonderful ( amarillo ) hops ; grapefruit , pineapple , orange juice . perfect and sweetly bitter . sooo bitter but sooo delicious .  good light body and moderately high carbontion .

a bottle poured slightly vigorously into my victoy tulip glass . a nice tan head formed and lingered . a- the appearance is nice and dark . it looks black in the shadows , but once held up in some light appears a gorgeous dark brown/red .  mouthfeel is quite slick , has a good texture from the booziness , goes down pretty well .

bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass fantastic appearance . glowing orangey-amber with a two-plus finger tall head of bubbly , light tan foam .  mouthfeel : very crisp , as a lager should be .

sweet , roasty chocolate goodness . is this stuff available as an air freshener ? `` alcoholic chocolate milk for adults '' . really good !  on the lighter side of medium bodied . carbonation is moderate and not harsh . nice texture to the beer .
pours a cascading mocha which settles to a dark brown topped with a creamy white nitro-head that lasts the whole glass . excellent lacing .  m- good strong mouthfeel , adequate carbonation .

admirable mix of pink and white grapefruit in the nose , floral with chamomile tea notes , spoonful of pine sap , no herbaceous nor ultra-sweet elements , stays within itself and on message , you could sniff it for some time . the grapefruit and tangerine citrus starts things off well , after that there 's momentary pine , green hay , wet stone aspects .  the mouthfeel is good , not too light and not overly heavy either .

s : smoky , meaty , and malty . good , but not nearly as complex a the nose . m/d : a full body and medium carbonation .  m - think & syrupy , reminds me of an american barleywine . nice low carbonation .

delicious hop aromas . strong citrusy grapefruit with a touch of orange and lime . call me crazy , but i also get a hint of sea spray in the nose . wonderful hop nose . very nice hop bitterness with lightly grassy and piney notes that you can taste through your nose when you sip . hops take charge with very nice flavor and bitterness and burps .  its very dry and has good carbonation .

the smell is dry and robust with flavours of coffee , lemons , liquorice , roasted malt , white bread , and porridge rolled oats . the carbonation is fresh and surprisingly strong , but it suits the beer fine .  m : the feel is about the only thing good about this one . thick and oily with a big finish . not sure why they put so much hops in this one to where it drowns out the barrel flavors .
it smelled of brandy , fruitiness and sweet caramel malt .  mouthfeel is good , nothing wrong .
pours black with creamy light brown head .  there is a strong body feel to this but the taste is not what i am expecting .
smell : very nice , best part of this beer .  mouthfeel is good . nice carb for the beer .
aromas of plums , raisins , roasted malt , syrup , and bark were detectable .  m - medium coating with a tingle over entire tongue .

it 's a big warming malty beer with orange , citrus , and spices over a very dark -- deep brown to almost black -- translucent malty beer . huge hops over the top of the dark malt . hugely improved from last year 's christmas ale with a big , bitter hop and astringent ending . well be upping the citrus quotient of this brew with additions of sweet orange peel , bitter orange peel , lemon peel and toasted whole coriander and then wrap the whole thing up with dry hop doses of cascade and chinook hops .  mouth : it enters with a strong carbonated feeling on the tongue but without a lot of flavor .
pours a two-finger cream head that fades very slowly leaving a very good lace .  m : very good here for an imperial stout .

s- smells of plum , tobacco and a great vanilla bourbon-y aroma . very enticing . t/m- this is definitely sweet , but the taste is a bit bland past that .  it has a rich , creamy mouthfeel , but not a lot of taste .

it pours black . not inky black like some others but dark enough . the amazing part is that you can see the bubbles rise from the bottom of the glass to the top ! head retention is pretty good not that i care .  body light and lagerlike , tho quite cohesive . rather lightly malted , like most of leine 's beers . god bless this family for outlasting the merger mania of the 1970s , but i wish they 'd brew some more substantial beers , like yueungling 's does .

it looks good , smells delightful , tastes good and feels quite pleasureable on the palate .  mouthfeel : now this was actually where i can praise the brew . it has a creamy , yet light feel . very interesting . drinkability : while the appearance and mouthfeel are quite good , the smell and taste to do not pay off .

that being said , this is a fantastic smelling beer . pineapple upside down cake all the way , with huge sweet bready notes , caramel , tart cherries , some raisin , and , implausibly , tropical fruit . the aroma really impressed me and i love bready beers .  body is a creamy medium .

this red smells fantastic ! i 'm disappointed that the taste does n't back up the great nose . it 's ok .  zero carbonation evident . palate : medium body and medium carbonation . this is the best aspect of the beer . average .

sweet and bready smelling . actually smells just like a warm bob evans biscuit slathered in honey ! sweetness still lingers on the tongue , but the fruity and floral hops are felt in the nose and throat . i prefer my american pale ales more dry and bitter , but this is a tasty little drink with no real conflict from the mountains of west by god virginia .  there 's a lot of hype for this brew , perhaps that 's because it 's trappist , but i ca n't for the life of me see what a lot of others see in it . not with brews like st. bernardus , rochefort , westmalle and chimay coming out of the same country . the flavour is equally misplaced , with notes of cherry amidst a weak , bark-like overtone . i notice the previous reviewer mentioned champagne , and this definitely has a somewhat champagne finish . it 's a brew that does n't quite know what it wants to be ... ale , kriek , champagne ? pass , thanks .
poured out the bottle this beer displays an attractive head of foam that takes awhile to settle out .  medium mouthfeel .
bomber poured into a mug a - beautiful black color with a nice thick , stiff head .  light mouthfeel with the right amount of carbonation .

a-pours quite black . barely any light penetration . dark tan head forms and retains . head is about an inch high and leaves good lacing .  rich , buttery mouthfeel holds a palate of light hops , fruit ( apricots ? ) , and some breadiness . finishes with a very nice buttery texture and a taste of dry roasted malt .

very pungent scents of juicy pumpkin flesh with the autumn spice of nutmeg , cinnamon , all spice . not one scent overpowers the next creating a very unique bouquet . they must be melting pumpkin pies into beer up their in new york because this tastes almost spot on to a home made pumpkin pie .  small head that dissipates quickly , solid carbonation throughout , seems like a dirty iced tea . mouthfeel : solid and crisp . very clean .

excellent aroma , a very clean fresh cake-y malt , a bit like stepping into a bakehouse .  first sip has the strong body you 'd expect from an english stout , but the positive impressions begin to dissolve when the taste coalesces into a bland , mild muddiness that lasts throughout the pint . unless you look for a beer on the basis of mouthfeel and consistency alone , there is little to be found in this blandsville brew .

when you smell it , the cinamon , ginger and nutmeg really come out . the taste is equally as impressive .  t- watery some chocolate start ok but falls flat on its face . m- its nitro so smooth with a good thickness right for the style nothing great but right .
bottle into tulip glass . a - pours semi-cloudy golden , with a huge , thick , white head ... - some good lacing .  m : light body with mid-high carbonation , this beer is nicely light and crisp .
aroma is just fantastic , pils malt with a tantalizing phenolic spice .  it had a good mouth feel , but the bitter pine after taste was over powering , at least for me .
it has a massive tan head that turns into a couple of inches of foam .  the body is moderate with a good carbonation .

walk into the spice aisle at the grocery store . that 's what it feels like to be taking in this beer 's *powerful* aroma . just dominated with a perfectly blended holiday mix of spices -- obviously cinnamon and nutmeg , predominantly , with hints of ginger and cardamom . this is the gale 's christmas ale of pumpkin beers . just perfectly balanced , vigorous , forcefully spicy and sweet . you very much can drink this with pumpkin pie , i 'd imagine , or on its own as dessert . and most importantly , it passed the fiance test -- she 's the resident expert on ( read `` obsessed with '' ) pumpkin ales , and this one passed the test with flying colors .  m : medium bodied with moderate carb . nice dry finish .
really strong and good . has a spice to it .  mouthfeel is fine .

the nose is just outrageous , showing a huge aroma of coffee , milk duds ( the sure sign of extended barrel aging ) , bourbon and light leather . the flavor profile replicates the nose , but is n't quite as intense or outrageous .  m : tingly on the top and smooth and light going down .

vibrant , acuate waft of fresh , overripe , sugary raspberry with a rounded , blooming floral edge hits the nose at first . quickly complementing are understated notes of cork and hay , which add a surprisingly subtle barnyard contrast .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is pretty good .
the aroma absolutely wakes your nose up- piney and clean . smells good , so the taste ?  m- medium body with pervasive delicate carbonation .

leaves super thick lacing and retains well , great looking beer .  mouthfeel is spot on , maybe a bit heavier and not quite as ethereal as some others , but good . if you have n't tried the style and want to see what its all about , save your money for the deus or the malhuer brut .

bottle clearly states that it 's brewed in bottled at the royersford locations ... picked this one up at the sharp edge creekhouse . appears a clouded golden honey nectar something along those lines and it forms an off white head thick mountainous fine bubbled carbonation leaves behind thick chunky patches of lacing clinging to my chalice quite the resilient head definitely sticks around for quite awhile .  m : fairly creamy , thick , and smooth .

the smell , and everything else , however , was really something ! fantastic aromas of chocolate , sweetened coffee , caramel , and perhaps some candied dark fruit are all present here . taste , too , is full of nearly everything in the smell , with the addition of a rather nice medium dry finish that sort of reminds me of toasted cereal . mouthfeel is nothing to get overly excited about , as there is virtually no co2 at all present here , and the liquid , while not water-thin , is close to it .  the flavor also starts out with mostly malted flavors , slightly biscuity and once again a husky , grainy astringency . the hops are hidden in the background adding some minor floral and dry herb flavors and a mild bitterness , that is well balanced overall . the beer is well balanced , maybe a touch too malt forward , but their is a slight drying astringency and the flavors are n't well pronounced , and i would prefer a bit more hoppiness . not a bad beer per say , but i can say with confidence , i will never buy it again .

aroma is interesting , reminiscent of an english strong ale with complex hop character.. or a mellow american barleywine with a few years of age .  there is a hint of citrus t : thin and watery with nearly no hop until the very end . m : the mouthfeel is nice and hearty . it is n't over or under carbed and it carries well throughout the tongue .
pours a dark flat black color with a nice lasting tan head .  m - creamy mouthfeel with moderate carbonation . the best thing about this beer by far .
o : a great aroma , nice taste and very drinkable and smooth .  mouthfeel -- medium in body with an abundance of fluffy carbonation . best aspect of this one by far .
mad retention and lacing , it 's a pretty solid looking beer .  m : thick and syrupy with a warming alcohol tingle which turns hotter on the back of the tongue .

has a beautiful smell of blueberries with some beer , very nice if you 're expecting blueberries , not the best if you wanted beer . overall a pretty decent beer .  m & d : medium to full body , the mouthfeel was actuauly quite nice and creamy .

everything is in even amount and each whiff displays new charm ... t - the palette does n't live up to the wonderful nose ... it 's not bad , but rather quite average for the style ... the hops take on a light euro nobleness ... the great sweetness alluded to on the nose is missing in action ... a slight spice component ... some wheat notes ... m - medium bodied ... very slight carbonation ... a touch of dryness ... nothing much lasts for too long ... wham , bam , and gone before you know it ... a bit of a disappointment ... d - a solid belgian pale ale ... the nose is exceptional , but the rest of this brew is solidly slightly more than average in all other categories and you know the saying about being only as strong as your weakest link ... solid , respectable , and worthy , but not much more ...  t acrid as hell - some malty caramel sweetness coming through , but the stale hops were just over the top m full bodied and creamy from the carbonation d i had a real hard time getting through it - my mouth was exhausted i felt completely disappointed - it must have been an old bottle , there are no bod markings anywhere so it 's hard to tell how old it is .

aroma is very hoppy , as expected , a bit of malty sweet tucked in the back . the high level of aroma hops make this beer come off initally like a hop bomb , but it seems more bark than bite .  mouthfeel - a decent body medium thick , quite smooth , surprisingly .

a : deep copper color - great rocky head s : earthy , musty , caramel nose , vanilla undertones , alcohol presence t : the taste is very different than the nose , full , rich , chocolate , very , very good , pleasant surprise m : smooth , easy drinking , carbonated but not like some other belgians that are too gassy d : nice sipping beer  the mouthfeel is medium and there is a pleasant level of carbonation .

reviewed 8/8/2009 ( draft at flying saucer , houston , tx ) : pours a reddish amber clear orangish colored body .  taste : spices ( clove and banana ) and malt with the presence of alcohol flavor ( but not overpowering ) mouthfeel : high carbonation , crisp with a smooth finish .

a : pours a pretty light shade of gold , almost yellow with a huge fluffy white head s : huge nose full of sweetness , some spice , lemony citrus , and a bit grassy . very apparent as well you do n't need to stick your nose in it to get a feel for it . t : not a lot going on at the front end , a bit of spice flavor and some light malts then a huge punch in the mouth from some sour lemon flavor , followed toward the back end with a bit of grassyness and a kiss of oily hop flavor on the swallow with lingering flavors of spice coating the mouth m : light and crisp in the mouth a bit watery and prickly carbonation o : a pretty good saison , i might have let this one sit in the fridge a bit long but still pretty good .  m : mouthfeel is fine , leaving out the rest . it has a nice malt backbone of thickness , then hits you with great carbonation for this hefty of an ale .

passing the growler around , the smell on this baby is gorgeous . deep vanilla , spanky malts , coffee , all meld together to give one the shakes from anticipation . i really enjoy the base porter , but this one did n't seem well put together .  m : nice grainy feel .
nose is strong with citrus . dough and yeast as well . overall it gets better over time , but at first a bit much .  mouthfeel is nice had good body and goes down smooth .

aroma was perfect . fresh vanilla ... . just fantastic . i 've seen a couple of folks take a couple of minutes just smelling the beer .  the mouthfeel is pretty solid . medium bodied , decent carbonation , moderately sticky .
bottle a deep hazy amber color .  m fairly light bodied with medium carbonation .
aroma is perfect . very reminiscent of lss . great brew .  light to medium body with some nice light carbonation .
really beautiful scent to this one .  the mouthfeel is fine , drinkability is ok , the aftertaste is n't excessively long or unpleasant , but it 's just not that tasty .

strange , but pleasant . flowery hops as well . over all a great smelling beer . upon first taste i again got honey , then the flowery hops came back .  the body is smooth and creamy . moderate carbonation .
sampled on 8-13-07 pours a super-thick pitch black , with a foamy tan head that coats the glass .  mouthfeel : medium to fully body , dry , tingly hops on the tongue , medium carbonation .

smelling this , i get a malty , sweet vanilla-i , cherry aroma , w/ possibly my favorite fruit ( plums ) in there somewhere .  full carbonation to the mouth feel helps distract from taste , and it has some smoothness to it .

poured fairly aggressively and managed to aggravate a 1 and half finger width head of dark , dark tan , kind of like the color of a cup of coffee with a teaspoon of cream ... i am still talking about the head ! the fluid is jet black with absolutely no light getting through .  m - full-bodied and refreshingly crisp in carbonation d - i 'll drink the 6-pack over a few nights , but i 'm rather disappointed in the brew .
dark root beer brown body sits below a large cushion of dirty khaki head . looks good .  medium body and oily with low carbonation .

the aroma is pretty good . big , burnt sugar and roasted malt greet my nose , with perhaps a bit of chocolate behind that . a big burnt sugar flavor comes through first , and it is really nice .  it fades a little as it warms , letting chocolate eek through . it 's very hot , very boozy , with some chocolate bitterness coming through in the aftertaste . again , the alcohol overwhelms the other flavors . i 'm used to drinking big , strong beers , and this one does n't hide the alcohol at all .

smell is strong with spices , considerable nutmeg and cinnamon . overall this is a good quality beer .  it feels pretty dry , overall . mouthfeel : medium body with a good level of carbonation and creaminess . the texture is quite nice .

a : the beer pours a nice reddish brown pour that turns ruby red when held up to a light . the head is a light khaki color and is very frothy . great retention and great lacing as well as ample carbonation . a very low quality beer smell escapes as well ... t : earthy malts make up the bulk of the taste as well , and again the sweetness is peaking through .  nice fragrant hops in the nose and then ... butterscotch and band-aids full mouthfeel , hop bite on the tongue and then ... medicinal then ... finally an acrid farewell .
smells amazing - malt , spices , and alcohol , wow .  mouthfeel is slightly thick and slick with a little hint of carbonation tingle .
smells of butterscotch and over ripe peaches . also that classic belgian yeast .  medium body with crisp carbonation .
its smell was a balanced mix of caramel , yeast and hops .  m : medium body , smooth carbonation , dry finish but off a bit .

great bursts of citrus aroma coming off of this one . the fresh citrus aroma does n't translate into the flavor profile much .  the mouthfeel is good . it 's creamy and smooth and glides over my palate . overall this is just an average beer .

aroma is full of nutty almond-tinged columbus hops . deep sniffs bring forth a scent of lemon poppy muffin.. ridiculously complex aroma here . medium body , crisp , peppy . this beer is very drinkable and brilliantly showcases columbus hops , although the attempt to balance its aggressiveness seems to get a little too messy and covers up much of the potential flavor . with warmth , i 'm able to draw some additional floral spiciness and perfumey hops.. the malts , which seem honey-accented , are so far in the background drowned out by green cones .  cherry soda almost for flavor profile , minus the cola mouthfeel - light , acidic with good carbonation drinkability - very easy to consume , lawnmower or beach bum beer , i.e .

the aroma is oaky with lots of vanilla and a touch of coffee , but the taste falls short .  taste : again overwhelmed by oak and sugar , now i 'm willing to commit to calling it rum . mouthfeel : definitely full-bodied and creamy like a nitro stout should be . tha'ts nice at least .
pours an absolutely beautiful dark , opaque orange with a two-finger off-white head . great looking brew .  this is a full bodied beer , but totally not my taste .
great lacing on the pint glass i drank it from .  mouthfeel : good . it feels like beer .

pours onyx black with a dense medium brown head .  i get some of the caramel , but the roast does n't pair well with this . the lingering funk of this beer is n't very good . i really like the brewery , but this bottle really did n't hit the spot .

smell is lemons and citrus fruits ( grapefruit mostly ) . the aroma is strong , hits you right out of the bottle . it 's got a bite to it that is very tart and refreshing . full of flavor and aroma , and a great beer to end the summer season on .  mouthfeel is medium body and low carbonation .
this is one dark mofo . opaque , pitch black , with a creamy brown head with good retention .  m ) nice carbonation , not too heavy not too light .
it is a bright , sparkling gold with a medium , long-lasting , creamy white head that leaves beautiful , even lace .  feels a little viscous with a lively carbonation .

s : carmel malts , huge nutty notes , some bread-y yeast characters , hints of roasted malts , spices , and tiny bit of hops . quite complex and inviting , i would love to have a candle that smells like this . t : mirrors the aroma , nutty carmel malts , hint of roasted malt .  very sugary malt . mouthfeel is solid . creamy and smooth at first with a bitterness that soon meets it and rides out to a moderately dry finish .
pours out of the 330cl bottle an opaque black colour with a healthy , bubbly tan head . reduces to a fine film with some lace to boot .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

the aroma is great . very fruity with a character similar to a white wine .  this brew poured a small head of fine to large sized white bubbles and amber orange transparent body . it has a strong hoppy aroma and a strong hoppy flavor to boot . it has an initial hop flavor and a strong hop finish . you can summarize the brew in 1 word ! hoppy . a true hopheads delight .

and this is a `` good '' double ... the smell was incredible , i got alot of pinapple and the hops were very nice . it was still a very good beer and at 9.50 the alcohol was prominent , all the way up to the warming .  m- full body with low carbonation .

aroma is smooth and mellow , but strong and meaty . lovely notes of sweet barbecue char , fruity kalamata olive , rich oaken vanilla , maple leaves , and apple hum a rich , enticing , autumnal harmony . quite a nice beer , though , and one i 'd love to try with cheese or chocolate .  m- light body , nice carbonation .

that 's about it , but it 's really good ! what a let down ... it 's looks and smells great , but the taste is just wrong .  feels good especially for a pale . resinous and nicely carbonated . if the carbonation level is my favorite thing about a beer then i 'm not gon na get it again .

amazing fruity aroma of overripe goodness.. apricots , plums , cherries.. all soft-skinned and ready to rot . what a nice evolution on old ale . really not too 'drinkable , ' but enjoyable for its explosive flavor and unique sippable take on old ale .  this just smells `` german '' too , with notes of melanoidans and flowery noble hops . this was sooo sweet and overpoweringly cloying that i could not finish this beer . it 's got some really wonderful aromas and complex malty flavors but the sweetness is just to overwhelming . maybe this is intended by the brewer for the style and i just do n't get it , or maybe something went horribly wrong between the brewery and my glass . either way , i really wanted to like this beer because of it 's potential . darn .

*note : this is a 2007 vintage* a - poured into a goblet this has a nice mahogany , cloudy pour with one of the most impressive heads i 've ever seen . this 1 finger of big bubble head hung around for the duration of the ale leaving massive , clumpy side lacing . i'ver never seen bubbles of this size before in my brew , its insane !  m : medium bodied with a full juicy mouthfeel . the high carbonation dances around in your mouth .

mango , apricot , citrus , soft banana bread and slight pineapple aromas dominate . there 's some good'n funky hay-like , but relatively mild , qualities mixed with a slight ocean air ( good ) . wow , this smells delicous . a strawberry cream aroma develops with significant warmth .  mouthfeel is good , very smooth and full .
superb aromatic quality ... i get candied fruit , biscuits , and caramel .  had nice mouthfeel , esp .
