deep brown , pours with a frothy head and leaves generous lacing .  mf- nice and smooth , good for summer time relaxation slight carbonation and citrus invades the toungue .

s- incredible ... the vanilla comes through and lets you know that it is not going away . nice alcohol smells pierces through at first , and then mellows out . but this is a nice `` occasion beer '' .  light bodied with decent carbonation it is a very easy drinking brew ideal for a hot summer day .
popping the cap yields an absolutely intoxicating citrus scent - some tart apple , grapefruit , and maybe some peach .  feel is pretty good for the style .

smells really inviting . very complex but all nicely balanced and complimenting smells . t - same great taste from the bottle , perhaps even a bit better than i had remembered .  m : creamy , with low carbonation .

clear golden/amber body with about three finger of creamy white head . head retention is awesome , and leaves plenty of lacing down the sides of the glass .  its drinkability is smooth and somewhat water like with a bubbly , creamy , sweetness . this is the best coors product i 've had as of yet .
right away i was pleased with the copper color and rich caramel malt aroma .  medium bodied with good carbonation .

i find aroma to be very inviting . it is sweet , a bit oily and sticky , but very refreshing with citrusy hops in the foreround .  the beer felt good in the mouth : thick and velvety , but alas , no es bueno .

grassy noble hops hit the nose hard . almost like sticking my face in a bag of fresh hops . really a delightful experience . caramelly flavors rise to the front on the palate but a kick of hops smoothes everything-out exceptionally well even though it 's been around for awhile , this is a new favorite of mine and easily one of the most drinkable beers on the market .  m : pretty creamy overall with even carbonation .
batch # 2 a : cork and cage : nearly took my nose off as this one is very overcarbonated . s : wild fruity yeast . gum .  pretty good feel .
amazing . taste is also sweet and citrusy .  m : smooth , almost caramel .

i 've never been a huge fan of pumpkin beers , but i had high hopes for this one . the smell is a nice blend of sweet fruits , dry grains , and spices .  well i guess i just do n't have the make up to like belgian style beer . russian river is belgian heaven , out of belgium . so you belgian lovers , the worse i make it sound , the more you will love em . a hodgepodge of flavors assaulted you on this one . spice , cinnamon , pear , and a hint of banana . it also had a lightly toasted hint to it . probably a great beer to somebody other than me .

big noseful of hops of the most inviting nature , you just want to breathe in the beer for a while . very refreshing with a pleasing bitterness that lingers .  m - medium to full body beer . pretty thick .

s - oak , smoke , dark fruits , candi sugar , caramel , dark chocolate , vanilla , and some light vinous notes that also suggest dark fruits and berries . even with all the different elements it blends seamlessly in a rich and complex bouquet . t - the taste is a little bit less complex , with char , dark fruit , a hint of soy , and roasted malts . the finish is vinous , with a note of cherry , and there 's a lingering bitterness .  m : crisp full carbonation , medium-bodied , nice finish .

runs the gamut on hop aromas . bitter , floral , earthy and citric , resiny with grapefruit rinds and peach candy . mouthful of bitter hops with a surprisingly nice clean finish . nice flavor , but it 's a little too straightforward for a dipa . little malt presence , and the complexity from the aroma is missing from the flavor .  mouthfeel : a medium to full bodied beer , with a good amount of carbonation .

poured into a chimay chalice a - crystal clear copper with 2cm white head with tiny bubbles of carbonation running up the side of the glass s - tart and crisp ( almost like a dry champagne ) t - very tart and bitter . astringent with a strong warming alcohol presence m - slightly harsh and dry with ample carbonation d - this was out of a 750ml bottle , and i now wish i would have picked up the 11.2oz bottle instead .  nitro tap at the brew pub in new hope . i put this down to being a mix of flavors from my previous beer , the bengal gold ipa . it 's much like the smell of a dank basement where there is no fresh air and spiders are everywhere . perhaps the lines needed cleaning but i would likely not try this one again .

booze pokes through , but overall this is quite nice . spices work really well with the base . 3.5 t : the taste is good , but it 's a bit more muddled than the nose . nice belgian spiciness .  the frist sip is a good medium/heavy mouthfeel .
pours a cream , one finger-head that goes slowly leaving a decent lace . nice clear amber color .  medium body with some sticky sweet coating -but in a nice way .
pours a clear , pale gold , with two fingers of huge , white marshmallow fluff head . scant lacing .  m - it was crisp , sharp and smooth . a light bodied ale with a dry finish .

a -- appears black , but when held up to the light it reveals itself to be a deep shade of brown . a conservative pour still yields almost 2 fingers of tan head that recedes slowly and leaves good lacing s -- banana/clove , raisins , spices , funky breadiness , some citrus in the far background t -- this is my first of this style and i 'm not sure it is for me .  this is a sour brew , but not that sour that it 's offensive , and there were just enough spices and carbonation complexities to keep it from being like a cider . mouthfeel is creamy and smooth , with light carbonation , a light body and a sour finish that leaves a fruity pucker .

aroma is awesome . so much hops and a nice roastyness . taste was n't as good as the aroma would suggest but still very good . with the roastyness it could use a bit of sweetness .  medium carbonation .
beautiful hops on the nose that worked well in the mouth with an interesting , almost sticky maltiness adding backbone to it .  m : medium bodied . full , thick , and creamy . good .
nice light spices , fruitier than i remember , some bananas , apples and fresh peahes . sweet and nice .  mouthfeel : smooth , sweet and full bodied which leaves a delicious aftertaste .
smells rather nice . a honey , grapefruit hoppy concoction .  mouthfeel is pretty full for the size of the beer .

love the caramel aroma here on this one . great for the nose although the aroma is notably malt dominated . a decent copper , but nothing exceptional .  mouthfeel- medium bodied with light carbonation . slightly chewy texture .

the nose is one of the two or three most impressive of any beers i 've had . ( on tap it was definitely the very best nose ever for me . bold smell of fresh hops , pinesap , and fresh chopped mint leaves . flavor could use some more complexity , but overall an exciting and great pale ale .  mouthfeel : thick , medium-high viscosity . medium carbonation .

it smells of floral hops . something on the tail end of the boil really amped up the aromas on this beer . it 's a very bright smell , refreshing in itself . the beer tastes great . delicious ipa , probably one of my favorites i 've ever had .  4 body on the full side of medium , carbonation ample .
pours that perfect guinness black , with a cola like head , though lasts longer .  mouthfeel - smooth with mild carbonation conclusion not bad , but nothing special .

warrior and dry hopped with columbus hops . nice ! t : floral hops , grapefruity zestiness , piney kind-budness , and actually after the hops reside a bit there 's some maltiness detectable . ends dry and bitter ; a good beer .  though it 's called a nut brown ale , the only nuttiness in this is in the aftertaste , which is by far the most pleasant part of my experience with this beer . it reminds me of the tommyknocker imperial nut brown , but that at least had a 10 % abv to explain its unpleasantness . i really do n't understand why this is rated so highly ; apparently i just do n't `` get '' this particular kind of brown ales .

appearance : pours a modest hazed orange-yellow color beneath a truly enormous , champagne peach-blush white satiny pillow of a head that sparkles like freshly fallen snow .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with a viscous , chewy carbonation .
a- it pours very very very dark .  the body was light and pleasantly carbonated , but there was zero drinkability to this in my mind .

this is definately a unique esb in the grand scheme of things . i get even added bitter qualities from a slightly roasted malt goodness . notes : this is arguably the best in the style for my money . hell take style completely out of the equation , this is a kick ass offering .  the aftertaste is sweet with quite a lot of alcohol , but very little bitterness . `` bivaly '' means `` bullock '' in hungarian but could also mean `` powerful '' . the carbonation is good for a lager ; fresh but not sharp .

pours murky brown with a large head that fills the glass nicely . the swirled remnants of the bottle drizzled over the top take on the effect of a fudge topping , the foamy head holds very well giving this a very dessert-like appearance .  m - medium bodied ale that goes down smooth and finishes nice and wet .
smell : oh baby there is plenty of juicy citrusy hoppy goodness going on here !  it is a quality brew from the perspective that it carries a nice light bodied quality with lovely crisp carbonation .

( a ) - pours a clear caramel color that produced a nice foamy white head that clung to the sides of the glass leaving a cascade of lacing around the entire inside .  pokey , medium-light carbonation in a body just a shade above light . crisp and snappy .

thin layer of bubbly retention with nice patches of drippy lace . smells dank and potent ; right on . deep reserves of citrus ; spicy , zesty and pithy . it has everything to do with smelling amazing . definitely worth a shot .  mouthfeel is smooth . nice carb .

i really enjoyed the smell of this beer when i opened the bottle , but it was all downhill from there .  aroma was very complex , spicy , pungent . flavor was just a mass of confusion . sasion ? triple ? wtf ? the reason this `` triple is so hard to nail down is absolutely flabbergasting . the brewer was very proud to tell us that 9 different strains of yeast were use to ferment this concoction . why 9 ? what was there about each that he hoped to add to his beer ? the real answer is that for a triple , you triple the malt bill .

when you `` pop '' it and starts pouring it 's pure amber with a medium large head that leaves some lacings .  alcoholy , grape sweet taste with an aftertaste of smoke . strong and syrupy sweet , but tasty . creamy . will probably age well . pretty good .
aroma : similar to the tap version . very nice and warming . taste : way too hot and boozey .  the mouthfeel is good . it is a low bodied beer with adequate carbonation .

s. the fist impression is of apple cider , but the smell of champagne quickly takes hold of your attention . finishes off with a slight funkiness .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and perfectly carbonated .
very nice .  m - the spritzy carbonation is what i expected , giving this beer a crisp and light body .
smells wonderful . sweet malts , dried fruit and alcohol .  mouthfeel is good . decent body and nice carbonation level .

very dark beer topped with a frothy two finger head , excellent lacing . almost looked like cappuccino .  smells like a scotch ale . a clear miss . this may be the oddest beer i 've had in a very long time . it is mostly malt until the swallow where the hop shows up .
poured into a bowl goblet , revealing ultra thick and airy cream head over hazy frosted gold body .  full bodied and carbonated well .

smell is an amalgam of a whole bunch of things . sweet pale malts , grassy aromas , nice sweet citrusy orange notes , and a bit of apricot in the background . taste is not as impressive as the smell . heavier on the grassy hops , the apricot and citrus are there , but not as prominent .  medium-full in body with smooth moderate carbonation .

the nose is simply amazing w/ boat loads of cracked vanilla bean that can be realized without even completely bringing your nose to the glass . the taste is the same vanilla bean in your face w/ burnt caramel , coffee , and licorice on the finish .  right on mouthfeel .
s : excellent , good smell of toffee , nuts , and oak , with a hint of vanilla .  the mouthfeel is pretty good , long lasting ( forced ? ) carbonation .
this came from the tap a deep brown almost garnet with a thick frothy head ; tan in color with a thick sheet of lace .  m. very smooth with a little stickiness .

beautiful clear dark amber/brown coloring really makes this brew great to look at ... one of the best looking brews ever.. aroma of sweet dark roasted malts and maybe a little coffee here ... after all the recent hop bombs , this is great ... ridiculously smooth and delicious , i could drink this regularly .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

this is like a friend revisited , this beer pours ruby musky brown slightly hazed with a cream tan head with weak head retention . this is one malty treat wrapped in raisins and a load of perfectly ripened succulent fruit ( mainly pears and apples ) . flavor profile brings on a vinous grape tone with hints of mildly alcoholic plum brandy .  mouthfeel : medium body with a very good carbonation level .

a giant foam cap immediately surges up with the pour and never dissapears . huge swathes of lace drape the glass . this beer looks fantastic .  m : very light and frothy , has plenty of drinkability if you can deal with the skunkiness .
pours straight black , nothing more nothing less . amazing lacing and good retention .  it had a good thick body to it and was drinkable but not overly enjoyable .

the top is solid white , thick , frothy and never seems to completely go away . the appearance is just exceptional . smell is a little more subtle than i would have expected but there are definitely some spices and sweet malts present .  the classically unfiltered flagship beer from michigan - bell 's amber ale . one that seems to be divisive amongst die-hard larry bell fanatics and casual k-zoo stout and two-hearted quaffers . there 's a bit of that worn-out cheese-like hop character on the nose of this beer . there is something about the look and smell of the beer that evokes chewiness . there is a dulled hop bite in this beer floating atop of a cheeseburger-y blend of heavy yeasts and clunky sweet malts . the beer is thick and bold , one both a macro drinker and a blind taste-tester could harmonize negatively about .
pours into the snifter a terribly deep black color , with a creamy mocha-colored head that lasts and lasts and lasts .  lingers on the tongue a bit . this is the best part of the brew .
pours a beautiful dark honey-gold that is clear and has a thick , persistent , fine-bubbled head .  feels really smooth on the palate .
it smelled so delicious that it made my mouth water .  m. nicely carbonated and crisp , refreshing , light bodied .

s : lots of orange and mango on the nose , very smooth citrus is bursting from this . this smells fantastic . t : orange is a very big player in the taste here . this is amazing stuff that i would buy regularly , given the chance .  the mouthfeel is this beer 's only saving grace ( if i had to come up with one ) . very creamy and smooth with mild carbonation .

smell was very malty , sweet and smooth . rich , caramel malts and candied sugar came through strong , along with hints of alcohol soaked raisins , dried fruits and a general woodiness .  moderate body , w/ the dextrinous and full mouthfeel saving the beer .

aroma : amazingly exceptional -- coffee , hazelnut , frangelico . taste : rich ! almost keeps pace with the nose . nutty , frangelico-like ; sweetish , dark cherry , a good hop twist , and a bit of worcestershire near the end .  t- tastes pretty damn bitter , with grapefruit and pine leading the way , after taste is just straight bitter , i would call this a hop bomb . m- just the way and ipa should be , very true to the style . overall this is not a bad ipa , it was just way too bitter for me , its seems that if the flavors arent blended together the best and the bitterness just takes over the whole beer . do n't think i would every buy this again but there 's plenty other shorts brews i will be getting instead .

really nice amber appearance with very little head . i consider myself a big hophead , but this is one of the few big ipas that i find really undrinkable . there is a really nice piney hop aroma and boy is the taste just a magnification of that smell .  m- medium bodied and well carbonated .
it pours black with a light brown sugar thick head .  3/5 m : medium/full body , warm and smooth going down . 4/5 d : too sweet for me to have more than 12 oz .
the aromas are of polished , caramelized grain , vanilla and those chewy , peach-colored , peanut-shaped candies .  m - medium bodied and smooth as you drink it down .
this is tremendously balanced . everything in equal doses , nothing outshining anything else . fabulous . follows the nose closely .  m ) lively carbonation , smooth but strong . refreshing .

this beer has a wonderful sweet candy smell along with malt and spicy fruit aromas . the flavors are sweet and fruity , including belgian yeast , malt , candy sugar , vanilla , figs , spices , and brandy . i really enjoyed everything about this ale , the aromas , flavors , the creamy mouthfeel , and the warming alcohol finish .  mouthfeel is good , rich and creamy .
this beer pours an amber color with a medium head that falls slowly and leaves plenty of lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is crisp , yet smooth . very beefy . this is weird .

wonder when it was bottled.. this beer poured a deep red color , almost a dark garnet . heading was a decent , two finger thick off white in color .  the infection has n't totally killed the other flavors quite yet and there are still some bourbon notes that save the beer mouthfeel : medium body with medium to low carbonation overall : i really want to try this one when it is not infected .

pours a coffee black with a massive two and a half finger , super creamy light brown head . wonderful lacing absolutely coats the glass . the frothy head lingers for the duration . a fantastic looking stout .  the mouth feel is decent , smooth and rich .
impressive ! t : intense .  light , crisp , full bodied .
this one is really , really , really dark ! ! black liquid in a bottle !  body is right , but finish is somewhat boozy .

as soon as this bottle was popped the smell hit the room , and the catch phrase for the rest of the night was born - `` that smells hoppy . '' in fact , nothing i have ever tried smells remotely this hoppy . bhm , 90 minute , the professor , lenny 's ripa - none of them can compare to the fresh pungent fumes this monster is releasing . this bouquet is simply huge and fresh cut . the taste and mouthfeel is so good .  m- clean on the palate . light bite from medium carbonation .
love founders but they missed with this one .  mouthfeel- very fine carbonation .

aroma is honeyish in sweetness with floral qualities and some fresh herbs . very nature oriented , garden like , fresh .  mouthfeel is light and smooth . it 's a pretty good beer , a little bit too citrusy/floral for me .

sour cherries , oak , and vanilla fill your nose . m : sour , acidic , dry , tart , pretty nice except for the thinness in the middle .  good creamy mouthfeel adds to the `` what could have been '' feeling .

the smell is great , fresh saison . the yeast is also there , producing the classic saison twang . there is a hint of flowery perfume scent in there , presumably the dandelion . slippery mouthfeel , not one of my favorites .  m : medium bodied with just a medium carbonation .

smell & gt ; grains , cereal , caramel . notes & gt ; not the best red i have ever had but it is quite good , and the people running the brewery pub are great crack .  it has a nice mouthfeel and i definately would n't drink another one .
into a pint glass , pours a deep black with decent head , good retention , leaving thick rings around the glass after each sip .  m : good mouthfeel on a reasonably full body .
a - beautiful looking pour of a beautiful looking beer .  so the mouthfeel is the biggest asset , followed by a fairly cool bottle .
a- beautiful rich , golden-bronze color . hundreds of tiny bubbles , and a thick white two finger sized head .  very little carbonation .

aroma is chocolate with a capitol c. smells more like hershey 's syrup than an imperial stout . taste follows the smell , but adds some alcohol as well .  overall : medium bodied with a smooth mouthfeel , this porter is better paired with food rather than drank as a session beer . minimal carbonation holds back its potential .
s - best smelling ipa i have had . sweet floral . it is definitely good , but has room for improvement .  m : a very nice , light and crisp mouthfeel that was very pleasant and easy to enjoy .

appearance 5/5 golden-tangerine with the appropriate haze of a dry hopped ipa , sculpin poured with a big off white head that took its time to settle and left kickass lacing . signature american ipa looks . perfect .  nice mouthfeel , but thats about it .

bomber bought at shawan liquors pours a deep , cloudy orange with about two fingers of creamy off-white head that recedes gradually , leaving behind considerable lacing .  mouthfeel is good , big , full and creamy . mayflower is one of those breweries that seems to do a good job with the mouthfeel of their beers .

appearance - a beautiful dark golden beer with a fingers worth of snow white head that quickly disappears . head sticks to the side of the glass very nicely , a very good looking beer .  this must be the least enjoyable rouge `` ale '' i have had so far ... it looks ok , deep golden orange hue with thin , soapy head . the aroma is very pleasant with a nice balance of sweet toasted malt and domestic ( that 's usa ) hops . the flavor is just plain weird to me . finishes with a sweetish , smoky flavor that continues with the oddness . what is most odd about this `` ale '' is that it is not an ale at all . it is a maibock , which is a german lager beer . it is as much an ale as bill cosby is a young white dude .
absolutely fantastic yeasty earthiness with the clay and some spiciness that plays well with the banana nose .  d- goes down very smooth , definitely a good summertime beer .
packaged 12/01/07 appearance - fully black on the pour , almost a finger of finely bubbled light tan foam , almost like a nitro head .  m : pretty nice mouthfeel , good levels of carbonation .

the nose is a mix of candied apples , caramel , red wine , wood , toffee , bread , and a smell i often get from english ales , a buttery aroma . impressive . the taste is a muted mirror of the nose , unfortunately .  m - carbonation level is actually quite nice , unlike a lot of pils/lagers . slightly slick mouthfeel .

sleeman porter 68 is a very dark and dim red ale with a huge , frothy , waxy and dimpled off-white head that leaves great lacing . looks supreme .  this bastard was the best looking thing in the bar , so i 'm sippin it in . that said , i 'm tired of drinking bourbon beers . but maybe i 'm not suited for a `` wee heavy '' style scotch strong ale like this one . maybe i 'm a lightweight low abv smooth drinking bastards . not from the backwoods . still well made though .

s - big nose of citrus and pine up front . the hop aroma is the star here with tangerine , grapefruit and a very subtle pineapple aroma burst out of the glass . a roasted malt profile is present but definitely subdued behind the hops . the wonderful tangerine and grapefruit aromas from the nose are difficult to specifically detect but the roasted malt flavours are much more prominent , creating a fairly well balanced black ipa . o - this was an excellent beer .  m : actually quite pleasant ... weighty but not heavy , well carbonated and textured ... a saving grace d : less than pleasant adjuncty aftertase brings down the score

tons of lacing ... aroma is awesome , smells like crown , tons of sweet alcohol , wood , lots of vanilla ... the taste is still pretty sweet , oak and vanilla , but not as strong , after such a great aroma , a slight let down ... feel is silky smoth , light warmness just smoothness . worth seeking out .  mf : light body , carbonated well , nice bitter finish .

'05 vintage great looking beer .  somewhat thick and sweet on the mouth , with lingering cherry flavors . i 've had a lot of lambics but not a lot of krieks , but i can tell you doubtlessly that this is a very sweet beer that lacks many lambic characteristics .

pours a dark amber , tiny bit of head , nothing really special but o the smell , it 's delicious , my stomach told me i needed some sweets as soon as i smelled it . i liked the first sip a lot , carmelized maple glazed bacon ? if the mouthfeel had had something more to it , this would have been perfect .  m/d - medium bodied and rather smooth and creamy . after two of the bbc big ipa 's i can safely say i dont have the need to go back .

smells pretty nice actually , much better than the appearance .  consumed 12/03/07 at crown city brewing , pasadena . creamy nitro texture . then , unexpected black coffee bitterness appears on tongue long after beer is gone .

yeah , coffee leads the way . a strong , dark , black coffee at that . the strong char must cover any vanilla , because i 'm getting no vanilla at all .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , and rather smooth with a gentle carbonation .

leaves a big , crazy , foamy biege head of more than three fingers in depth , and it has excellent retention , and leaves sticky webs of excellent lacing . beautiful to behold . appearence will be this ale 's high point .  mouthfeel : it is very thick and pretty smooth . this beer caught me completely off guard .
the beer poured a most remarkable dark gold like a fine whiskey with a good bit of off white head .  perhaps it was this sweetness that gave it a nice body and a good mouthfeel .

heavily aromatic , mainly passion fruits ( peach , tangerine and lemon . an interesting , unorthodox approach to the style but i do n't find this to be all that different from loads of others . it is hoppier , no doubt , but whatever the hops bring they take away equally . notes of lemon and other citrus fruits .  mouthfeel is light bodied , dry , some creaminess .
smell was big and malty , full of bread , biscuits , and something sweet too . there was a tangy smell in there as well , which ended up being alcohol .  mouthfeel is big , thick and creamy .

smell : this has the most beautiful smell . very floral and citrus hops permiate the area once this beer is opened . there is not much bitterness but the aroma and flavor make this beer very good . mouthfeel : nice and rich . there is some great flavor and aroma .  this was a bit dissapointing after the string of excellent beers i had from taps .

the beer had a very strong coffee-like aroma . you could wake up to this beer . full flavor in the mouth with a great smoky character .  a strange medicine taste too mouthfeel - the one good part of the beer . nicely full body and a pleasently smooth carbonation feel to it .

a : pours a vibrant chestnut ruby , with a good 1.5 '' light tan head that promises some retention . very nice touch though .  4.0 m : medium body . good moderate carbonation . not particularly smooth from the acridity , but feels good when it 's in my mouth . i really liked the mouthfeel though and it almost made the experience a good one .

not very complex , but darn good ! t - fresh bushels of strawberry are quite the unique experience in a brew .  and this is with some decent aging on it so the hops have had some time to calm down.. medium light bodied with lightish carbonation , this has a good mouthfeel .

i had to sniff this beer over a dozen times before i could place the heavy , yet appealing , aroma , and black licorice was as close as i got . tastes almost like roasted wood smells , with sweet , caramelized , licorice tones .  mouthfeel - the feel is fluid and smooth .
black with ruby red highlights and a nice creamy brown head .  m : light bodied , crisp and clean .

smell : lots of chocolate right away and actually some hoppiness , believe it or not . some coffee , roasted malt , hazelnut , and oak but mostly dark chocolate , smells like my kind of imperial stout . taste : bitter dark chocolate and coffee right away , but there 's a lot more of the nut flavor in the taste than i was expecting from the smell . not a bad thing though .  the palate is soft and tart with some nice and not so nice subtle flavors .
really impressive . t : definitely not balanced , but i was n't expecting that .  mouthfeel is good . hearty liquid , with just a less than moderate carbonation .

aroma is incredibly fragrant and fruity , with huge raspberry notes . this is a pretty remarkable beer for an american brewery to be making .  m : light to moderate body is well-carbonated & refreshing .

s- wow , smells exactly like a fresh hop . i 'm not saying it is really fruity or anything , but it legitimately has the hop aroma with a nice natural woodiness and slight grassy tint to really make you think this is a glass full of real hop pellets . o- damn surly nailed this one .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with spritely carbonation , and a velvety texture .
the smell had me excited . but the bourbon and alcohol smash everything that was awesome in the nose .  feels good in the mouth with a decent carbination for a dark beer .

my oh my , nice oily citrusy nose on this . amazing and sweet-bitter promise !  m : this is where it 's most reminiscent of its style : sticky hop resin , lingering alcohol heat , bitterness hanging on the tongue .
a nice strong whiff of red ripe grapes .  surprisingly , this has a great mouthfeel . lighter carbonation than your cheap macro swill means it is easy on the old tastebuds .

poured to a golden yellow with good carbonation , and a thin white head that lingered as a film on the glass throughout the drink , and left excellent lacing on the glass .  alcohol present in the smell , along with butter , raisin and a hop finish . lots of flavors on this , but a little out of control for me . an initial grassy flavor of butter that does n't blend well with the raisin , pineapple , alcohol , brown sugar and hops . some seemed to like it , so chalk it up to personal taste i guess , but i did n't feel like the flavors in this one were in order . too much alcohol and too much buttery sweetness .

smell is very fruity , citrus and peaches , very sweet in an entirely natural way . wonderful . taste is n't quite as complex , but banana and light yeastiness come to the fore with spices in the mix and slightly noticeable alcohol .  m - it was fairly crisp and smooth . a very light-bodied brew .
s- this is one of the best beers i have ever smelled . it is almost a fruity smell and makes you want to drink the beer .  medium-light bodied with quite a bit of carbonation .

the color is the most pleasant thing about this beer . it pours a beautiful clear coppery amber color . there is a small white head that vanishes quickly and no lacing on the glass .  medium in body ; surprisingly the malt character stands up well to the array of spices .
into a corsendonk tulip ... a - lots of attractive head with nice staying power . attractive amber body .  m : full-bodied , thick , and syrupy with moderate carbonation .

n : flavorful aroma for such a lighter sided beer . much much more complex than i expected . t : malty and nutty , not all the characters of the nose but tasty . smokiness takes over , interesting beer .  m : overall pretty good . medium at best compared to other ris , but very smooth . carbonation was appropriate or at least not distracting d : for the high abv and the taste profile losing its way this is a beer i could tolerate , but would not look forward to in the future .

1 finger light fine head , rich golden color , opaque s : citrus/apricot , very fruity , nice . nose is best part of this beer .  light bodied , smooth and crisp . wow , a wheat that i actually enjoyed .
the prettiest beer i have ever seen . pours a dark red with a majestic pink , creamy head . ah , luxurious .  it is medium bodied and has a good level of carbonation .
very clean and sharp looking bronze color with a huge , fluffy , pale caramel colored head on top .  medium-light body ; crisp and more than semi-dry on the finish .

the beer poured into the glass very dark amber , with a gorgeous head that left a nice lace as it disappeared .  it 's quite crisp and clean that really jolts the sense . the mouth feel really holds this beer together .

a strong aroma of honey appeared about 1/3 into the beer . this immense and pleasant aroma stayed around until the end . taste was light , crisp , citric hops .  m - full bodied that really fills your mouth and feels heavy .

on the nose is sweet wintery smell , berries and rye , very nice !  caramel malt , with some spicy rye thrown in , as well as the caraway seed . somehow this all molds together well . well balanced , minimal bitterness . interesting combonation of flavors .

the nose is very sweet ... spot on for the style in my opinion . i do n't think i would get this again , but its worth a try .  i almost feel like i got a little spice bite on my tongue from the peppers . m= smooth and delicious . feels like a good doppelbock .

the aroma was outstanding . super smooth and sweet with strong notes of coffee , vanilla and a touch of caramel . while both the appearance and the aroma were nearly flawless , the flavor and mouthfeel reminded me more of a mediocre irish dry stout than a well crafted american-style stout .  m : medium-full and well carbonated d : this beer nicely fits the characteristics appropriate for abbey beers , but is lacking in intensity ( as compared with other classic examples ) .

poured black with mahogany tint to it with a tan head .  lacqueredmouse caned this beer and i 'm not sure if i like it but i do n't think it 's that bad . flavourwise , its a light malt with a dash of honey that makes it sweet and like a hefe with no bitterness except the usual balance hops . i guess its an ale that 's nearly true to style except for the honey . there 's some clove and malt and a hint of banana but compared to pure blood hefeweizens it 's not in the race . i 'm glad it exists though because there 's room in the world for craft beers having a go .
a : pours a nice looking dark red color with a cream colored head that stays for a pretty long time .  the feel is a little redeeming . it 's nice and crisp , with pleasant carbonation .

the body is a dark and beautiful orange . the head is huge and defines the term pillowy .  feel was full-bodied , smooth , with a nice creaminess . lacking a good balance of maltiness to offset the powerful punch of hoppiness .
the nose is nice , with a good banana and nice sweetness from the wheat coming through .  good mouthfeel and drinkability despite taste .

smell : rich and sweet , hoppy . drink : it 's not as strong as i 'd like , and considering the terrific smell , the taste leaves something to be desired .  not too overpowering , but not very pleasant mouthfeel is pretty good .

the scent was a melange of baking chocolate and an almost chocolate liqueur/baking vanilla type scent , like sweetness with a distinctly alcoholic edge . hanging around in the background was a very nice hoppy character that the bitter finish tempers well so it does n't become to overwhelming .  creamy smooth , this delivers a subtle blend of caramel malts and moderately bitter hops . every nitro beer that i 've tried has the same pluses of eye candy and mouthfeel , but i get disappointed in that they all remind me a little of the others .

a thin layer of head from pour that leaves very quickly with no lacing to be seen the smell is really what gets me , its a straight kick in the nose ! awesome fruits and hops come out here , tons of grapefruit , orange , and lemon . some of the orange in the smell gets hidden in the tastes .  mouthfeel : medium drinakbility : medium , though i do n't crave another conclusion : gets a bit more unsorted as this warms up a bit ... i 'm not enamored with it by any means ; it 's not bad , strictly speaking , but it 's not that good either .

a- pours black . a creamy 1 1/2 finger head is produced but reduces to a light film withing a couple minutes . this reminds me of guiness draught in a bottle which i can drink , but it 's actually a little offensive .  it is smooth and foamy , with a crisp finish . it has a simple , balanced , amply bitter flavor . this is much better than their `` ipa '' .
a : perfect . golden wheat yellow with nice carbonation and great lacing .  good mouthfeel . silky on the palate with a good level of carbonation .
aroma : big bouquet of grassy hops . definitely the highlight of this beer . taste : wit like wheat flavor with extremely subtle citrus hop notes .  well carbonated .
excellent lacing left behind . s - big citrus aroma with lots of grapefruit and just a little tangerine .  with its light body and fine carbonation , it is very drinkable .

mmmm big beer . the nose is an homage to chocolate , earthy charred oak and vanilla bourbon . there is even a little hint of coffee and sweet coconut milk . the mouthfeel also dips from the high water mark set by the nose . an imperial stout should be thick and chewy with a rich velvety mouthfeel . combine that with a dry and crusty finish instead of the big flavors lingering and you have a beer that looks and smells better then it actually tastes .  m - it 's fine in the mouth . it 's medium to tight bodied with minimal carbonation .

poured from the bottle into a pilsner glass a- nice two inch head on the pour that sticks around . nice dark reddish-brown color .  mouthfeel -- full in body with mild creamy carbonation . drinkability -- a bit of a letdown , quite frankly . the mouthfeel , however , is pretty phenomenal , even if it 's more akin to a nice double/imperial stout .

... other than the 20 fingers of head ... this beer opened up to be , i 've got to believe , the best smell i have ever smelled in a beer in my entire life ! ... sweet cedar blend so well with the american citrus hops ... .  m : medium bodied with ample , fizzy carbonation .
there is a tarty smell , fruity and spicy .  the texture is thick or syrupy , and reminiscent of the cognac finish . too much sugar .

this beer has heavy clouding in its body but no sediments ; very thick white head that lasts for several minutes ; caramel-colored body with brown whisps throughout smell is absolutely outstanding : a sugary-sweet , fruity blend of aromas that is complimentary to the rest of the beer and very clean and crisp .  mouthfeel -- medium to light in body , with ample prickly carbonation . it suits the style well .

a - pours orange with 2 fingers of orange-white head , which dissipates slow and leaves beautiful lacing . very nice !  the mouthfeel is fuller bodied , with a creamy and bubbly feel to the carbonation . this sits with some heft in the mouth ( this actually feels a little heavier than 7 % ) but other than that the overall flavor is alcohol free .

smell : horseblanket , frankincense , plums and/or mincemeat fruit , minty freshness . ho yeah ! taste : very acidic , tart with raspberry and blackberry tang , milk chocolate , oak and an all around aura of funkalishiousness , if you do n't mind the expression .  aroma was pale malt and a weird kind of `` synthetic funk '' . it literally tasted like sugar water . there is a great carbonation in this beer which made it drinkable , but none of the great flavors of a true saison are present .

the aroma starts with a big punch of home-made rye crisp and white flour . the delicate and complex graininess of this one makes me think i 'm about to eat something .  this strong bite while being a little sweet m : texture is full , the foam stays with you while its in the mouth . the flavors really spark the tongue while it is in your mouth .
very nice ! t : dominant taste of toasted black malt paired with unsweetened chocolate and coffee .  thick body , moderate carbonation .

a - very nice , darker than expected , nice two finger tan head that only slightly dissipated . nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and initially crisp on the tongue , before getting more creamy feeling on the edges . this was pretty smooth overall , especially for 6 % .
i like the voluptuous bottle , very ergonomical . a huge 3 finger pillowy white froth tops my rapscallion snifter , a cloudy dark golden beer supports it .  mouthfeel is full and round .
very nice aroma . taste does n't quite live up to the nose .  md-thick body and moderately carbonated .

a : pours a straw color with a fluffy white head that lingers s : nice spice notes , a very clean , refreshing pear/green apple fruit aroma , a bubble gum sweetness t : at first , a big blast of sour , which then turns into a refreshing , slightly fruity sweetness , and finishes with an apple skin sort of dry , fruity finish .  mouthfeel is semi creamy , and not too bad .

the smell , as others have noted , is the quite exceptional . it smells like the belgian strong dark ale of my dreams . overall a satisfactory beer and the best smelling beer ever . give it a shot !  the taste unfortunately got skewed right away as the butteriness of this brew superceded any and all other flavors . the feel was medium/full and creamy .

looks fine sitting there ... three finger bone white head slightly hazy straw hue ... smells great lemons and brett are present along with some other fresh fruits like mango . the brett is there but hiding very well and all you get is a bit of lemon and then a long seemingly unending note of bitterness ... .from what ? it 's light and easy to drink but the unwelcome surprising bitterness character makes it not something i 'd drink a lot of ... thanks for the chance to try this idatetheforumla allagash i am disappoint ... if it 's between this and interlude , get interlude ...  mouthfeel was creamy and smooth .

very dark beer with a foamy head that lasts . very appealing in my eyes .  average at best ; certainly a letdown . mouthfeel : smooth and malty with light , rolling carbonation . sturdy body , that 's pretty chewy as well .

the nose on this beer is definitely great . it has strong spice notes , especially of cinnamon , and ginger , with some bready aromas as well . however , this beer is very very drinkable and could definitely be a session beer with the family over the holidays .  the mouthfeel was good - slightly unctuous from the alcohol - definitely knew you were drinking beer .

i do seem to get a mineral quality as well ( i wonder if that 's a yeast thing ) . really good looking brown and garnet crystal clear .  there just is n't enough going on if you can get past all the sugar . it drinks medium to full in body and is a smooth drink with no alcohol left behind in the aftertaste . it does n't come anywhere near anything by st. bernardus and it 's in the same price range .

the aromas were the best attributes to this drink . authentic smelling raspberry flavors ( i know they usually put actual fruits in there drinks when you are at the brewpub ) . overall , this was really good .  this beer aint for the weak . it is bold on flavor and will challenge your conceptions of acceptability , bordering on ..not sure the right word , was gon na say cloying but it aint sweet , just chipotle-ish ... which is interesting and nice and present but a bit hard to take in . best appreciated when drinking slowly with food . but one damn interesting beer .
poured a one-finger light tan head over a crystal clear light orange rusty liquid .  smooth , almost creamy medium body .

pours straw golden yellow with nice fine and foamy two fingers of white head that is slow to subside , slight lacing as well . somewhat hazy body - i can see the outline of my fingers through the glass , but not much else .  definately the best part about this beer . drinkability . thin and light , i was expecting more body in this beer .

this beer looks beautiful ! dark , dark red , almost black out of the light , a one inch head that lessens bit by bit , about a millimeter stays .  at first it 's all pine resin , which was a bit of a let down for me . do n't get me wrong , pine is great , but the taste just did not live up to the tantalizing smell at all . initially , it came as just a hint ... a whisper of apple cider/hard apple cider .
brilliantly clear pale spring bud liquid with a large half finger of shock white foam which ( surprisingly ) lasts and lasts . good lacing , no legs .  mouthfeel : medium body and carbonation .
however , beyond the great aromas and interesting sourness , there is n't a ton of complexity of flavors .  first sip reveals an average body with soft texture and very fine yet tingly carbonation .

pours a really nice looking dark gold with a thick and creamy one finger head which leaves a solid ring of lacing .  taste- incredibly biting bitterness , lays thickly across palate for being only five percent beer .
that smell is brilliant but the taste does n't even come close .  m- lighter side of medium in body and carbonation seems about right on .

wacky stuff . spicy aromas dominated by caramel and banana but tempered with some cinnamon and clove . basically banana nut bread .  a little too spicy for my liking m- thick , with a malty character . goes down smooth d- a little tough to handle all the spice .

a- dark red with a tight off white head . lots of lacing on the glass that fades slowly .  mouthfeel - medium body ( for the style ) . nice level of carbonation . it really gets to dancing over the toungue .
nitro poured with the creamiest , smoothest head i have ever seen .  mouthfeel is solid . a little resiny .
carbonation dances off the bottom in a very refreshing looking beer .  nicely carbonated , medium bodied . enjoyable in the mouth .

good smell , but subdued : pineapple , apple , banana , menthol , rubbing alcohol , slightly buttery shortbread . tastes of ripe golden delicious apple , pineapple , yeast , alcohol .  medium body with light carbonation .
smell has brett , vanilla , black cherry , and a deep earthy wood undertone .  mouthfeel : moderate and pleasant carbonation with a slightly creamy mouthfeel .
nicely balanced . taste is lightly sweet , dry finish .  mouthfeel is medium with good body and carbonation .

the aroma is great . sweet cherries , alcohol , and raisins .  m : perfectly carbonated with a medium body and a texture that rolls right off the tongue , which works out favorably for me since i 'm not a huge fan of the flavor .

nicely integrated and wonderfully inviting . such a wonderful aroma , but does n't quite integrate with the taste .  with some bready and slight fruity flavors up front m : medium bodied beer , carbonation seems pretty good o : this is a different beer , not horrible but not really my favorite beer .

pours an extremely dark brown , nearly black , and viscous looking with a good-sized dark tan head . retention is decent from the initial pour but pretty good after it settles .  m : good mouthfeel , carbonated just about right .
nose has that distinctive sam adams smell which is very pleasant , but the taste disappoints .  m : crisp sharp , and carbonated like a belgian should be .
bomber pours a perfect hazy orange into a pint glass with a huge head .  light crisp body with a good amount of carbonation .

huge beechwood smoked malt aroma dominates . secondary to that raisiny , decocted malanoidin malty aromas are noticeable , but the rauchmalt dominates .  m = medium-heavy bodied , good smooth foamy carbonation on swish , good mouthcoating .

decent one finger head has great retention and leaves decent lace down the glass s sweet grains with some booze and some petrol t not much better then the smell , pretty bad you know this beer has one purpose and that is getting drunk without spending money m/d i 've never drank petrol but i would guess it would feel something like this . looks great but it makes you gag as you swallow and that 's a trait i do n't like in my beer  the mouthfeel is the only area that garnered points other than appearance in my opinion . this beer was exceptionally smooth with good carbonation and a medium body .
aromais extremely sweet . taste is extremely malty as would be expected .  m : mouthfeel is fine . somewhat sticky which is nice in this style .

smell is rich and malty with strong notes of citrus , grape and green apple blended together . nicely balanced and well presented . overall a fine beer .  a lot of expectations on it , which did n't let me down as far as booze . has a decent first taste but does n't last long as soon as it hits the back of your tongue . hard to finish the bottle by yourself ... so recommended to share with a friend for the experience . with that said , i still respect and love dfh beers .

was hoping to hold onto this for a bit longer , but the cellar cleanse beckons . sexy mahogany , dark and impenetrable . strong maltiness , smells thick and caramelized . thick and enjoyable , very drinkable .  mouthfeel is light , carbonation is medium .

aroma is pleasant with darkly roasted and slightly smoked malts , oily french roast , distant bitter chocolate , slight hink of chalk..actually quite nice smell going on here . overall , the aroma on this is a winner , but the alcohol hurts it 's enjoyability .  despite the finish , the mouthfeel is excellent . d : avoid .

wonderful brown sugar malt and citrusy hop aromas . i love amarillo hops , and i can really pick up their influence in this beer ( the fact they 're listed on the label helps too ) .  m- crisp , refreshing , and highly carbonated .

smell is amazing - peaty scotch , some smokiness , dank hops , musty wood and stick malt sugar , with some hoppy fruitiness .  the mouthfeel is pretty nice with some mild carbonation and a smooth overall feel .

s : i get a nice blueberry aroma as well as saison yeast and bread . it has a very pleasant blueberry aroma . o : this beer has a nice aroma and appearance , but the flavor is just off for me .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel and very smooth .

i kept smelling it until i could n't smell it anymore , it was that good . tastes robustly of grains and alcohol .  maybe a few faint whisps of caramel and soapiness t : heavy caramel flavor with a touch of soapy floral hops m : not bad at all , there is some creaminess , and it is full bodied enough for the style d : i think i will pass after this one .

much thanks to chris for tapping this one as i enjoyed lunch today ... served a golden copper color with a full finger of off white head ... most fades but some tight , striated lacing forms as i work my way thru the pint .  has a medium body with medium carbonation that makes the beer crisp .

these schwarzbier 's pour jet black with a big fluffy brown/tan head that holds some great retention . the head laces the glass beautifully .  at first taste , i was hit with a licorice and pine flavor -- and then some real sweetness from the honey . it 's earthy and sweet . tiny bubbles make for a pleasant feel . color of the brew is a brown orange -- very similar , again , to iced tea . this beer is a novelty . the root beer brew is close in taste to yard 's ben franklin spruce ale -- but not as good .

the smell is intensely bourbon , with plenty of malt , fruit , and a hint of vanilla . the bourbon is a great , warming smell . awesome . when i put it to my lips , call me nuts , but i think i picked up on some bourbon ! at the end of the day , this is surely a damn good beer , but it 's too one note with the bourbon for me to give it a great mark . but i do think that with some vanilla or coffee to cut the bourbon , this would be truly spectacular . i guess i need to obsess on the vanilla or coffee versions of bcbs .  mouthfeel is fine . good carbonation .
appearance - beautiful orange/amber . nice level of floaties ( which i like ) .  moutfeel is nice and crisp due to a decent amount of carbonation .

the aroma is excellent . rich chocolate , coffee , dark grains , oil , soy sauce , and much more that i ca n't readily pick out . flavour is a bit lacking compared to the aroma , but still damn good . the coffee comes out a lot in the finish , and the beer overall is a heavy , sweet stout rampant with roasted grain bitterness .  mouthfeel is the only thing this beer is good at . medium body while still crisp .

good head , not the best retention s - spicy hops with a little maltiness supporting the smell t - very spicy , bitter almost like an under-ripe tangerine .  the taste is well , again kinda stale hops , but still some lingering hop bitters , mouthfeel is rich , and this beer is pretty strong .

s - a very aromatic nose of lemon zest , bubblegum , and sweet malt with a huge floral profile . coriander , rosemary , pepper , chamomile , and flowers are all present . fantastic nose . t - there 's quite a lot of complex flavors in here , and many carry over from the nose . the floral aspect is again rather strong , with chamomile and rosemary leading the way , and pepper and some cinnamon providing a nice , spicy counterpoint . very crisp and refreshing beer . o - really a fantastic brew , one of the most well-crafted saisons i 've ever had the pleasure to try . easily on par with the belgian masters .  m - bold and consuming .

smells great . lots of grapefruit and apricot . the hops bouquet is absolutely wonderful . the taste is n't quite as good as the aroma , unfortunately . would be much better if that beautiful hops aroma would show itself in the flavor .  feel is pretty good with a good carbonation and some oiliness .
this beer smells wonderful but the taste seems like a mess .  mouthfeel is medium with a nice thick body and a tiny bit of carbonation .

solid yeasty alcohol aroma , just perfect . small off-white head never amounted to much and faded to nothing , not a trace anywhere , it 's kind of weird .  mouthfeel is good for what ever style it is .

deep brown , with brilliant garnet flashes when held to light . steadfast , dogged tan head leaves sticky , dense lace .  body is the high point probably , some malt thickness is evident , but it makes its way around the mouth nicely with good medium carbonation to match .

poured chilled in party cup ( sorry y'all ) a : clear brown ; good creamy head ; strong carbonation ; very nice lacing s : slight stench , but goes away soon t : standard brown ale ; malty , sweet ; hops subdued ; thin flavor , not complex it 's all right .  m - thick , viscous , smooth , moderate carbonation .

aromas of citrus , orange , malts , and even a little bit of vanilla . somewhat intense at times , but overall a mellow yet refreshing bouquet . bitter flavors include grapefruit , caramel , pine , and a bit of sweetness on the finish ( which is different considering most non-west coast ipas exhibit sweetness up front and bitterness in the back ) . this is a decent dipa , and i would drink it again , but ( here comes my regionally elitist moment ) it ai n't got squat on some of our west coast dipas ( e.g. , pliny the elder , yulesmith , ruination ) .  the mouthfeel is on the lighter side of medium bodied with lively carbonation . it is nice to see leinie 's not going overboard with the carbonation like they usually do .

pours jet black with huge frothy head and a thick coating of lacing .  m : this is probably one of the heaviest ipa/dipas that i have had so far . mouthfeel is quite thick , if you swish it around in your mouth its almost like a syrup .

s - stron pungent aroma of big citrusy and tropical hops . orange and pineapple primarily with hints of tangerine and mango . excellent bitterness without being overwhelming . taste is more dipaish like the bottle says than just straight ipa like it is classified as .  m - light and crisp . high carbonation .
one of the best aromas i have ever encountered - smells like cherries and alcohol . i like it a lot .  mouthfeel : thick , syruppy and sweet ... just what i like .
you can not beat the appearance of this stout . a midnight opaque black with a huge creamy and cascading tan head .  m- good lingering bitterness , nice body .

nice spicy belgian yeast smell as well .  m : slick , fine carbonation in a medium to heavy body . leaves my tongue a bit coated and creamy , which is a nice surprise and levels out the bitterness quite a bit .

the coloration of this triple is outstanding , however the taste let me down . my bottle came corked in a 1pint 9.4 fluid oz size . very stong taste alcohol .  being some what of a foodie , i was excited to try this beer . i had their commander barleywine and was amazed , and was hoping for some of the same quality in this brew . can smell small hints of the vanilla , with a small hint of sweetness . t - as with the smell , it had to warm up quite a bit to even get any of the tastes depicted on the bottle . not impressed , solid made brew , just what was listed on the bottlle was not much in the taste . m- very easy to drink , goes down easy with very little alcohol taste . o - a solid made beer , just was not getting the tastes out of the beer described on the bottle . really wished there was more vanilla and anise flavor .

smells really very lovely . huge citric hop whiff with lots of tangy lemon , orange , pineapple , sherbet and passionfruit . lovely , as i said .  appearence was pale and fizzy . mouthfeel was standard for american pale lagers , and actually , had a bit of fullness in the cheek , which was nice .

haze is very minimal . sweet glorious citrusy amazingness . there is a nice blend of sweet and citrusy in the smell . very enjoyable . really deep examination into the smell reveals a bit of sharp cheddar cheese aroma , but just a touch .  a soft beer in terms of mouthfeel . i like the texture -- a bit richer than most pilsners .
nice head , opaque body , plenty of lacing , great smokey nose .  m : light , crisp , highly carbonated . spot on for the macro style .

the beer pours a very light shade , straw colored with an srm of 2 or 3 . the head is enormous , a big pillowy poof , like a dry cumulus cloud , large solid chunks of dry lace on the glass .  nemesis is full-bodied , and very viscous . slick and chewy , with a dry , boozy finish . not a drainpour ... thorn telling rabbit to `` well , finish it up '' after a syrup chug victory in super troopers comes to mind , somewhat appropriately .

really pretty complex , with molasses , bourbon , and chocolate aromas intermingling . d - definitely has a boozy aspect and alcohol is present , but it is still pretty drinkable as those flavors do n't go unchecked . really enjoyable beer .  m- mouthfeel is good enough , adequate carbonation .

1/8 inch tan head and some spotty lacing smell : this smell like a peanut butter and jelly sandwich in a glass the nose is perfect for what they were trying to do taste : unfortunately the taste does fall short and instead of resembling a pb & j it is kind of a mess in a glass . as great as the nose was the taste is almost equal bad .  very odd approach to the normally lush pumpkin pie nose in good pumpkin ales ... '' let 's go for the crust '' . mouth is also crust-forward , throughout the palate with little bitterness to speak of . a crust bomb .

brew , purchased from a man named peanut with a handle-bar mustache at the dilly deli in cincinnati extremely viscous liquor that pours like black corn syrup . aroma of figs soaked in alcohol spiked molasses , enjoyed by a warm fire near a peat bog . very interesting brew and my first impy from england . would be excellent as a marinade .  m : light-medium body , moderate-lively carbonation and a very creamy , smooth texture .
the nose was a very promising sweet malt aroma with some peat smoke on the bottom .  mouthfeel is well carbonated and medium bodied .

nose is creamy sweet with hints of vanilla bean ice cream , spicey fruit , and yeast doughnuts . nice dark fruit notes twords the end of the palate .  mouthfeel : the thing that 's done correctly with this brew , as it 's full , creamy , and has enough carbonation to make me crave the other wheat flavors and aromas that are too obfuscated by the boysenberry flavors and aromas .

an almost black beer that pours with a creamy , tan head that shows very good retention . the head fades to a thin layer of foam , which leaves a thin lace on the glass .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with good carbonation and good retention .

a really nice smell . the taste comes immediately as chocolate and ripe fruits , like raisins and such .  mouthfeel- the weight changes radically once the liquid has a chance to explore the mouth ... thin at first , it swells to a slicker , more enjoyable texture as time goes on . the swallow is relatively quiet and nice .
a fantastic blend of schlafly stout and local coffee-bar favorite kaldi 's coffee . i , for one , love it .  mouthfeel is medium to full in body with a creamy , inactive carbonation .

after all , they are the `` dark beer specialists '' . big , decadent notes of chocolate and mildly charred coffee , plus toffee and tobacco . all in all , a well-crafted doppelbock from the geniuses that dwell in farmville , nc . a must-try for fans of the style .  medium body and carbonation with slight clingy feel .

no lace at all in my pour . smells citruisy and earthy , the dry hopping is dominated by an aggresive american hop , my guess would be amarillo , brett is present in the background , but the american hops definetly dominate the aroma in this beer . and the draft version has less tartness , and you get more of the belgian funk , brett , horseblanket character .  the mouthfeel was also very nice , it was silky smooth and almost kinda chewy . the alcohol gave a warming feeling to my mouth and throat .
s - this is actually pretty remarkable smelling . a blast of grapefruit , pineapple , and orange , with full notes of fresh bread and caramel supporting .  small crispness .

did n't gush when i opened it , but it poured even at a full right angle with 70 % head . after a while the head settled down to a decent size , still thick and impressive . brilliant clarity , amber cooper color . highly carbonated , not sure if this was the brewers goal .  mouthfeel is actually pretty good .

smell is distinctively of sweet caramel , red apple , fresh yeast , sweet grape , and banana . rich smell before and after sips . the taste very nearly lives up to said smell , though not completely .  healthy carbonation lends a slightly acidity to the mouthfeel .

it smells so good ! but this body ?  in the end there 's a soap hoppy bitterness ( more soap than hop ) that sticks on your tongue . in fact , i want to wipe my tongue and mouth off . maybe it 's something in the colorado water . i 'll have to ask coors ! for that reason , drinkability is low for me , although if this is your thing , it 's a truly smooth brew for the abv and the category .

body is a hazy purplish ruby when held to the light . a thick , tanned head comes out from the pour and maintains a good 1/4 '' . leaves thick and raised lacing .  mouthfeel is full bodied and thick ; really syrupy , hot with alcohol , chewy , with decent carbonation .
has a wonderful roasted aroma to it .  mf- light bodied and cool with very soft delicate carbonation . bubbles still have enough vigor to keep the beer from feeling flat .
the nose was quite pleasent ... wonderful notes of peach and apricot .  the sourness is there but not terrible m- good carbonation and surprisingly not as thin as i expected .
pours the color of brazilian walnut wood , deep and beautiful , with minimal head from a bomber .  good moderate carbonation and med-light body .
if the brew had tasted as good as it smelled i would have been exceptionally happy . good flavor , malts with a bourbon note throughout .  full bodied , lowly carbonation .

aroma : fresh fresh hops ! wet dripping goodness ! wow that smells great ! appearance : hazy gold , thin to no head but a swirl will produce a nice white cap that rises and falls leaving lace in spots . flavor : matches the aroma perfectly ! ) hops heavy on the aroma and taste side , not so much on the bittering , coriander and clean . wow , ive drunk the kool-aid , ive seen the light .  mouthfeel- medium body , with a nice level of carbonation that pushes the hops to the fore-front .

my score 4.5 the smell is very strong . plenty of alcohol there with a ton of dark fruits , mostly plums , and a definite woody aroma . now some sherry like smells are coming into the picture as well as some caramel malt sweetness , though the latter is tough to pick out .  the chewy mouthfeel will keep you around to finish the pint you ordered , but i doubt you 'll want another .

quite simply , the finest aroma i have ever encountered in a beer . this is a grapefruit/orange bomb and still maintains some decent lingering grainy background to balance well .  body is medium with good belgian carbonation .

i really dig the 100 barrel series batch 10/01/04 deep copper , approaching brown , with an off-white , choppy , rocky , creamy head that pours thick and leaves heavy swilred-islands and cloudy glassware .  carbonation and feel were quite nice , but the taste just seemed to be lacking .

'' it smells pretty spot on like vanilla custard and creme brulee . damn . there 's a slight bite to this beer that hints at the 10 % strength and the flavor pales a bit compared to the deep and rich aroma . still , more custard comes out on the palate with a mocha edge .  feel is right on point for a five percenter . carbonation is there , seen and felt without biting the tounge .
the smell of this beer is nothing short of amazing . taste is fantastic , color is a rusty , bubbly and quite dazzling array of sheer beer goodness ( or perhaps godliness ) .  quite well carbonated .
spicy floral aroma , maybe coriander . very spicy nose . spicy floral taste , some lemon .  the mouthfeel was nice , but i did n't take many notes about it .

poured little or no head.the smell was strong of raspberries and cranberrries.you could smell the sweetness in the aroma , ,very inviting.the color was a ruby red and very cloudy with a swirl of sediment.looks like iced tea almost.crisp mouthfeel with a light body.i would of liked to try more but i only had one of these and the bottle cracked and chipped when i opened it.the first time that has happened to me.i was afraid glass splinters were in the beer so i didnt finish it.i hope to rate this again someday .  this is the fifth hefeweizen i 've tried . of the five this ranks fifth best . something about these dundee beers that initially offers a metallic taste when cold . perhaps i 'd call this a beer that is better than dull but in need of some more flavor . at this moment , my hefe-universe is franzikaner and weihenstapher taking the lead , with sierra nevada a distant third , followed by paulaner . dundee sits behind paulaner .
this beer poured an opaque dark brown , almost black with a rich , foamy head that easily covered the top 50 % of the tulip i poured it into .  mouthfeel is another positive factor of this beer .
rosemary specifically is very robust . 4/5 o : it smells great but fails on the taste .  full bodied , smooth and creamy , low carbonation .

moving right along , aroma is bursting with that familiar banana along with some fairly strong flowery noble hops .  m : starts off lightly sweet but finishes lightly dry . a nicely balanced beer that rations its flavors out well .

the smells really setup and highlight this beer .  a - one inch off-white creamy and fluffy head ; light copper/bronze colored ; clear appearance with visible carbonation ; small patches of lacing s - floral , herbal , and perfume-like aroma of hops ; butterscotch lingers in the background t - very floral , perfume-like taste up front that reminds me of bubble gum ; diacetyl buttery flavor is also noticeable beyond the floral/perfume characteristics ; taste becomes more leafy and vegetable-like at the end of the taste with diacetyl still present - this taste lingers on the palate ; somewhat bitter towards the end of the taste m - light to medium bodied ; moderate carbonation ; fairly smooth mouthfeel that 's a little dry in the finish o - i 'm not sure of the last time i had an english ipa , but maybe i 'm just not a fan of this style .
pours jet black with thick , foamy head .  the mouthfeel is on point for the style : creamy and smooth without too much carbonation .
had an awesome vinous hoppy scent too it .  mouthfeel is light having good body with crisp carbonation .

one of the most extraordinary aromas in any beer , a complex weave of malt , syrup , plums , tart yeast . i always sit and enjoy the nose for ages before actually taking my first sip . ( this beer is a rarity as the aroma is actually far better than the taste .  very mild tingle on sides of front of tongue .

a : pitch black body , with a thin tan head ... very little lacing s : rich roasted coffee and chocolate.. bold and assertive ... t : dulled down version of the nose ... the flavors are still there , they are just lacking the pronounced `` pop '' the nose had ... slight alcohol coming through .  the body is solidly full for being an under 5 % brew . the carbonation is right near where it needs to be , but to me comes across as just a touch low at times .
this beer looked great . mahogony in the glass , and ruby when held up to a light .  full body but light in the sense that it seemed to evaporate from the tip of my tongue before i could swallow .

the slight pumpkin pie smell is subtle but nice . the taste is nice , a strong cinnamon uprfront will lent into a nice caramel malt smoothness in the end , a hint of pine fall hops in the back .  quite refreshing and smooth .

i liked the aroma of this beer , ..very malty with a barley scent to ( ive been in a whisky distillery and this smelt like the malted barley stage ) ... liked it a lot . nice dry malty taste though less than i had expected given the aroma..nice crisp on the palate .  slightly thicker feeling that i would have expected , i 'd put this on down as being on the light side of medium bodied and with a smooth texture . it is quite clean and crisp with strong carbonation and a mild bitter finish .
the nose is piney with a little citrus underneath . fresh pine tar and grapefruit .  m - light to medium body with medium carbonation .

strong fruity scent of bananas , very nice . initial tastes of light banana and general fruitiness .  finishes dry and bitter m : light/medium bodied , goes down easy d : would probably not buy this again , lacked any good hop flavor , ended up just being too bitter , ended up pitching this down the drain
i loved the aroma and really enjoyed the taste .  mouthfeel : lower than average carbonation , good for a stout . body is very good .

n : rich and spicy butterscotch brownie malt , spiced hot cider , molassas , and even a touch of stewed red cabbage ( in a very good way ) . totally different from any of the other oktoberfests i have tried so far this season but a little wild and smile inducing . p : powdery malt with a bit of spice that waits several beats before it introduces itself . where are those lovely flavors the nose promised us ? but what a nose , i 'll tell ya !  it tatsed like pine sap to me .
a - mahogany with a two finger head . gorgeous !  f : nice carbonation .

the smell was very positive , but the brew did not deliver as i had expected , might be better in a really warm surrounding .  this is the shining moment for this beer . the carbonation just tickles the tongue .
s : the aroma was fantastic similar to sour dough bread .  m- light in body and good amount of carbonation .
s - strong roasted malts , dark chocolate , coffee and a touch of fruit , maybe that is the honey ?  mouthfeel was smooth , with a medium body .
s : elegant full bourbon nose . vanilla central , wood , a joy to smell .  medium bodied , decent carbonation .
pours a nice reddish orange with a creamy off white head that has good retention and rings the glass .  mouthfeel medium in the body with a nice smoothness in between the cheeks .
smell is outstanding . huge roasted malt , with bits of vanilla and anise , and a good smokiness .  good mouthfeel ... lightly carbonated , somewhat creamy .

quite intense and intriguing . taste is sweet and sharp up front - malts and figs , but the follow through is almost dry and bitter . all in all , i think this beer 's stongest quality is in its aroma . a nice beer to savor .  fairly full with nice carbonation i was a bit let down with this .
very nice . taste starts sweet with some honey and mollasses .  m - medium-light body , low english-style carbonation , and a fairly clean finish .

( just kidding ) cork removes like that of a bottle of fine cognac immediately releasing ... ever light a candy apple on fire ? the maple syrup factory has burned to the ground ... let 's drink the ashes .  the mouthfeel is thick and creamy and the taste is very sweet with tons of malt , though nothing particularity interesting . the hops in this taste very medicinal . the taste is a bit blunt and lacks refinement .

this beer 's smell is really nice - citrusy , a little apricot , some yeast & spices - very impressive nose .  m : medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . keeps good with the style o : stays within style guidelines for some of the aspects like appearance and mouthfeel , but really lacks the flavor and bitterness that is usually present .

aroma is just plain incredible mix of dry fruits ( figs , prunes and raisins ) with some floral malt . i probably wouldnt drink more then one in a session but i would love to smell this aroma over and over again .  m- rather creamy and smooth . at least something is going right with this beer .

lacing while drinking is exceptional consisting of scatters waves of foam while drinking . once again like their blonde , an amazing appearance .  body is more impressive with a gentle carbonation through a medium-thin body that makes you want to chew it . crisp with the pils , but still comes out tasting like a macro .

the smell is of raisins and spice with a touch of soy on the backnote . a veritable fruitcake of aromas , with a rummy alcohol and candies fruits as well .  the joy of this beer is in its exact representation of the stated ingredients on the bottle . in this case , the beer was light on the tongue in terms of crispness . there is a mild bitterness imparted by the hops but the gist is spice . definitely compelling . as for drinkability , this falls into the one and done category that is best shared amongst guests who are already drinking spiced eggnog .
very appealing . taste : initially , more sweet than i was expecting .  m : light body and good carbonation .

smells absolutely delicious : sweet and malty with a lot of vanilla caramel and milk chocolate on the nose along with bourbon-soaked dates . so excited to try this .  feels pretty good going down , kinda thick with a long lingering bittersweet aftertaste and just a touch of warming slightly reminiscent of a tripel .

pours dark ruby red to mahogany with a tightly packed 2 fingers mocha head . good head retention & lacing smell : slight malt , smoky & licorice hints .  mouthfeel and drinkability are this beers best attributes ... the beer is crisp and has a little bit of a bite on the tongue and lips .
the smokin ' lager poured a cloudy copper-red with a lot of tiny floating particulates . it had a huge light tan head the had great retention .  big full bodied beer .

the nose is huge and full of fresh cascades . it 's like i just opened a bag of leaf hops to dry hop a beer . it 's an excellent ipa , but i think i 'd like a bit more malt flavor and body to back up the raging hops .  m : high carbonation keeps it fairly light . quite drying .

not to disparage this beer , i love the smell , i love soy sauce ... taste ... the more intense `` soy '' flavors poked through to me instantly , a bit intense ... not surprising considering the higher alcohol content ... .the finish is coffeelike , delicious . overall , the men at spaten really know what they 're doing , and this dopplebock reaffirms my high opinions of their creations ... i 've never met a spaten i didnt like .  m : good amount of carbonation runs off the middle of my tongue . medium thickness feel .
the smell on this beer is fantastic . never have i had a honey beer that smelled this close to raw honey in it 's own jar still .  m - medium body and low carbonation .
intriguing and complex ; very good overall .  the feeling in the mouth is much warmer than the feeling of the glass in the hand .

appearance vibrant orange and clear body ; decent sized head that settles fast smell wonderful nose-juicy citrus hops as well as some nice dry malt taste & body taste does n't quite follow the delicious smell . the bittering hops seem to be outweighing the flavor hops , and the body is a bit on the weak side .  mouthfeel is nice and smooth , coats well , but this is a 20 % + beer , and it should feel good going down .

color is really similar to that of a red smells of yeast and tart blueberries . tart makes itself known in terms of flavor , and the yeast almost makes me think of a belgian . it almost has a bitter aftertaste- which sort of reminds me of unripe berries . having it be just a smidge sweeter would make it perfect .  with this final rogue , top 100 brew , i am now done with the brewery for the indefinite future . i could do without the funky ceramic bottle , but maybe i 'll find a use for it in home brewing . the aroma is a jumbled mix of bitter hops , bitter chocolate , and stale coffee . it 's acceptable , but not overly enjoyable . raw , acrid pine hops mixed with bitter chocolate does not a pleasing combination make . too sour and bitter , with almost a hint of saltiness about it . this is a melding of styles that did n't work at all . this is only the second below average grade i 've ever given to an ris .

at first smell , i 'm reminded of brandy angel 's share . there 's dark , alcohol soaked fruit ( cherries ) with a strong barrel aroma . brown sugar mixed with some morning coffee and as it warms , more of the brandy barrel comes out . it smells divine and very different than the other 2010 versions . upon tasting , bitter bakers chocolate with cocoa , coffee with some slight dark fruit at the front .  well carbonated , with pretty good mouthfeel .
s- the bittersweet chocolate aroma is nice and represents the flavor well .  good body , bit of carbonation but not harsh .
there 's a light tan head that crumples with some sticky lacing . the beer is a dark ruby color .  m : well carbonated , crisp .

appearance : 1/4 inch head , low carbonation , red-brown in color , hazy , some sediment smell : oak , vanilla , cherry , and caramel -- this is an awesome smelling beer . taste : cherry taste similar to sa cherry wheat , toasted malt , caramel , alcohol , and a touch of oak .  a nice mouthfeel , creamy medium body that is buoyed by the airy , not fizzy , carbonation .
