smell is a brett bomb , it 's bugged out . brett brett and more brett , a ton .  it 's not bad , necessarily , it 's just totally wrong for the style . that said , the mouthfeel is smooth , thick and rich , and the 6.3 % abv is nicely concealed .

smell is exceptionally potent for beer , smelling of spice , nutmeg , and brown sugar .  decent body ... it 's a carbonation supported medium body which makes it clean and crisp like crunchy fall leaves . i like the mouthfeel , just not too much else .

3.5/5 s : bready/caramel malt with a flavorful and abundant citrus hop . 4.5/5 t : like the smell , though the hop is n't as strong as i might have hoped , and the hop flavor has less grapefruit to it .  md thick mouthfeel and strong carbonation .

pretty cloudy which takes away from it in my eyes s : wow , this is an amazing floral bouquet coming from this one . does finish dry and clean o : this is a good ipa , its reputation may be better than the beer itself but i liked it and would definitely try another .  m - kind of a lingering bitter finish . fairly full bodied with moderate carbonation .
smell : strongly sweet and fresh smell , similar to belgian dark ales .  full-bodied with moderate carbonation .

poured softly , but suprized by the abundant , dark brown head that forms ; especialy for how softly i poured . one of the darkest heads i have ever seen . this beer is alot more drinkable than the color and smell infer .  m - light-bodied but definately present . nice carbonation .
aroma is incredible , i think . the taste i do not think compares to the aroma .  m - creamy and full d - not what i was expecting .

pours a light amber , strong banana haze . great two finger head that slowly recedes to a very thic foam throughout the whole 12 ounces .  mouthfeel is medium-full , and is actually quite nice , but still this is not a stout in any way , shape , or form . sorry potosi , had to review to style , but i know you can do better !

smell : dipa hoppy , but distinctly different . spicy , minty , floral , a bit of orange juice a-la bspa and a bit buttery . amazingly , a malty caramel sweetness comes through loud and clear .  mouthfeel is full bodied and not overly thick or viscous .

smell : plum , raisin , figs , cherry , banana , brown sugar , and all other kinds of sweet , fruity goodness . i could smell this all day and be happy . taste : tastes exactly like the aroma ( see description above - too lazy to repeat it or attempt to paraphrase ) , but is ultimately a trifle too sweet for my tastes .  lindemans faro drinks pretty much like an apple juice infused gueuze . the problem is an unwelcome bombardment of sweetness . where i wish i would find increased tartness , its more layers of sugar . the way the sweetness lingers and mixes up with some unexpected must is interesting . it contains more funk , sour apple , and only a hint of the sweetness to follow on the tongue . this may ( or may not ) be a good example of the style , but i cant get into this beer . still , not entirely undrinkable .
overall a solid , and particularly great smelling , ipa .  medium mouthfeel , smooth .
reviewed 9/11/2007 ( bottle ) : pours a dark black colored body , with a dark tan head , smallish but good lacing and lasting .  perfect for the style , extra stout all the way .

smell is hoppy , citrus , and sweet fruitiness that i really like . taste is pretty good , the hops are much more spicy then fruity like the nose .  not a lot of carbonation . has a smooth feel and quite a heavy body .

review adapted from notes taken 12/4/10 note : 2010 batch appearance : pours a beautiful copper/amber color - a little hazy , with an amazing head that lasts forever - honestly , i do n't think ipas can look better than this smell : wild , untamed hops - lots of citrus , orange , pine - on the leafy/herbal side , a little too much for my taste - some interesting malts underneath taste : solid - lots of intense , borderline harsh hops - tons of citrus flavors with a hint of piney resin - a great amount of bitterness - malts provide a great backbone - toasted biscuits - kind of dry , with a salt flavor that i taste in all sn bottled beers ( sadly loses some points for this ) mouthfeel : medium bodied , mostly smooth with some bitter , leafy harshness overall : an undeniable classic that i intend to enjoy every winter while celebration is not my favorite ipa , it is extremely tasty and it has a certain charm that i appreciate more every year .  its palate was very smooth and it gad a plesant malt fore and after taste .
smells insanely strong ! it smells strong but wonderful . i ca n't wait for the first sip !  the mouthfeel is pleasant though , it has a fairly robust body , and a good level of carbonation .

on tap at bj 's brewery ... a - poures black with a two finger light tan head . head is really frothy , but has nice retention . decent amount of lacing in this one ... s - not much to smell here .  m-has a good medium creamy carbonation with a slightly dry finish .
s- from the tap , big aromas chocolate , roasted malt and toasted hazelnut soar from the glass .  mouthfeel : smooth , medium-bodied mouthfeel . also a little zing from the carbonation .
smell : a good deep fresh cherry aroma .  mouthfeel-medium full body , with moderate carbonation .
powerful peach scent at first .  m : nice and crisp , full-bodied , but like a soda , making it pretty easy to drink for an 8 % beer .
d- great concept and the smell was wonderful but the follow through just was n't there .  its semi smooth with a mild carbonation touch .

a- incredibly aromatic , my nose does n't need to be near the glass . a very sweet fruity aroma with a slight spiced smell . the aroma alone is worth it , just pour a glass and enjoy the smell .  feel is a bit beefy though comparetively speaking with whats offered in taste ; the full crisp feel more then makes up for some of the faultering taste .

terrific aroma . t : sweetness is up front , with both vanilla and caramel leading in to the smoke , fruitiness , and finally some rich dark chocolate . perfect . o : this is a terrific beer , plain and simple .  not even a hint to it being a beer . i would think this is just black cherry soda . in fact , i thought it was way too sweet and a strong black cherry flavor overpowered the beer . there was a slight ketchup taste that i find in flemish sours .

smell is richly malty with with notes of earth and whiskey , raisins and apples , caramel and smoke . really great complexity and balance . taste is amazing .  s : this is the best part of this beer . m : it 's fairly smooth and none abrasive .

great looking beer . cloudy golden body w/plenty of floaties .  the beer pours a fantastic long lasting head and was very murky although there is a full half inch of yeast slurry in the bottom of the bottle that i tried to leave behind . the yeast character of the beer overall is superb . the ester/higher alcohol balance is perfect . overly bitter , lingering , harsh and leaving an unpleasant finish . a shame the recipe let down the other quality work here . not quite as good as american flatbread or otter creek 's recent tripels .

produced a good cap of frothy white foam . ( s ) - a mildly dry profile with an awesome burst of lemon , banana , wheat , and bubblegum . finishes in a dry biscuit aspect . ( t ) - very yeasty and dry . on the far end spectrum of dry , earthy , and yeasty parts that carries a bitterness with it uncharacteristic of the style . not bad , but far from the best of the style .  a- bright crisp golden-orange , with a thin , though relatively resilient , head . t- a faint , watery lead-in leads to a sudden crescendo of unbalanced , un-alloyed bitterness . my wife finds a much more citric flavor , if i find this to be the case in future bottles , i will revise this review to reflect that . m- decent , sturdy , not to thin , slightly creamy . d- this bottle , to me , is unballanced and hard to enjoy .

smell : hop damn ! unique . taste : i was expecting some kind of freaky concoction with off-centered flavors and just too much of everything , but i was pleasantly surprised to find a very well balanced ale , with everything in it 's proper place , leaving room for everyone make a statement on my tastebuds .  medium mouthfeel .

i 've had a nice handfull of smoked beers in my life and this one smelled the most like how i would want my smoked beers . notes of bacon and baked beans hit me first . it was a great aroma without much bitterness , roastiness , or astringency that some other had . i knew i had found a winner .  md-sstrong carbonation is about right .

the aroma is very sweet - malty sweetness and pretty floral . very unusual but pleasant . the flavor is a little too hoppy for me and a little watery .  it 's not quite what i expected in way of body and flavor , but as it 's warm outside i found that i drank it very fast . this beer has a smooth and very mild flavor , with little hops . the aroma is also very mild , with light citrus . while i do n't feel that this beer is very representative of the wheat ale , i do think it 's an excellent beer for beginner beer drinkers . it 's an easy beer to help transition from the common american beers .

s : as sweet as you can get . caramel and chocolate covered raisins . this is one of the most chocolate smelling beers i have had the pleasure of drinking- like liquified charleston chew . american strong is a catch-all category and i guess this goes there but to put this and compare to a beer like arrogant bastard is not right . enormous full body with low carbonation and creamy .  good body for the style .
smell : the hops remind me of carrots , and they are very floral , not citrusy . there 's a scent of rose hips , but no scent of malt .  medium/light mouthfeel .

it looks good ; nice , moderately cloudy appearance .  taste is smoky , doughy and of some dark fruitiness as well . smoky lingering flavor in the finish . light bitterness but i just was n't a fan of the smokiness in this beer .
pour is just amazing . a very dark brown liquid with a very thick off white head that sticks around and leaves some thick lacing .  mouthfeel is creamy and bold .

smell : smoky aroma with traces of hickory & a barbecue-like aspect . the aroma is exquisite & heavenly . taste : malty with a dominant smoky aspect . trace of burnt wood but not as bold as the aroma would have led me to believe .  the mouthfeel is the creamy nitro , and definitely the most pleasurable aspect of this brew .

excellent aroma . cherries are the star but they do not dominate to the point that the other aromas are masked . t - the taste is a touch of a let down after the incredible nose , though it still is a nice tasting beer . very effervescent and i might say it is a touch too carbonated . o - a very solid beer though i would say it is a touch of a let down , especially given how amazing the nose was . certainly a good beer and i would not mind having one to lay down for a while .  m - medium body with a good amount of carbonation .

this beer pours a very dark reddish brown with about a finger thick head to it .  the pumpkin and yam really gives it a nice full flavor and sweetness to counter the bitterness of the hops . m/o : very crisp and drinkable but also has a lot of complicated flavors . it 's nice but a little overwhelming with the flavors .

above average head retention & average lacing s : lovely oak & port notes , raisins & other dark fruits t : dark fruits by the bushel , brown sugar , dryness up front . finishes dry , plummy with candi sugar , rich toffee , & a little more booze ; a little more depth & this would 've pulled 5.0 mf : chewy , slick , low carbonation , some booze warmth drinks easy , but i could feel the booze grabbing me from the get-go .  some alc in the taste 4 m light to medium bodied , goes down easy but for abv 1.5 d 6.5 abv a bit excessive for single ipa .

massive amounts of sweet raspberries moderated with a blast of spicy hops . a quote from mrs . t-a healthy dose of fresh raspberry flavour up front that starts pleasant but is quickly `` ruined '' with an overdose of spicy hops and a syrupy sweetness . the finish becomes medicinal at times and reminds me of chewing st. joseph 's children 's aspirin .  m : heavy bodied giving it a syrupy texture and has relatively low carbonation . it leaves a very sweet sticky feeling in the mouth begging for another drink .

a blast of malt and hops laced with notes of caramel and fruit assaults the olfactory initially . hints of freshly mown hay weave their way through the citrus complex midway but fail to dethrone the resurgent malt and resiney hops . with such a powerful aroma profile , one would expect the flavours and mouthfeel to present an equally potent response , but this is not the case .  medim bodied with good effervescence .
a - gorgeous . it 's brown with ruby hues and a never-ceasing tan head . there 's great clarity , but the beer is very dense .  nice sweet malty straw taste with a medium mouthfeel .

holy grail produces the most cranium i 've seen on any pale ale . it 's nearly pure white and is about three inches thick . the body is copper in color and is crystal clear ... highly filtered .  m - good carbonation , fairly large amount of bubbles .

sorry to give bell 's such a horrible review , but after purchasing this beer in keg form and wasting $ 130 ... .i got ta say it is just bad ... .no way anyone can drink more than 1 of these ... i have to dilute mine with kalamazoo stout just so i can burn through the keg and get something new ... .contimplating drain pour ... way too thick ! my friends laugh at me and say `` you paid how much for that valvoline stout ? `` ... embarrassing ... .terrible , terrible beer ... .not to mention it wont work with nitro !  feel : nicely velvety and soft , with a prickly medium carbonation and a body a shade over medium light .

zesty orange and citrus aroma , sweet , dank , and resiny . as it sits , it has a pleasant woody , leafy , vinous scent that emerges . really fresh and appealing . full bodied and almost viscous , with a strong bitter hop edge . very potent stuff .  m : mouthfeel is on the mark . thick , moderate carbonation .

smells wonderful : malty , woodsy , maple-syrupy , and the taste is very satisfying , with a vanilla/oaky/boozy overlay that makes it a wonderful sipper .  thin mouthfeel with a miniscule note of grains and hops .

served on tap into a snifter for the winking lizard 's glass of the month a- poured a clear light amber color with very creamy head that left tons of chunky lace s- smells like bourbon and booze .  mouthfeel was fairly flat .
a : this beer looked great , but looks can be deceiving . a wonderful clear amber color , and a thick white head .  mouthfeel : thin with no carbonation .

a - poured a red mahogany with a billowing chimney of carbonation from the neuculation point going up to the huge , dense , lumpy , tan two-finger head . awesome !  weak , watery mouthfeel with a mineral water like flavor .

nose : fresh berries , fruitiness , pineapple . wow . it all fits together so beautifully . the hint of alcohol warms your senses , but the fragrant bliss of the sweet raspberries makes your mouth water .  mouthfeel : very light and flat .
clear copper/orange body was topped by a huge 3+ fingers of tan head .  m- thin . somewhat creamy , but overall a bit watery and thin .
huge , fluffy , white head with a clear amber body .  m -- watery , definitely could use a bit more body .

a : pours an oily , tar-like impenetrable black with 1 finger of chestnut brown , fine-laced head that dissipates slowly . this is one beautiful looking beer !  mouthfeel was pretty thin after drinking through such a promising head .
poured into a pint glass , revealing four fingers of thick creamy head under a radiant clear golden body with orange hues .  this medium bodied beer is too fizzy and overcarbonated .

pours an dark amber/copper color with a full sized off-white head , fades at a slow rate , bits of lacing along the glass , leaves a nice creamy looking cap that lasts much longer .  mouthfeel was surprisingly thin for the style .
a : two finger width head , which dissolves into 1/2 . golden yellow much akin to a pear . has a strong lace that stays throughout the life of the brew .  mouthfeel dissipated quickly .
a : aggressive pour yields 2/3 finger eggshell colored head with good retention . cloudy dark reddish-brown .  mouthfeel is thin and watery with low carbonation .

superb pour ; an impressive black body with a impressive brown head , nice lacing .  mouthfeel , like i said was cold , also way too fizzy . i 'm not used to a white beer feeling like soda . drinkability is 'average ' because it 's not terrible , it basically is a normal run-of-the-mill white beer , but the carbonation and temp .
pours a honey gold color out of the pint can with a nice , mellow white head . lacing and retention are great .  mouthfeel was a bit watery and flat .
this starts strong , with a luminescent orange and plenty of wispy white head .  mouthfeel : the weakest aspect of this beer , very thin .

the bock poured a very clear deep brown with a firm off white head that lingers as a layer of bubbles and leaves lace clinging to the sides of the glass .  m - moderately carbonated , and starts off with a light to medium body . by the end of the sip though , this turns completely watery and flat . the mouthfeel is what messes this beer up for me .
louie 's demise pours a nice copper color , with a good size head .  too thin , and too carbonated . the mouthfeel is killing all the fun of drinking this for me .
it pours a beautiful cooper color and has a foam that lingers . low carbonation .  very carbonated . watery mouthfeel .

an off white head with great retention and even better lacing , totally full and coating .  way , way too thin for an oatmeal stout . the body is light and watery , while the moderate massaging carbonation makes the beer break out in soft fizziness .

pours an oily black , opaque and viscous , with a thick dollop of tan head slowly spinning in the middle of the beer . very nice lacing as you drink it .  very dry finish ... watery , no body , but some bitterness .

this poured a beautiful inky black with a nice foamy head and i could n't see through this thing at all .  mouthfeel : no carbonation really hurts this beer when it comes to mouthfeel and overall enjoyment .

this beer poured nicely with a light frothy head and an excellent smell . lightly spicy with hints of cloves and lemon and the sweetness of the wheat is pleasantly subdued making the beer easy to drink without over powering the palate .  very thin in the mouth , like carbonated water .

a : standard pour yields a 1.5 finger off-white fine cream head with awesome retention . an all-around beautiful beer .  mouthfeel was poor due to the lack of carbonation . it felt quite heavy , flat and oily with no real finish to each sip other than the burnt bitterness .

winking lizard tour beer ohhh sweet coriander . spicy aroma with more zing than other wits ( cinnamon or allspice ? ) . hazy straw color with a haze of spotty head that once was a solid creamy strata the flavor is n't as exciting as the nose . in fact , i do n't have any reason to think what i smelled and what i tasted were the same beer .  not bad , but this is one of those rare beers for me that struggles on mouthfeel ; this one is thin to the point of watery .

a- holy head , i 'd say about three inches of the top of my tulip is an off white head . the actual beer is a beautiful clear red hue . head is frothy an sticks around quite awhile , excellent thick ( ! ) lacing as well . i enjoy the looks of this beer immensely .  overcarbonated with more cola likeness in the mouthfeel . more lace , less cola character , less carbonation .
pours completely black with a big rich creamy chocolate brown head .  the flavor has a slight bit of chocolate and a hint of roastedness , but it 's very plain and thin . almost watered down .

serving glass : poured from bottle into tulip . appearance : extremely dark ruby with massive , billowing tan head that leaves bubbles sticking to everything it touches .  m : very watery looks thick , but is not .
pours a dark black with a great copper dried lava rock head . excellent retention and lacing .  m : medium-bodied , almost completely flat , and 100 % boring .

topped largely with a massively thick beige foam about two fingers high which stands for length . eventually the crown slowly moves its way into a thick skim always present and tons of lacing caked on all over the glass .  the body was weak in depth , even for a lager/pilsner based beer : almost watery in fact , even though it was highly carbonated .

this stuff is cheap in italy if you can find it ! beautiful color , like dark stained mahogany with ruby . not much head to speak of , but a bit of lacing .  the taste is pretty sugary on the tongue and a little sticky . very watery with not much in the way of depth .

appearance : motor oil black , nice carbonation coming up the sides but you really have to look for it with how dark this stuff is , about an inch of brown head on the top . smell : chocolate , vanilla , rumcake very rich , hits the nose pretty hard .  very thin body , low carbonation .
amazing lacing comes after every drink .  it 's medium-light bodied and pretty scratchy in the mouth . it 's a bummer about the mouthfeel .
the head is very good looking ( looks like a cloud ) .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied but very watery .
a real pretty beer .  mouthfeel was very thin for a porter .

s- best part about this beer . intensely hoppy and citrusy . t- nice and hoppy without being overly bitter . goes down very easily . d- very easy to drink .  12 oz bottle poured into a tulip glass a : orange and hazy with no head s : spices a bit of sweetness and faint alcohol t : sweetness both malty and from the sugar , spicy , apple-cider like flavor , faint alcohol m : almost no carbonation , medium body d : due to the lack of carbonation and mediocre taste this one was hard to swallow .

pours a crystal clear light golden straw hue with an insane 3 finger dense , rocky , creamy , billowing , i ca n't think of anymore words to describe it , head that has excellent retention and leaves big chunks of sticky , patchy lacing down the sides of the glass . if the colour was a bit more attractive , this beer 's appearance could n't get any better .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and thin with low carbonation , underwhelming .

smells just like a really tasty pumpkin pie . it 's easy drinking and it smells great . easily the most drinkable pumpkin ale around , and generally not a bad example of the style .  m ) all up front , empty at the back , light & bland d ) a good value lawnmower beer , that starts off well , but disappears quickly .
looks nice : super clear light golden/orange colour . good amount of off-white head - okay retention .  m - watery , thin , and weak .
the beer poured into the chalice dark brown , heck , almost black with a tan and frothy head which rose tall and fell very slowly to coat the glass .  m & gt ; very watery .
the aroma is pure malty bourbon with a nice sweet caramelized bourbon aroma .  mouthfeel was very very weak .
pour is beautiful . almost pitch black , chunky , long lasting tan head . about as good as it gets .  pretty thin mouthfeel also .

huge crazy rock of white head literally climbing out of the glass . it looks like ice cream and the resulting foam in a root beer float .  this brew starts out weak flavored , weak bodied , and , for me , continued to seem weaker and weaker as my palate adjusted to it . the bottom line : if you want to give mr. sam smith your money , exchange it for some oatmeal stout or imperial stout .

pours a deep , dark mahogany color under a mighty head of dense , beige foam .  it tasted wheaty , slightly spiced and flat . it leaves a flat taste in the mouth as the taste sticks in the mouth . aftertaste does n't stick around that long and the beer goes down fairly easily .

long pleasant finish is spicy . awesome .  carbonation could be better ( little more then a tickle ) , but then it would feel even thinner . not a strong bite , no body , barely hopped , dark with good flavor .
deep auburn chestnut with red highlights and a nice head of meringue like foam .  mouthfeel : this beer was too bland for me and on the thin side .

the dark chocolate/caramel color is beautiful , with a large head made of tight , compact bubbles . looks like a root beer let out of the insane asylum . really good looking beer , and unfortunately the best aspect of this one , by far .  the mouthfeel is very very fizzy , it 's almost like drinking foam .
excellent belgium lace that lasts and lasts .  m : worst part by far . way too light of a body and poor carbonation . it feels watery .

a : black with a tan head . great retention & lacing .  yeah , i know , it 's an irish dry stout , and yeah , it 's supposed to be light for drinkability 's sake ... but it 's awful thin stuff , as if beer and water were mixed 50-50 . i love guinness extra stout , but guinness draught is just too anemic in taste , too watery in the mouth , just overall too ... lite .
looks excellent .  mouthfeel : thin .

nice bubbles race continuously to the top , excellent retention and lacing .  m : this is by far the thinnest doppelbock i 've ever had . it 's too thin even for a plain bock . the low carbonation gives this the mouthfeel of a coke that 's been sitting out too long .
appearance - this came out a good-looking brown with orangish hues and a very nice , full fluffy head that left good lacing .  m : way too watery , thin bodied .
appearance straight black in color with a dark brown head like the crme you find on top of an espresso shot .  it goes down okay , but the body is quite thin .

aroma involves sweet bread , a thin vein of sour funk , a mixture of light and dark fruits and a smack of butterscotch . sweet malts , beer bread , cherries , and a fleeting hop undercurrent to the tongue initially . taffy , grapes and plums rise from the depths as the brew warms . a most dangerously quaffable and imminently enjoyable brew that does absolutely no disservice to the real thing .  m : very poor mouthfeel .

355ml bottle poured into pint glass may27 2010 a a glowing peachy amber with plenty of bubbles feeding a big ass off white head that had excellent retention slowly falling to an island holding its own to the bitter end ( pun intended ) leaving multiple rings of lace well down the glass , not much i would change in this department s some citrus with mild pine balanced out with a healthy amount of sweet malts t even more malt while tasting but nothing overwhelming , some caramel and orange rind go with the flow m no reasons to complain here not too thin well carbonated and a lingering aftertaste d i 'm feeling this beer for sure , a 4.25 option may have come in handy for this brew , well rounded and strong in all areas all that being said this beer is way to expensive here in alberta at 22 $ for 6 i ca n't see myself drinking this too often .  unsatisfying feel .
well , it looks great . the cascading cream and perfect head are par for the course with a nitro , but still i love it every time .  carbonation is a bit overkill . fizzy and annoying .

bottle poured a clear dark reddish brown with a lasting creamy tan head .  the beer is fizzy with no head , light and tastes of strong lime with a soured aftertaste which is supposed to give the `` salt '' taste . overall , i commend miller for going outside the box on this one , and it does live up to the hype - however fizzy and without the polarizing hot sauce . i would choose this over any corona or other such .

`` extra hoppy amber weiss '' on the back label . deep orangey amber , huge voluminous head that takes a few pours to let settle then top off . plenty of sticky , sparkly suds inside the glass . the retention is excellent , it 's head is steadfast with little deflation .  i like ported to be fuller in the body and this has relatively no mouth feel , the mouth is like an american larger minus the over carbonation .
appearance- golden-orange hued color with a huge four fingered large bubbled head .  thin bodied beer .

appearance : nice golden color , two fingers of white lush foam , good head retention , great clarity , lacey aroma : typical tripel ... clovey and malty ; toast , floral hops flavor : mild malt sweetness , some acidity , a bit raspy and grainy , a fair amount of herbal hop flavor , bubblegum , finishes quite dry with not much aftertaste mouthfeel : medium body , prickly club-soda carbonation , minerally overall impression : it 's ok .  in terms of mouthfeel , this beer was way too carbonated .

color is a hazy orange to amber shade and the head is outta control ! a gentle pour gave me three fingers of thick , tan foam that calms to a pinky 's worth and hangs around for quite a while . leaves big , cloud like puffs of sticky lace all over the glass too .  m - i found it very thin and watery , very surprising for a porter .
poured a beautiful copper reddish-brown . the fluffy head left copious amounts of lacing .  the mouthfeel is pretty thin and seltzer like , nothing to hold onto .

22oz pours a very impressive black with a cascade of dark brown bubbles . awesome head . i found myself watching the head settle .  very overly carbonated . carbonation makes it seem cheap and unbalanced .
big , fluffy light-tan head retained very well and the lacing was nice too . great looking beer .  the mouthfeel is thin to medium .

pretty dark and cloudy with a beautiful light purply pink head . i do n't think i 've ever seen a cooler looking beer . the stuff just looked very impressive .  mouthfeel is watered down . a little too much carbonation bite too .

a : hazy copper pour with a wispy white head . lacing is great .  i was at first really disappointed by this beer , but i let it rest and open up to find a much better beer after 20 or so minutes m- for too much carbonation to start , almost felt like seltzer water .
great looking beer .  somewhat watery mouthfeel , due to thin carbonation .
it was the perfect colour for a porter and was just a great looking beer .  m- the mouthfeel is what ruined this for me .

batch 360/362 madrugada obscura pours an opaque black body beneath a massive head of brown foam . the head retention is excellent , and it leaves sheets of interesting lacing about the glass .  very thin mouth feel do to the carbonation being way way way too low .
appearance : wonderfully dark with a slight cream colored head .  seemingly overfiltered and quite thin , but passably drinkable .

22 ounce bomber into a pint glass ( 2 pours ) pours out a deep red with 3 fingers of thick and dense off-white foam that leaves paneling of lace everywhere . this is really the epitome of what beer can look like . i stared at my half empty glass for about 5 minutes .  very watery mouthfeel , which dilutes the flavor .

pour starts a peachy-copper color to an amazing ruby red grapefruit color . head is bubbly and very bright white . being a wit ages in pinot noir barrels with pinot juice it has an awesome , super cool color .  m - this is where the beer suffers the most . basically flat .

the nose is very potent . heady-sweet malt ( carmel and brown sugar ) one of the more aromatic stouts i 've had . starts sweet and roasty finishing bitter and a bit `` earthy '' from the hop effect . the enjoyable and sustained excellence of the look , aroma , taste and feel makes this one of my favorite big stouts .  m - disappointing . loose . watery . needs at least more carbonation .

a : pours an amber/caramel/golden brown . cloudy and appropriate for the style . big , frothy head that gradually recedes to about a finger and sticks around . thick , benchmark lacing .  body is really light and watery .
incredible appearance overall !  m : watery wash more than anything .
color is nice amber with a good head that leaves solid lacing .  way too thin and carbonated . the mouthfeel really limited my enjoyment of this beer .

poured from bottle into a tulip . a : wow , this is a great looking ale . murky , with a hint of gold right at the stem of the glass . the head , which was a full 2 fingers plus , is a light golden/tan .  t- light crisp taste that shows a no bite . m-light taste that becomes watery the longer it stays in your mouth . d- goes down as light as any beer i 've had in recent memory , the best characteristic of beer . if i was at a bar and it was either this or macro lagers , i 'd probably take the macro lager because the price does n't add up to the taste .
smell great , pumpkin pie all day . taste is a huge letdown .  m-light and actually thin , needs more malt heft to have it fit to style , imho .

tastes like an unpolished or amateur version of deschutes obsidian stout . this has a very simple taste for a porter -- well crappy i thought . for the $ 9 a six pack price , a huge dissapointment .  mouthfeel : thin , thin , thin , not a trace of carbonation .

a : impressive look for a porter .  but it looks very good , promising almost : a - a beautiful ruby to dark fawn colour - this must be great s - smells lovely also - fruit notes , hops , some malt and spiciness t - now it starts to disappoint it s not hideous but just a bit bland with a confused taste of a bit of everything m - too stale and manages to be dry also d - i would not recommend this beer and probably not drink it again myself unless in dire need .
batch # 38 very hazy orangy light brown with an amazingly creamy top . impressive retention and lacing .  m - cheap macro feel .
a popular and very classy beer , especially when served in the tulip shaped duvel glasses . a cloudy golden color with a big white foamy head .  mouthfeel was mediocre , felt a bit like grape juice .

it took me close to an hour to drink my one pint , and the thick and frothy head never once let up . deep , rich , and gold-tinged amber in colour , the head on this brew is just unbelievable , and certainly a new legend and classic .  the carbonation is overly apparent , the stout taste is watered down , and the milkiness is subdues to a minimum .
huge foamy white head , good lacing & lasting .  beer is nearly flat in carbonation . feels lifeless and stale .
the double white ale pours a neon golden hue that is quite unique . the head is pretty thick and rocky .  2.0 m : way , way , way too much carbonation .

if you have n't seen one of these beers before , they pour like a stout with the nitrogen head , only with a lighter colored beer . the settled beer is a deep straw and the thick head sticks around throughout the drink .  some creaminess in the mouthfeel , but the water really overtakes it leaving the mouthfeel flat and dull .

finally a beer in my favorite color . poured black with nice tan head that left something on the inside of the glass .  what an absolute bummer of a warmer . it barely makes it as a standard english bitter , but this was a lame 5.2 % warmer and i generally like youngs brews . taste was flat and boring ( nothing to describe ) . actually a little harsh and unsavory . again , a very surprising dead brew .
the color is jet black but it 's light bodied , which still just stuns me .  the mouthfeel is very thin for a winter beer .

appears almost black without light behind it . a massive , frothy , firm light tan head last forever , leaving big clumps of lacing . it really does n't get much better .  roasted malt and a medium to strong coffee flavor , but the flavor and body are just too thin , and kill this otherwise nice beer .
served in a snifter , the beer pours black with a 2 inch frothy tan head .  mouthfeel - kinda thin , kinda lifeless . some weak bubbles make it feel kind of watery , too bad .
a - very dark with ruby highlights . a ridiculous amount of head that leaves some incredible lace as it slooowly dies down .  quite thin and without backbone .

cascade hops dominated the aroma ( not surprisingly ) giving it a somewhat floral and citrus aroma . cascade is simply and excellent hop variety . there was also a slight corniness .  mouthfeel is really thin for the style ... very watery .
a - moderately vigorous pour produces a huge mocha-colored , dense , sponge-like 3 '' head that recedes to a broken 1/8 '' head that remains to end leaving heavy lace .  f : filmy and a bit watery .
a very large scummy buff head recedes to a violent mottled landscape .  unfortunately , the feel is watery and light , rather than full and meaty like you 'd expect a pumpkin pie .

the aroma is intense . roasted malt , milk and dark chocolate , dark roasted coffee , dark fruit , red wine , rubber , alcohol , and more alcohol . crazy and intense . taste is equally crazy and intense .  i was looking forward to trying this beer and just found it to be really average , almost watered down .

a billowing and rocky head , light khaki color , sits on top that last forever leaving an amazing amount of lace .  m - probably the worst part about this , too much carbonation makes a coffee beer seem really cheap and bad .
pours pitch black with a good three finger of puffy light brown head . the head lasts a good ten minutes .  way too carbonated and pretty thin for the style .
pours hazy golden-orange color with a huge foamy head and lovely carbonation .  mouthfeel - this beer really felt thin , almost too thin .
a- great look .  m- boy is this watery . damn shame .

a : pours with a huge thick creamy light brown head , similar in look to a guinness but more porous . good lacing . deep but clear black in color .  all i can say about the mouth is that its way too over carbonated . it was clear this would be the case right from the pour , but wow ... it 's almost painful how carbonated this beer is .
light color on the line between straw and golden , with a nice soft off-white head leaving good lacing . plenty of bubbles racing up inside the glass .  mouthfeel surprisingly thin in the mouth .
this looks amazing . s : hershey 's .  mouthfeel is dry , poorly textured and thin .

nice reddish brown body with a good glow and a nice buttered bread-colored fluffy head that 's not too big but sizeable . slow to recede and laces nicely .  m : medium body . old krusher finishes way too crisply for the style .

the head is cream in color , has tight bubbles , looks very creamy , and is about an inch thick . the lace is amazing . s - light hop smell .  m - feel is bizarre - somehow this is watery , tannic , and overcarbonated at the same time . medium body is adequate , but otherwise this is harsh and flaccid .

a -- black color with a thick finger of head that left rings around the pint glass with every sip s -- faint coffee and roasted malts , pretty standard t -- this was n't too heavy on any of the flavors that i want in my stouts , it was fairly basic with hints of coffee .  quite thin , watery even on the palate ; sweetish stout with milk chocolate again , and very faint roasted malts .

a - dark garnet pour with a big dense almost two finger head that fades to probably a quarter inch head and just kinda stays there . really spectacular head retention on this one .  mouthfeel : very thin , maybe one of the thinnest beers i have ever tasted .
a : beautiful clear red/dark amber color topped by a thick 2 finger off-white head .  m : super thin in body for the style and abv - almost like drinking water .

beautiful beer , with a white head on deep black ... ca n't smell too much more than the nitro and slight notes of roasted barley .  m : low carbonation , too bitter for a chocolate stout d : i wo n't be buying this in the future .

appearance : black as black can be , this is a very dark beer , which allows no light to pass through . it pours with a nice , half-inch deep head . unfortunately , the head dissipates quickly , leaving a few islands of bubbles and a crown of bubbles around the top .  perhaps i was being suggestible , because i found the body to be thin with a faintly grainy , rough texture .

this pours a nice golden straw color with a bright white fluffy billowing two finger head that settles down to a rocky covering with rings and patches of lace . after a quick swirl , the head seems to boil up from below and replenish its self .  with all the acidity and bite , the mouthfeel is pretty bad .

gurgles out of the bottle an absolute pitch black topped with a sturdy milk chocolate head . that simple combo of black under brown is striking , always , and more intense here than almost any . for as thick and viscous as the body appears , it carries an impotent weight , as it seems both heavy and thin at the same time .  interesting beer , not really my style very thin , and super spicy .
a- dark rich brown with a tan head and sticky lacing .  it seems to have a very thin mouthfeel for the style to me and the aftertaste is mostly just burnt malt .
poured a gorgeous ruby amber , with great lacing .  far too thin of a body for the style . lots of flavor and a particularly good aroma , hurt only , though significantly , by its thin mouthfeel .

a : an aggressive pour resulted in a body that was somewhere between a bright rich copper and brick orange and a massive white head . the head was dense and sticky and receded slowly to a even cover over the liquid and fed a layered even curtain of lace .  if i had one complaint with this beer it was its thin , unsatisfying body .

pours out a deep dark amber with copper highlights . a four finger tan head sits atop and leaves big thick sticky clumpy lacing behind .  the flatness of the mouthfeel really detracts from the beer as there is no carbonatin at all .

i poured this beer in it 's dedicated orval glass and drank it slowly which lasted about 20-30 minutes . the head stayed at a peak the entire duration and even after the last sip , it was still hanging on to the side of the chalice for it 's dear life . burnt sugar , stale fruit , earthy malty taste .  thin mouthfeel , swirling around in my piehole , waiting for a flavor epiphany , studying the reaction of my tastebuds , wondering when everything is going to kick in .
redish copper colored beer with a nice amount of carbonation and a huge creamy head .  the mouthfeel is a little fuller than light bodied , with a watery texture .

dope fly 750ml silkscreen bottle , lots of information and graphical content . here it is.. certainly golden , bubbly with a massively carbonated head . settles like a cotton candy pillow with volcanic lace .  mouthfeel : carbonation is pretty high making this fizzy and light , two things i do n't care for in beer .

the beer pours motor oil black with a tiny mocha head . very slow and viscous pour , noticable from the moment the beer leaves the can . additionally this is as black as beer gets , some deep brown highlights on the edges but no light penetrates it , impressive .  mouthfeel was quite thin , certainly not what you 'd expect when looking at this beer .

corked and caged green 12.7oz with 2.004 stamped on the cork poured into a tulip . pale , hazy gold with a massive ( despite a gentle pour ) head of big white bubbles that has great retention and clings to the glass in odd rocky lumps .  the beer is thin on the tongue and the taste , while there was something in the aftertaste , was just not there .

a : this beer looks quite good , fluffy bright white head atop a crystal clear dark-honey colored malt base sporting visible carbonation bubbles .  mf- pure water , flat as can be and the most watery feel possible . some heat but too much water feel . the mouthfeel is very distracting but the taste is pretty good .
very cool . nice amber color and carbonation rising nicely .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .

three fingered head that reduced to one finger , with a really nice lace around the glass . brilliantly clear , tawny colored beer .  heavy , flat yeasty mouthfeel , one dimensional wheat flavor . almost no carbonation .

all centennial hops here . that 's alright because they are great for aroma and flavor as well as bittering . real snappy , almost peppery finish .  the carbonation is way too low , unfortunately , making it feel pretty much flat . body is medium to medium light and could really use the help of some carbonation .
poured into a tulip glass . produced three fingers width of white/pinkish head . nice head retention .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is weak . there 's simply no body here to speak of .

poured a opague black with a extremly creamy off white colored heading . left amazing lacing throughout the tasting and all the way to the bottom with a thick creamy heading finish looked amazing .  m - watery mouthfeel is really disappointing . o - good flavor and balance , but the mouthfeel really hurts this one .

appearance is wonderful ! pours a hazy golden amber with a thick rocky white head . lots of lace on the glass , and it was fun watching the head make different formations with each drink .  mouthfeel= fizzy , high in carbonation which i dont like to burp , bubbly drink ability= easy to drink this ( in my opinion moderate strength beer ) anywhere , have longevity for the night , however , be careful of the budweiser craps the next day .

the beauty of watching the head settle at the top of the glass is a treat all on its own . tasting the foam is also a treat , because usually i 'm not a big fan of most beer foam .  thin mouthfeel , no aftertaste .

in-between hazy and clear , with a beautiful , thick , two-finger head , and amazing sticky lacing . it gives you a taste of what an ipa should be , looks amazing , but falls short of what an ipa can be .  appearance : gold with a 3/4 '' white head that dissipates quickly ; transparent smell : blueberries with a malty lager smell taste : blueberry mixed with a pale ale ; little bit of banana flavor too mouthfeel : very thin : ( drinkability : light and pleasant flavor so you could do two or three in a night
this beer has a deep black color with a huge almost white foam head .  feels very flat and a little watery .
medium amber hue . looks dense .  mouthfeel is very thin and the taste is a little bitter and super dry .
bottle into a tulip glass . a : nice foamy head , glowing amber color , great lacing , carbonation floating up adds to the effect . perfect !  mouthfeel is very light , and drinkability is average .

it produces a large amount of off-white head that sticks around until the very end . the body is hazy and amber/caramel in color .  m : forget about it . water is more filling in your mouth than this is .

pours jet black with a massive foamy tan head that shows no sign of dissipating .  this beer had very little body and not much flavor with the exception of some light , and not altogether unpleasant , corn adjunct flavor .

a - a hazy copper in my snifter topper by nearly four inches of pristine , frothy , white , enduring head .  t & m : the taste is pretty good , but mouthfeel takes away from it . watery very highly carbonated beer gross o : not super impressive .

a- pours a very bright & clear golden honey colored yellow . poured a huge fluffy bright white giving way to its fine cover of a white layer . looks great .  it 's not bad , i think it 's really lacking in the body and any sort of maltiness .
careful with the pour , as this beer made a fast rising 4-finger fluffy white head that lasted several minutes and left tons of lacing .  very flat on the tongue .
poured from a 22oz bomber into a pilsner glass . dark jet black color , tiny amount of light penetrates this beast .  m : very light , almost like a macro lager in feel , watery , fizzy .
a nice black pour with a thick tan head .  the mouthfeel is left with a dry metal feel , again perhaps the can .

a : totally black body , head is light brown creamy with good retention . lacing is great .  mouthfeel/ drinkability : this beer seemed to be a bit on the watery thin side . the taste doesnt linger and is a bit thin .

a- deep ruby/amber in color . looks yummy . d- this beer looks great and thats about it .  a side effect of the carbonation . i must have had a bad bottle because the carbonation took away from everything that could have been good about this one .

crazy . flavor is indeed affected a bit by the `` wild '' , but not as much as i thought from the smell . still very assertive and lush - rich , spicy deep quad flavors , smooth and bready , with a slight pang of earthy funk , not sour .  m- light body , very carbonated , and watered down.. nothing special at all , as expected .
it is near perfect in the glass . no , make that perfect .  mouthfeel - watery , low carbonation , mediocre aftertaste .

malty fresh aroma with slightly spicey twist . this smells like a winner . after such a lovely aroma , i thought i had found a winner , but i will just stick with my andechs .  m- too light and watery for its style .

look : pours a cool looking copper color with a great 1 inch off white head and great retention and great circular lacing smell : great hop aroma .  the body was by far one of the thinnest i 've ever had for a stout .

very good lacing & head retention s : bready with a touch of grassyness t : deep herbal bitterness followed by grapefruit & a touch of biscuitty malt hiding underneath the astrigency .  though this tastes great i find the thin mouthfeel distracting . i dont drink any fruity or sugary drinks to quench my thirst , im a water guy . when i opt for a beer , i want a mouthfeel that reflects that . it tastes very good but the thin mouthfeel just kills it .
pours a clear deep copper color with a huge fluffy white head that shows great retention and a huge amount of lace . 5 stars for appearance !  mouthfeel is thin with very little carbonation .

the pint glass was filled with a black liquid with a tan 2 '' head . the head lasted quite a while and some nice lacing developed .  faint regardless t not far from the smell but with some faint grassy hops and the lemons not skunky , oh wait a minute the skunk comes out on the finish m i think the tap water here has more body , not as much carbonation as i could see and the aftertaste leaves something to be desired o looks great but tastes a little light struck , considering its a 3 $ 6pack i 'll cope just another basic bottle form peru , not the best one i 've had though but i 'd see this being a little better if the bottle was n't green and the brew was n't light struck

being a pale ale lover , i will say that the appearance is flawless . a subservient head over a clear , amber body is how i define perfection .  the mouthfeel is light-medium bodied ( i 'm guessing the abv is 4-5 % ) with a welcome crispness to the carbonation but this is unfortunately overall coming off as too watery and lacking in the mouth at times . and the aforementioned weak body did n't do this any favors either .
fantastic billowing head , soapy and sudsy with fat chunks of lace and supreme retention .  mouthfeel is watery - like any other light beer .

wonderfully striking in the glass . nice dark brown that lets the light dance through , topped with a pale yellow head that outlasted the beer .  s - um ... leaves something to be desired , a bit skunky and reminescent of a pharmacy t - much better than the smell let on , pleasing malts , a little corn m - not impressed with the mouthfeel , really light , carbonation comes through too weakly for a adjunct d - totally average , no place for taste in this bottle
the head is beautiful and has deeply sunken trenches all through it . excellent retention . very nice patterns of lacing .  rather flat carbonation leads to poor mouthfeel .

this is more of an entry level stout for someone who wants to move up from some lighter beers . wo n't be my everyday session stout .  but the glaring problem here is that the carbonation here is quite low , which i do not like in an ipa . it makes this beer taste almost like flat soda . even though i enjoy the flavor quite a bit , the mouthfeel ruins it . o- great flavor here but the mouthfeel really brings down the quality here .

had this on-tap at fox and hound a - as advertised in color . good retention . lots and lots of sticky lacing all the way around the glass .  body is the main drawback of the beer ; very watery for the style .

smell is amazing . big sweet bretty fruit aromas accentuated by the vinous blackberries , pineapple mainly , ripe and luscious . the smell is fantastic , but taste does n't really live up .  m : even worse , overly thin body , low carbonation , and slick on the palate make the alcohol stand out .
the smell is amazing . the brandy is prominent but not overpowering and blends nicely with sweet malts .  light and watery mouthfeel and low carbonation .

thick inky black pour with sticky rings for lace as the mocha head settles .  m - have to give it a low score considering that all the carbonation was lost when i cracked it resulting in an almost completely flat drink .
poured pitch black with a large tan head which quickly diminished .  thin bodied , sharp cola carbonation .
pours a dark thick black appearance with a two finger dark brown head .  mouthfeel : very thin and watery .
this cask ale poured it 's typical brilliant clarity , a deep copper with a thinnish head . lacing was solid and beautiful .  m- incredibly thin body with higher than expected carbonation .

beautiful crystal clear amber honey golden body . big rocky slightly off-white head with amazing lace hanging in large clumps and never ending retention .  this beer is very light bodied and finishes very thin .

the smell coming out of this glass is amazing . notes of bourbon , coconut , caramel , chocolate , and fig , with some very earthy wet leaves hiding just beneath . some palates might whine about the sweetness and seemingly unnecessary richness of overall taste , but i love it . a nice smooth feel , with some astringency from the alcohol at the finish .  m - almost none . no hops , no carbonation , no metal , no cardboard dryness on the tongue .
sinking sediment complements rising bubbles , all capped with a large dense off-white head . incredible lacing for the style .  carbonation is almost nonexistant after the pour .

a - deep , reddish amber with a finger silky smooth tan head . the lacing is impressive - when you til tthe glass , the bubbles all fall together , then break . nice eye candy .  too high of carbonation level created an almost uncomfortable mouthfeel . beyong this fault , a light mouthfeel with a semi-dry finish , dominated by a heavy-feeling hop bitterness .

first off , this is a truly gorgeous looking beer in the glass . completely pitch black with a frothy mocha head that showing exceptional retention and sheets of lacing .  a very watery taste and mouthfeel . noticeable malt , but it tastes like they watered down my beer . too watery to be very drinkable . but light , so it helps its drinkability a little .
the widget certainly did its job this one has a nice dense foamy head on top of an almost black brew .  m - low carbonation and very thin .

poured pretty aggressively from the bottle to a unibroue tulip . a - pours black , very very black with about 2 fingers of brown sugar colored head that lightens up a bit over a few minutes .  mouthfeel was thin and flat ( as expected ) .

2001 : first thing you notice is a big custard-like dark tan head over a perfectly black body .  pitch black , ca n't see thru it at all . bit thin , watery . lactose then black patent are the first things i taste , but then falls flat . touch of bitterness at the end which is probably from the roasted grains and not from the hops .

a : i 'm not sure how a porter could look any different . the head is full , dark and does dissipate . the body is nearly and opaque black .  again , coffee and tobacco , plus a hint of cedar , m : very thin for a beer of this lineage , d : overall , not worth retaining for a long haul .

black with a brown ring of bubbles on the top .  fair warning : it smells like the brewers trapped a skunk fart within the bottle , and , to swill it between your cheeks reminds me why i need to get my cavities filled . it 's an unpleasant , sour taste that warms all too quickly . however , i think it pours pretty well and has a great taste when drank from a glass . the aromas are much more pleasant when let out of the dank green bottle . as far the appearance , it seems a little too much on the light side for a beer that tastes as heavy as it does .
here 's what i thought : a-golden brown , a little cloudy with about a half an inch of head . overall , very attractive in appearance .  very thin .
great looking beer . great dark brown look .  no foam in the mouth , it got a rich taste with just alittle to much sweetnes , got spice , vanilla and licorice .

deep amber body with absolutely no chill haze . proud two fingers of foamy head hardly move over the course of the beers ' life . really , it 's a beautiful looking brew .  low carbonation , lack of vanilla , coffee and hints at cocoa m : flat and thin , has some carbonation issues .
simply incredible looking .  no mouthfeel but easy to finish and perhaps order another .

a- pours a pitch black with slight dark mahogany edges when held up to the light . 3/4 '' espresso like foam top with a few medium bubbles mixed in a mostly fine creamy head . espresso like clingy edges . looks like a picture perfect stout to me .  way too watery for a stout .

huge tan head that has good retention and nice lacing .  big sweet amber malt scent , touch of bitter hops mixed in there . the thinness immediately strikes me . the malt and hop tastes are kind of underwhelming , there are some fruit and yeast tones that are fairly pleasing though . im not really a major amber guy to begin with , but this one seems like they forgot to put in half of the ingredients .

thanks for the opportunity ... poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 2 '' beige head over the clear orangey amber brew . thick head holds steady , with heavy coating lace .  and it could have been better ; this beer is vastly undercarbonated , which gives the beer a nearly flat , somewhat thin feeling .

the pour is absolutely gorgeous ! this is one of the best looking beers i 've seen in a while . dark brown with massive head and tons of lace .  s : malty/burnt smell t & m : the taste and mouth feel were both disappointing from what i was expecting . the watery flow of this beer was the greatest disappointment after pouring it and seeing the thick head .

poured black with a 3 finger head and decent lacing .  theres a fruity sweetness up front , and a very light hopiness . overall , id describe this beer as watery and uninspiring.another gimmick beer .

appearance - pours a cola black with the largest mocha head i 've ever seen on stout . 6 fingers easily , 3/4ths the volume in the glass is a solid wall of foam , plus i had to 'power-sip ' a mouthful off the top to avert a mess . a cratery head well above the glass 's top slowly melts down to a chunky cover .  it is cheap . so when i want three or ten of these after work they are ok. not a bad flavor for a cheap macro . cheap .

) this stout poured jet black with a creamy tan head that left a great coating on the glass as the beer was sipped .  unfortunately , the look and smell of this beer were the best part . it 's bland to the tongue , blah to the mouth . calling it kenya 's version of budweiser is too mean , but i could probably reproduce the flavor of this beer by mixing singha , budweiser , and water .
appearance - black body , thick offwhite creamy head with good retention .  but the thin mouthfeel really detracts from the experience .
a - hazy yellow/peach coloured with a mammoth creamy head s - notes of apple , but overall a muted aroma .  carbonation is too high .
a : cloudy dark mahogony color . big head retention with high amount of lacing .  m : thin , watery , and yet sticky . pretty gross .

the nose a sharp and floral with a brutal pickled hopped up back end nose . a lot of lemon citrus , with a salty , piney astringancy holy shite this beer is pretty damn big !  m : awful dry , tannic bitterness , d : not so average

a- pours a the haziest of pale yellow-orange . produced a 1/2 finger of white head looks spot on for an unfiltered wheat . good head retention , constant bubbling throughout the beer .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied low carbonation , and an annoying cloying texture .

drank on-tap at redbones barbecue , somerville , ma served in a pint glass the beer poured a translucent brown/black with an ultra smooth and creamy , two-finger , coffee-colored head . thick rings of lacing stuck all down the glass .  appearance : bright golden-yellow in color , one inch head , cloudy , high carbonation smell : banana , wheat , and clove taste : wheat dominates ... there are touches of bananas , clove , and a bit of honey mouthfeel : very light bodied , high carbonation , very very sweet drinkability : light and weak for the style .

pours a very day brown , almost black .  the hop bitterness is clearly present , but it seems to fight the sweetness also present . a very uncomfortable aftertaste develops that leaves my mouth overly dry and soap-like . i did n't want to finish my pint , nor would i want another one of these .

a - it is a pretty golden color , and the head is thick and beautiful white color . it lasted for a long time , and there is thick lacing . s - this is the most average part of this beer .  mouthfeel is very thin .

pours pitch black into the corsendonk tulip , and an aggressive pour produce a thick and sexy tan capper , sheets of lace on the way down .  mouthfeel - weak and watery , not very enjoyable . very little carbonation .

poured a lovely orange-rust color with a high level of carbonation with a thick , white head that left behind full rings of lacing in my pint glass .  very watered down . nothing special to see here .

s : absolutely mind blowing . just a wonderful smell . t : more tropical fruits on the taste .  m : even though there are some pleasant tastes the mouthfeel is pretty bland and watery , almost no bubbles or carbonation .
pours a hazed brown color , opaque in the glass and a very nice thick creamy foam head .  plate is quite watery , really watery in fact even for a sub-5 % beer .
a vigorous pour produced a thick , rocky , mocha colored head that produces substantial lacing .  the mouthfeel was very thin , light and highly carbonated .

the aroma is huge on bourbon with mild hints of coffee , vanilla , and chocolate but dominated by bourbon . this is a really good stout , but the bourbon is a bit overwhelming for me .  the body is fairly watery which is probably the biggest downfall of this beer .
a- pours a beautiful copper/orange with a huge , spritzy , white head . amount of head makes me think this scratch beer is overcarbonated . decent lacing .  mouthfeel is thin and tinny .

a : pours a dark black color , good sized tan head . good lacing down the glass s : coffee , sweet bready malts t : coffee , slight harsh maltiness also slight hint of chocolate m : light very thin bodied beer .  palate is weak .
it 's good , but not as impressive as the awe inspiring aroma led me to believe .  m - thin soda pop feel .

after a minute of settling , there 's a still a luscious , thick white head nearly an inch deep . rest of the beer is a dark , clear gold color .  m : this is where i have to knock off major points . despite being medium to full bodied for the style , this beer is flabby , slick , and gritty in the mouth .
bottle pours a nicely clear garnet color with a creamy beige head . decent retention and lots of lacing . a beautiful beer , i must say .  m : seltzer water , but this is slightly less carbonated .

hops run across the nose . sweet and rindy citrus -- orange , lemon , and grapefruit . it 's nice for a couple of sips , but i 'm left wanting something more well rounded .  mouthfeel : thin and a little flat . needs more carbonation to make the mouthfeel more lively to compensate for the rather weak flavor .
bottle into pint glass : a : beautiful medium-to-dark brown hazy body with good , creamy head . great , thick cap .  mild carbonation , watery .
pours black , as the name implies it will , with a thick tan head and great lacing .  mouthfeel is very limp flat and lifeless .

22 oz bomber pours a deep amber with a massive tightly bubbled head ( one of the best i 've ever seen !  same story with the flavours ; chocolate , golden syrup , not all that complex very high carbonation , pretty ridiculous .

pours a dark brown , opaque body with thick , fluffy head that fills the schneider weizen edle-weisse glass ( and then some ) ... malt and yeast esters float clove , banana and vanilla -- quite a tantalizing combination , clear and crisp ... thin , slightly effervescent in the mouth ; the weakness may be in due part to its age ( drink by 12/07 ? ) ... smooth with only a bit of back bite ... the sightest sediment tickles with a soft acidic presence ... the malt and yeast explosion simmers quickly , and what promises by look and smell to be a strong , thirst-quenching palate pleasure turns out only half right : smooth and easy drinking , yes , but the weight that would be the dunkel seems to have been misplaced ...  body is too thin and watery , however , and i would definitely call it the primary issue that needs improvement .
really a very complex and interesting nose on this beer .  entry seems flat and introduces a mouthfeel which seems thin and uninspired .

a nice 3 finger deep tan head shows fat bubbles and decent lace after a strong pour . the body is the blackest brown you can get , only showing hints of brown around the edges .  the body was very weak and insubstantial .
pours a dark dark brown with a red hue when looking down onto the beer . has a one finger off-white head that stays until the end .  finish and mouthfeel are virtually nonexistent .
( enjoyed with devilish glee at bridgid 's in philly ) this beer glows a menacing red that appealed to me right away .  mouthfeel is very thin , alomst non-existent .
produces a great head retention with two and a half fingers thick worth of cranium , and has a flawlessly clear copper colored body .  the texture is rather flat and uninviting .

a- very dark black with a creamy rich tall head . it reduced slowly as i drank and left a good lacing s- the smell is initially good .  taste is similar , although it tastes like watered down coffee . very thin , not very interesting , and leaves a lot to be desired .
citrus cascade hops aroma .  just way to thin , watery and even under carbonated . give this a little more body and some more carbonation , and this will be a decent beer .

a : very very dark brown in color with almost no light shining through . great retention and very nice lacing .  something is missing in the carbonation and mouthfeel as it lingers and never really cleans up .

great clouds of clingy creme ! the dark brown and brandy booze looks ready to go ... smells of three heavy hitters ; coffee , cocoa , and caramel . overall a solid seasonal , one that makes me very excited for the colder seasons as those are just as good here in co as are the warm ones  s : basic dark beer , some roasted malt and generic hops t : thin , distant malt and hops . m : not much , water comes to mind .

i think it smells fantastic , and inviting . it 's pretty overpowering , so if you like sour flavors , you might love this one .  some funky , dusty aroma , reminiscent of all abita 's beers . maybe the spring water . some fruitiness too . watery palate . tasty .

the most impressive aspect is the head , which is cloud-like in texture , and tenacious in retention .  thin-bodied and watery with adequate carbonation that lends itself to good drinkability , true to style .
light orange body , sticky lacing , with great retention .  mouthfeel : very light body that leaves me hanging .
poured a maroon with a beige head .  mouthfeel : thin , watery . foams a bit upon swishing over the palate .
pours a 1.5 finger light tan whitish head over a crystal clear dark orange-gold liquid .  mouthfeel and carbonation are pretty weak overall .
this is a nice looking beer . pours out a cloudy sunset with a massive head .  the mouthfeel is disappointingly thin .
12 oz bottle a : light golden under a white head . good lace and retention .  mouthfeel is quite thin .

appearance- a mahogany hue with red highlights . one finger of foamy white head . head disapates into quarter inch with beautiful lacing . beautiful light carbonation .  m : too much carbonation for me d : could be drinkable but not really worth it for the lack of flavor would n't buy this again ...
appearance : arrives at my table a dark black colour with a big , fine , creamy off white head that stayed the duration of the drink .  the mouthfeel is incredibly watery .

the apperance of this ipa is among the best i 've seen deep orange hazy body with a think creamy white head that lasted the enitre way to the bottom , awesome sticky lacing . there is not a huge defining scent just malt hops and some sweetness from honey or citrus .  palate was thin and rather crisp for the style . mouthfeel is wide then crashes to thin making me think this beer was n't fully fermented . no carbonation to speak of on the mouthfeel .

pours the absolute quintessence of an american pale . billowy pillow of lasting , off-white foam upon a brew as golden as cortez ' daydreams . multiple swipes of a spatula would be needed to remove the gorgeous lace .  mouthfeel : thin and watery with too much carbonation .

s - smell is actually quite nice - oak , citrus hops , herbs , tequila , some vanilla , and a sugary malt backdrop . it 's something that i kept returning to , as it was very unique . flavors integrate surprisingly well .  way too much carbonation .

the aroma is majestic . very floral right up front , but the nose also contains some serious hop notes as well . the hop aroma is tempered by this amazing sweetness , honey like and malty . what a good flavor . however , as a non-fan of hop bombs , this is a damn fine one .  m/d : a light body that is thin and watery .
it looked great . unfortunately it smelled like hot alcohol .  m : surprisingly light in body live a clean , watery finsih .
a : the beer poured a creaamy and nearly black hue . the head receded leaving a beautiful tan lacing .  the palate is thin .
it pours dark brown to nearly black with an impressive brownish-reddish foamy head .  m= flat as a board . wish it was carbonated but there is nothing here . flat as a board .

pours a hazy dark-gold and gets cloudier as it sits . topped with a four finger puffy white head , well carbonated - full of tiny bubbles . leaves lots of lacing behind , partial rings and partial webs .  extremely light feeling on the tongue , watery , but with a fair amount of carbonation .
very fruity and loaded with tingling carbonation . it is very flavorful and enjoyable .  m : lacking , really felt like a light lager in my mouth , it 's that fizzy .
deep , rich cloudy red with about two inches of foamy , off-white head that took a while to dissolve and left noticeable lacing on the snifter .  mouthfeel is thin and watery and low on carbonation .
pours out black with a beautiful thick brown head .  the palate is thin .

served in a perfect pint . a=nice rich medium gold color with 1 finger head .  average . better than extremely cheap beers , worse than expensive ones . if you do n't want anything interesting to drink , grab a michelob .
the head displays great retention and absolutely coats the glass in lacing .  medium-bodied with a hard water mouthfeel . palate is left dry with notes of dusty herbal and grain .

a huge frothy 1.5 finger white head , which the server apologized for , but that i was more than willing to accept . one of nicest looking lacing patterns i 've seen in a while .  this tastes empty , watery and thin on the palate , the carbonation sorely lacking what is otherwise a quite pleasant taste .
looks amazing in the glass ! the bottle is really beautiful too .  the mouthfeel was totally ruined by the insane level of carbonation .
looks like it will be an amazing beer . lots of lacing throughout .  mouth feel is thin but warms to an alcoholic finish .
great clear , reddish brown with an excellent head . amazing looking beer .  mouthfeel was poor , super thin with way too much carbonation .
appearance : clear orange-brown big head and lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is marginal , thin and fizzy , very mexican macro .
the head is tan and billowy , sitting 4+ fingers high . good retention and excellent lace in the glass .  really thin body , goes down faster than you can taste it .
large , rocky , light tan head . a truly beautiful beer .  thin and somewhat watery body .

appearance - pours fully black , nearly four fingers of mocha foam pile up and fade back unevenly , with meringue-like peaks and valleys . thick ropes of lacing , clumps as well , very sticky .  coming from a bottle , this beer does not have a creamy enough mouthfeel for what i want from a stout . i have had some bottled stouts that were excellent , but this is too light and carbonated .

pours a slightly dark orange amber with a nice 2 finger head that stays thick as it turns to beautiful lacing . i really , really had to sniff hard to get any aroma at all ... just light malt to me .  m : only thing i can really knock , for having such strong flavors , this is quite thin on the palate for what it is . only thing i can seriously knock is the body , it 's so thin and watery .

look : the beer pours an orange color with a nice fluffy light-amber-orange head smell : sweet malts , caramel , yeast , fruits ( orange ) and almonds .  t- watery flavor , i thought it was lacking . pumpkin is nicely present and i sort of lost the other great flavors that i had smelled . m- worst part of the beer , way too watery for the flavor and smell .
appearance - yellowish orange clear beer with nice head and retention smell - a superb scent !  carbonation seems weak too ... and it is pretty light on the mouthfeel .

excellent grain aroma , and the taste quite a bit heartier than what i would expect from most browns .  the body is the lightest i 've had for such a high abv stout , and this is probably the culprit for me not liking this beer or any of atwater 's as much as i might . everything i 've had by them so far has a diet coke body and a medium at best finish . vanilla java porter was okay for me , but definitely on the thin side .

poured from bottle into brooklyn tulip glass . pours a rich black/brown color- fizzy head fills the top of the glass but then recedes quickly , no lacing . appears rich in carbonation . nearly pitch black in color after getting into the glass .  thin , watery with no carbonation . i didnt realize the age when i bought it and i would say this really went past its prime in carbonation .

a- one of the nicest looking pale ales i 've ever seen . pours a brilliantly clear rich amber color , with a 3 finger head . textbook definition of a gorgeous beer .  the result is a thin , watery , and disappointing mouthfeel .

black in colour with a good tan head and good glass lacing .  mf- the body here is pretty watery to me with lower carbonation that i would expect . db- pretty much the sort of flavor you would expect in the style but with a weak mouthfeel that does n't compliment the beer .
a : nice amber color with a very thick lacing head .  i 'm not sure if the previously mentioned stout flavors are influencing my perception here but the feel seems very watery .
gold color . slight haze . very thick frothy off white head . excellent lacing .  for me , the beer really went downhill in the mouthfeel .

i love just turning these kinds of cans 180 degrees and just letting them guzzle into the glass , then watching the awesome cascade of bubbles form a perfect head . i really liked the smell .  t. i love the taste , for a cheap beer it is quite good m. very watery d. i can and do drink this beer all night long .
this one is another jet black beer with a frothy tan head .  mouthfeel is pretty watery , some fizz as it goes down .

appearance : black liquid with a well-retained one-finger head . head clings to glass as the beer goes down . drinkability : this beer looks wicked cool , but once you start pouring it back it 's a real disappointment .  m : watery d : just okay , and i know its wrong but the limn and la sal go into this one .
appearance : this brew pours wonderful tan full head .  m very very thin , maybe the thinnest i have rated .
pours a dark black with a nice head , head recedes quickly leaving minimal lacing .  over the top carbonation . other than the carbonation it 's an ok lager but there are better ones out there .

33cl brown bottle with a silver label appearance : beautiful thick honey-golden color with an ethereal , snow-white lacing .  t : more of the same from the nose , and as watery as expected . m : not much going on here . i imagine leaving a club soda open for an hour and then drinking it would feel about the same .

looks like this one has come out of retirement . a - clear bronzed orange liquid with copper tones and a creamy , milky white head that reduced to a quarter inch of retention but deposited a thick coat of opaque , sheet-like lacing all over the sides of the glass .  slightly flat . ends up feeling a bit watery .

poured on nitro into a pint glass , the beer gives a beautiful cascade settle . bright , vibrant , crystal clear yellow-gold color with a thick , dense , bright white , foamy head .  flavor and mouthfeel were a bit confusing . however , the flavor seemed to be sort of hiding behind a rather watery mouthfeel which made me lukewarm on this beer .

s : here we go complexity here . woody , chocolate , alcohol , charcoal , with hints of a toffee and caramel sweetness . wow and this beer is n't even warmed up . t : lets see here it starts out sugary sweet with an alcohol kick surfacing in the middle with a drying burnt chocolate finish . m : very rich lush thick feeling in the mouth .  it quickly became apparent that there was very little mouthfeel , and whatever taste -either from the malt or hop bill - was absent .

great three finger white head , with an orangish and caramel colored body -- firm and sticky lacing .  m : the worst part it my experience . it was so carbonated that the first sip felt like it was cutting my mouth .

beautiful foam bubble mix of a rich milk chocolate colored head . perfect oil black body makes for a apitizing stout standard .  m- high carbonation and medium body . the carbonation reminded me of seltzer water , way too much and which had a sharp mouthfeel . pretty sweet and the carbonation was just way too high to make it very drinkable .

poured the beer had a lovely gold color and the head was huge so i was looking forward to drinking this beer . honestly , the appearance is amazing . then i smelled the beer and it actually turned my stomach .  m - to much carbonation in consideration with the taste . the high carbonation presence kills this beer .
rich black pour , white foamy head that falls off kind of quick , but leaves beautiful lacing . this stuff looks like a million bucks .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .
very pungent and totally awesome . t- super bitter .  thin harsh mouthfeel .
