pours an effervescent amber/orange with 3 fingers of fluffy tan head . insane lacing & head retention s : citric & floral hops show up early , but muted t : floral & piney hops , plus biscuitty malt up front .  citrusy and maybe some pineapple as well m : full bodied , harsh bitter mouthfeel that is not very enjoyable really d : not a horrible beer but nothing i would willingly buy again .

a - medium brown with mocha colored head and thin lacing that lasted throughout the beer .  both of these co-mingle into the aftertaste m : light bodied with too much carbonation o : this is a great dessert beer that manages to mimmic apple pie with the spices and apples and is easy to drink , but as a stand-alone `` pale wheat ale , '' this one is way off the mark .

appearance : poured a beautifuly ruby/coppery color . a solid 1 and 1/2 finger head formed and it lasted the entire pint -- do n't know if i 've ever seen retention quite like that . solid carbonation is present in the glass .  very light . in the mouth it is awfully fizzy ( hmm , maybe that was a pow after all ) .
the beer poured crystal clear pale straw . the head was white , moussy and everlasting .  the body was light , the mouthfeel watery and the carbonation light .

a- this beer looked almost like a rootbeer float as it settled after the pour . there was a 1 finger tan head atop a black brew with some mahogany tones at the edges . the head lasted throughout the drink and left lots of sticking on the glass .  nose was faint and grainy , mouthfeel flat , and the flavor followed the nose . pass on this one .
appearance - dark black with a tannish head .  watery body , carbonation is vital to keep it from boring [ me ] .
a very good looking beer overall .  mouthfeel is very thin and watery , very little body to speak of .

this beer is quite beautiful . it pours a honey-gold color with high clarity and an eggshell-colored head that has good staying power .  this is definitely a flavorful beer , but the feel in my mouth and stomach is pretty similar to that of your bmc lager . thin , watery , and generally just empty feeling . overall i 'd call this one very average .
pours a cloudy , ruddy amber with a lighter copper along the bottom of the glass . great retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel is weak , fizzy beer .

pours from the bottle a reddish-orange color , topped with a gorgeous three-fingers worth of white head .  the end falls flat due it 's lack of carbonation m : flat and poor . it loses me on the lack of carbonation , loses taste , body and overall feel .

sweet brown sugar , vanilla , and bourbon dominate with undertones of wood and a hint of smoke . there is a very subtle spicy booze aroma at the end as well .  m - medium-bodied and drastically under-carbonated . d - easy enough to drink , but the lack of carbonation combined with a lack of flavor complexity make it difficult to enjoy .

hazy titanium yellow body ( which catches the shadows forming a beautiful mysterious gradient ) with an incredibly dense pillow of magnolia cream . heavy persistent head and rich creamy lacing .  mouthfeel is as thin as it gets . the best thing about a bud light is its drinkability .
a : pours a nice ruby color with quite a bit of head that leaves a ton of lacing .  only downside is the lack of body here .
beer is a very attractive hazy gold with an ivory head .  mouthfeel is quite thin and watery , and leads to a soapy feeling .
12oz bottle app : a beautiful cloudy amber . a nice , chunky off-white head .  the body 's mouthfeel and accompanying appearance issues are too much for me to recommend this as being drinkable .
another brew i have to thank dim for . the body of the brew was black as night no light coming through at all .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and pretty watery .

pitch black colour with a nice 1/2 '' head . lots of beige lacing around the glass .  the taste ... .well , it 's one of the most watery and flavor devoid beers i 've ever had . the body is of a somewhat watery cereal grain taste ... .which leads into a finish with more cereal sweetness mixed with a bit of grassiness and hay . but , with all the decent beers out there , i 'm not sure why i should seek this one out .

best by date is 31 march 09. a - pours very dark almost pitch black , big two-finger dense mocha head on an easy pour , great retention and lacing , beautiful s - very strong espresso aroma , some bittersweet chocolate and a slight hint of alcohol t - very intense taste , begins with a slightly sweetened espresso flavor that develops into a nice deeply roasted malt and more sweetness in the midpalate , the finish is a bit disappointing however as the flavors sort of disappear m - medium-to-full-bodied , mildly carbonated , fairly dry on the finish d - pretty drinkable , alcohol really is n't an issue , finish is dry but not overly so very nice beer .  mouthfeel is extremely watery with almost no carbonation .

beautiful looking beer - poured a nice thick 3-finger off-white head that very gradually receded to a sheet .  it was fairly thin and very carbonated , with a mild coffee aftertaste . there was no distinguishing character to it , and it was too thin . and like all of the cooperstown beers , it had way too much head and carbonation .

a-reddish gold with a thick light tan head , quite a neat site actually s-i 'll be honest , it smells like something in between a heavy belgian white ale and a champagne ... leaning more towards the champagne ... unfortunately .  mouthfeel : very thin and in my opinion over carbonated .
a- deep golden colour , 5 finger creamy head from typical aggressive weizen pour . very good head retention and lively beading .  feel still sucks though , very slick and watery .

'' my pour left me with two dense fingers of tawny head with decent retention . color was a deep coppery-red ( with ne-quality clarity ) that makes me think of former g/fs and women with that natural hair color that speaks to the reptilian/neanderthal part of my brain .  for a cheap 3.79 beer ... this is good stuff ! very light body and almost zero head even when poured vigorously like a rice beer .

pours with a very nice large head with great lacing but not really much retention . very clear amber body , absolutely gorgeous and inviting .  aromas come through but are trumped by a tangy , thin , watery mouthfeel .

pours a deep amber with a creamy thick off-white head that lasts for a long time . excellent lace trails stick to the glass .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with light watery carbonation . the only downside is the watery mouthfeel .
fantastic head retention & lacing s : coffee & dark chocolate , great nose t : coffee grounds up front , a touch of charred grain & dryness up front .  very thin , but not too much carbonation .
appearance : pours into my snifter with a dark reddish-brown body and a thick one-finger off-white head .  m : the body of old guardian is almost thin .

pours a misty gold with the most impressive head i 've ever seen . just a huge billowing white cloud of foam that clings to the edges of my jackie o 's tulip . it live an intricate map of lacing all the way down the glass .  m - bad . champagne-esque carbonation ; prickly and somewhat thin .

a= pours a pitch black color with a nice two finger thick brown head on it . the head and color is really suprising for a lager .  the mouthfeel is light bodied with aggressive carbonation , and a watery texture .
settles to a wonder layer and lacing from top to the bottom ... . fantastic looking beer .  mouthfeel is painful due to the high acidity .

a : pours a clear orange tinted lemon-yellow with that signature duvel billowing whipped egg white head that we 've all come to love . a huge oily dense pillar of foam appeared as the frothy white mound slowly receded into fuzzy lace .  m : very watery and thin body with medium carbonation .

this beer pours an absolutely beautiful black which might be this beers greatest attribute . a small tan head accompanies the pour .  mouthfeel is too light for the style and carbonation is too high .

pours a slightly hazy bronze with a tightly packed 1.5 '' white head . great lacing & head retention in my chimnay glass smell : lemons & latic acid , a bit overpowering taste : tart & more tartness ( grapefruit ) that just wraps around the whole tounge .  m- not much to the mouthfeel , very bland and left a weird aftertaste .

a beautiful beer that shows a bright amber color that seems to glow in the glass . brilliantly clear and carries a stark white head that lingers through the session , leaving a lot of lacing behind .  the body is watery thin .
appearance- somewhat deep golden color ... maybe a dull golden . scads of chunks and streaks everywhere .  very watered down .
grower fill from h 24 . a : wonderful copper color . lighter then a lot of ipas but not much .  mouthfeel is definitely thin .

initially pours a fairly clear light amber with little head , but as the nitro works it 's magic , it builds a thick creamy head that lasts until the last sip .  i can not find any hop first impression is how thin the liquor is . the low carbonation matches this and also explains why there is little lasting head . even as a lesser dry stout , it is watery and flat .

light amber with an almost orange hue , and a thick pillowy cream-colored head .  everything suggested about complexity and structure within the nose and the appearance is met with a waters , formless and thin feeling beer . some wheat prevails , and some smoothness of texture , but there is not half as much of the pillowy champagne carbonation that i would have wanted .

appearance - the ideal pour . motor oil on the way out , a reverse cascading head . thick mocha cap is creamy with some large bubbles . a sticky layer of solid lace adheres all the way around .  first sip is fairly thin body especially for a milk stout . i keep coming back to how thin the body is and find it a little disappointing .

the pour was very nice , a beautiful copper hue color with a nice thick head . it is high in carbonation with helps with head retention and also has a good lace to it .  very thin . high carbonation simple and uninspiring , breaks a few key rules for the macro lager style too .

i poured it into a basic tulip and almost had a beer-gasm . it looked amazing ! i mean it looked like the other two big irish dry 's but still , beautiful .  m- way , way too carbonated . it makes the thinner body feel worse

the beer pours a deep cocoa brown with a spongey tan head foaming up very easily to 3cm and fading slowly leaving a cratered surface as it recedes .  okay i know alot of people hate on cobra for being cheap malt liquor , but ive had many many cheap beers that tasted much worse for example bud ice .

12oz bottle app : golden amber with a wonderful frothy , white head .  taste is ok - same roasted chocolate malt that was in the nose again no coffee - weak flavors - i have had stronger porters mouthfeel - a very thin light body with low carbonation overall - maybe this was past its prime or i got a bad bottle - but after drinking this i would not buy this beer again

poured into tulip glass . almost clear despite full pour w/ bottle conditioned sediment , 2-finger off-white head , gradually fades to wisps and ring . great lacing , almost curtain-like further down the glass .  m- this beer was basically flat . theres no reason an ipa shouldnt be carbonated .

smuttynose really old brown dog is a very clear , dense , brown ale with a generous , thick , dense , foamy yellow head that has incredible retention .  earthy hop flavors , finishes and lingers into the after with hop flavors , though mild m- start out pretty thin but develops as brew warms , dry and crisp finish , hops abuse can felt in aftertaste ( still mild though ) d- the flavor is decent throughout with improvements as the beer warms , the body does n't recover like the flavor however , starts damn near watery and has little progress .

the beer pours a straight orange , fairly clear . a slightly aggressive pour yields an absolutely towering bone colored head , filling half the glass . retention is off the charts , almost ten minutes after my pour and i still have frothy foam cap of about two fingers in height .  m-very thin and watery with light carbonation and a slightly sticky feel .

pours a hazy bright blond color with a lemon hue , lots of frothy white head that sticks around , and some carb action .  less complex flavours , there is a little chocolate and coffee but then it quickly falls flat . carbonation is to high , body too watery .
look : incredible .  m - very thin bodied and carbonation level seems a little off .
on tap at the brewery ... a-dark lacing with a nice smooth greyish tan head and good lacing s-smells like burnt chocolate .  mouthfeel was nothing to write home about . watery and boring .

this gem pours jet black and thick , no head to speak of save for a chestnut brown ring around the glass .  m : the feel is where the flatness really kills this beer . it 's nice and slick but the lack of carbonation really puts a damper on the rest of the experience . d : this has all the right components for a great dipa if port brewing could just get their carbonation issues solved .

body is a hazy gold , with an amazing rush of co2 . head is thick , white , and meringue-like . head retention is amazing . that thick head never smaller than 3/8 inch .  in the mouth it is thin and watery lacking concentration of flavor and depth .

pours opague black with a nice inch light brown creamy heading that only a beer on nitro can give . nothing to fancy with this beer .  mouthfeel : hugely carbonated , paired with such a strong showing of sour lemon it 's almost sickening . no real body on this one , just very light and carbonated .
a truly phenomenal looking belgian ale .  m : very thin with very little carbonation .

a-pours a dark brown , almost black liquid with a ton of tight creamy tan head .  thin , fizzy mouthfeel . i 'd rate this lower if i really thought they were trying to brew a `` dubbel , '' but as a generic misguided `` abbey ale '' this is more flavorful than much of new belgium 's regular offerings for example ...

a - my pour was a little over the top , so out sprouts a 4+ finger light brown head that is bubbly , frothy and slowly craters as it dies down . the lacing is a bit ridiculous ; super sticky and goopy . the beer itself is a menacing looking black with purple and brown tints .  mouthfeel - light to watery side .

pours a slightly cloudy copper amber with intense streams of carbonation rising to the top , capped by a frothy 3/4 '' head that wo n't quit leaving heaps of gorgeous , sticky , foamy lacing .  a vigorous and sustained bead fed the head as i took my first sip to find that this beer had no real texture or body .
deep cherry red hues with brilliant clarity when held up to the light . very appealing !  the mouthfeel is extremely watery - it tends to wash out the flavor .
smells amazing - citrusy and sweet , with a hint of malt .  a little too much roughness . feel is tacky , raw and sweet .

impressive appearance that 's almost stout-like . a bordering on black body rests resplendent underneath a generous tan coloured head .  not much taste , just thin malts and an odd taste i ca n't really describe . thin , watery , not too carbonated . the bad taste is n't really apparent seeing how thin it is .
a : super cloudy golden yellow . enormous off white white head with some lacing .  mouthfeel this one is sour and very alcoholic .

( a ) - pours a near pitch black color that produced a huge fluffy tan heat with superb retention . plenty of lacing left behind , not wanting to disappear .  mouthfeel was thin and light with a lot of carbination , not my ideal , but what you 'll expect from an average lager i suppose .
